nce1     =\n| party1 = Indian National Congress\n| alliance1 =  United Democratic Front (India)\n| leaders_seat1 = [[Puthuppally, Kottayam|Puthuppally]]\n| last_election1 = 42\n| seats_needed1 = {{increase}}30\n| seats1 = 72\n| seat_change1 = {{increase}}30\n| popular_vote1 = 8,002,874\n| percentage1 = 45.83%\n| swing1 = {{gain}} 2.85%\n| image2 = [[File:V. S. Achuthanandan 2008.jpg|100px]]\n| leader2 = [[V S Achuthanandan]]\n| leader_since2 =\n| party2 = Communist Party of India (Marxist)\n| alliance2 = Left Democratic Front (Kerala)\n| leaders_seat2 = [[Malampuzha]]\n| last_election2 = 98\n| seats_needed2 = {{decrease}}27\n| seats2 = 68\n| seat_change2 = {{decrease}}30\n| popular_vote2 = 7,846,703\n| percentage2 = 44.94\n| swing2 = {{loss}} 3.69%\n| map_image = Map of Kerala showing 2011 Assembly Election Results.svg\n| map_size = 200px\n| map_caption = [[List of constituencies of Kerala Legislative Assembly|Kerala Assembly Constituencies]]\n| title = [[Chief Minister of Kerala|Chief Minister]]\n| posttitle = [[Chief Minister of Kerala|Chief Minister]]\n| before_election = [[V. S. Achuthanandan]]\n| before_party = Communist Party of India (Marxist)\n| after_election = [[Oommen Chandy]]\n| after_party = Indian National Congress\n}}\n\nThe '''thirteenth legislative assembly election''' was held on 13 April 2011 to elect members of the 140 constituencies in [[Kerala]]. Election results were released on 13 May 2011. The results proved to be one of the closest elections in Kerala's history, with the UDF beating the LDF by a margin of 4 seats.\n\n==Parties and coalitions==\nThere are Three  major political coalitions in Kerala. The [[United Democratic Front (India)|United Democratic Front]] ('''UDF''') is the coalition of centrist and centre-left parties led by the [[Indian National Congress]]. The [[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|Left Democratic Front]] ('''LDF''') is the coalition of leftwing and far-left parties, led by the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] (CPI-M). The right-wing [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP) is also contesting in the state and fielded candidates in 139 constituencies, with one seat to their [[National Democratic Alliance (India)|NDA]] alliance partner [[Janata Dal (United)]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2011/03/29/stories/2011032962480600.htm |title=Kerala / Thiruvananthapuram News : Not eyeing specific posts: Kannanthanam |publisher=The Hindu |date=29 March 2011 |accessdate=16 May 2011 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mytips4help.blogspot.com/2011/04/kerala-assembly-elections-2011_04.html |title=Help Desc: Kerala Assembly Elections 2011 |publisher=Mytips4help.blogspot.com |date=4 April 2011 |accessdate=16 May 2011}}</ref>\n\n===[[United Democratic Front (India)|United Democratic Front]]===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Sl.No: !! Name of the Party !! Party Flag!!Party Leader in Kerala\n|-\n| 1 || [[Indian National Congress]] || [[File:Flag of the Indian National Congress.svg|50px]]  ||[[M. M. Hassan|M M Hassan]]\n|-\n| 2 || [[Indian Union Muslim League]]  ||[[File:Flag of the Indian Union Muslim League.svg|50px]]  ||[[Sayed Hyderali Shihab Thangal]]\n|-\n| 3 || [[Kerala Congress (M)]] || [[File:Kerala-Congress-flag.svg|50px]]  ||  [[K. M. Mani]]\n|-\n| 4 || [[Revolutionary Socialist Party (India)|Revolutionary Socialist Party]] ||[[File:RSP-flag.svg|50px]] || A.A. Azeez\n|-\n\n|-\n| 6 || [[Kerala Congress (Jacob)]] ||  ||  [[Johnny Nellore]]\n|-\n| 7 || [[Communist Marxist Party|Communist Marxist Party (John)]] ||[[File:CMP-banner.svg|50px]]  || C. P. John\n|-\n|}\n\n===[[Left Democratic Front (Kerala)|Left Democratic Front]]===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Sl.No: !! Name of the Party !! Party Flag!! Party Leader in Kerala\n|-\n| 1 || [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] || [[File:South Asian Communist Banner.svg|50px]] || [[Kodiyeri Balakrishnan]]\n|-\n| 2 || [[Communist Party of India]] ||[[File:CPI-banner.svg|50px]]  || [[Kanam Rajendran]]\n|-\n| 3 ||