{"title_page": "Passport (automobile dealership)", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=September 2009}}\n{{Infobox company\n| fate = Dissolved\n| name = Passport International Automobiles\n| logo = Passport Logo.jpg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1|7|1988}}\n| defunct   = {{End date and age|7|1|1991}}\n| type = \n| industry = [[Automotive]]\n| products = \n| successor = [[As\u00fcna]]\n| parent = [[General Motors]]\n}}\n'''Passport''' was a [[Canada|Canadian]] [[car dealership]] network owned by [[General Motors]]. It sold vehicles from [[Isuzu]] and [[Saab Automobile|Saab]] as well as its own branded [[Passport Optima]], a Korean ([[GM Daewoo|Daewoo]]) made [[badge engineered]] [[Opel Kadett#Kadett E|Opel Kadett E]], starting in [[model year]] 1988.  General Motors' [[Geo (automobile)|Geo]] import brand was introduced in the United States at the same time.\n\nThe Optima was offered in either hatchback or sedan and achieved 52mpg on the highway. It was designed by European Opel and had a slew of standard features for a relatively low price. The Optima sedan made the minority of the sales, while the hatchback remains more common, however, fewer than 500 Optimas were registered for road use as of 2012. Sales of the Optima were extremely slow and with relatively low survival rates, the Optima is a rare sight today. Very few pictures document the existence of the Optima.\n\n[[General Motors Canada]] changed its branding strategy in 1991, disbanding Passport (the Optima was rebadged as the [[As\u00fcna SE]] and [[As\u00fcna GT]]). Isuzu was grouped together with [[Saab Automobile|Saab]] and GM's new, import-fighting [[Saturn Corporation|Saturn]] division to form Saturn-Saab-Isuzu dealerships.\n\nPassport's sibling, Geo,  carried on until 1998 while another GM import brand, [[As\u00fcna]], debuted for model year 1992 but lasted only two model years.\n\n==Models==\n*Passport Optima - [[Daewoo LeMans]], built in [[South Korea]]\n*[[Isuzu Rodeo|Passport Rodeo]]\n*[[Isuzu Stylus|Passport Stylus]]\n*[[Isuzu Trooper II|Passport Trooper II]]\n*[[Isuzu Impulse|Passport Impulse]]\n*[[Isuzu I-Mark|Passport I-Mark]]\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Passport Optima GSi (6810302205).jpg|Passport Optima GSi in a junkyard\nFile:Passport Optima GSi wheel (6810301257).jpg|Passport Optima GSi wheel\nFile:Passport Optima.jpg|Passport Optima\nFile:Passport Optima GLS sedan front.jpg|Passport Optima GLS Sedan front\nFile:Passport Optima GLS Sedan rear.jpg|Passport Optima GLS Sedan rear\nFile:Passport Optima GLS sedan window stickers.jpg|Passport window sticker\n</gallery>\n\n{{commonscat|Passport (auto brand)}}\n{{General Motors brands}}\n{{General Motors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Passport (Automobile Dealership)}}\n[[Category:Auto dealerships of Canada]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies established in 1991]]\n[[Category:Retail companies disestablished in 1991]]\n[[Category:Defunct motor vehicle manufacturers]]\n[[Category:General Motors marques]]\n[[Category:Passport (automobile dealership)| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=September 2009}}\n{{Infobox company\n| fate = Dissolved\n| name = Passport International Automobiles\n| logo = Passport Logo.jpg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1|7|1988}}\n| defunct   = {{End date and age|7|1|1991}}\n| type = \n| industry = [[Automotive]]\n| products = \n| successor = [[As\u00fcna]]\n| parent = [[General Motors]]\n}}\n'''Passport''' was a [[Canada|Canadian]] [[car dealership]] network owned by [[General Motors]]. It sold vehicles from [[Isuzu]] and [[Saab Automobile|Saab]] as well as its own branded [[Passport Optima]], a Korean ([[GM Daewoo|Daewoo]]) made [[badge engineered]] [[Opel Kadett#Kadett E|Opel Kadett E]], starting in [[model year]] 1988.  General Motors' [[Geo (automobile)|Geo]] import brand was introduced in the United States at the same time.\n\nThe Optima was offered in either hatchback or sedan and achieved 52mpg on the highway. It was designed by European Opel and had a slew of standard features for a relatively low price. The Optima sedan made the minority of the sales, while the hatchback remains more common, however, fewer than 500 Optimas were registered for road use as of 2012. Sales of the Optima were extremely slow and with relatively low survival rates, the Optima is a rare sight today. Very few pictures document the existence of the Optima.\n\n[[General Motors Canada]] changed its branding strategy in 1991, disbanding Passport (the Optima was rebadged as the [[As\u00fcna SE]] and [[As\u00fcna GT]]). Isuzu was grouped together with [[Saab Automobile|Saab]] and GM's new, import-fighting [[Saturn Corporation|Saturn]] division to form Saturn-Saab-Isuzu dealerships.\n\nPassport's sibling, Geo,  carried on until 1998 while another GM import brand, [[As\u00fcna]], debuted for model year 1992 but lasted only two model years.\n\n==Models==\n*Passport Optima - [[Daewoo LeMans]], built in [[South Korea]]\n*Passport [[Isuzu Rodeo]]\n*Passport [[Isuzu Stylus]]\n*Passport [[Isuzu Trooper II]]\n*Passport [[Isuzu Impulse]]\n*Passport [[Isuzu I-Mark]]\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Passport Optima GSi (6810302205).jpg|Passport Optima GSi in a junkyard\nFile:Passport Optima GSi wheel (6810301257).jpg|Passport Optima GSi wheel\nFile:Passport Optima.jpg|Passport Optima\nFile:Passport Optima GLS sedan front.jpg|Passport Optima GLS Sedan front\nFile:Passport Optima GLS Sedan rear.jpg|Passport Optima GLS Sedan rear\nFile:Passport Optima GLS sedan window stickers.jpg|Passport window sticker\n</gallery>\n\n{{commonscat|Passport (auto brand)}}\n{{General Motors brands}}\n{{General Motors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Passport (Automobile Dealership)}}\n[[Category:Auto dealerships of Canada]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1988]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturin