{"title_page": "Love Canal", "text_new": "{{Infobox superfund\n| name         = Love Canal\n| image        = [[File:Looking into Love Canal.jpg|300px]]\n| caption      = (2012)\n| city         = [[Niagara Falls, New York|Niagara Falls]]\n| county       = [[Niagara County, New York|Niagara County]]\n| state        = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| location_map = USA New York\n| coordinates  = {{coord|43.080518|-78.948956|region:US-NY_type:landmark|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| CERCLIS_ID   = NYD000606947\n| contaminants = [[#Contaminants|Various chemicals]]\n| responsible  = [[Hooker Chemical Company]]\n| proposed     = December 30, 1983\n| listed       = September 8, 1984\n| construction = September 29, 1998\n| partial_del  =\n| deleted      = September 30, 2004\n}}\n\n'''Love Canal''' is a neighborhood in [[Niagara Falls, New York]], infamous as the location of a {{convert|70|acre|ha mi2 km2|adj=on}} landfill that became the site of a massive environmental disaster in the 1970s. Decades of dumping toxic chemicals harmed the health of hundreds of residents;<ref name=\":0\" /> the area was cleaned up over the course of 21 years in [[Superfund]] operation.\n\nIn 1890, Love Canal was created as a model [[planned community]], but was only partially developed. In the 1920s, the canal became a dump site for municipal refuse for the city of Niagara Falls. During the 1940s, the canal was purchased by [[Hooker Chemical Company]], now [[Occidental Chemical Corporation]], which used the site to dump 21,800 short tons of chemical byproducts from the manufacturing of dyes, perfumes, and solvents for rubber and synthetic resins.\n\nLove Canal was sold to the [[Niagara Falls City School District|local school district]] in 1953, after the threat of [[eminent domain]]. Over the next three decades, it attracted national attention for the public health problem originating from the former dumping of toxic waste on the grounds. This event displaced numerous families, leaving them with longstanding health issues and symptoms of high [[white blood cell]] counts and [[leukemia]]. Subsequently, the federal government passed the [[Superfund]] law. The resulting Superfund cleanup operation demolished the neighborhood, ending during 2004.\n\nIn 1988, [[New York State Department of Health]] Commissioner [[David Axelrod (physician)|David Axelrod]] called the Love Canal incident a \"national symbol of a failure to exercise a sense of concern for future generations\".<ref>{{cite web | first =  Sam How | last = Verhovek | title = After 10 Years, the Trauma of Love Canal Continues | work = The New York Times | date = August 5, 1988 | url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DE6D9143CF936A3575BC0A96E948260 | accessdate = 2008-07-29}}</ref>  The Love Canal incident was especially significant as a situation where the inhabitants \"overflowed into the wastes instead of the other way around\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OFhfAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Road to Love Canal: Managing Industrial Waste before EPA|last=Colten|first=Craig E.|last2=Skinner|first2=Peter N.|publisher=[[University of Texas Press]]|year=1996|isbn=978-0292711839|location=Texas|page=153|access-date=2017-04-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170402091909/https://books.google.com/books?id=OFhfAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|archive-date=2017-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[University of Buffalo]] Archives house a number of primary documents, photographs, and news clippings pertaining to the Love Canal environmental disaster; many items have been digitized and are viewable online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://library.buffalo.edu/specialcollections/lovecanal/|title=Love Canal Collections - University Archives - University at Buffalo Libraries|website=library.buffalo.edu|access-date=2018-02-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180206190152/https://library.buffalo.edu/specialcollections/lovecanal/|archive-date=2018-02-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nLove Canal is a neighborhood located in the city of [[Niagara Falls, New York|Niagara Falls]] in the northwestern region of [[New York (state)|New York state]]. The neighborhood covers 36 square blocks in the far southeastern corner of the city, stretching from 93rd Street comprising the western border to 100th Street in the east border and 103rd Street in the northeast. [[Bergholtz Creek]] defines the northern border with the [[Niagara River]] marking the southern border {{convert|1/4|mi|m|spell=in}} away. The [[LaSalle Expressway]] splits an uninhabited portion of the south from the north.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Love+Canal,+Niagara+Falls,+NY+14304/@43.0823332,-78.9596629,15z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m5!3m4!1s0x89d368ea99493cdd:0x337e99fa18f076ce!8m2!3d43.0819258!4d-78.950037|title=Google Maps|website=Google Maps|access-date=2017-02-16}}</ref> The canal covers {{convert|16|acre|}} of land in the central eastern portion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health.ny.gov/environmental/investigations/love_canal/lcreport.htm|title=Love Canal: A special Report to the Governor & Legislature|website=www.health.ny.gov|access-date=2016-03-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305190502/http://www.health.ny.gov/environmental/investigations/love_canal/lcreport.htm|archive-date=2016-03-05|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Early history==\nIn 1890, William T. Love, an ambitious entrepreneur from the [[Western Railways and Light Company|Western Railroad Corporation,]] envisioned a perfect urban area called \"[[Model City, New York|Model City]]\". He prepared plans to construct a community of parks and residences on the banks of [[Lake Ontario]], believing it would serve the area's burgeoning industries with much-needed hydroelectricity.<ref>Parry, David W., Dept. of Architecture, SUNY at Buffalo. \"William T. Love and the Development of Model City.\" Unpublished manuscript, 1975.</ref> He gave his name to the ensuing project, envisioning a perfect urban area.<ref>{{cite journal|title=United States: Lessons of Love Canal Prompt Clean up|first=David|last=Dickson|journal=[[AMBIO]]|volume=11|number=1|year=1982|pages=46\u201350|publisher=Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences|jstor=4312752}}</ref>\n\nAfter 1892, Love's plan incorporated a shipping lane that would bypass the Niagara Falls. Love quickly arranged backing from financial banks in [[New York City]], Chicago, and England. During October 1893, the first factory opened for business. In May 1894, work on the canal had begun. Steel companies and other manufacturers expressed interest in the chance of opening plants along the Love Canal.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.health.ny.gov/environmental/investigations/love_canal/lctimbmb.htm|title=Love Canal - Public Health Time Bomb|website=www.health.ny.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2017-02-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202200543/https://www.health.ny.gov/environmental/investigations/love_canal/lctimbmb.htm|archive-date=2017-02-02|url-status=live}}</ref> Love began having a canal dug and built a few streets and houses.<ref name=\"Berton\">[[Pierre Berton|Berton, Pierre]].  Niagara: a history of the falls.  McClelland & Stewart Inc. 1994. {{isbn|0771012179}}</ref> The [[Panic of 1893]] caused investors to end sponsorship of the project.{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=21}} In addition, Congress passed a law prohibiting the removal of water from the Niagara River, to preserve Niagara Falls.<ref name=\"Levine, p.9\">Levine, p. 9</ref>  Only {{convert|1|mi|spell=in}} of the canal was dug, about {{convert|50|ft|}} wide and {{convert|10-40|ft||0}} deep, stretching northward from the [[Niagara River]].{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=21}}{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=20}}\n\nThe [[Panic of 1907]] proved economically disastrous as Love had to abandon the project. The deathblow came with the development of the transmission of electrical power over great distances by means of an alternating current. No longer was it necessary for the industry to locate near the source of electrical power.\n\nLove's financial backers deserted him, and the last piece of the properties owned by his corporation was subjected to mortgage foreclosure and sold at public auction in 1910.\n\nWith the project abandoned, the canal gradually filled with water.<ref name=\"Berton\" /> The local children swam there during summers and skated during the winters. In the 1920s, the canal became a [[dump site]] for the City of Niagara Falls, with the city regularly unloading its municipal refuse into the landfill.\n\nIndustry and tourism increased steadily throughout the first half of the 20th century due to a great demand for industrial products and the increased mobility of people to travel. Paper, rubber, plastics, petrochemicals, carbon insulators, and abrasives composed the city's major industries. This prosperity would end by the late 1960s as aging industrial plants were relocated to less expensive locations.\n\n==Love Canal disaster==\n=== Pre-disaster state of town ===\nAt the time of the dump's closure in 1952, Niagara Falls was experiencing prosperity, and the population had been expanding dramatically, growing by 31% in twenty years (1940-1960) from 78,020 to 102,394.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=us+census,+niagara+falls&spell=1&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjQ5P7ArMjUAhXH5oMKHbwtBNAQvwUIJSgA&biw=1366&bih=638|title=us census, niagara falls - Google Search|website=www.google.com|language=en|access-date=2017-02-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Hooker Chemical Company ===\nBy the end of the 1940s, [[Hooker Chemical Company]] was searching for a place to dispose its large quantity of [[chemical waste]]. The Niagara Power and Development Company granted permission to Hooker during 1942 to dump wastes into the canal. The canal was drained and lined with thick clay. Into this site, Hooker began placing {{convert|55|USgal|l|adj=on}} [[Drum (container)|metal or fiber barrels]]. In 1947, Hooker bought the canal and the {{convert|70|ft|m|adj=mid|-wide}} banks on either side of the canal.<ref>Levine, p. 10</ref> It subsequently converted it into a {{convert|16|acre||adj=on}} landfill.<ref>{{cite news|title=Actions At The Love Canal Site|date=February 23, 1983|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/02/23/us/actions-at-the-love-canal-site.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207134502/http://www.nytimes.com/1983/02/23/us/actions-at-the-love-canal-site.html|archive-date=February 7, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, the City of Niagara Falls ended self-sufficient disposal of refuse and Hooker Chemical became the sole user and owner of the site.\n\nIn early 1952, when it became apparent that the site would likely be developed for construction, Hooker ceased use of Love Canal as a dumpsite.{{sfn|Colten & Skinner|1996|p=158}} During its 10-year lifespan, the landfill served as the dumping site of {{convert|21,800|ST|}} of chemicals, mostly composed of products such as \"[[Corrosive substance|caustics]], [[alkaline]]s, [[fatty acid]] and [[chlorinated hydrocarbon]]s resulting from the manufacturing of dyes, perfumes, and solvents for rubber and synthetic resins\".{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=22}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://myamericanodyssey.com/dumped-on-the-messy-truth-about-love-canal-ny/|title=Dumped On: The Messy Truth About Love Canal, NY|newspaper=My American Odyssey|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170115235952/http://myamericanodyssey.com/dumped-on-the-messy-truth-about-love-canal-ny/|archive-date=2017-01-15|url-status=live}}</ref> These chemicals were buried at a depth of {{convert|20 to 25|ft||round=0.5|spell=in}}.<ref name=\"Levine, p.9\" /> Upon its closure, the canal was covered with a clay seal to prevent leakage. Over time, vegetation settled and began to grow atop the dump site.\n\nBy the 1950s, the city of Niagara Falls was experiencing a population increase. With a growing population, the [[Niagara Falls City School District]] needed land to build new schools and attempted to purchase the property from Hooker Chemical. The population reached more than 98,000 by the 1950 census.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/library/publications/decennial/1950/population-volume-1/vol-01-35.pdf|title=Number of Inhabitants of New York|last=|first=|date=|website=Bureau of Census|access-date=March 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824122002/https://www2.census.gov/library/publications/decennial/1950/population-volume-1/vol-01-35.pdf|archive-date=August 24, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Sale of the site ===\nDuring March 1951, the school board prepared a plan showing a school being built over the canal and listing condemnation values for each property that would need to be acquired.<ref name=\"Zuesse-LoveCanal\">{{cite web | first = Eric | last = Zuesse | title = Love Canal: The Truth Seeps Out | publisher = Reason Magazine | date = February 1981 | URL = https://reason.com/archives/1981/02/01/love-canal/print | accessdate = 2017-10-31 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170127105829/http://reason.com/archives/1981/02/01/love-canal/print | archive-date = 2017-01-27 | url-status = live }}</ref> During March 1952, the superintendent of [[Niagara Falls City School District|Niagara Falls School Board]] inquired of Hooker with regard to purchasing the Love Canal property for the purpose of constructing a new school. After this, in an internal company memorandum dated March 27, 1952, Bjarne Klaussen, Hooker's vice president, wrote to the works manager that \"it may be advisable to discontinue using the Love Canal property for a dumping ground.\"{{sfn|Colten & Skinner|1996|p=158}}<ref name=\"Glaberson\">{{cite news|title=Love Canal: Suit Focuses On Records From 1940's|first=William|last=Glaberson|date=October 22, 1990|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/10/22/nyregion/love-canal-suit-focuses-on-records-from-1940-s.html|accessdate=February 27, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227233450/http://www.nytimes.com/1990/10/22/nyregion/love-canal-suit-focuses-on-records-from-1940-s.html|archive-date=February 27, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> During April 1952, after discussing the sale of the land with Ansley Wilcox II, Hooker's in-house legal counsel, Klaussen then wrote to the company president, R.L. Murray, suggesting that the sale could alleviate them from future liabilities for the buried chemicals:\n\n{{quote|The more we thought about it, the more interested Wilcox and I became in the proposition, and finally came to the conclusion that the Love Canal property is rapidly becoming a liability because of housing projects in the near vicinity of our property. A school, however, could be built in the center unfilled section (with chemicals underground). We became convinced that it would be a wise move to turn this property over to the schools provided we could not be held responsible for future claims or damages resulting from underground storage of chemicals.{{sfn|Colten & Skinner|1996|p=158}}<ref name=Glaberson/>}}\n\nWhile the school board condemned some nearby properties, Hooker agreed to sell its property to the school board for $1. Hooker's letter to the board agreeing to enter into negotiations noted that \"in view of the nature of the property and the purposes for which it has been used, it will be necessary for us to have special provisions incorporated into the deed with respect to the use of the property and other pertinent matters.\" The board rejected the company's proposal that the deed require the land to be used for park purposes only, with the school itself to be built nearby.<ref name=\"Zuesse-LoveCanal\"/>\n\nAs \"a means of avoiding liability by relinquishing control of the site\", Hooker [[deed]]ed the site to the school board in 1953 for $1 with a liability limitation clause.{{sfn|Colten & Skinner|1996|p=161}} The sale document signed on April 28, 1953, included a seventeen-line [[Caveat emptor|caveat]] purporting to release the company from all legal obligations should lawsuits occur during the future.{{sfn|Colten & Skinner|1996|p=158}}{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=22}}<ref name=\"Zuesse-LoveCanal\"/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Brown|first1=Michael H.|title=Love Canal and the Poisoning of America|journal=The Atlantic|date=December 1979|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1979/12/love-canal-and-the-poisoning-of-america/376297/|access-date=2017-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160715030152/http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1979/12/love-canal-and-the-poisoning-of-america/376297/|archive-date=2016-07-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Prior to the delivery of this instrument of conveyance, the grantee herein has been advised by the grantor that the premises above described have been filled, in whole or in part, to the present grade level thereof with waste products resulting from the manufacturing of chemicals by the grantor at its plant in the City of Niagara Falls, New York, and the grantee assumes all risk and liability incident to the use thereof. It is therefore understood and agreed that, as a part of the consideration for this conveyance and as a condition thereof, no claim, suit, action or demand of any nature whatsoever shall ever be made by the grantee, its successors or assigns, against the grantor, its successors or assigns, for injury to a person or persons, including death resulting therefrom, or loss of or damage to property caused by, in connection with or by reason of the presence of said industrial wastes. It is further agreed as a condition hereof that each subsequent conveyance of the aforesaid lands shall be made subject to the foregoing provisions and conditions.<ref name = \"Zuesse-LoveCanal\"/>}}\n\nCritics of Hooker's actions believe that, in the words of Craig E. Colton and Peter N. Skinner, \"Hooker assigned the board with a continuing duty to protect property buyers from chemicals when the company itself accepted no such 'moral obligation'.\"{{sfn|Colten & Skinner|1996|p=159}} The transfer effectively ended what provision of security and maintenance for the hazardous waste had existed before and placed all responsibility in clearly unqualified hands. It was this attempt to evade their responsibility, Colten and Skinner contend, that would \"ultimately come back to haunt not only Hooker but all other chemical producers in the United States through the strict liability provisions of Superfund legislation.\"{{sfn|Colten & Skinner|1996|p=157, 159, 161}} However, Eric Zeusse writes that Hooker's decision to sell the property rather than allowing the school board to condemn it stemmed from a desire to document its warnings. \"Had the land been condemned and seized, says Hooker, the company would have been unable to air its concerns to all future owners of the property. It is difficult to see any other reason for what it did.\"<ref name = \"Zuesse-LoveCanal\"/>\n\nNot long after having taken control of the land, the Niagara Falls School Board proceeded to develop the land, including construction activity that substantially breached containment structures in a number of ways, allowing previously trapped chemicals to seep out.\n\nThe resulting breaches combined with particularly heavy rainstorms released and spread the chemical waste, resulting in a [[public health]] emergency and an [[urban planning]] scandal. In what became a test case for liability clauses, Hooker Chemical was found to be \"negligent\" in their disposal of waste, though not reckless in the sale of the land. The dumpsite was discovered and investigated by the local newspaper, the ''[[Niagara Gazette|Niagara Falls Gazette]]'', from 1976 through the evacuation in 1978.\n\n[[File:Hooker Electrochemical Quit Claim Deed to Board of Education.pdf|thumb|Hooker Electrochemical Quit Claim Deed to Board of Education.]]\n\n===Construction of the 93rd Street School and the 99th Street School===\nDespite the disclaimer, the School Board began construction of the \"99th Street School\" in its originally intended location. In January 1954, the school's architect wrote to the education committee informing them that during excavation, workers discovered two dump sites filled with {{convert|55|USgal||adj=on}} drums containing chemical wastes. The architect also noted it would be \"poor policy\" to build in that area since it was not known what wastes were present in the ground, and the concrete [[Foundation (engineering)|foundation]] might be damaged.<ref>Levine, p.12</ref> The school board then relocated the school site {{convert|80 to 85|ft||spell=in}} further north.{{sfn|Colten & Skinner|1996|p=153}} The kindergarten playground also had to be relocated because it was directly on top of a chemical dump.\n\nUpon completion in 1955, 400 children attended the school, and it opened along with several other schools that had been built to accommodate students. That same year, a twenty-five-foot area crumbled exposing toxic chemical drums, which then filled with water during rainstorms. This created large puddles that children enjoyed playing in.{{sfn|Colten & Skinner|1996|p=153}} In 1955, a second school, the 93rd Street School, was opened six blocks away.\n\n===Usage by the schools===\nDuring 1957, the City of Niagara Falls constructed sewers for a mixture of low-income and single family residences to be built on lands adjacent to the landfill site. The school district had sold the remaining land, resulting in homes constructed by private developers, as well as the Niagara Falls Housing Authority. In total, 800 private houses and 240 low-income apartments were constructed.<ref name=\"Love Canal:: Start of a Movement\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/lovecanal/canal/|title=Love Canal :: Start of a Movement|website=www.bu.edu|access-date=2017-01-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207031620/https://www.bu.edu/lovecanal/canal/|archive-date=2017-02-07|url-status=live}}</ref> The sale came despite the warning of a Hooker attorney, Arthur Chambers, that, as paraphrased in the minutes of a board meeting, \"due to chemical waste having been dumped in that area, the land was not suitable for construction where underground facilities would be necessary. He stated that his company could not prevent the Board from selling the land or from doing anything they wanted to with it but, however, it was their intent that this property be used for a school and for parking. He further stated that they feel the property should not be divided for the purpose of building homes and hoped that no one will be injured.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Curtin|first1=John|title=United States v. Hooker Chemicals & Plastics Corp|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/850/993/2132540/|accessdate=31 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107020506/https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/850/993/2132540/|archive-date=7 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> While building the gravel sewer beds, construction crews broke through the clay seal, breaching the canal walls.<ref name=\"Zuesse-LoveCanal\"/> Specifically, the local government removed part of the protective clay cap to use as [[fill dirt]] for the nearby 93rd Street School, and punched holes in the solid clay walls to build water lines and the [[LaSalle Expressway]]. This allowed the toxic wastes to escape when rainwater, no longer kept out by the partially removed clay cap, washed them through the gaps in the walls.<ref name=Stroup/> Hence, the buried chemicals could migrate and [[soil mechanics|seep]] from the canal.\n\nThe land where the homes were being built was not part of the agreement between the school board and Hooker; thus, none of these residents knew the canal's history.<ref name=\"Levine, p.13\">Levine, p. 13</ref> There was no monitoring or evaluating of the chemical wastes stored under the ground. Additionally, the clay cover of the canal which was supposed to be impermeable began to crack.<ref name=\"Levine, p.13\"/> The subsequent construction of the [[LaSalle Expressway]] restricted [[groundwater]] from flowing to the Niagara River. After the exceptionally wet winter and spring of 1962, the elevated expressway turned the breached canal into an overflowing pool. People reported having puddles of oil or colored liquid in yards or basements.{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=25}} There were 410 children in the school during 1978.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Leadup and discovery ===\nResidents were suspicious of black fluid that flowed out of the Love Canal.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=YH1xBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=love+canal+reception|title=Greening the Globe|last=Hironaka|first=Ann|date=2014-09-15|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9781107031548|language=en}}</ref> For years, residents had complained about odors and substances in their yards or the public playgrounds. Finally the city acted and hired a consultant, [[Calspan|Calspan Corporation]], to do a massive study.<ref name=\"Love Canal:: Start of a Movement\" /> In 1977, a [[1977 Blizzard|harsh winter storm]] dumped {{convert|33-45|in|cm}} of snow, significantly raising the water table.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/2013/10/18/love-hurts-243690.html|title=Love Hurts|last=Alexander Nazaryan On 10/17/13 at 2:17 PM|date=2013-10-17|website=Newsweek|access-date=2017-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314161611/http://www.newsweek.com/2013/10/18/love-hurts-243690.html|archive-date=2017-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://buffalonews.com/2017/01/22/blizzard-77-still-measuring-rod-massive-snowstorms/|title=The Blizzard of '77: Buffalo's storm for the ages|last=Warner|first=Gene|date=2017-01-22|website=The Buffalo News|access-date=2017-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314154631/http://buffalonews.com/2017/01/22/blizzard-77-still-measuring-rod-massive-snowstorms/|archive-date=2017-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref> The excess water got into the ground water and raised the elevation of contaminates including dioxin.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Health/story?id=5553393&page=1|title=Love Canal Kids at 30: 'Ticking Time Bombs'|last=James|first=Susan Donaldson|date=2008-08-11|website=ABC News|access-date=2017-02-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217143134/http://abcnews.go.com/Health/story?id=5553393&page=1|archive-date=2017-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref> During the spring of 1977, the State Departments of Health and Environmental Conservation began an intensive air, soil, and groundwater sampling and analysis program after qualitative identification of a number of organic compounds in the basements of 11 homes adjacent to the Love Canal. It was also revealed that the standards at the time did not require the installation of a liner to prevent leaching; this became very common among companies.<ref>Colten, C., and Skinner, P. (1996). ''The road to Love Canal: Managing industrial waste before EPA'', Univ. of Texas Press, Austin, Tex. {{isbn|0292711824}}</ref>\n\n====Contaminants====\nNumerous contaminants dumped in the landfill included chlorinated hydrocarbon residues, processed sludge, [[fly ash]], and other materials, including residential municipal garbage.<ref>\"New York State Task Force on Toxic Substances Files of Chairman and Assemblyman Maurice Hinchey.\" Rep. L0134, New York State Archives</ref>\n\nData showed unacceptable levels of toxic vapors associated with more than 80 compounds were emanating from the basements of numerous homes in the first ring directly adjacent to the Love Canal. Ten of the most prevalent and most toxic compounds - including benzene, a known human carcinogen - were selected for evaluation purposes and as indicators of the presence of other chemical constituents.<ref>Thomas, Lewis, M.D. \"Report of the Governor's Panel to Review Scientific Studies and the Development of Public Policy on Problems Resulting from Hazardous Wastes.\" Albany, N.Y.: Oct. 1980.</ref>\n\nLaboratory analyses of soil and sediment samples from the Love Canal indicate the presence of more than 200 distinct organic chemical compounds; approximately 100 of these have been identified to date.{{As of when|date=November 2017}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health.ny.gov/environmental/investigations/love_canal/lcreport.htm#toxicological|title=Love Canal: A special Report to the Governor & Legislature|website=www.health.ny.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2017-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217143450/https://www.health.ny.gov/environmental/investigations/love_canal/lcreport.htm#toxicological|archive-date=2017-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nNumerous other chemicals seeped through the ground.<ref>New York State Department of Environmental Conservation. \"Hazardous Waste Disposal Sites in New York State: First Annual Report; A Joint Report of the New York State Departments of Environmental Conservation and Health,\" Vol. I-III. Albany, N.Y.: 1980.</ref> Some of the chemicals and toxic materials found included benzene, chloroform, toluene, dioxin, and various kinds of PCB. \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\" rowspan=2|Type of Waste\n!scope=\"col\" rowspan=2|Physical State\n!scope=\"col\" colspan=2|Total Estimated Quantity\n!scope=\"col\" rowspan=2|Container\n|-\n![[Short tons]]\n![[Metric tons]]\n|-\n|Misc. [[Acyl chloride|acid chlorides]] other than benzoyl - includes acetyl, caprylyl, butyryl, nitro benzoyls\n|liquid and solid\n|{{convert|400|ST|t|disp=table|sortable=on}}\n|drum\n|-\n|[[Thionyl chloride]] and misc. sulfur/chlorine compounds\n|liquid and solid\n|{{convert|500|ST|t|disp=table|sortable=on}}\n|drum\n|-\n|Misc. chlorination - includes waxes, oils, [[naphthene]]s, [[aniline]]\n|liquid and solid\n|{{convert|1,000|ST|t|disp=table|sortable=on}}\n|drum\n|-\n|Dodecyl (Lauryl, Lorol) [[Thiol|mercaptans]] (DDM), chlorides and misc. organic sulfur compounds\n|liquid and solid\n|{{convert|2,400|ST|t|disp=table|sortable=on}}\n|drum\n|-\n|[[Trichlorophenol]] (TCP)\n|liquid and solid\n|{{convert|200|ST|t|disp=table|sortable=on}}\n|drum\n|-\n|[[Benzoyl chloride]]s and [[benzotrichloride]]s\n|liquid and solid\n|{{convert|800|ST|t|disp=table|sortable=on}}\n|drum\n|-\n|Metal chlorides\n|solid\n|{{convert|400|ST|t|disp=table|sortable=on}}\n|drum\n|-\n|Liquid [[disulfide]]s (LDS/LDSN/BDS) and [[chlorotoluene]]s\n|liquid\n|{{convert|700|ST|t|disp=table|sortable=on}}\n|drum\n|-\n|[[Hexachlorocyclohexane]] ([[Lindane]]/BHC)\n|solid\n|{{convert|6,900|ST|t|disp=table|sortable=on}}\n|drum and nonmetallic containers\n|-\n|[[Chlorobenzene]]s\n|liquid and solid\n|{{convert|2,000|ST|t|disp=table|sortable=on}}\n|drum and nonmetallic containers\n|-\n|[[Benzylchloride]]s - includes [[benzyl chloride]], [[benzyl alcohol]], benzyl thiocyanate\n|solid\n|{{convert|2,400|ST|t|disp=table|sortable=on}}\n|drum\n|-\n|[[Sodium hydrosulfide|Sodium sulfide/sulfhydrates]]\n|solid\n|{{convert|2,000|ST|t|disp=table|sortable=on}}\n|drum\n|-\n|Misc. 10% of above\n| \n|{{convert|2,000|ST|t|disp=table|sortable=on}}\n| \n|-\n| \n|align=\"right\"|TOTAL\n|{{convert|21,800|ST|t|disp=table|sortable=on}}\n| \n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" |*Interagency Task Force on Hazardous Wastes, Draft Report on Hazardous Waste Disposal in Erie and Niagara Counties, New York, March 1979\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Chemical\n!Water & Leachate\n!Air\n!Soil & Sediment\n|-\n|[[Benzene]]\n|ID**\n|{{convert|522.7|\u00b5g/m3|oz/cuin|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|<{{convert|0.1-0.8|\u00b5g/kg|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|-\n|\u03b1-Benzene Hexachloride\n|{{convert|3.2|\u00b5g/l|oz/cuin|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|0.002-0.1|\u00b5g/m3|oz/cuin|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|ID\n|-\n|\u03b2-Benzene Hexachloride\n|{{convert|38|\u00b5g/l|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|3|\u00