\n|{{convert|0.1-0.1|\u00b5g/l|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|334|\u00b5g/m3|oz/cuin|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n| \n|-\n|[[Polychlorinated biphenyl]] (PCB)\n|{{convert|0.64|mg/l|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n| \n|2-6 [[parts per million|ppm]]\n|-\n|[[Methylene Chloride]]\n|<{{convert|0.3-0.3|\u00b5g/l|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|<{{convert|0.7-11.6|\u00b5g/m3|oz/cuin|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|-\n|Bis (2-ethylhexyl) Phthalate\n|{{convert|8.1-24|\u00b5g/l|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" |* These analyses are a summation of work performed by the Toxicology Institute, Division of Laboratories and Research, New York State Department of Health and various laboratories of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and their subcontractors.\n<nowiki/>** ID \u2013 Identified but not quantified\n\nug/l \u2013 microgram per liter\n\nug/m<sup>3</sup> \u2013 microgram per cubic meter\n|}\n\n=== Consequences ===\n==== Activism ====\n[[File:Love Canal protest.jpg|thumb|right|upright|A protest by Love Canal residents, ca. 1978.]]\nIn 1976, two reporters for the ''[[Niagara Gazette|Niagara Falls Gazette]]'', David Pollak and David Russell, tested several [[sump pump]]s near Love Canal and found toxic chemicals in them. The ''Gazette'' published reports, once in October 1976 and once in November 1976, of chemical analyses of residues near the old Love Canal dumpsite indicated presence of 15 organic chemicals, including three toxic chlorinated hydrocarbons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.buffalo.edu/specialcollections/lovecanal/about/chronology.php|title=Love Canal Chronologies - Love Canal Collections - University Archives - University at Buffalo Libraries|website=library.buffalo.edu|access-date=2017-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222185203/http://library.buffalo.edu/specialcollections/lovecanal/about/chronology.php|archive-date=2017-02-22|url-status=dead}}</ref> The matter became quiet for more than a year and was then revived by reporter Michael Brown, who then investigated potential health effects by performing an informal door-to-door survey during early 1978, writing a hundred news items on toxic wastes in the area and finding birth defects and many anomalies such as enlarged feet, heads, hands, and legs. He advised the local residents to create a protest group, which was organized by resident Karen Schroeder, whose daughter had many (about a dozen) birth defects. The New York State Health Department investigated and found an abnormal incidence of miscarriages. Brown discovered the size of the canal, the presence of dioxin, the expanding contamination, and the involvement, to an extent, of the U.S. Army. Hooker threatened to sue him and he fought the firm tooth and nail for years, including on the Today Show. His book on toxic wastes, Laying Waste: The Poisoning of America By Toxic Chemicals (Pantheon), was the first written on the subject of toxic wastes and created a national firestorm, as did articles of his in The New York Times Magazine and The Atlantic Monthly. He also discovered a massive dump called the Hyde Park landfill (or Bloody Run) and the \"S-Area,\" which was leaking into the water supply for Niagara Falls. His work inspired many activists. He spoke for ten years on the college lecture circuit.\n\nBy 1978, Love Canal had become a national media event with articles referring to the neighborhood as \"a public health time bomb\", and \"one of the most appalling environmental tragedies in American history\".<ref name=\"epa1\" />  Brown, working for the local newspaper, the ''Niagara Gazette'', is credited with not only revealing the case, but establishing toxic chemical wastes as a nationwide issue as well.  Brown's book, ''Laying Waste'', examined the Love Canal disaster and many other toxic waste catastrophes nationwide.<ref>Brown, Michael, ''Laying Waste:  The Poisoning of America by Toxic Chemicals.''  New York:  Washington Square Press, 1981, ii.</ref>\n\nThe dumpsite was declared an unprecedented state emergency on August 2, 1978. Brown, who wrote more than a hundred articles concerning the dump, tested the groundwater and later found the dump was three times larger than originally thought, with possible ramifications beyond the original evacuation zone. He was also to discover that toxic [[dioxins and dioxin-like compounds|dioxins]] were there.\n\n=====Activism tactics=====\nActivism at Love Canal was initially organized by community residents Tom Heiser and [[Lois Gibbs]], with Lois Gibbs often serving as spokesperson.  Gibbs' strategies emphasized concerns for children and families of the affected area, with women taking the most prominent public and active roles{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}.  Many men also helped women in these efforts, though not always publicly{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}. Men who were hesitant to oppose Hooker Chemical openly for example, were able to contribute to the movement through increased contributions to family labor in the absence of their activist wives.<ref>''E. Blum, Love Canal Revisited: Race, Class, and Gender in Environmental Activism (2008)''</ref>\n\nIn addition to community organizing and pressuring authorities for appropriate responses, direct-action forms of activism were employed.  Tactics included protests and rallies, which were intentionally timed and planned in an effort to maximize media attention.  Such events included \"controversial\" methods such as mothers protesting while pushing strollers, marching by pregnant women, and children holding protest signs.  Notably, two EPA employees were also held hostage by activists for approximately five hours at the LCHA office, in order to bring their demands to the attention of the federal government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publicintegrity.org/environment/from-homemaker-to-hell-raiser-in-love-canal/|title=From homemaker to hell-raiser in Love Canal|website=Center for Public Integrity|access-date=2019-02-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190224231550/https://publicintegrity.org/environment/from-homemaker-to-hell-raiser-in-love-canal/|archive-date=2019-02-24|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=====Role of community organizations=====\n{{more citations needed|section|date=August 2018}}\nNumerous organizations were formed in response to the crisis at Love Canal, with members' activism emphasizing variously overlapping interests.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kansaspress.ku.edu/978-0-7006-1820-0.html|title=Love Canal Revisited|website=kansaspress.ku.edu|access-date=2018-05-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511081736/https://kansaspress.ku.edu/978-0-7006-1820-0.html|archive-date=2018-05-11|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to the Love Canal Homeowners Association ([[Love Canal#Lois Gibbs and the Love Canal Homeowners' Association|LCHA]]), other major organizations are the Ecumenical Taskforce (ETF), National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP), and the Concerned Love Canal Renters Association (CLCRA). These organizations are often overlooked in the story of Love Canal, according to research by Elizabeth Blum in '[https://kansaspress.ku.edu/978-0-7006-1820-0.html 'Love Canal Revisited']'.\n\nThe Ecumenical Taskforce (ETF) was a religious organization composed of volunteers from the surrounding area. In conjunction with other citizens' groups such as LCHA and LCARA, the ETF used their resources to promote environmental health and gender, class, and racial equality. {{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nThe [[NAACP]] became involved with the Love Canal issue after William Abrams Sr., president of the Niagara Falls chapter drew concerns to his wife's fatal liver failure. Abrams involvement drew attention to racial inequality present in the community and concerns about how this could affect comprehensive relocation efforts. Abrams contacted the regional NAACP director who announced that discrimination against minorities at Love Canal would be met with legal action. This involvement inspired additional support and activism, particularly on behalf of members of the renting community, many of whom were also members of the African-American and immigrant communities at the site. {{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nAnother subgroup of local residents formed the Concerned Love Canal Renters Association (CLCRA). This group's action sought to address the needs of the (largely, but not exclusively, African-American) renter community, whose interests were at times perceived to be in conflict with those of some members of the (predominantly white) property owners represented by the LCHA. {{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nIn 1980 [[Lois Gibbs]] established the Center for Health, Environment, and Justice as a continuation of her activism at Love Canal. {{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n==== Lois Gibbs and the Love Canal Homeowners' Association ====\nOn August 2, 1978, [[Lois Gibbs]], a local mother who called an election to head the Love Canal Homeowners' Association, began to rally homeowners. Her son, Michael Gibbs, began attending school in September 1977. He developed [[epilepsy]] in December, suffered from [[asthma]] and a [[urinary tract infection]], and had a low [[white blood cell]] count,<ref name=\"gibbsheroproj\">{{cite web|url=http://www.heroism.org/class/1970/gibbs.html|title=Heroism Project - 1970s - Lois Gibbs|author=|date=|website=www.heroism.org|access-date=2007-07-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071006195542/http://www.heroism.org/class/1970/gibbs.html|archive-date=2007-10-06|url-status=live}}</ref>{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=26}} all associated with his exposure to the leaking chemical waste. Gibbs had learned from Brown that her neighborhood sat atop the buried chemical waste.<ref name=\"goldman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goldmanprize.org/node/103|title=Goldman Environmental Prize - Lois Gibbs|author=|date=|website=goldmanprize.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007023204/http://www.goldmanprize.org/node/103|archivedate=2007-10-07|df=}}</ref>\n\nDuring the following years, Gibbs organized an effort to investigate community concerns about the health of its residents. She and other residents made repeated complaints of strange odors and \"substances\" that surfaced in their yards. In Gibbs' neighborhood, there was a high rate of unexplained illnesses, miscarriages, and intellectual disability.{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=21}} Basements were often covered with a thick, black substance, and vegetation was dying.  In many yards, the only vegetation that grew were shrubby grasses.<ref>Levine, p.14</ref> Although city officials were asked to investigate the area, they did not act to solve the problem. Niagara Falls mayor Michael O'Laughlin infamously stated that there was \"nothing wrong\" in Love Canal.\n\nWith further investigation, Gibbs discovered the chemical danger of the adjacent canal. This began her organization's two-year effort to demonstrate that the waste buried by Hooker Chemical was responsible for the health problems of local residents. Throughout the ordeal, homeowners' concerns were ignored not only by Hooker Chemical (now a subsidiary of [[Occidental Petroleum]]), but also by members of government. These parties argued that the area's endemic health problems were unrelated to the toxic chemicals buried in the Canal. Since the residents could not prove the chemicals on their property had come from Hooker's disposal site, they could not prove [[legal liability|liability]]. Throughout the legal battle, residents were unable to sell their properties and relocate.\n\n==== Federal response ====\nOn August 7, 1978, United States President [[Jimmy Carter]] announced a federal health emergency, called for the allocation of federal funds, and ordered the Federal Disaster Assistance Agency to assist the City of Niagara Falls to remedy the Love Canal site.{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=28}} This was the first time in American history that emergency funds were used for a situation other than a natural disaster.<ref name=\"epa.gov\">{{cite news|last=Beck|first=Eckardt C.|title=The Love Canal Tragedy|work=EPA Journal|date=January 1979|url=http://www.epa.gov/aboutepa/history/topics/lovecanal/01.htm|accessdate=February 5, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110408141141/http://www.epa.gov/history/topics/lovecanal/01.htm|archive-date=April 8, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>  Carter had trenches built that would transport the wastes to sewers and had home [[sump pump]]s sealed off.{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=28}}\n\n[[United States Congress|Congress]] passed the Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability Act (CERCLA), better known as the [[Superfund]] Act. Love Canal became the first entry on the list.<ref name=\"Depalma\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/03/18/nyregion/love-canal-declared-clean-ending-toxic-horror.html|title=Love Canal Declared Clean, Ending Toxic Horror|last=Depalma|first=Anthony|date=2004-03-18|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=2017-02-16|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217204323/http://www.nytimes.com/2004/03/18/nyregion/love-canal-declared-clean-ending-toxic-horror.html|archive-date=2017-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Superfund|CERCLA]] created a tax on the chemical and petroleum industries and provided broad Federal authority to respond directly to releases or threatened releases of hazardous substances that may endanger public health or the environment. CERCLA also created a [[National Priorities List]], a shortened list of the sites that has priority in cleanup. Love Canal was the first Superfund site on that list. Eventually, the site was cleaned and deleted off the list in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cumulis.epa.gov/supercpad/cursites/csitinfo.cfm?id=0201290|title=EPA Superfund Program: LOVE CANAL, NIAGARA FALLS, NY|last=|first=|date=|website=CERCLA|publisher=[[Environmental Protection Agency]]|access-date=18 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201085600/http://cumulis.epa.gov/supercpad/cursites/csitinfo.cfm?id=0201290|archive-date=1 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Because the Superfund Act contained a \"retroactive liability\" provision, Occidental was held liable for cleanup of the waste even though it had followed all applicable U.S. laws when disposing of it.\n\n==== Health effects ====\nAt first, scientific studies did not conclusively prove the chemicals were responsible for the residents' illnesses yet scientists were divided on the issue, even though eleven known or suspected [[carcinogens]] had been identified, one of the most prevalent being [[benzene]]. Also present was dioxin ([[polychlorinated dibenzodioxins]]) in the water, a very hazardous substance. Dioxin pollution is usually measured in [[parts per trillion]]; at Love Canal, water samples showed dioxin levels of 53 [[parts per billion]] (53,000 parts per trillion).{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=28}} [[Geologist]]s were recruited to determine whether underground [[Swale (geographical feature)|swales]] were responsible for carrying the chemicals to the surrounding residential areas. Once there, chemicals could [[soil contamination|leach]] into [[basement]]s and evaporate into [[Indoor air quality|household air]].\n\nIn 1979, the EPA announced the result of [[blood test]]s which showed high [[white blood cell]] counts, a precursor to [[leukemia]],<ref name=\"epa1\" /> and [[chromosome]] damage in Love Canal residents. 33% of the residents had undergone chromosomal damage. In a typical population, chromosomal damage affects 1% of people.{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=28}} Other studies were unable to find harm.<ref>''Cancer incidence in the Love Canal area.'' Science, v. 212, June 19, 1981: 1404\u20131407. {{pmid|7233229}} \"Data from the New York Cancer Registry show no evidence for higher cancer rates associated with residence near the Love Canal toxic waste burial site in comparison with the entire state outside of New York City.\"</ref><ref>Ember, Lois R. ''Uncertain science pushes Love Canal solutions to political, legal arenas.'' Chemical & Engineering News, v. 58, August 11, 1980: 22\u201329. Relates the chronology of Hooker Chemical Company and the discovery of toxic chemicals at Love Canal and describes the medical research on the former residents to determine the health effects. {{doi|10.1021/cen-v058n032.p022}}</ref><ref>Maugh, Thomas H., 11. ''Health effects of exposure to toxic wastes.'' Science, v. 215, January 29, 1982: 490\u2013493; February 5: 643\u2013647. This two-part series first addresses the question \"Just how hazardous are dumps?\" and then, in \"Biological markers for chemical exposure\", suggests alterations in chromosomes indicate exposure but long term studies will be necessary to determine the severity of effects of health.</ref><ref>''The Risks of living near Love Canal.'' Science, v . 212, August 27, 1982: 808\u2013809, 811. {{doi|10.1126/science.7100924}} {{pmid|7100924}} \"Controversy and confusion follow a report that the Love Canal area is no more hazardous than areas elsewhere in Niagara Falls.\"</ref><ref>[https://digital.library.unt.edu/govdocs/crs//data/1983/upl-meta-pcc-1156152365knordstr_nt104619_unt/83-160L_1983Aug12.pdf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081031163405/http://digital.library.unt.edu/govdocs/crs//data/1983/upl-meta-pcc-1156152365knordstr_nt104619_unt/83-160L_1983Aug12.pdf |date=2008-10-31 }}\nCongressional Research Service, Report No. 83-160 L, LIABILITY FOR INJURY RESULTING FROM THE DISPOSAL OF HAZARDOUS WASTE: Preliminary Bibliography on the 1983-1984, Intercollegiate Debate Resolution, August 12, 1983</ref> The [[United States National Research Council]] (NRC) surveyed Love Canal health studies during 1991. The NRC noted the major exposure of concern was the groundwater rather than drinking water; the groundwater \"seeped into basements\" and then resulted in exposure through air and soil<ref name=\"NRC1991\" />{{rp|196}} noted several studies reported higher levels of low-birth weight babies and birth defects among the exposed residents<ref name=\"NRC1991\">National Research Council, Committee on Environmental Epidemiology, [http://www.nap.edu/catalog.php?record_id=1802 Environmental Epidemiology, vol. 1: Public Health and Hazardous Wastes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218015704/http://www.nap.edu/catalog.php?record_id=1802 |date=2012-02-18 }} (Washington: National Academy Press, 1991)</ref>{{rp|190\u201391}} with some evidence the effect subsided after the exposure was eliminated.<ref name=\"NRC1991\" />{{rp|165}} The National Research Council also noted a study which found exposed children were found to have an \"excess of seizures, learning problems, hyperactivity, eye irritation, skin rashes, abdominal pain, and incontinence\" and stunted growth.<ref name=\"NRC1991\" />{{rp|196}} [[Vole]]s in the area were found to have significantly increased mortality compared to controls (mean life expectancy in exposed animals \"23.6 and 29.2 days, respectively, compared to 48.8 days\" for control animals).<ref name=\"NRC1991\" />{{rp|215}} New York State also has an ongoing health study of Love Canal residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.health.state.ny.us/environmental/investigations/love_canal/|title=Love Canal|author=|date=|website=www.health.state.ny.us|access-date=2007-08-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814095537/http://www.health.state.ny.us/environmental/investigations/love_canal/|archive-date=2007-08-14|url-status=live}}</ref> In that year, the Albert Elia Building Co., Inc., now Sevenson Environmental Services, Inc., was selected as the principal contractor to re-bury safely the toxic waste at the Love Canal Site.\n\nAccording to the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) in 1979, residents exhibited a \"disturbingly high rate of [[miscarriage]]s ... Love Canal can now be added to a growing list of environmental disasters involving toxics, ranging from industrial workers stricken by [[anxiety disorder|nervous disorders]] and [[cancer]]s to the discovery of toxic materials in the milk of nursing mothers.\" In one case, two out of four children in a single Love Canal family had [[Congenital disorder|birth defects]]; one girl was born [[hearing impairment|deaf]] with a [[cleft palate]], an extra row of teeth, and slight [[mental retardation|retardation]], and a boy was born with an eye defect.<ref name=epa1>{{cite web|url=https://archive.epa.gov/epa/aboutepa/love-canal-tragedy.html|title=The Love Canal Tragedy|first=US|last=EPA, OA, OEAEE, OWC|date=|website=archive.epa.gov|access-date=2017-04-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610141257/https://archive.epa.gov/epa/aboutepa/love-canal-tragedy.html|archive-date=2017-06-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Aftermath ===\n[[File:Love Canal (5621742089).jpg|thumb|Love Canal residents discuss revitalizing their contaminated neighborhood with EPA Administrator [[Lee M. Thomas]] in 1985.]]\nWhen Eckhardt C. Beck (EPA Administrator for Region 2, 1977 \u2013 1979) visited Love Canal during the late 1970s, he discerned the presence of toxic substances in the community:\n\n{{quote|I visited the canal area at that time. Corroding waste-disposal drums could be seen breaking up through the grounds of backyards. Trees and gardens were turning black and dying. One entire swimming pool had been popped up from its foundation, afloat now on a small sea of chemicals. Puddles of noxious substances were pointed out to me by the residents. Some of these puddles were in their yards, some were in their basements, others yet were on the school grounds. Everywhere the air had a faint, choking smell. Children returned from play with burns on their hands and faces.<ref name=epa1 />}}\n\nRobert Whalen, then-New York's Health Commissioner, also visited Love Canal and believed that the Canal constituted an emergency, stating: \"Love Canal Chemical Waste Landfill constitutes a public nuisance and an extremely serious threat and danger to the health, safety and welfare of those using it, living near it or exposed to the conditions emanating from it, consisting among other things, of chemical wastes lying exposed on the surface in numerous places pervasive, pernicious and obnoxious chemical vapors and fumes affecting both the ambient air and the homes of certain residents living near such sites.\"{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=27}} Whalen also instructed people to avoid going into their basements as well as to avoid fruits and vegetables grown in their gardens.  People became very worried because many had consumed produce from their gardens for several years.<ref>Levine, p.29</ref> Whalen urged that all pregnant women and children under the age of two be removed from Love Canal as soon as possible.\n\nThe 99th Street School, on the other hand, was located within the former boundary of the Hooker Chemical landfill site. The school was closed and demolished, but both the school board and the chemical company refused to accept liability. The 93rd Street School was closed some two years later because of concerns about seeping toxic waste.\n\n==== Evacuation ====\nThe lack of public interest in Love Canal made matters worse for the homeowners' association, which was opposed by two organizations that sought to disprove negligence. Initially, members of the association had been frustrated by the lack of a public entity that could advise and defend them. Gibbs met with public resistance from a number of residents within the community. Eventually, the federal government relocated more than 800 families and reimbursed them for the loss of their homes. The state government and federal government used $15 million to purchase 400 homes closest to Love Canal and demolished several rings of houses. {{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n==== Litigation and compensation ====\nIn 1994, Federal District Judge [[John Thomas Curtin|John Curtin]] ruled that Hooker/Occidental had been [[Negligence|negligent]], but not reckless, in its handling of the waste and sale of the land to the [[Niagara Falls School Board]].<ref>U.S. v. Hooker Chemicals and Plastics Corp., 850 Federal Supplement, 993 (W.D.N.Y., 1994)</ref> Curtin's decision also contains a detailed history of events leading up to the Love Canal disaster. [[Occidental Petroleum]] was sued by the EPA and in 1995 agreed to pay $129 million in restitution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usdoj.gov/opa/pr/Pre_96/December95/638.txt.html|title=Occidental to pay $129 Million in Love Canal Settlement|date=December 21, 1995|publisher=U.S. Department of Justice|accessdate=2007-02-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060930023208/http://www.usdoj.gov/opa/pr/Pre_96/December95/638.txt.html|archive-date=September 30, 2006|url-status=live}}</ref> Out of that federal lawsuit came money for a small health fund and $3.5 million for the state health study.<ref name=\"justice.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/archive/opa/pr/Pre_96/December95/638.txt.html|title=#638 Occidental to pay $129 million in Love Canal settlement|website=www.justice.gov|access-date=2017-02-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217142819/https://www.justice.gov/archive/opa/pr/Pre_96/December95/638.txt.html|archive-date=2017-02-17|url-status=live}}</ref> Residents' lawsuits were also settled in the years following the Love Canal disaster.{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=29}}\n\nThe Department of Justice published a report noting that the sites have been successfully remediated and are ready again for use. The Love Canal Area Revitalization Authority sold a few abandoned homes to private citizens. Virtually all remedial activities of the site, other than the operation of the [[leachate]] collection system, were completed by 1989.<ref name=\"justice.gov\" /> [[File:Abandoned Streets in Love Canal.jpg|thumb|Abandoned streets on the west side of Love Canal.]]\n\n==== Remediation ====\n[[File:Looking down 99th Street in Love Canal.jpg|thumb|Looking down 99th Street in Love Canal.]]\nHouses in the residential areas on the east and west sides of the canal were demolished. All that remains on the west side are abandoned residential streets. Some older east side residents, whose houses stand alone in the demolished neighborhood, chose to stay. It was estimated that fewer than 90 of the original 900 families opted to remain.{{sfn|Blum|2008|p=28}} They were willing to remain as long as they were guaranteed that their homes were in a relatively safe area.<ref name=\"Levine, p.215\">Levine, p. 215</ref> On June 4, 1980, the [[Government of New York|state government]] founded the Love Canal Area Revitalization Agency (LCARA) to restore the area. The area north of Love Canal became known as Black Creek Village.  LCARA wanted to resell 300 homes that had been bought by New York when the residents were relocated.<ref name=\"Levine, p.215\"/>  The homes are farther away from where the chemicals were dumped. The most toxic area ({{convert|16|acre|m2}}) was reburied with a thick plastic liner, clay and dirt.  A {{convert|2.4|m||adj=on}} high barbed wire fence was installed around the area.<ref name=\"Jordan, Michael 2003, p.108\">Jordan, Michael, ''Hush Hush: The Dark Secrets of Scientific Research''. Buffalo: Firefly Books, 2003, p.108.</ref> It has been calculated that 248 separate chemicals, including {{convert|60|kg}} of dioxin, have been unearthed from the canal.<ref name=\"Jordan, Michael 2003, p.108\"/>\n\n==== Analysis ====\nIn 1998, Dr. [[Elizabeth Whelan]], founder of industry advocacy group [[American Council on Science and Health]], wrote an editorial about the Canal in which she stated that the media started calling the Canal a \"public health time bomb\", an editorial that created minor hysteria. She declared that people were not falling ill because of exposure to chemical waste, but from stress caused by the media.<ref name=\"Jordan, Michael 2003, p.108\"/>  Besides double the rate of birth defects to children born while living on Love Canal, a follow-up study two decades after the incident \"showed increased risks of low birth weight, congenital malformations and other adverse reproductive events\".<ref name=\"Love Canal Follow-up Health Study\">{{cite web |url=http://www.health.ny.gov/environmental/investigations/love_canal/docs/report_public_comment_final.pdf |title=Love Canal Follow-Up Health Study - Final Report |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2019-07-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815144855/https://www.health.ny.gov/environmental/investigations/love_canal/docs/report_public_comment_final.pdf |archive-date=2019-08-15 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nLove Canal, along with [[Times Beach, Missouri]] and the [[Valley of the Drums|Valley of the Drums, Kentucky]], are important in [[Environmental movement in the United States|United States environmental history]] as three sites that significantly contributed to the passing of the [[Superfund|CERCLA]]. Love Canal \"become the symbol for what happens when hazardous industrial products are not confined to the workplace but 'hit people where they live' in inestimable amounts\".<ref>Levine, p.218</ref>\n\nLove Canal was not an isolated case. Eckardt C. Beck suggested that there are probably hundreds of similar dumpsites.<ref name=\"epa.gov\"/> President Carter declared that discovering these dumpsites was \"one of the grimmest discoveries of the modern era\".<ref name=\"epa.gov\"/> Had the residents of Love Canal been aware that they were residing on toxic chemicals, most would not have moved there in the first place. Beck noted that one main problem remains that ownership of such chemical companies can change over the years, making liability difficult to assign (a problem that would be addressed by CERCLA, or the Superfund Act).<ref name=\"epa.gov\"/>  Beck contended that increased commitment was necessary to develop controls that would \"defuse future Love Canals\".<ref name=\"epa.gov\"/>\n\nThe [[free market environmentalist]] activists have often cited the Love Canal incident as a consequence of government decision-makers not taking responsibility for their decisions. Stroup writes, \"The school district owning the land had a laudable but narrow goal: it wanted to provide education cheaply for district children. Government decision makers are seldom held accountable for broader social goals in the way that private owners are by liability rules and potential profits.\"<ref name=Stroup>{{citation|url=http://www.nesgeorgia.org/files/free_market_environmentalism.pdf|author=Stroup, Richard|title=Free-Market Environmentalism|publisher=The Library of Economics and Liberty|access-date=2010-08-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405015942/http://www.nesgeorgia.org/files/free_market_environmentalism.pdf|archive-date=2016-04-05|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Conclusion===\nIn 2004, federal officials announced that the Superfund cleanup has ended, albeit cleanup had concluded years prior.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=TPwhvm4DfdwC&pg=PT182&lpg=PT182&dq=2004+love+canal#v=onepage&q=2004%20love%20canal&f=false|title=Love Canal|last=JD|first=Penelope Ploughman PhD|date=2013-03-25|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=9781439641996|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=2GURDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT297&lpg=PT297&dq=2004+love+canal#v=onepage&q=2004%20love%20canal&f=false|title=Love Canal: A Toxic History from Colonial Times to the Present|last=Newman|first=Richard S.|date=2016-04-12|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780190262846|language=en}}</ref> The entire process occurred over 21 years and costed a total of $400 million.<ref name=\"Depalma\"/> About 260 homes north of the canal have been renovated and sold to new owners, and about {{convert|150|acre|}} east of the canal have been sold to commercial developers for light industrial uses. In total, 950 families had been evacuated. The site was removed from the Superfund list on September 30, 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.epa.gov/epapages/newsroom_archive/newsreleases/40a7e32b0bbe56018525712a006fca02.html|title=09/30/2004: EPA Removes Love Canal from Superfund List|website=archive.epa.gov|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170506021249/https://archive.epa.gov/epapages/newsroom_archive/newsreleases/40a7e32b0bbe56018525712a006fca02.html|archive-date=2017-05-06|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Controversies related to moved Love Canal waste and reports of illness ===\nThe Niagara Sanitation landfill covers {{convert|18.7|acre|}} in [[Wheatfield, New York]].  The state Department of Transportation moved approximately {{convert|1,600|cuyd|}} of material from the Love Canal landfill to Niagara Sanitation. Residents of [[North Tonawanda]] and Wheatfield suffering severe health problems say the waste was subsequently disturbed during the construction of the LaSalle Expressway in Niagara Falls. The New York Department of Environmental Conservation (DEC) contends there is no proof the landfill leaks. A lawsuit asserts that Hooker's creation of a brine pipeline along the edge of the landfill used to move brine from Wyoming County to its Niagara Falls plant location, may have created a conduit for the landfilled waste to leak out.<ref>[http://buffalonews.com/2017/04/03/draft-landfill-lawsuit/ Residents feel 'trapped' by Wheatfield landfill, once home to Love Canal waste] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822120106/http://buffalonews.com/2017/04/03/draft-landfill-lawsuit/ |date=2017-08-22 }} by Thomas J. Prohaska, ''Buffalo Evening News'', Published Mon, Apr 3, 2017</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nThe legacy of the disaster inspired a fictionalized 1982 made-for-TV film entitled ''Lois Gibbs and the Love Canal''. An award-winning documentary by [[Lynn Corcoran]] entitled ''[[In Our Own Backyard]]'' was released in the U.S. in 1983.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bullfrogfilms.com/catalog/lc.html |title=In Our Own Backyard &#124; Bullfrog Films: 1-800-543-3764: Environmental DVDs and Educational DVDs |publisher=Bullfrog Films |date= |accessdate=2019-07-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716212647/http://www.bullfrogfilms.com/catalog/lc.html |archive-date=2019-07-16 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Modern Marvels]]'' retold the disaster in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.epa.gov/region1/education/pdfs/GREENModule1VideoLinks.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-09-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120709232337/http://www.epa.gov/region1/education/pdfs/GREENModule1VideoLinks.pdf |archive-date=2012-07-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Joyce Carol Oates]] included the story of Love Canal in her 2004 novel ''[[The Falls (Oates novel)|The Falls]]'', but changed the time period of the disaster to the 1960s. The latest history of Love Canal, ''Love Canal: A Toxic History From Colonial Times To The Present'', written by Richard S. Newman, was published by Oxford University Press in 2016.\n\nThe movie ''[[Tootsie]]'' has a character (played by [[Bill Murray]]) attempting to produce a play called \"Return to Love Canal\". In response to the pitch for the play, [[Sydney Pollack]] tells [[Dustin Hoffman]] that \"Nobody wants to produce a play about a couple that moved back to Love Canal. Nobody wants to pay twenty dollars to see people living next to chemical waste. They can see that in [[New Jersey]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0084805/|title=Tootsie|author=Sidney Pollack|date=1982|access-date=2018-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728090352/https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0084805/|archive-date=2018-07-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n\"Love Canal\" was also a segment in the premiere episode of [[Michael Moore]]'s television series ''[[TV Nation]]'', which featured realtors attempting to lure prospective residents to the area.\n\nIn the 1998 [[first-person shooter]] [[video game]], ''[[Blood II: The Chosen]]'', the sixth level of the second episode, which takes place in part of the water system of a housing project built by the villains over a pit of radioactive waste, is named \"Love Canal\" in reference to the disaster.\n\n\"Love Canal\" is the name of a 7\" single released by the [[noise-punk]] band [[Flipper (band)|Flipper]] in February 1981. The lyrics are about the disaster.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/grunge-is-dirt-43364/ |title=Grunge is dirt. |author=Mark Arm |date=8 September 2006 |website=www.uncut.co.uk |publisher=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |accessdate=31 January 2020 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917082912/http://www.uncut.co.uk/features/grunge-is-dirt-43364 |archivedate=17 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[102nd Street chemical landfill]], a landfill located immediately to the south of Love Canal.\n* [[Cancer Alley]] (in Louisiana)\n* [[Landfills in the United States]]\n* [[Spring Valley, Washington, D.C.]]\n* [[Times Beach, Missouri]]\n* [[Valley of the Drums]]\n* [[Centralia, Pennsylvania]] and its [[Centralia mine fire|mine fire]]\n* [[William Ginsberg]], member of New York State task force investigating Love Canal in 1979, and author of state report.\n* ''[[The Killing Ground (film)|The Killing Ground]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book|last=Blum|first=Elizabeth D.|title=Love Canal Revisited : Race, Class, and Gender in Environmental Activism\n|publisher=University Press of Kansas|year=2008|location=Kansas|isbn=978-0-7006-1560-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Colten|first1=Craig E.|last2=Skinner|first2=Peter N.|title=The Road to Love Canal: Managing Industrial Waste Before EPA|location=Austin|publisher=University of Texas Press|year=1996|ref=harv|isbn=0292711824|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/roadtolovecanalm0000colt}}\n*{{cite book|last=Levine|first=Adeline Gordon|title=Love Canal: Science, Politics and People|location=Lexington, MA|publisher=D.C. Heath and Company|year=1982|isbn=978-0-669-05411-8|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/lovecanalscience0000levi}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Love Canal}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100613105310/http://library.buffalo.edu/lovecanal/ Love Canal Collections in the University Archives], University at Buffalo Libraries\n* [http://purl.org/net/findingaids/view?docId=ead/bechs/bechs_c94_2.xml Adeline Levine Love Canal Papers] at The [[Buffalo History Museum]]\n* [http://www.lcmf.org/ Love Canal Medical Fund, Inc.]\n* [http://www.nyheritage.org/collections/love-canal-images New York Heritage: Love Canal Images]\n*[https://www.health.ny.gov/environmental/investigations/love_canal/docs/report_public_comment_final.pdf 2008 Follow Up Study]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Love Canal| ]]\n[[Category:Canals in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Disasters in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Environmental issues in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Environmental controversies]]\n[[Category:Environmental disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:Health disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:Former landfills in the United States]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Niagara Falls, New York]]\n[[Category:Pollution in the United States]]\n[[Category:Superfund sites in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Waste disposal incidents in the United States]]\n[[Category:Environmental disaster ghost towns]]\n[[Category:1978 in the environment]]\n[[Category:Urban decay in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Love_Canal"}
{"title_page": "Feudal earldom", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2019}}\nA '''feudal earldom''' is a [[Scotland|Scottish]] feudal title that is held ''en baroneum'', which means that its holder, who is called a feudal earl, is also always a [[Scottish feudal barony|feudal baron]].  A feudal earldom is an ancient title of [[nobility]] in Scotland. The holder may or may not be a [[Lord of Regality]], which meant that the holder was appointed by [[the Crown]] and had the power of \"pit and gallows\", meaning the power to authorise the death sentence. A feudal earl ranks above a feudal lord and a feudal baron (being a feudal baron of a higher degree), but below an earldom which is a title in the [[Peerage of Scotland]]. Feudal earldoms are very rare.<ref>http://www.baronage.co.uk/2003a/fbandml.pdf</ref> As well, due to rights granted from ancient Scots law, in a very few instances, the holder of a feudal earldom may be different than the holder of a peerage title of the same name.  A peer is invariably addressed as 'Lord Placename' or 'Lord Such-and-so', whilst those holding a feudal earldom are addressed 'Earl of Placename'. Scottish titles, in order of precedence, are as follows: Duke, Marquis, Earl, Viscount, Lord, Baronet, Knight, feudal Baron, Clan Chief, Esquire/Gentleman. Wallace states that \"Lordships, [[Feudal Earldom|Earldoms]], Marquisates and Dukedoms differ only in name from Baronies\" but continues \"one whose property was erected into a Lordship ranked before a simple Baron\" and \"A person to whom an Earldom belonged, would be superior to a person who had no more than a lordship ... One, whose lands were incorporated into a Marquisate, was superior to both ... A man, who owned a fief elevated into a Dukedom, was exulted above all three.\" <ref>Ancient Peerages, 2nd Edition, Edinburgh, 1785, pp 127-130</ref> However, [[James Dalrymple, 1st Viscount of Stair|Lord Stair]] states that Lordships or Earldoms are \"but more noble titles of a Barony\".<ref>Institutes, II.3.45</ref>\n\n==Modern status==\nIn 2014 the Lord Lyon King of Arms issued the \"Note on the Petition of George Menking\", under which he determined to accept petitions for the grant arms for feudal dignities including Earldoms since such dignities have historically always been of the genus of a barony and as such represent a higher form of barony and fall within the jurisdiction of the King of Arms.\n\nThe Menking Note is considered an important change (and return to similar status of an earlier Lord Lyon) from an interim ruling on the petition in 2010 by a Swiss national Willi Ernst Sturzenegger, who had purchased the feudal Earldom of Arran, and wished to be titled as \" 'Sturzenegger of Arran, holder of the territorial Earldom of Arran\", or  'Sturzenegger of Arran, holder of the feudal Earldom of Arran'. In 2006, an earlier Lord Lyon had recognised three petitioners as \"Feudal Countess of Crawfurd-Lindsay\", \"Feudal Earl of Breadalbane\" and \"Feudal Earl of Rothes\". In the ruling in 2010, the Lord Lyon stated that as a general rule previous decisions should be followed, but he could not agree with them as the arguments in the previous cases did not appear to have been tested and no reasoning had been given by the prior Lord Lyon for his decisions. The title \"feudal Earl\", \"territorial Earl\", or simply \"Earl\", being used or recognised in respect of an assemblage of lands into an earldom had never existed until recently. He stated that while the ''Abolition of Feudal Tenure Act of 2000'' divorced feudal baronies from land title, it preserved the title of baron. This was not the case he found with \"territorial\" or \"feudal earldoms\": \"On the contrary there is a clear break between the type of territorial earldoms which existed before the evolution of a personal peerage, and the later erection of lands into what has been termed a \u201cterritorial earldom\u201d. I therefore do not accept that it follows from the recognition of a feudal baron, or one possessed of the dignity of a former feudal barony, as \u201cBaron of X\u201d, that the person in possession of a \u201cterritorial earldom\u201d stemming from the erection by the Crown of lands into a free earldom, should be recognised as an \u201cEarl\u201d or \u201cCountess\u201d, \u201cfeudal\u201d or otherwise.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf|title = Lyon Court Note|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181027/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf|archive-date = 3 March 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nUnder the 2014 Menking Note, the Lord Lyon effectively revoked the 2010 restrictions on recognition of such dignities and customary title as long provided to those properly holding them. \n\n==See also==\nSee also [[Peerage of Scotland]] and [[List of feudal baronies]].\n\n==List of Feudal Earldoms (created before 1707)==\nBelow is an incomplete list of Scottish feudal earldoms created in Scotland before 1707.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Feudal earldom!!County!!Date created<sup>a</sup>!!Claimant/Holder!!Date succeeded!!Arms\n|-\n|[[Earl of Arran (Scotland)|Arran]]||[[Ayrshire]]|| ||Claimant: Herr Willi Ernst Sturzenegger; \"Petition of date 10th February 2006 brought by Willi Ernst Sturzenegger of Arran, designing himself as \"Feudal Earl of Arran\", in which he seeks official recognition \"in the name, style and dignity of Willi Ernst Sturzenegger of Arran, Feudal Earl of Arran\" with appropriate heraldic additaments\" refused by Lord Lyon King of Arms 8 October 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |title=Decision of  Lord Lyon King of Arms \"Skye, 8 October 2009\" |access-date=10 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181027/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>In 2010 the Lord Lyon [[King of Arms]] issued an interlocutor holding that the title \"feudal earl\" cannot be recognised, and has no basis in either law or history</ref>||In 1995 he received (from the Duke of Hamilton, by way of sale) \"conveyance to him of All and Whole the Earldom of Arran including the caput thereof which grant can be traced back to an erection by the Crown of lands in unum comitatum\"<ref>Decision of  Lord Lyon King of Arms \"Skye, 8 October 2009\"</ref>||[[File:Arran arms.svg|thumb|200px|Arms of feudal Earls of Arran: ''Argent, a [[lymphad]] with the sails furled proper flagged gules''. These are [[Quartering (heraldry)|quartered]] today with the arms of Hamilton (''Gules, three cinquefoils ermine'') by the [[Duke of Hamilton]]<ref>Debrett's Peerage, 1968, p.528</ref>]]\n|-\n|[[Breadalbane, Scotland|Breadalbane]]||[[Atholl]]||unknown||John Sullivan<ref name=Breadalbane>{{cite web |url=http://www.armorial-register.com/arms-sco/sullivan-j-arms.html |title=The Arms of J. Sullivan of Braemar, Earl of Breadalbane, Lord of Braemar and Kildrummie |work=www.armorial-register.com |accessdate=2017-10-24}}</ref>||2004<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |title=Decision of  Lord Lyon King of Arms \"Skye, 8 October 2009\" |access-date=10 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181027/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|Crawfurd-Lindsay||[[Fife]]||unknown||Abigail Bush Reisinger||2004<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |title=Decision of  Lord Lyon King of Arms \"Skye, 8 October 2009\" |access-date=10 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181027/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|Erroll||[[Aberdeenshire (Errol /Slains)|Tay Estuary Perthshire]]||1452\n|Paul Allan Bell\n|2015\n|-\n|[[Earl of Ormond (Scotland)|Hamilton]] (feudal dukedom)||[[South Lanarkshire]]||1661<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |title=Decision of  Lord Lyon King of Arms \"Skye, 8 October 2009\" |access-date=10 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181027/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>||||\n|-\n|Huntly (feudal marquessate)||[[Aberdeenshire]]||1662<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |title=Decision of  Lord Lyon King of Arms \"Skye, 8 October 2009\" |access-date=10 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181027/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>||||\n|-\n|[[Earl of Nithsdale|Nithsdale]]||[[Dumfriesshire]]||1620||||\n|-\n|[[Earl of Rothes|Rothes]]||[[Moray]]||1458||James Malcolm David Leslie||2005\n|-\n|[[Earl of Wigtown|Wigtown]]||[[Wigtownshire]] ([[Wigtown]])||1341||||\n|}\na: The creation date is the earliest known date for the Earldom and subject to revision\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* Register of the Great Seal of Scotland; \n* Abolition of Feudal Tenure Act, Scotland; \n* Statutes of 1592; \n* Baronetcy Warrants of Charles I.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.baronage.co.uk/2003a/fbandml.pdf The Baronage]\n*[[Knights Templar|www.celticcrossministry.com/]]\n\n[[Category:Earldoms in the Peerage of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Feudalism in Scotland|Earldom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2019}}\nA '''feudal earldom''' is a [[Scotland|Scottish]] feudal title that is held ''en baroneum'', which means that its holder, who is called a feudal earl, is also always a [[Scottish feudal barony|feudal baron]].  A feudal earldom is an ancient title of [[nobility]] in Scotland. The holder may or may not be a [[Lord of Regality]], which meant that the holder was appointed by [[the Crown]] and had the power of \"pit and gallows\", meaning the power to authorise the death sentence. A feudal earl ranks above a feudal lord and a feudal baron (being a feudal baron of a higher degree), but below an earldom which is a title in the [[Peerage of Scotland]]. Feudal earldoms are very rare.<ref>http://www.baronage.co.uk/2003a/fbandml.pdf</ref> As well, due to rights granted from ancient Scots law, in a very few instances, the holder of a feudal earldom may be different than the holder of a peerage title of the same name.  A peer is invariably addressed as 'Lord Placename' or 'Lord Such-and-so', whilst those holding a feudal earldom are addressed 'Earl of Placename'. Scottish titles, in order of precedence, are as follows: Duke, Marquis, Earl, Viscount, Lord, Baronet, Knight, feudal Baron, Clan Chief, Esquire/Gentleman. Wallace states that \"Lordships, [[Feudal Earldom|Earldoms]], Marquisates and Dukedoms differ only in name from Baronies\" but continues \"one whose property was erected into a Lordship ranked before a simple Baron\" and \"A person to whom an Earldom belonged, would be superior to a person who had no more than a lordship ... One, whose lands were incorporated into a Marquisate, was superior to both ... A man, who owned a fief elevated into a Dukedom, was exulted above all three.\" <ref>Ancient Peerages, 2nd Edition, Edinburgh, 1785, pp 127-130</ref> However, [[James Dalrymple, 1st Viscount of Stair|Lord Stair]] states that Lordships or Earldoms are \"but more noble titles of a Barony\".<ref>Institutes, II.3.45</ref>\n\n==Modern status==\nIn 2014 the Lord Lyon King of Arms issued the \"Note on the Petition of George Menking\", under which he determined to accept petitions for the grant arms for feudal dignities including Earldoms since such dignities have historically always been of the genus of a barony and as such represent a higher form of barony and fall within the jurisdiction of the King of Arms.\n\nThe Menking Note is considered an important change (and return to similar status of an earlier Lord Lyon) from an interim ruling on the petition in 2010 by a Swiss national Willi Ernst Sturzenegger, who had purchased the feudal Earldom of Arran, and wished to be titled as \" 'Sturzenegger of Arran, holder of the territorial Earldom of Arran\", or  'Sturzenegger of Arran, holder of the feudal Earldom of Arran'. In 2006, an earlier Lord Lyon had recognised three petitioners as \"Feudal Countess of Crawfurd-Lindsay\", \"Feudal Earl of Breadalbane\" and \"Feudal Earl of Rothes\". In the ruling in 2010, the Lord Lyon stated that as a general rule previous decisions should be followed, but he could not agree with them as the arguments in the previous cases did not appear to have been tested and no reasoning had been given by the prior Lord Lyon for his decisions. The title \"feudal Earl\", \"territorial Earl\", or simply \"Earl\", being used or recognised in respect of an assemblage of lands into an earldom had never existed until recently. He stated that while the ''Abolition of Feudal Tenure Act of 2000'' divorced feudal baronies from land title, it preserved the title of baron. This was not the case he found with \"territorial\" or \"feudal earldoms\": \"On the contrary there is a clear break between the type of territorial earldoms which existed before the evolution of a personal peerage, and the later erection of lands into what has been termed a \u201cterritorial earldom\u201d. I therefore do not accept that it follows from the recognition of a feudal baron, or one possessed of the dignity of a former feudal barony, as \u201cBaron of X\u201d, that the person in possession of a \u201cterritorial earldom\u201d stemming from the erection by the Crown of lands into a free earldom, should be recognised as an \u201cEarl\u201d or \u201cCountess\u201d, \u201cfeudal\u201d or otherwise.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf|title = Lyon Court Note|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181027/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf|archive-date = 3 March 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nUnder the 2014 Menking Note, the Lord Lyon effectively revoked the 2010 restrictions on recognition of such dignities and customary title as long provided to those properly holding them. \n\n==See also==\nSee also [[Peerage of Scotland]] and [[List of feudal baronies]].\n\n==List of Feudal Earldoms (created before 1707)==\nBelow is an incomplete list of Scottish feudal earldoms created in Scotland before 1707.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Feudal earldom!!County!!Date created<sup>a</sup>!!Claimant/Holder!!Date succeeded!!Arms\n|-\n|[[Earl of Arran (Scotland)|Arran]]||[[Ayrshire]]|| ||Claimant: Herr Willi Ernst Sturzenegger; \"Petition of date 10th February 2006 brought by Willi Ernst Sturzenegger of Arran, designing himself as \"Feudal Earl of Arran\", in which he seeks official recognition \"in the name, style and dignity of Willi Ernst Sturzenegger of Arran, Feudal Earl of Arran\" with appropriate heraldic additaments\" refused by Lord Lyon King of Arms 8 October 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |title=Decision of  Lord Lyon King of Arms \"Skye, 8 October 2009\" |access-date=10 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181027/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>In 2010 the Lord Lyon [[King of Arms]] issued an interlocutor holding that the title \"feudal earl\" cannot be recognised, and has no basis in either law or history</ref>||In 1995 he received (from the Duke of Hamilton, by way of sale) \"conveyance to him of All and Whole the Earldom of Arran including the caput thereof which grant can be traced back to an erection by the Crown of lands in unum comitatum\"<ref>Decision of  Lord Lyon King of Arms \"Skye, 8 October 2009\"</ref>||[[File:Arran arms.svg|thumb|200px|Arms of feudal Earls of Arran: ''Argent, a [[lymphad]] with the sails furled proper flagged gules''. These are [[Quartering (heraldry)|quartered]] today with the arms of Hamilton (''Gules, three cinquefoils ermine'') by the [[Duke of Hamilton]]<ref>Debrett's Peerage, 1968, p.528</ref>]]\n|-\n|[[Breadalbane, Scotland|Breadalbane]]||[[Atholl]]||unknown||John Sullivan<ref name=Breadalbane>{{cite web |url=http://www.armorial-register.com/arms-sco/sullivan-j-arms.html |title=The Arms of J. Sullivan of Braemar, Earl of Breadalbane, Lord of Braemar and Kildrummie |work=www.armorial-register.com |accessdate=2017-10-24}}</ref>||2004<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |title=Decision of  Lord Lyon King of Arms \"Skye, 8 October 2009\" |access-date=10 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181027/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|Crawfurd-Lindsay||[[Fife]]||unknown||Abigail Bush Reisinger||2004<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |title=Decision of  Lord Lyon King of Arms \"Skye, 8 October 2009\" |access-date=10 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181027/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|Erroll||[[Aberdeenshire (Errol /Slains)|Tay Estuary Perthshire]]||1452\n|Paul Allan Bell\n|2015\n|-\n|[[Earl of Ormond (Ireland)|Hamilton]] (feudal dukedom)||[[South Lanarkshire]]||1661<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |title=Decision of  Lord Lyon King of Arms \"Skye, 8 October 2009\" |access-date=10 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181027/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>||||\n|-\n|Huntly (feudal marquessate)||[[Aberdeenshire]]||1662<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |title=Decision of  Lord Lyon King of Arms \"Skye, 8 October 2009\" |access-date=10 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303181027/http://www.lyon-court.com/lordlyon/files/WES%20Note.pdf |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>||||\n|-\n|[[Earl of Nithsdale|Nithsdale]]||[[Dumfriesshire]]||1620||||\n|-\n|[[Earl of Rothes|Rothes]]||[[Moray]]||1458||James Malcolm David Leslie||2005\n|-\n|[[Earl of Wigtown|Wigtown]]||[[Wigtownshire]] ([[Wigtown]])||1341||||\n|}\na: The creation date is the earliest known date for the Earldom and subject to revision\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* Register of the Great Seal of Scotland; \n* Abolition of Feudal Tenure Act, Scotland; \n* Statutes of 1592; \n* Baronetcy Warrants of Charles I.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.baronage.co.uk/2003a/fbandml.pdf The Baronage]\n*[[Knights Templar|www.celticcrossministry.com/]]\n\n[[Category:Earldoms in the Peerage of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Feudalism in Scotland|Earldom]]\n", "name_user": "Qazyminaz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eList of Feudal Earldoms (created before 1707):Hyperlink now point to the Scottish peerage of the Earls of Ormond and not the Earls of Ormond in the Peerage of Ireland.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feudal_earldom"}
{"title_page": "Rory Stewart", "text_new": "{{For|the Scottish squash player|Rory Stewart (squash player)}}\n{{short description|British Independent politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name                = Rory Stewart\n| honorific-suffix    = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|O7yyBE|OBE|FRSL|FRSGS|size=100%}}\n| image               = Rory Stewart MP (cropped).jpg\n| caption             = Stewart in 2015\n| office              = [[Secretary of State for International Development]]\n| primeminister       = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start          = 1 May 2019\n| term_end            = 24 July 2019\n| predecessor         = [[Penny Mordaunt]]\n| successor           = [[Alok Sharma]]\n| office1             = [[Minister of State for Prisons]]\n| primeminister1      = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start1         = 9 January 2018\n| term_end1           = 1 May 2019\n| predecessor1        = [[Sam Gyimah]]\n| successor1          = [[Robert Buckland]]\n| office2             = [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Minister of State for Africa]]\n| primeminister2      = [[Theresa May]]\n| predecessor2        = [[Tobias Ellwood]]\n| successor2          = [[Harriett Baldwin]]\n| term_start2         = 15 June 2017\n| term_end2           = 9 January 2018\n| office3             = [[Department for International Development|Minister of State for International Development]]\n| primeminister3      = [[Theresa May]]\n| predecessor3        = [[Desmond Swayne|Sir Desmond Swayne]]\n| successor3          = [[Harriett Baldwin]]\n| term_start3         = 17 July 2016\n| term_end3           = 9 January 2018\n| office4             = [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]\n| primeminister4      = [[David Cameron]]\n| predecessor4        = [[Dan Rogerson]]\n| successor4          = [[Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Coffey]]\n| term_start4         = 12 May 2015\n| term_end4           = 17 July 2016\n| office5             = [[Defence Select Committee|Chair of the Defence Select Committee]]\n| predecessor5        = [[James Arbuthnot]]\n| successor5          = [[Julian Lewis]]\n| term_start5         = 14 May 2014\n| term_end5           = 12 May 2015\n| office6             = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br/> for [[Penrith and The Border (UK Parliament constituency)|Penrith and The Border]]\n| predecessor6        = [[David Maclean]]\n| successor6          = [[Neil Hudson (politician)|Neil Hudson]]\n| term_start6         = 6 May 2010\n| term_end6           = 6 November 2019\n| birth_name          = Roderick James Nugent Stewart\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1973|01|03}}\n| birth_place         = [[British Hong Kong]]\n| residence           = [[South Kensington]], [[London]], England\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| spouse              = {{marriage|Shoshana Clark|2012}}\n| children            = 2\n| father              = [[Brian Stewart (diplomat)|Brian Stewart]]\n| party               = [[Independent politician|Independent]] (2019\u2013present)\n| otherparty          = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] (2009\u20132019)<br/>[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (before 1993)\n| education           = [[Dragon School]], [[Eton College]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Balliol College, Oxford]]\n| website             = [http://www.roryforlondon.co.uk www.roryforlondon.co.uk]\n| allegiance          = {{flag|United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland}}\n| branch              = {{army|UK}}\n| rank                = [[File:British Army OF-1a.svg|10px]] [[Second Lieutenant]] (on probation)\n| serviceyears        = 1991\u20131992\n| unit                = [[File:Royal Regiment of Scotland TRF.png|23px]] [[Black Watch]]\n}}\n\n'''Roderick James Nugent Stewart''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE|FRSL|FRSGS}} (born 3 January 1973), known as '''Rory Stewart''', is a British diplomat, author, writer and politician. He served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Penrith and The Border (UK Parliament constituency)|Penrith and The Border]] from [[UK general election, 2010|2010]] to [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]] and was [[Secretary of State for International Development|international development secretary]] in 2019.<ref name=Alleg1>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/oct/26/rory-stewart-penrith-tory-seat | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Former royal tutor Rory Stewart selected for safe Tory seat | first=Allegra | last=Stratton | date=26 October 2009 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.penrithandtheborder.org.uk Penrith and the Border Conservatives] Rory Stewart becomes MP for Penrith and the Border</ref> First elected as a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]], Stewart had the [[September 2019 suspension of rebel Conservative MPs|party whip removed in September 2019]] and subsequently sat as an independent.\n\nAfter education at the [[Dragon School]], [[Eton College]] and [[Balliol College, Oxford]], Stewart became a [[diplomat]], working in [[Indonesia]] and [[Montenegro]]. He left the [[Civil Service (United Kingdom)|civil service]] to undertake a two-year walk across [[Afghanistan]], [[Iran]], [[Pakistan]], [[India]] and [[Nepal]]. He later wrote a best-selling book, ''[[The Places in Between]]'', about his experiences. He subsequently served as a deputy governor for the [[Coalition Provisional Authority]] following the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], and wrote a second book covering this period, ''[[The Prince of the Marshes: And Other Occupational Hazards of a Year in Iraq|Occupational Hazards or The Prince of the Marshes]]''. He later lectured at [[Harvard University|Harvard]] and worked for several [[non-governmental organization|non-governmental organisation]]s, including as executive chairman of the [[Turquoise Mountain Foundation]].\n\nIn 2009, Stewart joined the Conservative Party and was selected as the parliamentary candidate for Penrith and The Border. He was elected to the [[House of Commons]] the following year, and was later elected as chair of the [[Defence Select Committee]]. In 2015, he was appointed to the [[Second Cameron ministry|Cameron Government]] as minister for [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]. From 2016 to 2019, Stewart served in the [[First May ministry|May Government]] as [[Department for International Development|international development minister]], [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Africa minister]], and [[Minister of State for Prisons|prisons minister]].<ref name=\"Rory Stewart MP OBE\">{{cite web|title=Rory Stewart MP OBE|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/rory-stewart|website=GOV.UK|publisher=British Government|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref> In 2019, he was promoted to the cabinet as [[Secretary of State for International Development|international development secretary]]. Stewart stood as a candidate for [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|leader of the Conservative Party]] in the [[2019 Conservative Party (UK) leadership election|2019 leadership contest]], finishing fifth.\n\nOn 3 October 2019, Stewart announced he had resigned from the Conservative Party and that he would stand down as an MP at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|next general election]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/04/rory-stewart-resigns-from-conservative-party|title=Rory Stewart resigns from Conservative party|last=Walker|first=Peter|date=4 October 2019|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 October 2019}}</ref> He is now an independent candidate in the [[2021 London mayoral election]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Photograph of Brian Stewart in Malacca in 1953.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Stewart's father, [[Brian Stewart (diplomat)|Brian Stewart]], in 1953]]\nStewart was born in [[British Hong Kong]], the son of [[Brian Stewart (diplomat)|Brian Stewart]] and his wife, Sally Elizabeth Acland Nugent (''n\u00e9e'' Rose). Stewart's father, born in [[Edinburgh]], Scotland, was a colonial official and diplomat who, in the 1970s, was a candidate to become the Chief of the UK's [[Secret Intelligence Service]] or MI6.<ref name=\"NY101108\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/11/15/paths-of-glory-ian-parker|title=Paths of Glory|first=Ian|last=Parker|date=8 November 2010|publisher=|via=www.newyorker.com}}</ref>\n\nHis father's family is from Broich House (built in 1770), which is near [[Crieff]] in [[Perth and Kinross]], Scotland.<ref name=\"satnam\">{{cite news|work=The Times | date=4 December 2013 |last1=Satnam |first1=Sanghera |title=Rory Stewart: Adventurer, academic, MP - PM? |url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/rory-stewart-adventurer-academic-mp-pm/ |accessdate=18 June 2019}}</ref> His maternal grandfather was [[History of the Jews in Britain|Jewish]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/beset-rory-stewart-bagel-boris-johnson-london-mayor-jw3-1.489819|title=Rory Stewart enjoys a bagel and reveals his 'special connection' to the Jewish community|newspaper=The Jewish Chronicle|last=Harpin|first=Lee|date=7 October 2019}}</ref> Stewart spent his early years in [[South Kensington]], London<ref name=\"telegraphKensington\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/0/rory-stewart-boris-complete-chalk-cheese-suspicious-whole-show/|title=Rory Stewart: 'Boris and I are complete chalk and cheese. I\u2019m suspicious of the whole show'|website=The Telegraph|last=Fletcher|first=Martin|date=1 November 2019|access-date=12 January 2020}}</ref> before his family moved to [[Malaysia]]. He returned to Britain for boarding school, being educated at the [[Dragon School]], in Oxford, and [[Eton College]].<ref name=\"NY101108\"/>\n\nAs a teenager, he was a member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/jan/14/rory-stewart-tory-mp-penrith|title=Rory Stewart's awfully big adventure|last=Glover|first=Julian|date=14 January 2010|work=The Guardian|accessdate=22 May 2010|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/11/15/paths-of-glory-ian-parker|title=Paths of Glory|last=Parker|first=Ian|date=7 November 2010|website=The New Yorker|accessdate=12 January 2020|url-access=limited|quote=He had been a member of the Labour Party in his late teens. (A few pounds a year; occasional meetings.)}}</ref> and he has spoken about this in a number of interviews, including on BBC Radio 4's ''Political Thinking'' with [[Nick Robinson (journalist)|Nick Robinson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p07873d3|title=BBC Radio 4 \u2013 Political Thinking with Nick Robinson, The Rory Stewart One|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=18 May 2019}}</ref> During his [[gap year]] in 1991, he was [[commissioned officer|commissioned]] (a short service limited commission) in the [[Black Watch]] for five months as [[second lieutenant]] (on probation).<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=52792 |date=14 January 1992 |page=493 |supp=y}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=52910 |date=5 May 1992 |page=7744 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\nStewart studied [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]] at [[Balliol College, Oxford|Balliol College]], [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]].<ref name=\"NY101108\" /> While a student at Oxford, Stewart was a private tutor to [[Prince William]] and [[Prince Harry]] during the summer.<ref name=\"NY101108\"/>\n\n==Foreign Office==\nAfter graduating, Stewart joined the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]].<ref>[http://rorystewart.co.uk/index.php/about-me/biography Biography] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100120201645/http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/index.php/about-me/biography |date=20 January 2010 }} Rory Stewart</ref> He served in the [[Embassy of the United Kingdom, Jakarta|British embassy in Indonesia]] from 1997 to 1999, working on issues related to [[History of East Timor|East Timor independence]], and was appointed at the age of 26 as the British Representative to [[Montenegro]] in the wake of the [[Kosovo War|Kosovo campaign]].<ref name=\"NY101108\"/>\n\n===Coalition Provisional Authority===\nAfter the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], Stewart became the [[Coalition Provisional Authority]] Deputy Governorate Co-ordinator in [[Maysan]] and Deputy Governorate Co-ordinator/Senior Advisor in [[Dhi Qar]] in 2003, both of which are provinces in [[southern Iraq]].<ref name=\"NY101108\"/> He was posted initially to the KOSB Battlegroup then to the Light Infantry.<ref name=\"Stewart 2007 87\">{{Cite book|title=Occupational Hazards|last=Stewart|first=Rory|publisher=Picador|year=2007|isbn=|location=London|page=87}}</ref> His responsibilities included holding elections, resolving tribal disputes, and implementing development projects.<ref name=\"Stewart 2007 87\"/> He faced growing unrest and an incipient civil war from his base in a [[Civil-Military Co-operation]] (CIMIC) compound in [[Amarah|Al Amarah]], and in May 2004 was in command of his compound in [[Nasiriyah]] when it was besieged by Sadrist militia.<ref name=\"NY101108\"/> He was awarded an OBE for his services during this period.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/rory-stewart-days-of-hope-and-hubris-6097377.html|title=Rory Stewart: Days of hope and hubris|date=23 June 2006|work=The Independent|access-date=6 March 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nWhile Stewart initially supported the [[Iraq War]], the [[Coalition of the willing|international coalition]]'s inability to achieve a more humane, prosperous state led him in retrospect to believe the invasion had been a mistake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harcourtbooks.com/PrinceOfTheMarshes/interview.asp|title=Interview: Rory Stewart|publisher=Harcourt Trade Publishers|accessdate=2 January 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100215051006/http://www.harcourtbooks.com/PrinceOfTheMarshes/interview.asp|archivedate=15 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Suggested links to MI6 ===\nSome have suggested that Stewart was an employee of the [[Secret Intelligence Service]] (MI6), during his time as a British Representative to Montenegro - allegedly being recruited to MI6 shortly after he graduated from Oxford University.<ref name=\"NY101108\"/><ref name=\"Merrick\">Rob Merrick, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/conversative-leadership-elections-brexit-boris-johnson-rory-stewart-no-deal-a8961896.html Tory leadership: Rory Stewart claims 100 Conservative MPs would rebel against Boris Johnson to stop no-deal Brexit] (17 June 2019): \"He was also asked if, as strongly rumoured he was an MI6 spy when working as a diplomat, but replied: 'No.'\"</ref> Stewart has said that his career progression and his father's work for MI6 might \"give the appearance\" that he worked for MI6,<ref>Jon Swain, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/8116481/Rory-Stewart-concedes-career-gives-appearance-that-he-worked-for-MI6.html Rory Stewart concedes career 'gives appearance' that he worked for MI6], ''Telegraph'' (8 November 2010).</ref> but says he did not work for MI6 while a diplomat.<ref name=\"Merrick\" /> Stewart has acknowledged that due to the [[Official Secrets Act 1989|Official Secrets Act]], even if he had worked for MI6, he would not be able to admit if he had.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/06/18/rory-stewart-denies-spy-mi6-admits-prohibited-law-saying-otherwise/|title=Rory Stewart denies being a spy for MI6 - but admits he is prohibited by law from saying otherwise|last=Reporters|first=Telegraph|date=18 June 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=3 September 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Academic, nonprofit, and advisory work==\nIn late 2004, Stewart became a fellow at the [[Carr Center for Human Rights Policy]] at [[Harvard University]]'s [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]], and in July 2008, he was appointed Ryan Family Professor of Human Rights at Harvard and director of the Carr Center.<ref name=\"NY101108\" />  Stewart left his position at Harvard in 2010 in order to campaign for Parliament.<ref>[https://neubauercollegium.uchicago.edu/events/uc/directors_lecture_with_rory_stewart/ Director's Lecture with Rory Stewart], [[University of Chicago Oriental Institute]].</ref> [[W.W. Norton]] published his book ''Can Intervention Work?'' in 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/bookreviews/8811125/Can-Intervention-Work-by-Rory-Stewart-and-Gerald-Knaus-review.html|title=Can Intervention Work? by Rory Stewart and Gerald Knaus: review|last=Oborne|first=Peter|date=10 October 2011|access-date=6 March 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Stewart has frequently been called on to provide advice on Afghanistan and Iraq to policy-makers, particularly in the United States, United Kingdom, and Canada.<ref name=\"NY101108\"/> In an article in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', he was described as an advisor on Afghan issues to [[U.S. Secretary of State]] [[Hillary Clinton]] and the [[United States Special Envoy|U.S. Special Envoy for Afghanistan and Pakistan]] [[Richard Holbrooke]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/6475289/Rory-Stewart-A-new-kind-of-Tory.html|title=Rory Stewart: A new kind of Tory|last=Praagh|first=Anna van|date=1 November 2009|access-date=12 April 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2005, he joined the [[Turquoise Mountain Foundation]], a human development NGO established by [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], and [[Hamid Karzai]], in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/newsandgallery/focus/the_turquoise_mountain_foundation_becomes_the_prince_s_18th__917731594.html|title=The Turquoise Mountain Foundation becomes The Prince's 18th charity|date=25 March 2007|publisher=Prince of Wales|accessdate=28 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701210105/http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/newsandgallery/focus/the_turquoise_mountain_foundation_becomes_the_prince_s_18th__917731594.html|archive-date=1 July 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> For this role he relocated to Kabul for the next three years, working to restore historic buildings in the old city of Kabul, managing its finances, installing water supply, electricity, and establishing a clinic, a school and an institute for traditional crafts.<ref name=\"NY101108\" /> Stewart was awarded the [[Royal Scottish Geographical Society]]'s Livingstone medal in 2009 \"in recognition of his work in Afghanistan and his travel writing, and for his distinguished contribution to geography\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsgs.org/awardsandmedals/|title=Medals and Awards|publisher=Royal Scottish Geographical Society|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212031439/http://www.rsgs.org/awardsandmedals/|archivedate=12 February 2010|url-status=dead|accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> Stewart stepped down as executive chairman of the Turquoise Mountain Foundation in May 2010.<ref>[https://archive.today/20130421075510/http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/index.php/declarations-of-interests Declarations of Interests] Rory Stewart</ref>\n\nStewart served for a time on the board of governors of the International Development Research Centre of Canada.<ref>[Board of Governors: November 02, 2010], International Development Research Centre of Canada.</ref>\n\nIn 2009 Stewart appeared before the [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|Senate Foreign Relations Committee]], arguing that Obama's strategy on Afghanistan was 'trying to do the impossible'. He suggested, in an argument that he would later expand in his [[Ted Talk|TED Talk]], that a heavy American military footprint would be counterproductive, alienating Afghans, and that it would be better to reduce the size of the American Army in Afghanistan. This smaller force, he suggested, would be able to handle al-Qaeda, while helping achieve the West's long-term objectives in the country.<ref name=\"WashPost\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/afghanistan-wasnt-destined-to-fail-heres-how-we-could-have-fought-it-better/2019/12/19/b7d4ef66-21e7-11ea-a153-dce4b94e4249_story.html|title=Perspective {{!}} Afghanistan wasn\u2019t destined to fail. Here\u2019s how we could have fought it better.|last=Jaffe|first=Greg|newspaper=The Washington Post|language=en|date=20 December 2019|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> His ideas were rejected by Senators, including future [[Secretary of state (U.S. state government)|Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]].<ref name=\"WashPost\"/>\n\n== Political career ==\n\n===Member of Parliament===\n\nStewart had considered a parliamentary career in the past but only decided to stand when, in the aftermath of the expenses scandal, David Cameron decided to \"reopen the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidates' list to anybody who wants to apply\". Stewart has said that his experience in Afghanistan made him a \"Burkean conservative\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/11/15/paths-of-glory-ian-parker|title=Paths of Glory|last=Parker|first=Ian|date=7 November 2010|website=The New Yorker|accessdate=12 January 2020|url-access=limited|quote=\u201cThe experience of running this thing in Afghanistan made me a Burkean conservative,\u201d Stewart said.}}</ref> Having never voted for the Conservatives before (though, against his will, his parents cast his proxy vote for them in the [[2001|2001 general election]], when he was abroad),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/11/15/paths-of-glory-ian-parker|title=Paths of Glory|last=Parker|first=Ian|date=7 November 2010|website=The New Yorker|accessdate=12 January 2020|url-access=limited|quote=Stewart had never voted Conservative, except against his will; in 2001, when he was walking in India, his parents cast his proxy vote for the Conservatives, to his dismay.}}</ref> he joined the party in summer 2009.<ref>{{cite we|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/mar/20/new-tories-cameron-conservatives-election|title= Tories 2.0: Cameron's new breed|website=The Guardian|last=Glover|first=Julian|date=20 March 2010|access-date=11 January 2020|quote=In Penrith and the Border, Rory Stewart is one of those stars who is almost certain of election \u2013 an Etonian Harvard professor with an extraordinary life story and lively media career who joined his party only last summer.}}</ref> Stewart tried for selection for the [[Bracknell (UK Parliament constituency)|Bracknell constituency]] in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/berkshire/8312151.stm |title=Residents choose Tory candidate |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=17 October 2009 }}</ref> but the place went to [[Phillip Lee (politician)|Phillip Lee]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://waugh.standard.co.uk/2009/10/rory-stewart-for-pm.html |title=Rory Stewart for PM? |author=Paul Waugh |work=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=25 October 2009 |access-date=30 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028012122/http://waugh.standard.co.uk/2009/10/rory-stewart-for-pm.html |archive-date=28 October 2009 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Stewart was then shortlisted for the [[Penrith and the Border (UK Parliament constituency)|Penrith and The Border constituency]] and, at an open caucus, selected as the candidate on 25 October 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cumberlandnews.co.uk/ex_diplomat_heads_list_to_succeed_penrith_mp_david_maclean_1_620521?referrerPath=home |title=Ex-diplomat heads list to succeed Penrith MP David Maclean |work=Cumberland News |date=7 October 2009 |access-date=18 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224143747/http://www.cumberlandnews.co.uk/ex_diplomat_heads_list_to_succeed_penrith_mp_david_maclean_1_620521?referrerPath=home |archive-date=24 February 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> He was returned as the MP for the constituency on 6 May 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/nol/shared/election2010/results/constituency/d51.stm |title=Election 2010 \u2013 Penrith & the Border |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=6 May 2010 }}</ref> At the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], Stewart almost doubled his majority in Penrith and the Border from 11,241 to 19,894, the highest majority since the seat was created.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/border/2015-05-08/penrith-and-the-border-results/|title=Penrith and the Border: results|work=ITV News|access-date=6 March 2018|language=en}}</ref> In the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]], he received 60.4% of the vote.\n\nUpon joining the House of Commons, Stewart was elected a member of the [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]], serving until 2014. During his tenure on the Committee he was also chair of the trans-Atlantic group [[Le Cercle]] but did not declare his membership.<ref name=\"Johnston\">{{cite news |last1=Johnston |first1=John |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/news/105448/excl-top-tories-face-questions-over-links |title=EXCL Top Tories face questions over links to secretive foreign affairs group |accessdate=6 November 2019 |publisher=PoliticsHome |date=22 July 2019}}</ref> Stewart also served as the chair of the [[APPG]] for [[Mountain Rescue]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://allparty.org/all-party-groups/mountain-rescue |title=Mountain Rescue |publisher=All Party |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921060217/http://allparty.org/all-party-groups/mountain-rescue |date=24 January 2012 |archivedate=21 September 2013 |accessdate=29 August 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/rory-delivers-keynote-speech-at-uks-bi-ennial-mountain-rescue-conference/ |title=Rory delivers keynote speech at UK's bi-ennial Mountain Rescue conference |publisher=Rory Stewart |date=17 September 2012 }}</ref> and the APPG for Local Democracy<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/register/local-democracy.htm |title=Local Democracy |work=Register of All-Party Groups |publisher=[[House of Commons]] |date=30 March 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nalc.gov.uk/Latest_News/Rory_StewartMPleadsnationalcampaignforparishfinancing.aspx |title=Rory Stewart MP leads national campaign for parish financing |publisher=National Association of Local Councils |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130716182547/http://www.nalc.gov.uk/Latest_News/Rory_StewartMPleadsnationalcampaignforparishfinancing.aspx |date=30 April 2013 |archivedate=16 July 2013 |accessdate=19 December 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> and was an officer of the APPG for Rural Services.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/rory-stewart-mp-heralds-fuel-rebate-win-for-rural-areas/|title=RORY STEWART MP HERALDS FUEL REBATE WIN FOR RURAL AREAS \u2013 Rory Stewart|date=2 June 2015|work=Rory Stewart|access-date=6 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> He was elected chair of the [[Defence Select Committee]] in May 2014. He left these positions upon his appointment as environment minister.\n\nIn July 2010, Stewart apologised to his constituents after blogging about the relative poverty of rural areas and need for more public services.<ref name=\"beeb\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cumbria-10757609 |title=Tory MP 'sorry' for twine remark |date=25 July 2010 |work=[[BBC News Online]] |accessdate=26 July 2010 }}</ref> He was quoted in the ''[[Scottish Sun]]'' as saying that \"some areas around here are pretty primitive, people holding up their trousers with bits of [[twine]]\".<ref name=\"beeb\" /> He later said that he was making the point that Cumbria's beauty hides its \u201cpockets of poverty\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/11/15/paths-of-glory-ian-parker|title=Paths of Glory|last=Parker|first=Ian|date=7 November 2010|website=The New Yorker|accessdate=12 January 2020|url-access=limited|quote=This summer, a minor tabloid scandal broke after Stewart was quoted in a paper saying, of his constituency, \u201cSome areas around here are pretty primitive, people holding up their trousers with bits of twine and that sort of thing.\u201d (His point, he later said, was that Cumbria\u2019s beauty is misleading; there are \u201chidden pockets of poverty.\u201d)}}</ref> A light-hearted ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' article, \"In praise of ... binder twine\", whilst acknowledging the \"serious effort\" Stewart had made by \"walking hundreds of miles\" to get to know his constituency, concluded that he had simply underestimated the importance of the \"ubiquitous and indispensable\" twine to the rural community.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/jul/27/in-praise-of-binder-twine |title=In praise of ... binder twine |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=27 July 2010 |accessdate=27 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nHis speech about [[hedgehog]]s in Parliament in 2015 was named by ''[[The Times]]'' and ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' as the best parliamentary speech of 2015 and described by the deputy speaker as \"one of the best speeches [she] had ever heard in Parliament\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2015-11-10/debates/15111048000002/HedgehogConservation?highlight=hedgehog#contribution-15111048002639|title=Hedgehog conservation|date=2015|publisher=Hansard|access-date=22 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/why-llamas-are-the-hedgehogs-best-friend-9nd55k09vsd|title=Why llamas are the hedgehog's best friend|last=Parris|first=Matthew|date=23 December 2015|work=The Times|access-date=6 March 2018|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/foxhunting/12070944/If-only-we-could-consign-Tracey-Crouch-and-her-views-on-foxhunting-to-history.html|title=If only we could consign Tracey Crouch and her views on foxhunting to history|last=Moore|first=Charles|date=28 December 2015|access-date=6 March 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nStewart supported remain in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum on the UK's continued membership of the European Union]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35616946 |title=EU vote: Where the cabinet and other MPs stand |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=22 June 2016 }}</ref> but accepted the result, writing that \"the decision is made, and we should be energetic and optimistic [about it]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/statement-on-brexit/|title=Statement on Brexit|date=5 July 2016|website=Rory Stewart|language=en-US|access-date=15 February 2019}}</ref> Stewart was a prominent supporter of the [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]] negotiated by the prime minister [[Theresa May]],<ref>Rafael Behr, [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/jun/19/may-brexit-deal-not-dead-rory-stewart-boris-johnson May's Brexit deal is not dead \u2013 and only Rory Stewart will admit it], ''The Guardian'' (19 June 2019).</ref><ref>Jessica Elgot, [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/18/rory-stewart-the-black-watch-veteran-shaking-up-the-tory-leadership-race 'This is serious': the unlikely rise of Rory Stewart's pitch to be PM], ''The Guardian'' (18 June 2019): \"his energetic defence of Theresa May\u2019s Brexit deal\"</ref><ref>Andrew Woodcock, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/conservative-leader-rory-stewart-brexit-citizens-assembly-archbishop-canterbury-a8933741.html Rory Stewart: Tory leadership contender unveils proposal to break Brexit deadlock], ''Independent'' (28 May 2019): \"Mr Stewart, who backed Remain in the 2016 referendum and has been one of the most persistent public defenders of Theresa May\u2019s withdrawal deal\"</ref> arguing that the agreement respects the result of the referendum \"by leaving EU political institutions...and by taking back control over immigration\" while also addressing \"the concerns of the more than 16&nbsp;million who voted remain\" and [[Economic effects of Brexit|protecting the British economy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/on-brexit/|title=ON BREXIT|date=29 November 2018|website=Rory Stewart|language=en-US|access-date=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nStewart led the first backbench motion for expanding [[Consumer Broadband United Kingdom|broadband]] and [[list of mobile network operators of Europe#United Kingdom|mobile]] coverage, securing what was then the largest number of cross-party endorsements for a backbench motion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/category/broadband/|title=Broadband Archives \u2013 Rory Stewart|website=Rory Stewart|language=en-US|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> In a report published in 2011, Stewart won support from the House of Commons [[Culture, Media and Sport Committee]] in calling for mobile phone companies to be forced to provide coverage to 98% of the population,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/98-coverage-for-mobile-broadband/ |title=98% coverage for mobile broadband |publisher=Rory Stewart |date=4 November 2011 }}</ref> and in 2012, his campaign achieved its goal when regulator [[Ofcom]] announced its plans for the auction of fourth generation ([[4G]]) bandwidth for mobile phone services.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/rory-s-campaign-for-rural-mobile-coverage-in-4g-triumph/ |title=Rory's campaign for rural mobile coverage in 4G triumph |publisher=Rory Stewart |date=25 July 2012 }}</ref> In March 2018, [[Ofcom]] announced that the 98% target had been met.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ofcom.org.uk/spectrum/information/cellular-coverage|title=Mobile coverage obligation|website=Ofcom|language=en|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nStewart was successful in securing the [[Cumbria]]n broadband pilot in 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/rural-broadband-pilot-areas-named |title=Rural broadband pilot areas named |publisher=[[Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport]] |date=19 May 2011 }}</ref> and in November 2013, broadband provider [[EE Limited|EE]] cited the support of Government and regulatory policy in announcing that over 2,000 residents and businesses in rural Cumbria were to have access to superfast home and office broadband for the first time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://explore.ee.co.uk/our-company/newsroom/ee-switches-on-superfast-4g-broadband-in-rural-cumbria |title=EE switches on superfast 4G broadband in rural Cumbria |publisher=[[EE Limited]] |date=11 November 2013 }}</ref> In February 2015 Stewart secured more funding in order to continue the broadband roll-out in Cumbria.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/secretary-state-pays-testament-broadband-activist-rory-stewart-mp/ |title=Secretary of State pays testament to broadband activist Rory Stewart MP |publisher=Rory Stewart |date=5 February 2015 }}</ref>\n\nStewart supports fox hunting, and has been marked as a \"For\" voter to upkeep the traditional sport if it were voted on and has been seen at hunt meets in his local area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/foxhunting/11635617/Foxhunting-ban-Will-my-MP-vote-to-repeal-it.html|title=Fox Hunting - Will my MP vote to repeal it?|date=14 July 2015|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref> He said, \"I'm in favour. It's an important cultural tradition in Cumbria going back many hundreds of years, and hunts like Blencathra and Ullswater are a very important part of rural tradition. It's not something I've ever done myself but it's something I think people should have the right to do.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/16699375.general-election-candidates-our-views-on-fox-hunting/|title=General Election candidates: Our views on fox hunting|publisher=News&Star |date=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Hands Across The Border===\nIn July 2014, Stewart launched [[Hands Across The Border]], a project to construct a [[cairn]] called 'The Auld Acquaintance' as \"a testament to the [[United Kingdom|Union]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://handsacrosstheborder.co.uk/|title=Home|website=Hands Across the Border}}</ref> Built by members of the public, it is close to the [[Anglo-Scottish border|Scotland\u2013England border]] near [[Gretna, Scotland|Gretna.]] During the run up to the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|Scottish independence referendum]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/the-cairn-remains-a-powerful-symbol-of-the-ties-that-bind-us-says-rory-stewart/|title='THE CAIRN REMAINS A POWERFUL SYMBOL OF THE TIES THAT BIND US' SAYS RORY STEWART \u2013 Rory Stewart|date=14 April 2015|work=Rory Stewart|access-date=7 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Stewart said of the project: \"We wanted to come up with a lasting marker of our union, something that future generations will look back at and remember, with deep gratitude, the moment we chose to stay together.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cumbria-28216218 |title=Scottish independence: 'cairn to celebrate union love' |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=9 July 2014 |accessdate=2 August 2014 }}</ref> The campaign received support from several notable public figures in the UK, including actress [[Joanna Lumley]], explorer [[Sir Ranulph Fiennes]], mountaineers [[Alan Hinkes]] and [[Doug Scott]], and historians [[Simon Schama]] and [[David Starkey]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cumbria-28590490 |title=Joanna Lumley shows support for union with Scotland |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=31 August 2014 |accessdate=2 August 2014 }}</ref> Approximately 100,000 stones were laid on the cairn, many with personal messages.\n\nAt the same time, Stewart hosted a two-part documentary on [[BBC Two]] about the cross-border history of what he called \"Britain's lost middleland\",<ref name=\"Middleland\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0405x9j |title=''Border Country: The Story of Britain's Lost Middleland'' |publisher=[[BBC iPlayer]] |date=26 March 2014 |accessdate=20 December 2017 }}</ref> covering the kingdoms of [[Kingdom of Northumbria|Northumbria]] and [[Kingdom of Strathclyde|Strathclyde]] and the [[Debatable Lands]] of the [[Scottish Marches]] on the [[Anglo-Scottish border]].<ref name=\"Middleland\" />\n\n===Veterans in the justice system===\nIn January 2014, Stewart was asked by [[Chris Grayling]], [[Secretary of State for Justice]], to lead a Government review into the reasons why a number of British veterans become criminal offenders after returning to civilian life.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://veterans-aid.net/mp-rory-stewart-visits-veterans-aid-consult-rehabilitation-needs/|title=Rory Stewart visits VA to consult on rehabilitation needs|date=2 April 2014|work=Veterans Aid|access-date=7 March 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> The review looked at ways in which support and prevention for veterans in the justice system can be improved.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/veterans-within-criminal-justice-system/consult_view |title=Review of Veterans within the Criminal Justice System Call for Evidence |publisher=[[Ministry of Justice (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Justice]] }}</ref> Following his election to Chairman of the [[Defence Select Committee]], Stewart handed over the lead for the review to [[Stephen Phillips (politician)|Stephen Phillips]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-chair-announced-for-veterans-review |title=New chair announced for Veterans Review  |publisher=[[Ministry of Justice (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Justice]] |date=16 June 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Defence Select Committee===\nIn May 2014, Stewart was elected by MPs from all parties as Chairman of the [[Defence Select Committee]]. He was the youngest Chair of a select committee in parliamentary history, as well as the first MP of the 2010 intake to be elected to chair a committee.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27417912|title=Rory roars in|work=BBC News|last=D'Arcy|first=Mark|date=14 May 2014}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/2014/05/rory-stewart-elected-chairman-of-the-defence-select-committee/|title=Rory Stewart elected Chairman of the Defence Select Committee|work=Spectator Blogs|last=Blackburn|first=David|date=14 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/blighty/2014/05/parliamentary-committees |title=Rory Stewart's new triumph |work=[[The Economist]] |date=14 May 2014 |accessdate=29 August 2014 }}</ref>  In this capacity, Stewart argued strongly for a more vigorous response to [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|Russian aggression in Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/defence-committee/news/report-tndsr/|title=Ukraine must be a wake-up call for NATO \u2013 News from Parliament|website=UK Parliament|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> The committee also argued that Britain's commitments to Iraq and Syria were \"strikingly modest\" and that more should be done.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/feb/05/britain-greater-role-fighting-islamic-state-iraq-mps|title=Britain must play a greater role in fighting Islamic State in Iraq, say MPs|author=Ewen MacAskill|work=The Guardian|date=5 February 2015}}</ref> Under Stewart's chairmanship, the committee produced a report in favour of the proposals for a Service Complaints Ombudsman and also secured an amendment extending the powers of the Ombudsman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/defence-committee/news/report-armed-services-bill/|title=Forces Ombudsman should have further powers, says Defence Committee|work=UK Parliament}}</ref>\n\n===Environment minister===\n[[File:\u03a3\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7 \u0391\u039d\u03a5\u03a0\u0395\u039e, \u039d. \u039e\u03c5\u03b4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7, \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0392\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03cc \u03a5\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03cc \u0395\u03c0\u03b9\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b5\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7 \u0394\u03b9\u03b5\u03b8\u03bd\u03ae \u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03c0\u03c4\u03c5\u03be\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03ae \u03a3\u03c5\u03bd\u03b5\u03c1\u03b3\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03b1, Rory Stewart (\u03a5\u03a0\u0395\u039e, 22.9.2016) (29568248890).jpg|thumb|250px|Stewart pictured with the Greek politician [[Nikos Xydakis (journalist)|Nikos Xydakis]] in September 2016]]\nFollowing the Conservatives' return with an outright majority at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], Stewart was appointed [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State|Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Department for Environment, Food & Rural Affairs]] (DEFRA), with responsibilities including the natural environment, national parks, floods and water, resource and environmental management, rural affairs, lead responsibility for the [[Environment Agency]], [[Natural England]] and the [[Forestry Commission]], and acting as the secretary of state's deputy on the [[Environment Council]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/rory-stewart|title=Rory Stewart MP \u2013 GOV.UK}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, in his capacity as resource minister, he announced a review into the regulatory and enforcement barriers to growth and innovation in the waste sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/review-into-regulation-and-enforcement-in-waste-sector-launches|title=Review into regulation and enforcement in waste sector launches|work=GOV.UK}}</ref> Stewart as 'floods minister' joined the National Flood Resilience Review, formed in 2016 and chaired by the chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster, [[Oliver Letwin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/national-flood-resilience-review-government-action-to-tackle-floods|title=National Flood Resilience Review: Government action to tackle floods|website=GOV.UK}}</ref> Stewart initiated the Cumbria Floods Partnership in response to [[Storm Desmond]], with a focus on long-term flood defence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/a-country-more-flood-resilient|title=A country more flood resilient|website=GOV.UK}}</ref> The House of Commons cross-party Environment Audit Committee criticised the statement by Stewart that the extra \u00a3700m for flood defence was the result of a \"political calculation\" and that it might not be spent according to the strict value-for-money criteria currently used.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/jun/09/government-failing-to-protect-communities-at-risk-of-flooding-mps-say|title=Government failing to protect communities at risk of flooding, MPs say|first=Damian|last=Carrington|date=9 June 2016|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nAs environment minister he introduced the plastic bag tax which reduced the use of personal bags by 85% in 6 months;<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/plastic-bag-charge-to-protect-marine-environment/|title=Plastic bag charge to protect marine environment \u2013 Rory Stewart|date=7 October 2015|work=Rory Stewart|access-date=7 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and he was responsible for producing the first draft of the 25-year environment plan in which he emphasised, alongside biodiversity and ecosystems, the importance of human cultural features in the landscape, and particularly the conservation of small family sheep farms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complydirect.com/news/25-year-environment-plan-unveiled-by-the-government/|title=Government's 25-year environment plan|website=www.complydirect.com|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> As Minister responsible for the National Parks, Stewart secured five years of increased funding for [[national park]]s and [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty|AONB]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/call-wild-environment-minister-champions-weekend-walking-trips-national-parks/|title=The call of the wild: Environment Minister champions weekend walking trips in our National Parks \u2013 Rory Stewart|date=29 April 2016|work=Rory Stewart|access-date=7 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> He also ensured the extension of the [[Lake District]] and [[Yorkshire Dales National Park]] and supported the [[World Heritage Site|UNESCO World Heritage]] bid for the Lake District.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/rory-stewart-mp-celebrates-the-lake-districts-world-heritage-success-a-vindication-of-all-that-we-love/|title=RORY STEWART MP CELEBRATES THE LAKE DISTRICT'S WORLD HERITAGE SUCCESS \u2013 \"A VINDICATION OF ALL THAT WE LOVE\" \u2013 Rory Stewart|date=11 July 2017|work=Rory Stewart|access-date=5 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAs floods minister, Stewart oversaw the government's response to the [[2015\u201316 Great Britain and Ireland floods]], including the post-[[Storm Desmond]] floods,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/533457/cumbria-flood-plan-overview.pdf|title=Reducing flood risk from source to sea|last=|first=|date=2016|website=UK Government|access-date=}}</ref> including the reopening of the [[A591]] and the bridge at [[Pooley Bridge]] in the [[Lake District]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/border/update/2016-05-11/floods-minister-lake-district-is-open-for-business/|title=Floods Minister: 'Lake District is open for business'|work=ITV News|access-date=5 March 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Minister for International Development and Africa===\n\nAfter [[Theresa May]] replaced [[David Cameron]] as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]], Stewart was promoted to [[Department for International Development#Ministers|minister of state for international development]] on 17 July 2016.<ref name=\"Rory Stewart MP OBE\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=New ministerial role for MP Rory Stewart|url=http://www.itv.com/news/border/2016-07-17/new-ministerial-role-for-mp-rory-stewart/|website=ITV.com|publisher=ITV|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nStewart was promoted to become joint Minister for Africa, taking over responsibility for the Foreign Office and its embassies in Africa, as well as the [[Department for International Development]] (DfID) in Africa. In this capacity he visited a number of countries in Africa<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@mafita/uks-minister-for-africa-is-very-happy-with-what-he-saw-at-mafita-cosdec-in-mando-88731aab63c2|title=UK's Minister for Africa is 'very happy' with what he saw at MAFITA COSDEC in Mando|last=Mafita|date=3 August 2017|website=Medium|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2017/07/bruce-british-minister-stewart-push-trade-deals-uganda/|title=Bruce, British Minister Stewart push trade deals in Uganda \u2013 Vanguard News|date=15 July 2017|work=Vanguard News|access-date=7 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.1666568746710395.1073741835.121827597851192&type=3|title=Minister for Africa,Rory Stewart OBE MP Visit to Gaborone {{!}} Facebook|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> and the [[United Nations General Assembly|United National General Assembly]] in [[New York City|New York]] (UNGA).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-10-17/debates/F4A1FA8D-BB38-4A09-BB24-CD1B5CE77705/OralAnswersToQuestions|title=Oral Answers to Questions \u2013 Hansard Online|website=hansard.parliament.uk|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> During these trips he held personal meetings with [[Paul Kagame|President Kagame]] of Rwanda,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/paulkagame/albums/72157688998687374/|title=Meeting with UK Minister for Africa, Rory Stewart {{!}} Kigali, 7 November 2017|work=Flickr|access-date=7 March 2018|language=en-us}}</ref> [[Joseph Kabila|President Kabila]] of DRC,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kikayabinkarubi.net/_2017/2017/11/10/tete-a-tete-rory-stewart-joseph-kabila-ce-vendredi-a-kingakati/|title=T\u00eate-\u00e0-t\u00eate Rory Stewart-Joseph Kabila ce vendredi \u00e0 Kingakati \u2013 Le Portail de Barnab\u00e9 KIKAYA|website=kikayabinkarubi.net|language=en-GB|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> [[Edgar Lungu|President Lungu]] of Zambia,<ref name=\"gov.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/uk-minister-for-africa-rory-stewart-visits-zambia|title=UK Minister for Africa Rory Stewart visits Zambia \u2013 GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> [[John Magufuli|President Magufuli]] of Tanzania,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/uk-minister-rory-stewart-announces-450-million-for-development-in-tanzania|title=UK minister Rory Stewart announces $450 million for development in Tanzania \u2013 GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> and [[Emmerson Mnangagwa|President Mnangagwa]] of Zimbabwe.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/Cumbrian-MP-Rory-Stewart-meets-Zimbabwes-new-president-49286e10-e6a4-4b45-bef8-ba09efaa3b24-ds|title=Cumbrian MP Rory Stewart meets Zimbabwe's new president|access-date=7 March 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> In this role Stewart was the driving force behind the British Government's new Africa strategy and pushed for more resources to go into the Foreign Office network in Africa. His most notable trip was to Zimbabwe where he was the first foreign dignitary to be received by President Mnangagwa.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/23/zimbabwe-must-reform-mugabe-says-first-british-minster-visit/|title=Zimbabwe must reform after Mugabe, says first British minster to visit country in two decades|date=23 November 2017|work=The Telegraph|access-date=5 March 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> His Zimbabwe policy pressed for political reform, and free and fair elections.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/rory-stewart-returns-from-zimbabwe|title=Rory Stewart returns from Zimbabwe \u2013 GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Prisons minister===\n[[File:London Illegal Wildlife Trade (IWT) Conference 2018 (37331372894).jpg|thumb|Stewart at the London Illegal Wildlife Trade Conference 2018]]\nStewart was appointed [[Minister of State for Prisons]] with responsibility for prisons and probation in England and Wales in January 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/Rory-Stewart-given-new-role-in-cabinet-reshuffle-be354944-2f6f-4c53-91b4-d592e37bebb3-ds|title=Rory Stewart given new role in cabinet reshuffle|access-date=5 March 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> He was appointed in the aftermath of a highly critical leaked report on the state of [[HM Prison Liverpool|HMP Liverpool]], in which the inspector described it as the \"worst prison he had ever seen\" with piles of rubbish, rats, soaring violence and drug use and poor health provision.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jan/19/liverpool-prison-worst-conditions-inspectors-report|title=Liverpool prison has 'worst conditions inspectors have seen'|last=Travis|first=Alan|date=19 January 2018|work=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> Stewart immediately visited the prison and, testifying before the Justice Select Committee, announced his determination to clean up prisons in England and Wales.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/im-going-back-to-basics-to-clean-up-our-filthy-prisons-vows-minister-rory-stewart-gknxlcm9j|title=I'm going back to basics to clean up our filthy prisons, vows minister Rory Stewart|last=Ford|first=Richard|date=2018|work=The Times|access-date=5 March 2018|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nThis advocacy of a \"back to basics\" approach was recorded in ''The Guardian'', with Stewart writing an opinion piece in the publication, entitled \"I strongly believe we can improve our prisons and make progress\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/feb/17/rory-stewart-reform-prisons-crisis|title=I strongly believe we can improve our prisons and make progress|last=Stewart|first=Rory|date=17 February 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Stewart took the [[Assaults on Emergency Workers (Offences) Private Member's Bill]] through the House of Commons, on behalf of the government, which doubled the maximum sentences for those who attack emergency services personnel and introduced sexual assault as an aggravating factor in sentencing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=2018-04-27b.1142.2&s=Rory+stewart#g1194.1|title=Assaults on police constables: 27 Apr 2018: House of Commons debates \u2013 TheyWorkForYou|website=TheyWorkForYou|language=en|access-date=10 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Ten Prisons Project ====\nIn August 2018, during an interview with ''[[BBC Breakfast]]'', Stewart announced the launch of the Ten Prisons Project. He argued that, despite five years of continuous rise in violence in prisons, it was possible to turn it around. Stewart argued that it could be done through improving perimeter gate security (to catch drugs) and by improving training and support of staff. The key, he said, was to get the basics right. He undertook to create a new prison officer handbook and a new course at the training college for prison officers. Stewart pledged, in the same interview, that he would resign if this project was not successful.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-45214414|title=I'll quit if jails don't improve \u2013 minister|date=17 August 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=17 August 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe twelve months statistics showed a continuing positive trend when, in August 2019, the results from the Ten Prisons Project were published. These showed a 16% drop in the rate of assaults, and a 17% drop in the number of assaults, almost 10% greater than the national trend. At the same time, the percentage of positive results from random mandatory drug tests dropped by 50%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/826775/10-prisons-statistics.pdf|title=Results from the 10 Prisons Project Ad Hoc Statistics|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===International Development Secretary===\nIn May 2019, Stewart was promoted to the cabinet after the dismissal of [[Gavin Williamson]], replacing the new [[Secretary of State for Defence|defence secretary]] [[Penny Mordaunt]] in the [[Department for International Development]]. The position included membership of the political cabinet and the [[National Security Council (United Kingdom)|National Security Council]] and saw Stewart serve as a governor of the [[World Bank]], the [[African Development Bank]], the [[Caribbean Development Bank]] and the Inter-African Development Bank. He was also an alternative governor to the [[European Bank for Reconstruction and Development]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/ministers/secretary-of-state-for-international-development|title=Secretary of State for International Development - GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=24 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July, in his first overseas trip as international development secretary, Stewart visited UK aid funded programmes in Jordan and held meetings with Prime Minister [[Omar Razzaz]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/international-development-secretary-rory-stewart-visits-jordan-in-first-foreign-visit-in-role|title=International Development Secretary Rory Stewart visits Jordan in first foreign visit in role|last=|first=|date=4 July 2019|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 July 2019, Stewart resigned as international development secretary following [[Boris Johnson]]'s victory in the [[2019 Conservative Party leadership election|Conservative Party leadership election]] triggered by the resignation of [[Theresa May]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clifton |first1=Katy |title=Rory Stewart confirms resignation from Cabinet after Boris Johnson's victory |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/rory-stewart-confirms-resignation-from-cabinet-after-boris-johnsons-victory-a4196546.html |accessdate=24 July 2019 |work=[[Evening Standard]] |date=23 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Conservative Party leadership election===\nStewart was a candidate in the [[2019 Conservative Party (UK) leadership election|2019 Conservative leadership election]], announcing his intention to stand in an interview in ''[[The Times]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48140849|title=Rory Stewart: I'd bring country together as PM|work=[[BBC News]]|date=2 May 2019 |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/rory-stewart-we-need-a-standard-bearer-for-the-middle-ground-it-could-be-me-wvr3k93tf|title=Rory Stewart: We need a standard bearer for the middle ground \u2014 it could be me|date=13 April 2019|work=The Times|access-date=19 August 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> His candidacy was not initially taken seriously, with a piece in the ''[[New Statesman]]''<nowiki/>'s diary stating that he had a single supporter: himself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2019/04/commons-confidential-eurosceptic-hackocracy|title=Commons Confidential: The Eurosceptic hackocracy|website=www.newstatesman.com|language=en|access-date=19 August 2019}}</ref> As ''[[The Guardian]]'' noted: \"his campaign benefited at the start from low expectations, and for days leading up to the first vote his tally of supporters was in single figures. When he met the threshold he looked like the insurgent because so many had assumed he would be knocked out\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/18/rory-stewart-the-black-watch-veteran-shaking-up-the-tory-leadership-race|title='This is serious': the unlikely rise of Rory Stewart's pitch to be PM|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=18 June 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=19 August 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nAdopting an unconventional campaigning style, Stewart did not focus his attention on Westminster but, instead, went on a series of filmed walkabouts (dubbed 'RoryWalks'), which saw him take to the streets of Britain, talking to voters, to understand their priorities and concerns. These were then uploaded onto social media, with significant success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/the-londoner-rory-stewart-is-proving-to-be-a-master-of-pr-a4155091.html|title=The Londoner: Rory Stewart is proving to be a master of PR|date=30 May 2019|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=19 August 2019}}</ref> On 1 June, [[Kenneth Clarke]] was announced as one of Stewart's MP backers, with other supporters including [[David Lidington]], [[David Gauke]], [[Nicholas Soames]], [[Tobias Ellwood]], [[Gillian Keegan]] and [[Victoria Prentis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/c696b4d8-8ca2-11e9-a24d-b42f641eca37|title=Rory Stewart pledges grown-up approach in Tory leadership race|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|date=11 June 2019|url-access=subscription|access-date=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nStewart's use of social media later became the subject of controversy when, at a talk at the Emmanuel Centre in October 2019, in the course of discussing his use of social media during this contest, he referred to an encounter in Brick Lane with three \"sort of minor gangsters\". This drew accusations of racism from many politicians, including [[Dawn Butler]], [[David Lammy]] and [[Diane Abbott]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-rory-stewart-racism-london-mayor-minor-gangsters-latest-a9170941.html|title=Labour accuses mayoral candidate Rory Stewart of racism after describing three London men as 'minor gangsters'|newspaper=The Independent|last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|date=25 October 2019|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Stewart apologised the next day, tweeting \"I am very sorry towards the guys and towards everyone else. I was wrong\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/rorystewartuk/status/1187764597937324033?lang=en|title=I am very sorry towards the guys and towards everyone else. I was wrong.|last=Stewart|first=Rory|date=25 October 2019|website=@rorystewartuk|language=en|access-date=2 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nAgainst expectations, on 13 June 2019, Stewart made it through the first parliamentary ballot, gaining 19 votes, two more than the elimination threshold.<ref>{{cite web |title=Full results of the Conservative leadership election \u2013 round 1 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/ng-interactive/2019/jun/13/conservative-leadership-election-full-results |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=13 June 2019 |date=13 June 2019}}</ref> On 16 June, he appeared, as one of the six remaining candidates, in a televised debate on [[Channel 4]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-06-16/tory-leadership-race-tv-debate-conservative-contenders-take-part-channel-4-televised-debate/|title=Dominic Raab refuses to rule out suspending Parliament to push through no deal|website=ITV News |date=16 June 2019 |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref> He was widely judged to have won the debate, with [[Michael Deacon (journalist)|Michael Deacon]] writing in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' that \"If you were to judge it by the response of the studio audience, Channel 4's debate had only one winner. Rory Stewart got more rounds of applause than any other candidate \u2013 and, at the end, when each took turns to sum up, he was the only candidate to get a round of applause at all\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/06/16/rory-stewart-serious-threat-boris-johnson-tv-debate-proved/|title=Rory Stewart is the only serious threat to Boris Johnson \u2013 and the TV debate proved it|last=Deacon|first=Michael|date=16 June 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=19 August 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 June 2019, he also made it through the second parliamentary ballot, with 37 votes from a threshold of 33, surpassing [[Home Secretary]] [[Sajid Javid]] by four votes; however, following a lacklustre performance in that evening's [[BBC]] debate, he polled just 27 votes in the next day's ballot and was eliminated as the last-placed candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48696619|title=Rory Stewart out of Tory leadership race|date=19 June 2019|website=BBC News|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/andrea-leadsom-endorses-boris-johnson-in-tory-leadership-race-11743885|title=LIVE: Raab eliminated as Johnson wins second leadership contest ballot|website=Sky News|language=en |date=18 June 2019 |accessdate=18 June 2019 }}</ref> It was revealed on the same day that Stewart was in talks with [[Michael Gove]] to stop [[Boris Johnson]] becoming Prime Minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/rory-stewart-gove-boris-johnson-tory-leadership-contest-race-debate-a8964906.html|title=Rory Stewart in talks with Michael Gove to stop Boris Johnson becoming prime minister|date=19 June 2019|website=The Independent|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Sitting as an independent and resignation===\n{{Main|September 2019 suspension of rebel Conservative MPs}}\nOn 3 September 2019, Stewart and 20 other Conservative MPs voted in favour of MPs taking control of the order paper, as the first step to table a Bill to stop a [[no-deal Brexit]], in the process rebelling against the Government Whip.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2019/sep/03/commons-showdown-looms-in-battle-over-no-deal-brexit-live?page=with:block-5d6ed2f58f0845a5dab7cc88#block-5d6ed2f58f0845a5dab7cc88|title=Boris Johnson to table motion for election after failed vote - as it happened|newspaper=The Guardian|author1=Kate Lyons|author2=Kevin Rawlinson|author3=Andrew Sparrow|author4=Frances Perraudin|date=4 September 2019|quote=MPs back move to allow bill to block no-deal Brexit by majority of 27}}</ref> It had been widely reported in the media that any such action would lead to a withdrawal of the Conservative Whip, and all 21 were told that they had lost it,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-49578000|title=What is removing the whip, filibustering and other Brexit jargon?|website=BBC Newsbeat|date=4 September 2019|accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref> expelling them as Conservative MPs and requiring them to sit as independents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/about/mps-and-lords/principal/whips/|title=Whips|website=Parliament.uk|accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/03/boris-johnson-suffers-commons-defeat-as-tories-turn-against-him|title=Boris Johnson to seek election after rebel Tories deliver Commons defeat|accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref> If they should decide to run for re-election in a future election, the party would block their selection as Conservative candidates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/09/04/parliament-whip-removed/|title=Boris Johnson to strip 21 Tory MPs of the Tory whip in parliamentary bloodbath|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|last=Mikhailova|first=Anna|date=4 September 2019}}</ref> Stewart stated that he was informed of this decision by text message, while collecting his ''[[GQ]]'' Politician of the Year Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/tory-rory-stewart-sacked-text-19428060|title=Tory Rory Stewart sacked by text while he accepted politician of the year award|last=Bloom|first=Dan|date=4 September 2019|website=mirror|access-date=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt an event on 3 October 2019, Stewart announced he had resigned from the Conservative Party and would stand down as an MP at the [[Next United Kingdom general election|next general election]]. He read out a letter in which a housemaster at [[Eton College]] described [[Boris Johnson]] as being guilty of \"a gross failure of responsibility\". The next day, Stewart confirmed his resignation on [[Twitter]], saying: \"It's been a great privilege to serve Penrith and The Border for the last ten years, so it is with sadness that I am announcing that I will be standing down.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/04/rory-stewart-resigns-from-conservative-party|title=Rory Stewart resigns from Conservative party|last=Walker|first=Peter|date=4 October 2019|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== London Mayoral candidate ===\nIn October 2019, Stewart announced that he was to stand as an independent in the [[2021 London mayoral election|upcoming London mayoral election]] (initially scheduled to be held in 2020 and later postponed until 2021 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]])<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51876269|title=Coronavirus: English local elections postponed for a year|work=BBC News|date=13 March 2020|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> against incumbent [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] mayor [[Sadiq Khan]] and Conservative candidate [[Shaun Bailey (London politician)|Shaun Bailey]].<ref>{{cite tweet|user=RoryStewartUK|number=1180054614713999361|date=4 October 2019|title=I am running as an Independent candidate for Mayor of London, and here's why. Please join me in my campaign: join.rorystewart.co.uk #Rory4London|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> On the day he announced his run, Stewart's odds to win were placed at 2/1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/1186873/when-next-london-mayor-elections-who-stand-rory-stewart-candidates-latest-odds|title=When are next London mayor elections? Who will stand against Rory Stewart? Latest odds|last=Whitfield|first=Kate|date=5 October 2019|website=Express.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Writing==\n===Books===\nHis first book, ''[[The Places in Between]]'', was an account of his 36-day solo walk across Afghanistan in early 2002.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.panmacmillan.com/authors/rory-stewart/the-places-in-between|title=The Places In Between|website=Pan Macmillan|language=en-GB|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sattin |first1=Anthony |title=Review: Travel: The Places In Between by Rory Stewart |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/review-travel-the-places-in-between-by-rory-stewart-kcl59q9v3r0 |website=The Times |accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref> It was a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' best-seller, with the newspaper also naming it one of its 10 notable books of 2006 and hailing it as  a \"flat-out masterpiece\".<ref name=\"NY101108\" /> It won the Royal Society of Literature Ondaatje Prize,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rsliterature.org/library-article/two-way-traffic-rory-stewart-on-writing-about-place/|title=Royal Society of Literature \u00bb Two-way traffic: Rory Stewart on writing about place|website=rsliterature.org|language=en-GB|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref> a [[Scottish Arts Council]] prize,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottisharts.org.uk/1/artsinscotland/literature/projects/archive/bookawards2005.aspx|title=Scottish Arts Council \u2013 Book Awards 2005|website=www.scottisharts.org.uk|language=en|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref> the Spirit of Scotland award,<ref name=\"About Rory - Rory Stewart\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/about-rory/|title=About Rory \u2013 Rory Stewart|work=Rory Stewart|access-date=8 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and the {{ill|Premio de Literatura de Viaje Caminos del Cid|es}}.<ref name=\"About Rory - Rory Stewart\"/> It was short-listed for a Scottish Arts Council prize,<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scottisharts.org.uk/1/artsinscotland/literature/projects/archive/bookawards2005.aspx|title=Scottish Arts Council \u2013 Book Awards 2005|website=www.scottisharts.org.uk|language=en|access-date=6 March 2018}}</ref> the [[Guardian First Book Award]]<ref name=\":5\" /> and the [[John Llewellyn Rhys Prize]].<ref name=\":5\" /> The book was adapted into a radio play by [[Benjamin Yeoh]] and was broadcast in 2007 on BBC Radio 4.<ref name=\":6\">{{Citation|last=Benjamin Yeoh|title=Places In Between, The|date=15 February 2007|url=https://archive.org/details/PlacesInBetweenThe|accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nStewart's second book, ''[[Occupational Hazards|The Prince of the Marshes: and other Occupational Hazards of a Year in Iraq]]'', also published as ''Occupational Hazards: My Time Governing in Iraq'', describes his experiences as a Deputy Governorate Co-ordinator in Iraq.<ref name=\"NY101108\" /> The ''New York Times'' critic William Grimes commented that Stewart \"seems to be living one of the more extraordinary lives on record\", but for him the \"real value of the new book is Mr. Stewart's sobering picture of the difficulties involved in creating a coherent Iraqi state based on the rule of law\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-KJ7JInCUR0C&pg=PP3&lpg=PP3&dq=%22rory+stewart%22+AND+%22seems+to+be+living+one+of+the+more+extraordinary+lives+on+record%22|title=The Prince of the Marshes: And Other Occupational Hazards of a Year in Iraq|last=Stewart|first=Rory|date=1 February 2007|publisher=HMH|isbn=9780156033008|language=en}}</ref> Stewart's books have been translated into multiple languages.\n\nIn 2017, Stewart's memoir ''Occupational Hazards'' was the subject of a play at the [[Hampstead Theatre]], written by Stephen Brown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hampsteadtheatre.com/whats-on/2017/occupational-hazards/|title=OCCUPATIONAL HAZARDS|website=Hampstead Theatre|access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nStewart's reflections on the circumstances under which outside military and political intervention in countries' internal affairs may or may not hope to achieve positive results were distilled in a 2011 book, ''Can Intervention Work?'', co-authored with [[Gerald Knaus]] and part of the Amnesty International Global Ethics Series. He has also written about theory and practice of travel writings in prefaces to [[Wilfred Thesiger]]'s ''[[Arabian Sands]]'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/arabiansandspeng00wilf|title=Arabian Sands|last=Thesiger|first=Wilfred|last2=Stewart|first2=Rory|date=25 October 2007|publisher=Penguin Classics|isbn=9780141442075|edition=Reissue|location=London|language=English|url-access=registration}}</ref> [[Charles Montagu Doughty|Charles Doughty]]'s ''[[Travels in Arabia Deserta|Arabia Deserta]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foliosociety.com/book/ADB/travels-in-arabia-deserta|title=Travels In Arabia Deserta {{!}} Folio Illustrated Book|website=www.foliosociety.com|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> and [[Robert Byron]]'s ''[[The Road to Oxiana]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/the-road-to-oxiana-9780195325607?cc=gb&lang=en&|title=The Road to Oxiana|last=Byron|first=Robert|last2=Stewart|first2=Rory|last3=Fussell|first3=Paul|date=18 May 2007|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195325607|location=Oxford, New York}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he published ''The Marches: Border Walks With My Father'' a travelogue about a 1,000-mile walk in the borderlands separating England and Scotland, known as the [[Scottish Marches]], and an extended essay on his father, Brian Stewart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/nov/18/the-marches-rory-stewart-review-brian-border-england-scotland|title=The Marches by Rory Stewart review \u2013 farewell to an imperial class|last=Jack|first=Ian|date=18 November 2016|website=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref> ''The Marches'' was long listed for the [[Orwell Prize]], won the Hunter Davies Lakeland Book of the Year,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jamescropper.com/news/rory-stewart-lakeland-book-of-the-year-winner-for-the-marches|title=Rory Stewart is the 33rd Lakeland Book of the Year Winner for 'The Marches'|website=www.jamescropper.com|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> was a Waterstones Book of the Month,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/books/the-marches/|title=THE MARCHES \u2013 Rory Stewart|work=Rory Stewart|access-date=8 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and became a [[Sunday Times]] top ten bestseller.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/What-did-your-MP-receive-last-year-Parliaments-gifts-and-donations-list-revealed-4ad1fbe4-c94c-4f70-891d-6a4df83e934e-ds|title=What did your MP receive last year? Parliament's gifts and donations list revealed|last=Barber|first=Caroline|access-date=8 March 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Articles===\nStewart was a columnist for the ''[[Cumberland and Westmorland Herald]]'', contributing a monthly column,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwherald.com/|title=Latest Headlines|work=cwherald.com}}</ref> and has been a columnist for ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/23/opinion/23stewart.html|title=Opinion {{!}} The 'Good War' Isn't Worth Fighting|last=Stewart|first=Rory|date=22 November 2008|work=The New York Times|access-date=8 March 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> in addition to a contributor to the [[The New York Review of Books|''New York Review of Books'']],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nybooks.com/contributors/rory-stewart/|title=Rory Stewart|website=The New York Review of Books|language=en-US|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref> and the ''[[London Review of Books]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lrb.co.uk/contributors/rory-stewart|title=Rory Stewart \u00b7 LRB|website=www.lrb.co.uk|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Documentaries==\nStewart has written and presented three [[BBC]] documentaries: \n*''The Legacy of Lawrence of Arabia'' (2010).<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00pyrw1 The Legacy of Lawrence of Arabia] BBC Two</ref>\n*''[[Afghanistan: The Great Game \u2013 A Personal View by Rory Stewart]]'' (2012) a documentary in two parts that tells the story of foreign intervention by Britain, Russia and the United States in Afghanistan from the 19th century to the present day, which aired on [[BBC Two]] and which won a [[BAFTA Scotland|Scottish BAFTA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01jk6ch|title=BBC Two \u2013 Afghanistan: The Great Game \u2013 A Personal View by Rory Stewart|work=BBC}}</ref>\n*''Border Country: The Story of Britain's Lost Middleland'' (2014), which investigates the rift created by [[Hadrian's Wall]] and the issues of identity and culture in a region divided by the fabricated border.<ref name=\"Middleland\"/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n\n* In the [[2004 Birthday Honours|2004]] [[Queen's Birthday Honours]], Stewart was appointed an [[Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the Civil Division.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=57315 |date=12 June 2004 |page=23 |supp=y}}</ref>\n* He holds [[Honorary degree|honorary doctorates]] from the [[University of Stirling]] [[Doctor of the University]] (D.Univ) awarded on 23 November 2009. <ref>[http://www.externalrelations.stir.ac.uk/news/news_archive/2009/November2009.php#graduations Graduating Stirling students reap their rewards] University of Stirling, 23 November 2009</ref> and the [[American University of Paris]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aup.edu/news/commencement2011/honor.htm|title=AUP official website|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003153451/http://www.aup.edu/news/commencement2011/honor.htm|archive-date=3 October 2011|url-status=dead|access-date=26 July 2011}}</ref>\n* Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]] (2005).<ref name=\"rsliterature.org\">{{cite web|url=https://rsliterature.org/library-article/two-way-traffic-rory-stewart-on-writing-about-place/|title=Royal Society of Literature \u00bb Two-way traffic: Rory Stewart on writing about place|website=rsliterature.org|language=en-GB|access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n* Fellow of the [[Royal Scottish Geographical Society]] (FRSGS)  (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rsgs.org/inspiring-people/medals-awards/honorary-fellowship/|title=Honorary Fellowship (FRSGS) |work=rsgs.org|access-date=3 May 2019}}</ref>\n* The [[Livingstone Medal]] of the [[Royal Scottish Geographical Society]] (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rsgs.org/inspiring-people/medals-awards/livingstone-medal/|title=Livingstone Medal |website=rsgs.org|language=en-GB|access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n* The Prize del [[Camino del Cid]] (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caminodelcid.org/el-consorcio-informa/noticias/1629917-el-escoces-rory-stewart-gana-el-premio-de-literatura-de-viajes-camino-del-cid-con-su-libro-la-huella-de-babur/|title=Noticias Ruta Camino del CID {{!}}El escoc\u00e9s Rory Stewart gana el Premio de Literatura de Viajes Camino del Cid con su libro La huella de Babur|website=www.caminodelcid.org|language=es|access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n* [[BAFTA Scotland]] Award (2012).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/scotland/awards/ceremony/nominees-winners/british-academy-scotland-awards-winners-in-2012|title=British Academy Scotland Awards: Winners in 2012|website=www.bafta.org|language=en|access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n*In 2019 Stewart was chosen as the ''[[GQ]]'' Politician of the Year.<ref>{{cite news| work=The Telegraph|URL=https://www-telegraph-co-uk.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/09/03/gq-men-year-2019-andrew-scott-rory-stewart-greta-thunberg/|title=GQ Men of the Year 2019: Andrew Scott, Rory Stewart and Greta Thunberg |date=3 September 2019|last=Singh| first=Anita}}</ref>\n* He was sworn in as a member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council]] in 2019 upon his appointment as [[Secretary of State for International Development|International Development Secretary]] in the [[Second May ministry]]. This gave him the [[Honorific|Honorific Title]] \"[[The Right Honourable]]\" for Life.\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 20 January 2008, Stewart appeared on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]].''<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/factual/desertislanddiscs_20082001.shtml Desert Island Discs \u2013 Rory Stewart], [[BBC Radio 4]], 20 January 2008.</ref> On 22 November 2019, he appeared on [[BBC One]]'s ''[[Have I Got News for You]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000bj21|title=BBC One - Have I Got News for You, Series 58, Episode 6}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, he married American Shoshana Clark, a former employee.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\">{{cite web|title=Conservative MP Rory Stewart to marry American volunteer at his Afghan charity|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/penrith-mp-rory-stewart-to-get-married-next-week-1.1007268?referrerPath=|date=24 October 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130422044457/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/penrith-mp-rory-stewart-to-get-married-next-week-1.1007268?referrerPath=|url-status=dead|archive-date=22 April 2013|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cwherald.com/a/archive/penrith-and-the-border-mp-rory-stewart-and-his-american-bride.399926.html|title=Penrith and the Border MP Rory Stewart and his American bride, ...|website=www.cwherald.com|date=9 November 2012|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> They had their first child in November 2014, a son whom Stewart delivered at home in the absence of medical assistance,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/florence-of-arabia-tamed-by-a-toddler-bspbbvg08|title=Florence of Arabia tamed by a toddler|last=Thring|first=Oliver|date=9 October 2016|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=5 March 2018|language=en|issn=0956-1382}}</ref> and their second child was born in April 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/06/20/rory-stewarts-wife-shoshana-clark-leaves-tory-leadership-race-10017402/|title=Who is Rort Stewart's wife Shoshana Clark as he leaves the Tory leadership race?|newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|last=Milan|first=Aidan|date=20 June 2019|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/06/19/rory-stewart-eton-portrait/|title=Rory Stewart: the 'Florence of Belgravia' years, and the portrait that set him apart from his Eton peers|newspaper=The Telegraph|last=Tominey|first=Camilla|date=19 June 2019|url-access=subscription|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Shoshana and her former husband were volunteering at the Turquoise Mountain Foundation in Afghanistan when she met Stewart.<ref name=eden/>\n\nIn 2012, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' reported that in 2008, [[Brad Pitt]] bought the rights to make a film about Stewart, particularly his time in Afghanistan, with [[Orlando Bloom]] tipped to play the leading role.<ref name=eden>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9434945/How-lover-of-Conservative-MP-Rory-Stewart-left-her-husband-heartbroken-in-Afghanistan.html|title=How lover of Conservative MP Rory Stewart left her husband heartbroken in Afghanistan|first=Richard|last=Eden|date=29 July 2012|publisher=|accessdate=25 May 2019|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019 Conservative Party (UK) leadership election|2019 Conservative leadership election]], Stewart admitted he had smoked [[opium]] during a [[Persian wedding|wedding in Iran]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mikhailova |first1=Anna |title=Rory Stewart admits smoking opium in Iran as he continues Tory leadership tour of Britain |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/05/29/rory-stewart-admits-smoking-opium-spell-iran-tells-telegraph/ |website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |accessdate=9 June 2019 |date=29 May 2019}}</ref> Several other candidates admitted to previous illegal drug use during the leadership contest.<ref>{{cite web |title=Michael Gove admits he was lucky to avoid jail over cocaine use |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48572982 |website=[[BBC]] |accessdate=9 June 2019 |date=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nStewart lives in [[South Kensington]], [[London]]<ref name=\"telegraphKensington\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2019/10/rory-stewart-s-diary-running-london-mayor-life-gang-and-getting-coached-dominic|title= Rory Stewart\u2019s Diary: Running for London mayor, life in a gang, and getting coached by Dominic Cummings|website=NewStatesman|date=30 October 2019|access-date=12 January 2020|last=Stewart|first=Rory|quote=I live in the same house in London that I lived in when I was one.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.onlondon.co.uk/rory-stewart-less-politics-more-action-from-city-hall-if-i-become-london-mayor/|title=Rory Stewart: \u2018Less politics, more action\u2019 from City Hall if I become London Mayor|website=OnLondon|date=27 November 2019|access-date=12 January 2020|last=Wright|first=Charles|quote=And finally, the former Conservative, who has had a family home in Kensington all his life, revealed that he has decided who he\u2019s voting for on December 12, but wasn\u2019t saying any more.}}</ref> as well as [[Dufton]], [[Cumbria]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/gallery/2010/jan/14/general-election-2010-conservatives|title=Would-be Tory MP Rory Stewart|date=14 January 2010|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 May 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He is a member of the [[Athenaeum Club, London|Athenaeum Club]] and the [[Special Forces Club]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Letts |first1= Quentin |author-link1= Quentin Letts |date= 5 Apr 2016 |title= Everything you need to know about Tory MP Rory Stewart |url= https://www.tatler.com/article/everything-you-need-to-know-about-rory-stewart-mp |journal= Tatler  |volume= |issue= |pages= |doi= |access-date= 29 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Books ==\n* ''[[The Places in Between]]'', Picador, 2004\u20132006 <!--See main article for multiple edition information-->\n* ''[[Occupational Hazards: My Time Governing in Iraq]]'', Picador, 2006, {{ISBN|0-330-44049-7}}\n** Published in the US as ''[[The Prince of the Marshes: And Other Occupational Hazards of a Year in Iraq]]'', [[Reed Elsevier|Harcourt]], 2006, {{ISBN|0-15-101235-0}}\n*''Can Intervention Work? Amnesty International Global Ethics Series'', co-authored with Gerald Knaus.  W.W. Norton and Co. (Published in the USA on 15 August 2011; due for UK publication on 7 October 2011). {{ISBN|0-393-08120-6}}.\n*''The Marches: A Borderland Journey between England and Scotland'', Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, 2016, {{ISBN|978-0544108882}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.rorystewart.co.uk Rory Stewart MP] ''Official constituency website''\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = rory-stewart/4137 | hansard = <!-- mr-rory-stewart --> | guardian = 12748/rory-stewart | publicwhip = Rory_Stewart | theywork = rory_stewart | record = Rory-Stewart/Penrith-and-The-Border/951 | bbc = 83410.stm | journalisted = rory-stewart }}\n{{Prone to spam|date=November 2014}}\n{{Z148}}<!--     {{No more links}}\n\n       Please be cautious adding more external links.\n\nWikipedia is not a collection of links and should not be used for advertising.\n\n     Excessive or inappropriate links will be removed.\n\n See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.\n\nIf there are already suitable links, propose additions or replacements on\nthe article's talk page, or submit your link to the relevant category at\nDMOZ (dmoz.org) and link there using {{Dmoz}}.\n\n-->\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Maclean]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br>for [[Penrith and The Border (UK Parliament constituency)|Penrith and The Border]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Neil Hudson (politician)|Neil Hudson]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[James Arbuthnot]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Defence Select Committee|Chair of the Defence Select Committee]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Julian Lewis]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dan Rogerson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State <br/> for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]|years=2015\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Coffey]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Desmond Swayne|Sir Desmond Swayne]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department of International Development|Minister of State for International Development]]|years=2016\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Harriett Baldwin]]|rows=2}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tobias Ellwood]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Minister of State for Africa]]|years=2017\u20132018}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sam Gyimah]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Justice (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Prisons]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert Buckland]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Penny Mordaunt]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for International Development]]|years=2019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Alok Sharma]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ach}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Lammy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[GQ|''British GQ'' Politician of the Year]]|years=2019}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Second May Cabinet}}\n{{Secretary of State for International Development}}\n{{2019 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Rory}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:People educated at The Dragon School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Black Watch officers]]\n[[Category:British diplomats]]\n[[Category:Scottish non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government people]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Scottish Geographical Society]]\n[[Category:Independent members of the House of Commons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Scottish squash player|Rory Stewart (squash player)}}\n{{short description|British Independent politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name                = Rory Stewart\n| honorific-suffix    = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|O7yyBE|OBE|FRSL|FRSGS|size=100%}}\n| image               = Rory Stewart MP (cropped).jpg\n| caption             = Stewart in 2015\n| office              = [[Secretary of State for International Development]]\n| primeminister       = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start          = 1 May 2019\n| term_end            = 24 July 2019\n| predecessor         = [[Penny Mordaunt]]\n| successor           = [[Alok Sharma]]\n| office1             = [[Minister of State for Prisons]]\n| primeminister1      = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start1         = 9 January 2018\n| term_end1           = 1 May 2019\n| predecessor1        = [[Sam Gyimah]]\n| successor1          = [[Robert Buckland]]\n| office2             = [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Minister of State for Africa]]\n| primeminister2      = [[Theresa May]]\n| predecessor2        = [[Tobias Ellwood]]\n| successor2          = [[Harriett Baldwin]]\n| term_start2         = 15 June 2017\n| term_end2           = 9 January 2018\n| office3             = [[Department for International Development|Minister of State for International Development]]\n| primeminister3      = [[Theresa May]]\n| predecessor3        = [[Desmond Swayne|Sir Desmond Swayne]]\n| successor3          = [[Harriett Baldwin]]\n| term_start3         = 17 July 2016\n| term_end3           = 9 January 2018\n| office4             = [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]\n| primeminister4      = [[David Cameron]]\n| predecessor4        = [[Dan Rogerson]]\n| successor4          = [[Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Coffey]]\n| term_start4         = 12 May 2015\n| term_end4           = 17 July 2016\n| office5             = [[Defence Select Committee|Chair of the Defence Select Committee]]\n| predecessor5        = [[James Arbuthnot]]\n| successor5          = [[Julian Lewis]]\n| term_start5         = 14 May 2014\n| term_end5           = 12 May 2015\n| office6             = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br/> for [[Penrith and The Border (UK Parliament constituency)|Penrith and The Border]]\n| predecessor6        = [[David Maclean]]\n| successor6          = [[Neil Hudson (politician)|Neil Hudson]]\n| term_start6         = 6 May 2010\n| term_end6           = 6 November 2019\n| birth_name          = Roderick James Nugent Stewart\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1973|01|03}}\n| birth_place         = [[British Hong Kong]]\n| residence           = [[South Kensington]], [[London]], England\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| spouse              = {{marriage|Shoshana Clark|2012}}\n| children            = 2\n| father              = [[Brian Stewart (diplomat)|Brian Stewart]]\n| party               = [[Independent politician|Independent]] (2019\u2013present)\n| otherparty          = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] (2009\u20132019)<br/>[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (before 1993)\n| education           = [[Dragon School]], [[Eton College]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Balliol College, Oxford]]\n| website             = [http://www.roryforlondon.co.uk www.roryforlondon.co.uk]\n| allegiance          = {{flag|United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland}}\n| branch              = {{army|UK}}\n| rank                = [[File:British Army OF-1a.svg|10px]] [[Second Lieutenant]] (on probation)\n| serviceyears        = 1991 - 1992\n| unit                = [[File:Royal Regiment of Scotland TRF.png|23px]] [[Black Watch]]\n}}\n\n'''Roderick James Nugent Stewart''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE|FRSL|FRSGS}} (born 3 January 1973), known as '''Rory Stewart''', is a British diplomat, author, writer and politician. He served as [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Penrith and The Border (UK Parliament constituency)|Penrith and The Border]] from [[UK general election, 2010|2010]] to [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]] and was [[Secretary of State for International Development|international development secretary]] in 2019.<ref name=Alleg1>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/oct/26/rory-stewart-penrith-tory-seat | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Former royal tutor Rory Stewart selected for safe Tory seat | first=Allegra | last=Stratton | date=26 October 2009 | accessdate=22 May 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.penrithandtheborder.org.uk Penrith and the Border Conservatives] Rory Stewart becomes MP for Penrith and the Border</ref> First elected as a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]], Stewart had the [[September 2019 suspension of rebel Conservative MPs|party whip removed in September 2019]] and subsequently sat as an independent.\n\nAfter education at the [[Dragon School]], [[Eton College]] and [[Balliol College, Oxford]], Stewart became a [[diplomat]], working in [[Indonesia]] and [[Montenegro]]. He left the [[Civil Service (United Kingdom)|civil service]] to undertake a two-year walk across [[Afghanistan]], [[Iran]], [[Pakistan]], [[India]] and [[Nepal]]. He later wrote a best-selling book, ''[[The Places in Between]]'', about his experiences. He subsequently served as a deputy governor for the [[Coalition Provisional Authority]] following the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], and wrote a second book covering this period, ''[[The Prince of the Marshes: And Other Occupational Hazards of a Year in Iraq|Occupational Hazards or The Prince of the Marshes]]''. He later lectured at [[Harvard University|Harvard]] and worked for several [[non-governmental organization|non-governmental organisation]]s, including as executive chairman of the [[Turquoise Mountain Foundation]].\n\nIn 2009, Stewart joined the Conservative Party and was selected as the parliamentary candidate for Penrith and The Border. He was elected to the [[House of Commons]] the following year, and was later elected as chair of the [[Defence Select Committee]]. In 2015, he was appointed to the [[Second Cameron ministry|Cameron Government]] as minister for [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]. From 2016 to 2019, Stewart served in the [[First May ministry|May Government]] as [[Department for International Development|international development minister]], [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Africa minister]], and [[Minister of State for Prisons|prisons minister]].<ref name=\"Rory Stewart MP OBE\">{{cite web|title=Rory Stewart MP OBE|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/rory-stewart|website=GOV.UK|publisher=British Government|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref> In 2019, he was promoted to the cabinet as [[Secretary of State for International Development|international development secretary]]. Stewart stood as a candidate for [[Leader of the Conservative Party (UK)|leader of the Conservative Party]] in the [[2019 Conservative Party (UK) leadership election|2019 leadership contest]], finishing fifth.\n\nOn 3 October 2019, Stewart announced he had resigned from the Conservative Party and that he would stand down as an MP at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|next general election]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/04/rory-stewart-resigns-from-conservative-party|title=Rory Stewart resigns from Conservative party|last=Walker|first=Peter|date=4 October 2019|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 October 2019}}</ref> He is now an independent candidate in the [[2021 London mayoral election]].\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Photograph of Brian Stewart in Malacca in 1953.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Stewart's father, [[Brian Stewart (diplomat)|Brian Stewart]], in 1953]]\nStewart was born in [[British Hong Kong]], the son of [[Brian Stewart (diplomat)|Brian Stewart]] and his wife, Sally Elizabeth Acland Nugent (''n\u00e9e'' Rose). Stewart's father, born in [[Edinburgh]], Scotland, was a colonial official and diplomat who, in the 1970s, was a candidate to become the Chief of the UK's [[Secret Intelligence Service]] or MI6.<ref name=\"NY101108\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/11/15/paths-of-glory-ian-parker|title=Paths of Glory|first=Ian|last=Parker|date=8 November 2010|publisher=|via=www.newyorker.com}}</ref>\n\nHis father's family is from Broich House (built in 1770), which is near [[Crieff]] in [[Perth and Kinross]], Scotland.<ref name=\"satnam\">{{cite news|work=The Times | date=4 December 2013 |last1=Satnam |first1=Sanghera |title=Rory Stewart: Adventurer, academic, MP - PM? |url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/rory-stewart-adventurer-academic-mp-pm/ |accessdate=18 June 2019}}</ref> His maternal grandfather was [[History of the Jews in Britain|Jewish]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/beset-rory-stewart-bagel-boris-johnson-london-mayor-jw3-1.489819|title=Rory Stewart enjoys a bagel and reveals his 'special connection' to the Jewish community|newspaper=The Jewish Chronicle|last=Harpin|first=Lee|date=7 October 2019}}</ref> Stewart spent his early years in [[South Kensington]], London<ref name=\"telegraphKensington\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/0/rory-stewart-boris-complete-chalk-cheese-suspicious-whole-show/|title=Rory Stewart: 'Boris and I are complete chalk and cheese. I\u2019m suspicious of the whole show'|website=The Telegraph|last=Fletcher|first=Martin|date=1 November 2019|access-date=12 January 2020}}</ref> before his family moved to [[Malaysia]]. He returned to Britain for boarding school, being educated at the [[Dragon School]], in Oxford, and [[Eton College]].<ref name=\"NY101108\"/>\n\nAs a teenager, he was a member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/jan/14/rory-stewart-tory-mp-penrith|title=Rory Stewart's awfully big adventure|last=Glover|first=Julian|date=14 January 2010|work=The Guardian|accessdate=22 May 2010|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/11/15/paths-of-glory-ian-parker|title=Paths of Glory|last=Parker|first=Ian|date=7 November 2010|website=The New Yorker|accessdate=12 January 2020|url-access=limited|quote=He had been a member of the Labour Party in his late teens. (A few pounds a year; occasional meetings.)}}</ref> and he has spoken about this in a number of interviews, including on BBC Radio 4's ''Political Thinking'' with [[Nick Robinson (journalist)|Nick Robinson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p07873d3|title=BBC Radio 4 \u2013 Political Thinking with Nick Robinson, The Rory Stewart One|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=18 May 2019}}</ref> During his [[gap year]] in 1991, he was [[commissioned officer|commissioned]] (a short service limited commission) in the [[Black Watch]] for five months as [[second lieutenant]] (on probation).<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=52792 |date=14 January 1992 |page=493 |supp=y}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette |issue=52910 |date=5 May 1992 |page=7744 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\nStewart studied [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]] at [[Balliol College, Oxford|Balliol College]], [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]].<ref name=\"NY101108\" /> While a student at Oxford, Stewart was a private tutor to [[Prince William]] and [[Prince Harry]] during the summer.<ref name=\"NY101108\"/>\n\n==Foreign Office==\nAfter graduating, Stewart joined the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Foreign Office]].<ref>[http://rorystewart.co.uk/index.php/about-me/biography Biography] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100120201645/http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/index.php/about-me/biography |date=20 January 2010 }} Rory Stewart</ref> He served in the [[Embassy of the United Kingdom, Jakarta|British embassy in Indonesia]] from 1997 to 1999, working on issues related to [[History of East Timor|East Timor independence]], and was appointed at the age of 26 as the British Representative to [[Montenegro]] in the wake of the [[Kosovo War|Kosovo campaign]].<ref name=\"NY101108\"/>\n\n===Coalition Provisional Authority===\nAfter the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], Stewart became the [[Coalition Provisional Authority]] Deputy Governorate Co-ordinator in [[Maysan]] and Deputy Governorate Co-ordinator/Senior Advisor in [[Dhi Qar]] in 2003, both of which are provinces in [[southern Iraq]].<ref name=\"NY101108\"/> He was posted initially to the KOSB Battlegroup then to the Light Infantry.<ref name=\"Stewart 2007 87\">{{Cite book|title=Occupational Hazards|last=Stewart|first=Rory|publisher=Picador|year=2007|isbn=|location=London|page=87}}</ref> His responsibilities included holding elections, resolving tribal disputes, and implementing development projects.<ref name=\"Stewart 2007 87\"/> He faced growing unrest and an incipient civil war from his base in a [[Civil-Military Co-operation]] (CIMIC) compound in [[Amarah|Al Amarah]], and in May 2004 was in command of his compound in [[Nasiriyah]] when it was besieged by Sadrist militia.<ref name=\"NY101108\"/> He was awarded an OBE for his services during this period.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/rory-stewart-days-of-hope-and-hubris-6097377.html|title=Rory Stewart: Days of hope and hubris|date=23 June 2006|work=The Independent|access-date=6 March 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nWhile Stewart initially supported the [[Iraq War]], the [[Coalition of the willing|international coalition]]'s inability to achieve a more humane, prosperous state led him in retrospect to believe the invasion had been a mistake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harcourtbooks.com/PrinceOfTheMarshes/interview.asp|title=Interview: Rory Stewart|publisher=Harcourt Trade Publishers|accessdate=2 January 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100215051006/http://www.harcourtbooks.com/PrinceOfTheMarshes/interview.asp|archivedate=15 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Suggested links to MI6 ===\nSome have suggested that Stewart was an employee of the [[Secret Intelligence Service]] (MI6), during his time as a British Representative to Montenegro - allegedly being recruited to MI6 shortly after he graduated from Oxford University.<ref name=\"NY101108\"/><ref name=\"Merrick\">Rob Merrick, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/conversative-leadership-elections-brexit-boris-johnson-rory-stewart-no-deal-a8961896.html Tory leadership: Rory Stewart claims 100 Conservative MPs would rebel against Boris Johnson to stop no-deal Brexit] (17 June 2019): \"He was also asked if, as strongly rumoured he was an MI6 spy when working as a diplomat, but replied: 'No.'\"</ref> Stewart has said that his career progression and his father's work for MI6 might \"give the appearance\" that he worked for MI6,<ref>Jon Swain, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/8116481/Rory-Stewart-concedes-career-gives-appearance-that-he-worked-for-MI6.html Rory Stewart concedes career 'gives appearance' that he worked for MI6], ''Telegraph'' (8 November 2010).</ref> but says he did not work for MI6 while a diplomat.<ref name=\"Merrick\" /> Stewart has acknowledged that due to the [[Official Secrets Act 1989|Official Secrets Act]], even if he had worked for MI6, he would not be able to admit if he had.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/06/18/rory-stewart-denies-spy-mi6-admits-prohibited-law-saying-otherwise/|title=Rory Stewart denies being a spy for MI6 - but admits he is prohibited by law from saying otherwise|last=Reporters|first=Telegraph|date=18 June 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=3 September 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Academic, nonprofit, and advisory work==\nIn late 2004, Stewart became a fellow at the [[Carr Center for Human Rights Policy]] at [[Harvard University]]'s [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]], and in July 2008, he was appointed Ryan Family Professor of Human Rights at Harvard and director of the Carr Center.<ref name=\"NY101108\" />  Stewart left his position at Harvard in 2010 in order to campaign for Parliament.<ref>[https://neubauercollegium.uchicago.edu/events/uc/directors_lecture_with_rory_stewart/ Director's Lecture with Rory Stewart], [[University of Chicago Oriental Institute]].</ref> [[W.W. Norton]] published his book ''Can Intervention Work?'' in 2011.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/bookreviews/8811125/Can-Intervention-Work-by-Rory-Stewart-and-Gerald-Knaus-review.html|title=Can Intervention Work? by Rory Stewart and Gerald Knaus: review|last=Oborne|first=Peter|date=10 October 2011|access-date=6 March 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Stewart has frequently been called on to provide advice on Afghanistan and Iraq to policy-makers, particularly in the United States, United Kingdom, and Canada.<ref name=\"NY101108\"/> In an article in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', he was described as an advisor on Afghan issues to [[U.S. Secretary of State]] [[Hillary Clinton]] and the [[United States Special Envoy|U.S. Special Envoy for Afghanistan and Pakistan]] [[Richard Holbrooke]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/6475289/Rory-Stewart-A-new-kind-of-Tory.html|title=Rory Stewart: A new kind of Tory|last=Praagh|first=Anna van|date=1 November 2009|access-date=12 April 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2005, he joined the [[Turquoise Mountain Foundation]], a human development NGO established by [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], and [[Hamid Karzai]], in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/newsandgallery/focus/the_turquoise_mountain_foundation_becomes_the_prince_s_18th__917731594.html|title=The Turquoise Mountain Foundation becomes The Prince's 18th charity|date=25 March 2007|publisher=Prince of Wales|accessdate=28 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701210105/http://www.princeofwales.gov.uk/newsandgallery/focus/the_turquoise_mountain_foundation_becomes_the_prince_s_18th__917731594.html|archive-date=1 July 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> For this role he relocated to Kabul for the next three years, working to restore historic buildings in the old city of Kabul, managing its finances, installing water supply, electricity, and establishing a clinic, a school and an institute for traditional crafts.<ref name=\"NY101108\" /> Stewart was awarded the [[Royal Scottish Geographical Society]]'s Livingstone medal in 2009 \"in recognition of his work in Afghanistan and his travel writing, and for his distinguished contribution to geography\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsgs.org/awardsandmedals/|title=Medals and Awards|publisher=Royal Scottish Geographical Society|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212031439/http://www.rsgs.org/awardsandmedals/|archivedate=12 February 2010|url-status=dead|accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> Stewart stepped down as executive chairman of the Turquoise Mountain Foundation in May 2010.<ref>[https://archive.today/20130421075510/http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/index.php/declarations-of-interests Declarations of Interests] Rory Stewart</ref>\n\nStewart served for a time on the board of governors of the International Development Research Centre of Canada.<ref>[Board of Governors: November 02, 2010], International Development Research Centre of Canada.</ref>\n\nIn 2009 Stewart appeared before the [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|Senate Foreign Relations Committee]], arguing that Obama's strategy on Afghanistan was 'trying to do the impossible'. He suggested, in an argument that he would later expand in his [[Ted Talk|TED Talk]], that a heavy American military footprint would be counterproductive, alienating Afghans, and that it would be better to reduce the size of the American Army in Afghanistan. This smaller force, he suggested, would be able to handle al-Qaeda, while helping achieve the West's long-term objectives in the country.<ref name=\"WashPost\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/afghanistan-wasnt-destined-to-fail-heres-how-we-could-have-fought-it-better/2019/12/19/b7d4ef66-21e7-11ea-a153-dce4b94e4249_story.html|title=Perspective {{!}} Afghanistan wasn\u2019t destined to fail. Here\u2019s how we could have fought it better.|last=Jaffe|first=Greg|newspaper=The Washington Post|language=en|date=20 December 2019|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> His ideas were rejected by Senators, including future [[Secretary of state (U.S. state government)|Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]].<ref name=\"WashPost\"/>\n\n== Political career ==\n\n===Member of Parliament===\n\nStewart had considered a parliamentary career in the past but only decided to stand when, in the aftermath of the expenses scandal, David Cameron decided to \"reopen the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] candidates' list to anybody who wants to apply\". Stewart has said that his experience in Afghanistan made him a \"Burkean conservative\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/11/15/paths-of-glory-ian-parker|title=Paths of Glory|last=Parker|first=Ian|date=7 November 2010|website=The New Yorker|accessdate=12 January 2020|url-access=limited|quote=\u201cThe experience of running this thing in Afghanistan made me a Burkean conservative,\u201d Stewart said.}}</ref> Having never voted for the Conservatives before (though, against his will, his parents cast his proxy vote for them in the [[2001|2001 general election]], when he was abroad),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/11/15/paths-of-glory-ian-parker|title=Paths of Glory|last=Parker|first=Ian|date=7 November 2010|website=The New Yorker|accessdate=12 January 2020|url-access=limited|quote=Stewart had never voted Conservative, except against his will; in 2001, when he was walking in India, his parents cast his proxy vote for the Conservatives, to his dismay.}}</ref> he joined the party in summer 2009.<ref>{{cite we|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/mar/20/new-tories-cameron-conservatives-election|title= Tories 2.0: Cameron's new breed|website=The Guardian|last=Glover|first=Julian|date=20 March 2010|access-date=11 January 2020|quote=In Penrith and the Border, Rory Stewart is one of those stars who is almost certain of election \u2013 an Etonian Harvard professor with an extraordinary life story and lively media career who joined his party only last summer.}}</ref> Stewart tried for selection for the [[Bracknell (UK Parliament constituency)|Bracknell constituency]] in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/berkshire/8312151.stm |title=Residents choose Tory candidate |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=17 October 2009 }}</ref> but the place went to [[Phillip Lee (politician)|Phillip Lee]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://waugh.standard.co.uk/2009/10/rory-stewart-for-pm.html |title=Rory Stewart for PM? |author=Paul Waugh |work=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=25 October 2009 |access-date=30 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028012122/http://waugh.standard.co.uk/2009/10/rory-stewart-for-pm.html |archive-date=28 October 2009 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Stewart was then shortlisted for the [[Penrith and the Border (UK Parliament constituency)|Penrith and The Border constituency]] and, at an open caucus, selected as the candidate on 25 October 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cumberlandnews.co.uk/ex_diplomat_heads_list_to_succeed_penrith_mp_david_maclean_1_620521?referrerPath=home |title=Ex-diplomat heads list to succeed Penrith MP David Maclean |work=Cumberland News |date=7 October 2009 |access-date=18 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224143747/http://www.cumberlandnews.co.uk/ex_diplomat_heads_list_to_succeed_penrith_mp_david_maclean_1_620521?referrerPath=home |archive-date=24 February 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> He was returned as the MP for the constituency on 6 May 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/nol/shared/election2010/results/constituency/d51.stm |title=Election 2010 \u2013 Penrith & the Border |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=6 May 2010 }}</ref> At the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], Stewart almost doubled his majority in Penrith and the Border from 11,241 to 19,894, the highest majority since the seat was created.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/border/2015-05-08/penrith-and-the-border-results/|title=Penrith and the Border: results|work=ITV News|access-date=6 March 2018|language=en}}</ref> In the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]], he received 60.4% of the vote.\n\nUpon joining the House of Commons, Stewart was elected a member of the [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]], serving until 2014. During his tenure on the Committee he was also chair of the trans-Atlantic group [[Le Cercle]] but did not declare his membership.<ref name=\"Johnston\">{{cite news |last1=Johnston |first1=John |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/news/105448/excl-top-tories-face-questions-over-links |title=EXCL Top Tories face questions over links to secretive foreign affairs group |accessdate=6 November 2019 |publisher=PoliticsHome |date=22 July 2019}}</ref> Stewart also served as the chair of the [[APPG]] for [[Mountain Rescue]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://allparty.org/all-party-groups/mountain-rescue |title=Mountain Rescue |publisher=All Party |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921060217/http://allparty.org/all-party-groups/mountain-rescue |date=24 January 2012 |archivedate=21 September 2013 |accessdate=29 August 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/rory-delivers-keynote-speech-at-uks-bi-ennial-mountain-rescue-conference/ |title=Rory delivers keynote speech at UK's bi-ennial Mountain Rescue conference |publisher=Rory Stewart |date=17 September 2012 }}</ref> and the APPG for Local Democracy<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm/cmallparty/register/local-democracy.htm |title=Local Democracy |work=Register of All-Party Groups |publisher=[[House of Commons]] |date=30 March 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nalc.gov.uk/Latest_News/Rory_StewartMPleadsnationalcampaignforparishfinancing.aspx |title=Rory Stewart MP leads national campaign for parish financing |publisher=National Association of Local Councils |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130716182547/http://www.nalc.gov.uk/Latest_News/Rory_StewartMPleadsnationalcampaignforparishfinancing.aspx |date=30 April 2013 |archivedate=16 July 2013 |accessdate=19 December 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> and was an officer of the APPG for Rural Services.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/rory-stewart-mp-heralds-fuel-rebate-win-for-rural-areas/|title=RORY STEWART MP HERALDS FUEL REBATE WIN FOR RURAL AREAS \u2013 Rory Stewart|date=2 June 2015|work=Rory Stewart|access-date=6 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> He was elected chair of the [[Defence Select Committee]] in May 2014. He left these positions upon his appointment as environment minister.\n\nIn July 2010, Stewart apologised to his constituents after blogging about the relative poverty of rural areas and need for more public services.<ref name=\"beeb\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cumbria-10757609 |title=Tory MP 'sorry' for twine remark |date=25 July 2010 |work=[[BBC News Online]] |accessdate=26 July 2010 }}</ref> He was quoted in the ''[[Scottish Sun]]'' as saying that \"some areas around here are pretty primitive, people holding up their trousers with bits of [[twine]]\".<ref name=\"beeb\" /> He later said that he was making the point that Cumbria's beauty hides its \u201cpockets of poverty\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/11/15/paths-of-glory-ian-parker|title=Paths of Glory|last=Parker|first=Ian|date=7 November 2010|website=The New Yorker|accessdate=12 January 2020|url-access=limited|quote=This summer, a minor tabloid scandal broke after Stewart was quoted in a paper saying, of his constituency, \u201cSome areas around here are pretty primitive, people holding up their trousers with bits of twine and that sort of thing.\u201d (His point, he later said, was that Cumbria\u2019s beauty is misleading; there are \u201chidden pockets of poverty.\u201d)}}</ref> A light-hearted ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' article, \"In praise of ... binder twine\", whilst acknowledging the \"serious effort\" Stewart had made by \"walking hundreds of miles\" to get to know his constituency, concluded that he had simply underestimated the importance of the \"ubiquitous and indispensable\" twine to the rural community.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/jul/27/in-praise-of-binder-twine |title=In praise of ... binder twine |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=27 July 2010 |accessdate=27 July 2010 }}</ref>\n\nHis speech about [[hedgehog]]s in Parliament in 2015 was named by ''[[The Times]]'' and ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' as the best parliamentary speech of 2015 and described by the deputy speaker as \"one of the best speeches [she] had ever heard in Parliament\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2015-11-10/debates/15111048000002/HedgehogConservation?highlight=hedgehog#contribution-15111048002639|title=Hedgehog conservation|date=2015|publisher=Hansard|access-date=22 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/why-llamas-are-the-hedgehogs-best-friend-9nd55k09vsd|title=Why llamas are the hedgehog's best friend|last=Parris|first=Matthew|date=23 December 2015|work=The Times|access-date=6 March 2018|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/foxhunting/12070944/If-only-we-could-consign-Tracey-Crouch-and-her-views-on-foxhunting-to-history.html|title=If only we could consign Tracey Crouch and her views on foxhunting to history|last=Moore|first=Charles|date=28 December 2015|access-date=6 March 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nStewart supported remain in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum on the UK's continued membership of the European Union]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35616946 |title=EU vote: Where the cabinet and other MPs stand |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=22 June 2016 }}</ref> but accepted the result, writing that \"the decision is made, and we should be energetic and optimistic [about it]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/statement-on-brexit/|title=Statement on Brexit|date=5 July 2016|website=Rory Stewart|language=en-US|access-date=15 February 2019}}</ref> Stewart was a prominent supporter of the [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]] negotiated by the prime minister [[Theresa May]],<ref>Rafael Behr, [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/jun/19/may-brexit-deal-not-dead-rory-stewart-boris-johnson May's Brexit deal is not dead \u2013 and only Rory Stewart will admit it], ''The Guardian'' (19 June 2019).</ref><ref>Jessica Elgot, [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/18/rory-stewart-the-black-watch-veteran-shaking-up-the-tory-leadership-race 'This is serious': the unlikely rise of Rory Stewart's pitch to be PM], ''The Guardian'' (18 June 2019): \"his energetic defence of Theresa May\u2019s Brexit deal\"</ref><ref>Andrew Woodcock, [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/conservative-leader-rory-stewart-brexit-citizens-assembly-archbishop-canterbury-a8933741.html Rory Stewart: Tory leadership contender unveils proposal to break Brexit deadlock], ''Independent'' (28 May 2019): \"Mr Stewart, who backed Remain in the 2016 referendum and has been one of the most persistent public defenders of Theresa May\u2019s withdrawal deal\"</ref> arguing that the agreement respects the result of the referendum \"by leaving EU political institutions...and by taking back control over immigration\" while also addressing \"the concerns of the more than 16&nbsp;million who voted remain\" and [[Economic effects of Brexit|protecting the British economy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/on-brexit/|title=ON BREXIT|date=29 November 2018|website=Rory Stewart|language=en-US|access-date=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nStewart led the first backbench motion for expanding [[Consumer Broadband United Kingdom|broadband]] and [[list of mobile network operators of Europe#United Kingdom|mobile]] coverage, securing what was then the largest number of cross-party endorsements for a backbench motion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/category/broadband/|title=Broadband Archives \u2013 Rory Stewart|website=Rory Stewart|language=en-US|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> In a report published in 2011, Stewart won support from the House of Commons [[Culture, Media and Sport Committee]] in calling for mobile phone companies to be forced to provide coverage to 98% of the population,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/98-coverage-for-mobile-broadband/ |title=98% coverage for mobile broadband |publisher=Rory Stewart |date=4 November 2011 }}</ref> and in 2012, his campaign achieved its goal when regulator [[Ofcom]] announced its plans for the auction of fourth generation ([[4G]]) bandwidth for mobile phone services.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/rory-s-campaign-for-rural-mobile-coverage-in-4g-triumph/ |title=Rory's campaign for rural mobile coverage in 4G triumph |publisher=Rory Stewart |date=25 July 2012 }}</ref> In March 2018, [[Ofcom]] announced that the 98% target had been met.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ofcom.org.uk/spectrum/information/cellular-coverage|title=Mobile coverage obligation|website=Ofcom|language=en|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nStewart was successful in securing the [[Cumbria]]n broadband pilot in 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/rural-broadband-pilot-areas-named |title=Rural broadband pilot areas named |publisher=[[Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport]] |date=19 May 2011 }}</ref> and in November 2013, broadband provider [[EE Limited|EE]] cited the support of Government and regulatory policy in announcing that over 2,000 residents and businesses in rural Cumbria were to have access to superfast home and office broadband for the first time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://explore.ee.co.uk/our-company/newsroom/ee-switches-on-superfast-4g-broadband-in-rural-cumbria |title=EE switches on superfast 4G broadband in rural Cumbria |publisher=[[EE Limited]] |date=11 November 2013 }}</ref> In February 2015 Stewart secured more funding in order to continue the broadband roll-out in Cumbria.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/secretary-state-pays-testament-broadband-activist-rory-stewart-mp/ |title=Secretary of State pays testament to broadband activist Rory Stewart MP |publisher=Rory Stewart |date=5 February 2015 }}</ref>\n\nStewart supports fox hunting, and has been marked as a \"For\" voter to upkeep the traditional sport if it were voted on and has been seen at hunt meets in his local area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/foxhunting/11635617/Foxhunting-ban-Will-my-MP-vote-to-repeal-it.html|title=Fox Hunting - Will my MP vote to repeal it?|date=14 July 2015|publisher=The Telegraph}}</ref> He said, \"I'm in favour. It's an important cultural tradition in Cumbria going back many hundreds of years, and hunts like Blencathra and Ullswater are a very important part of rural tradition. It's not something I've ever done myself but it's something I think people should have the right to do.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/16699375.general-election-candidates-our-views-on-fox-hunting/|title=General Election candidates: Our views on fox hunting|publisher=News&Star |date=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Hands Across The Border===\nIn July 2014, Stewart launched [[Hands Across The Border]], a project to construct a [[cairn]] called 'The Auld Acquaintance' as \"a testament to the [[United Kingdom|Union]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://handsacrosstheborder.co.uk/|title=Home|website=Hands Across the Border}}</ref> Built by members of the public, it is close to the [[Anglo-Scottish border|Scotland\u2013England border]] near [[Gretna, Scotland|Gretna.]] During the run up to the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|Scottish independence referendum]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/the-cairn-remains-a-powerful-symbol-of-the-ties-that-bind-us-says-rory-stewart/|title='THE CAIRN REMAINS A POWERFUL SYMBOL OF THE TIES THAT BIND US' SAYS RORY STEWART \u2013 Rory Stewart|date=14 April 2015|work=Rory Stewart|access-date=7 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Stewart said of the project: \"We wanted to come up with a lasting marker of our union, something that future generations will look back at and remember, with deep gratitude, the moment we chose to stay together.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cumbria-28216218 |title=Scottish independence: 'cairn to celebrate union love' |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=9 July 2014 |accessdate=2 August 2014 }}</ref> The campaign received support from several notable public figures in the UK, including actress [[Joanna Lumley]], explorer [[Sir Ranulph Fiennes]], mountaineers [[Alan Hinkes]] and [[Doug Scott]], and historians [[Simon Schama]] and [[David Starkey]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cumbria-28590490 |title=Joanna Lumley shows support for union with Scotland |work=[[BBC News Online]] |date=31 August 2014 |accessdate=2 August 2014 }}</ref> Approximately 100,000 stones were laid on the cairn, many with personal messages.\n\nAt the same time, Stewart hosted a two-part documentary on [[BBC Two]] about the cross-border history of what he called \"Britain's lost middleland\",<ref name=\"Middleland\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0405x9j |title=''Border Country: The Story of Britain's Lost Middleland'' |publisher=[[BBC iPlayer]] |date=26 March 2014 |accessdate=20 December 2017 }}</ref> covering the kingdoms of [[Kingdom of Northumbria|Northumbria]] and [[Kingdom of Strathclyde|Strathclyde]] and the [[Debatable Lands]] of the [[Scottish Marches]] on the [[Anglo-Scottish border]].<ref name=\"Middleland\" />\n\n===Veterans in the justice system===\nIn January 2014, Stewart was asked by [[Chris Grayling]], [[Secretary of State for Justice]], to lead a Government review into the reasons why a number of British veterans become criminal offenders after returning to civilian life.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://veterans-aid.net/mp-rory-stewart-visits-veterans-aid-consult-rehabilitation-needs/|title=Rory Stewart visits VA to consult on rehabilitation needs|date=2 April 2014|work=Veterans Aid|access-date=7 March 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> The review looked at ways in which support and prevention for veterans in the justice system can be improved.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://consult.justice.gov.uk/digital-communications/veterans-within-criminal-justice-system/consult_view |title=Review of Veterans within the Criminal Justice System Call for Evidence |publisher=[[Ministry of Justice (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Justice]] }}</ref> Following his election to Chairman of the [[Defence Select Committee]], Stewart handed over the lead for the review to [[Stephen Phillips (politician)|Stephen Phillips]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-chair-announced-for-veterans-review |title=New chair announced for Veterans Review  |publisher=[[Ministry of Justice (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Justice]] |date=16 June 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Defence Select Committee===\nIn May 2014, Stewart was elected by MPs from all parties as Chairman of the [[Defence Select Committee]]. He was the youngest Chair of a select committee in parliamentary history, as well as the first MP of the 2010 intake to be elected to chair a committee.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27417912|title=Rory roars in|work=BBC News|last=D'Arcy|first=Mark|date=14 May 2014}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/coffeehouse/2014/05/rory-stewart-elected-chairman-of-the-defence-select-committee/|title=Rory Stewart elected Chairman of the Defence Select Committee|work=Spectator Blogs|last=Blackburn|first=David|date=14 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/blighty/2014/05/parliamentary-committees |title=Rory Stewart's new triumph |work=[[The Economist]] |date=14 May 2014 |accessdate=29 August 2014 }}</ref>  In this capacity, Stewart argued strongly for a more vigorous response to [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|Russian aggression in Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/defence-committee/news/report-tndsr/|title=Ukraine must be a wake-up call for NATO \u2013 News from Parliament|website=UK Parliament|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> The committee also argued that Britain's commitments to Iraq and Syria were \"strikingly modest\" and that more should be done.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/feb/05/britain-greater-role-fighting-islamic-state-iraq-mps|title=Britain must play a greater role in fighting Islamic State in Iraq, say MPs|author=Ewen MacAskill|work=The Guardian|date=5 February 2015}}</ref> Under Stewart's chairmanship, the committee produced a report in favour of the proposals for a Service Complaints Ombudsman and also secured an amendment extending the powers of the Ombudsman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/defence-committee/news/report-armed-services-bill/|title=Forces Ombudsman should have further powers, says Defence Committee|work=UK Parliament}}</ref>\n\n===Environment minister===\n[[File:\u03a3\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7 \u0391\u039d\u03a5\u03a0\u0395\u039e, \u039d. \u039e\u03c5\u03b4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7, \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0392\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03cc \u03a5\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03cc \u0395\u03c0\u03b9\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b5\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7 \u0394\u03b9\u03b5\u03b8\u03bd\u03ae \u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03c0\u03c4\u03c5\u03be\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03ae \u03a3\u03c5\u03bd\u03b5\u03c1\u03b3\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03b1, Rory Stewart (\u03a5\u03a0\u0395\u039e, 22.9.2016) (29568248890).jpg|thumb|250px|Stewart pictured with the Greek politician [[Nikos Xydakis (journalist)|Nikos Xydakis]] in September 2016]]\nFollowing the Conservatives' return with an outright majority at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]], Stewart was appointed [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State|Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Department for Environment, Food & Rural Affairs]] (DEFRA), with responsibilities including the natural environment, national parks, floods and water, resource and environmental management, rural affairs, lead responsibility for the [[Environment Agency]], [[Natural England]] and the [[Forestry Commission]], and acting as the secretary of state's deputy on the [[Environment Council]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/rory-stewart|title=Rory Stewart MP \u2013 GOV.UK}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, in his capacity as resource minister, he announced a review into the regulatory and enforcement barriers to growth and innovation in the waste sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/review-into-regulation-and-enforcement-in-waste-sector-launches|title=Review into regulation and enforcement in waste sector launches|work=GOV.UK}}</ref> Stewart as 'floods minister' joined the National Flood Resilience Review, formed in 2016 and chaired by the chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster, [[Oliver Letwin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/national-flood-resilience-review-government-action-to-tackle-floods|title=National Flood Resilience Review: Government action to tackle floods|website=GOV.UK}}</ref> Stewart initiated the Cumbria Floods Partnership in response to [[Storm Desmond]], with a focus on long-term flood defence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/a-country-more-flood-resilient|title=A country more flood resilient|website=GOV.UK}}</ref> The House of Commons cross-party Environment Audit Committee criticised the statement by Stewart that the extra \u00a3700m for flood defence was the result of a \"political calculation\" and that it might not be spent according to the strict value-for-money criteria currently used.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/jun/09/government-failing-to-protect-communities-at-risk-of-flooding-mps-say|title=Government failing to protect communities at risk of flooding, MPs say|first=Damian|last=Carrington|date=9 June 2016|publisher=|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\nAs environment minister he introduced the plastic bag tax which reduced the use of personal bags by 85% in 6 months;<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/plastic-bag-charge-to-protect-marine-environment/|title=Plastic bag charge to protect marine environment \u2013 Rory Stewart|date=7 October 2015|work=Rory Stewart|access-date=7 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and he was responsible for producing the first draft of the 25-year environment plan in which he emphasised, alongside biodiversity and ecosystems, the importance of human cultural features in the landscape, and particularly the conservation of small family sheep farms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.complydirect.com/news/25-year-environment-plan-unveiled-by-the-government/|title=Government's 25-year environment plan|website=www.complydirect.com|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> As Minister responsible for the National Parks, Stewart secured five years of increased funding for [[national park]]s and [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty|AONB]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/call-wild-environment-minister-champions-weekend-walking-trips-national-parks/|title=The call of the wild: Environment Minister champions weekend walking trips in our National Parks \u2013 Rory Stewart|date=29 April 2016|work=Rory Stewart|access-date=7 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> He also ensured the extension of the [[Lake District]] and [[Yorkshire Dales National Park]] and supported the [[World Heritage Site|UNESCO World Heritage]] bid for the Lake District.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/rory-stewart-mp-celebrates-the-lake-districts-world-heritage-success-a-vindication-of-all-that-we-love/|title=RORY STEWART MP CELEBRATES THE LAKE DISTRICT'S WORLD HERITAGE SUCCESS \u2013 \"A VINDICATION OF ALL THAT WE LOVE\" \u2013 Rory Stewart|date=11 July 2017|work=Rory Stewart|access-date=5 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAs floods minister, Stewart oversaw the government's response to the [[2015\u201316 Great Britain and Ireland floods]], including the post-[[Storm Desmond]] floods,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/533457/cumbria-flood-plan-overview.pdf|title=Reducing flood risk from source to sea|last=|first=|date=2016|website=UK Government|access-date=}}</ref> including the reopening of the [[A591]] and the bridge at [[Pooley Bridge]] in the [[Lake District]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/border/update/2016-05-11/floods-minister-lake-district-is-open-for-business/|title=Floods Minister: 'Lake District is open for business'|work=ITV News|access-date=5 March 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Minister for International Development and Africa===\n\nAfter [[Theresa May]] replaced [[David Cameron]] as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]], Stewart was promoted to [[Department for International Development#Ministers|minister of state for international development]] on 17 July 2016.<ref name=\"Rory Stewart MP OBE\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=New ministerial role for MP Rory Stewart|url=http://www.itv.com/news/border/2016-07-17/new-ministerial-role-for-mp-rory-stewart/|website=ITV.com|publisher=ITV|accessdate=5 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nStewart was promoted to become joint Minister for Africa, taking over responsibility for the Foreign Office and its embassies in Africa, as well as the [[Department for International Development]] (DfID) in Africa. In this capacity he visited a number of countries in Africa<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@mafita/uks-minister-for-africa-is-very-happy-with-what-he-saw-at-mafita-cosdec-in-mando-88731aab63c2|title=UK's Minister for Africa is 'very happy' with what he saw at MAFITA COSDEC in Mando|last=Mafita|date=3 August 2017|website=Medium|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2017/07/bruce-british-minister-stewart-push-trade-deals-uganda/|title=Bruce, British Minister Stewart push trade deals in Uganda \u2013 Vanguard News|date=15 July 2017|work=Vanguard News|access-date=7 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.1666568746710395.1073741835.121827597851192&type=3|title=Minister for Africa,Rory Stewart OBE MP Visit to Gaborone {{!}} Facebook|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> and the [[United Nations General Assembly|United National General Assembly]] in [[New York City|New York]] (UNGA).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2017-10-17/debates/F4A1FA8D-BB38-4A09-BB24-CD1B5CE77705/OralAnswersToQuestions|title=Oral Answers to Questions \u2013 Hansard Online|website=hansard.parliament.uk|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> During these trips he held personal meetings with [[Paul Kagame|President Kagame]] of Rwanda,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/paulkagame/albums/72157688998687374/|title=Meeting with UK Minister for Africa, Rory Stewart {{!}} Kigali, 7 November 2017|work=Flickr|access-date=7 March 2018|language=en-us}}</ref> [[Joseph Kabila|President Kabila]] of DRC,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kikayabinkarubi.net/_2017/2017/11/10/tete-a-tete-rory-stewart-joseph-kabila-ce-vendredi-a-kingakati/|title=T\u00eate-\u00e0-t\u00eate Rory Stewart-Joseph Kabila ce vendredi \u00e0 Kingakati \u2013 Le Portail de Barnab\u00e9 KIKAYA|website=kikayabinkarubi.net|language=en-GB|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> [[Edgar Lungu|President Lungu]] of Zambia,<ref name=\"gov.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/uk-minister-for-africa-rory-stewart-visits-zambia|title=UK Minister for Africa Rory Stewart visits Zambia \u2013 GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> [[John Magufuli|President Magufuli]] of Tanzania,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/uk-minister-rory-stewart-announces-450-million-for-development-in-tanzania|title=UK minister Rory Stewart announces $450 million for development in Tanzania \u2013 GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> and [[Emmerson Mnangagwa|President Mnangagwa]] of Zimbabwe.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/Cumbrian-MP-Rory-Stewart-meets-Zimbabwes-new-president-49286e10-e6a4-4b45-bef8-ba09efaa3b24-ds|title=Cumbrian MP Rory Stewart meets Zimbabwe's new president|access-date=7 March 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> In this role Stewart was the driving force behind the British Government's new Africa strategy and pushed for more resources to go into the Foreign Office network in Africa. His most notable trip was to Zimbabwe where he was the first foreign dignitary to be received by President Mnangagwa.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/11/23/zimbabwe-must-reform-mugabe-says-first-british-minster-visit/|title=Zimbabwe must reform after Mugabe, says first British minster to visit country in two decades|date=23 November 2017|work=The Telegraph|access-date=5 March 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> His Zimbabwe policy pressed for political reform, and free and fair elections.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/rory-stewart-returns-from-zimbabwe|title=Rory Stewart returns from Zimbabwe \u2013 GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Prisons minister===\n[[File:London Illegal Wildlife Trade (IWT) Conference 2018 (37331372894).jpg|thumb|Stewart at the London Illegal Wildlife Trade Conference 2018]]\nStewart was appointed [[Minister of State for Prisons]] with responsibility for prisons and probation in England and Wales in January 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/Rory-Stewart-given-new-role-in-cabinet-reshuffle-be354944-2f6f-4c53-91b4-d592e37bebb3-ds|title=Rory Stewart given new role in cabinet reshuffle|access-date=5 March 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> He was appointed in the aftermath of a highly critical leaked report on the state of [[HM Prison Liverpool|HMP Liverpool]], in which the inspector described it as the \"worst prison he had ever seen\" with piles of rubbish, rats, soaring violence and drug use and poor health provision.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/jan/19/liverpool-prison-worst-conditions-inspectors-report|title=Liverpool prison has 'worst conditions inspectors have seen'|last=Travis|first=Alan|date=19 January 2018|work=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> Stewart immediately visited the prison and, testifying before the Justice Select Committee, announced his determination to clean up prisons in England and Wales.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/im-going-back-to-basics-to-clean-up-our-filthy-prisons-vows-minister-rory-stewart-gknxlcm9j|title=I'm going back to basics to clean up our filthy prisons, vows minister Rory Stewart|last=Ford|first=Richard|date=2018|work=The Times|access-date=5 March 2018|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nThis advocacy of a \"back to basics\" approach was recorded in ''The Guardian'', with Stewart writing an opinion piece in the publication, entitled \"I strongly believe we can improve our prisons and make progress\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/feb/17/rory-stewart-reform-prisons-crisis|title=I strongly believe we can improve our prisons and make progress|last=Stewart|first=Rory|date=17 February 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Stewart took the [[Assaults on Emergency Workers (Offences) Private Member's Bill]] through the House of Commons, on behalf of the government, which doubled the maximum sentences for those who attack emergency services personnel and introduced sexual assault as an aggravating factor in sentencing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=2018-04-27b.1142.2&s=Rory+stewart#g1194.1|title=Assaults on police constables: 27 Apr 2018: House of Commons debates \u2013 TheyWorkForYou|website=TheyWorkForYou|language=en|access-date=10 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Ten Prisons Project ====\nIn August 2018, during an interview with ''[[BBC Breakfast]]'', Stewart announced the launch of the Ten Prisons Project. He argued that, despite five years of continuous rise in violence in prisons, it was possible to turn it around. Stewart argued that it could be done through improving perimeter gate security (to catch drugs) and by improving training and support of staff. The key, he said, was to get the basics right. He undertook to create a new prison officer handbook and a new course at the training college for prison officers. Stewart pledged, in the same interview, that he would resign if this project was not successful.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-45214414|title=I'll quit if jails don't improve \u2013 minister|date=17 August 2018|work=BBC News|access-date=17 August 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe twelve months statistics showed a continuing positive trend when, in August 2019, the results from the Ten Prisons Project were published. These showed a 16% drop in the rate of assaults, and a 17% drop in the number of assaults, almost 10% greater than the national trend. At the same time, the percentage of positive results from random mandatory drug tests dropped by 50%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/826775/10-prisons-statistics.pdf|title=Results from the 10 Prisons Project Ad Hoc Statistics|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===International Development Secretary===\nIn May 2019, Stewart was promoted to the cabinet after the dismissal of [[Gavin Williamson]], replacing the new [[Secretary of State for Defence|defence secretary]] [[Penny Mordaunt]] in the [[Department for International Development]]. The position included membership of the political cabinet and the [[National Security Council (United Kingdom)|National Security Council]] and saw Stewart serve as a governor of the [[World Bank]], the [[African Development Bank]], the [[Caribbean Development Bank]] and the Inter-African Development Bank. He was also an alternative governor to the [[European Bank for Reconstruction and Development]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/ministers/secretary-of-state-for-international-development|title=Secretary of State for International Development - GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=24 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July, in his first overseas trip as international development secretary, Stewart visited UK aid funded programmes in Jordan and held meetings with Prime Minister [[Omar Razzaz]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/international-development-secretary-rory-stewart-visits-jordan-in-first-foreign-visit-in-role|title=International Development Secretary Rory Stewart visits Jordan in first foreign visit in role|last=|first=|date=4 July 2019|website=GOV.UK|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 July 2019, Stewart resigned as international development secretary following [[Boris Johnson]]'s victory in the [[2019 Conservative Party leadership election|Conservative Party leadership election]] triggered by the resignation of [[Theresa May]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clifton |first1=Katy |title=Rory Stewart confirms resignation from Cabinet after Boris Johnson's victory |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/rory-stewart-confirms-resignation-from-cabinet-after-boris-johnsons-victory-a4196546.html |accessdate=24 July 2019 |work=[[Evening Standard]] |date=23 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Conservative Party leadership election===\nStewart was a candidate in the [[2019 Conservative Party (UK) leadership election|2019 Conservative leadership election]], announcing his intention to stand in an interview in ''[[The Times]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48140849|title=Rory Stewart: I'd bring country together as PM|work=[[BBC News]]|date=2 May 2019 |accessdate=25 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/rory-stewart-we-need-a-standard-bearer-for-the-middle-ground-it-could-be-me-wvr3k93tf|title=Rory Stewart: We need a standard bearer for the middle ground \u2014 it could be me|date=13 April 2019|work=The Times|access-date=19 August 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> His candidacy was not initially taken seriously, with a piece in the ''[[New Statesman]]''<nowiki/>'s diary stating that he had a single supporter: himself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2019/04/commons-confidential-eurosceptic-hackocracy|title=Commons Confidential: The Eurosceptic hackocracy|website=www.newstatesman.com|language=en|access-date=19 August 2019}}</ref> As ''[[The Guardian]]'' noted: \"his campaign benefited at the start from low expectations, and for days leading up to the first vote his tally of supporters was in single figures. When he met the threshold he looked like the insurgent because so many had assumed he would be knocked out\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jun/18/rory-stewart-the-black-watch-veteran-shaking-up-the-tory-leadership-race|title='This is serious': the unlikely rise of Rory Stewart's pitch to be PM|last=Elgot|first=Jessica|date=18 June 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=19 August 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nAdopting an unconventional campaigning style, Stewart did not focus his attention on Westminster but, instead, went on a series of filmed walkabouts (dubbed 'RoryWalks'), which saw him take to the streets of Britain, talking to voters, to understand their priorities and concerns. These were then uploaded onto social media, with significant success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/the-londoner-rory-stewart-is-proving-to-be-a-master-of-pr-a4155091.html|title=The Londoner: Rory Stewart is proving to be a master of PR|date=30 May 2019|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=19 August 2019}}</ref> On 1 June, [[Kenneth Clarke]] was announced as one of Stewart's MP backers, with other supporters including [[David Lidington]], [[David Gauke]], [[Nicholas Soames]], [[Tobias Ellwood]], [[Gillian Keegan]] and [[Victoria Prentis]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/c696b4d8-8ca2-11e9-a24d-b42f641eca37|title=Rory Stewart pledges grown-up approach in Tory leadership race|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|date=11 June 2019|url-access=subscription|access-date=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nStewart's use of social media later became the subject of controversy when, at a talk at the Emmanuel Centre in October 2019, in the course of discussing his use of social media during this contest, he referred to an encounter in Brick Lane with three \"sort of minor gangsters\". This drew accusations of racism from many politicians, including [[Dawn Butler]], [[David Lammy]] and [[Diane Abbott]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/labour-rory-stewart-racism-london-mayor-minor-gangsters-latest-a9170941.html|title=Labour accuses mayoral candidate Rory Stewart of racism after describing three London men as 'minor gangsters'|newspaper=The Independent|last=Cowburn|first=Ashley|date=25 October 2019|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Stewart apologised the next day, tweeting \"I am very sorry towards the guys and towards everyone else. I was wrong\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/rorystewartuk/status/1187764597937324033?lang=en|title=I am very sorry towards the guys and towards everyone else. I was wrong.|last=Stewart|first=Rory|date=25 October 2019|website=@rorystewartuk|language=en|access-date=2 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nAgainst expectations, on 13 June 2019, Stewart made it through the first parliamentary ballot, gaining 19 votes, two more than the elimination threshold.<ref>{{cite web |title=Full results of the Conservative leadership election \u2013 round 1 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/ng-interactive/2019/jun/13/conservative-leadership-election-full-results |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=13 June 2019 |date=13 June 2019}}</ref> On 16 June, he appeared, as one of the six remaining candidates, in a televised debate on [[Channel 4]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-06-16/tory-leadership-race-tv-debate-conservative-contenders-take-part-channel-4-televised-debate/|title=Dominic Raab refuses to rule out suspending Parliament to push through no deal|website=ITV News |date=16 June 2019 |accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref> He was widely judged to have won the debate, with [[Michael Deacon (journalist)|Michael Deacon]] writing in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' that \"If you were to judge it by the response of the studio audience, Channel 4's debate had only one winner. Rory Stewart got more rounds of applause than any other candidate \u2013 and, at the end, when each took turns to sum up, he was the only candidate to get a round of applause at all\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/06/16/rory-stewart-serious-threat-boris-johnson-tv-debate-proved/|title=Rory Stewart is the only serious threat to Boris Johnson \u2013 and the TV debate proved it|last=Deacon|first=Michael|date=16 June 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=19 August 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 June 2019, he also made it through the second parliamentary ballot, with 37 votes from a threshold of 33, surpassing [[Home Secretary]] [[Sajid Javid]] by four votes; however, following a lacklustre performance in that evening's [[BBC]] debate, he polled just 27 votes in the next day's ballot and was eliminated as the last-placed candidate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48696619|title=Rory Stewart out of Tory leadership race|date=19 June 2019|website=BBC News|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/andrea-leadsom-endorses-boris-johnson-in-tory-leadership-race-11743885|title=LIVE: Raab eliminated as Johnson wins second leadership contest ballot|website=Sky News|language=en |date=18 June 2019 |accessdate=18 June 2019 }}</ref> It was revealed on the same day that Stewart was in talks with [[Michael Gove]] to stop [[Boris Johnson]] becoming Prime Minister.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/rory-stewart-gove-boris-johnson-tory-leadership-contest-race-debate-a8964906.html|title=Rory Stewart in talks with Michael Gove to stop Boris Johnson becoming prime minister|date=19 June 2019|website=The Independent|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Sitting as an independent and resignation===\n{{Main|September 2019 suspension of rebel Conservative MPs}}\nOn 3 September 2019, Stewart and 20 other Conservative MPs voted in favour of MPs taking control of the order paper, as the first step to table a Bill to stop a [[no-deal Brexit]], in the process rebelling against the Government Whip.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2019/sep/03/commons-showdown-looms-in-battle-over-no-deal-brexit-live?page=with:block-5d6ed2f58f0845a5dab7cc88#block-5d6ed2f58f0845a5dab7cc88|title=Boris Johnson to table motion for election after failed vote - as it happened|newspaper=The Guardian|author1=Kate Lyons|author2=Kevin Rawlinson|author3=Andrew Sparrow|author4=Frances Perraudin|date=4 September 2019|quote=MPs back move to allow bill to block no-deal Brexit by majority of 27}}</ref> It had been widely reported in the media that any such action would lead to a withdrawal of the Conservative Whip, and all 21 were told that they had lost it,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/newsbeat-49578000|title=What is removing the whip, filibustering and other Brexit jargon?|website=BBC Newsbeat|date=4 September 2019|accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref> expelling them as Conservative MPs and requiring them to sit as independents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/about/mps-and-lords/principal/whips/|title=Whips|website=Parliament.uk|accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/03/boris-johnson-suffers-commons-defeat-as-tories-turn-against-him|title=Boris Johnson to seek election after rebel Tories deliver Commons defeat|accessdate=4 September 2019}}</ref> If they should decide to run for re-election in a future election, the party would block their selection as Conservative candidates.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/09/04/parliament-whip-removed/|title=Boris Johnson to strip 21 Tory MPs of the Tory whip in parliamentary bloodbath|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|last=Mikhailova|first=Anna|date=4 September 2019}}</ref> Stewart stated that he was informed of this decision by text message, while collecting his ''[[GQ]]'' Politician of the Year Award.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/tory-rory-stewart-sacked-text-19428060|title=Tory Rory Stewart sacked by text while he accepted politician of the year award|last=Bloom|first=Dan|date=4 September 2019|website=mirror|access-date=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt an event on 3 October 2019, Stewart announced he had resigned from the Conservative Party and would stand down as an MP at the [[Next United Kingdom general election|next general election]]. He read out a letter in which a housemaster at [[Eton College]] described [[Boris Johnson]] as being guilty of \"a gross failure of responsibility\". The next day, Stewart confirmed his resignation on [[Twitter]], saying: \"It's been a great privilege to serve Penrith and The Border for the last ten years, so it is with sadness that I am announcing that I will be standing down.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/oct/04/rory-stewart-resigns-from-conservative-party|title=Rory Stewart resigns from Conservative party|last=Walker|first=Peter|date=4 October 2019|website=The Guardian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== London Mayoral candidate ===\nIn October 2019, Stewart announced that he was to stand as an independent in the [[2021 London mayoral election|upcoming London mayoral election]] (initially scheduled to be held in 2020 and later postponed until 2021 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]])<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-51876269|title=Coronavirus: English local elections postponed for a year|work=BBC News|date=13 March 2020|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> against incumbent [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] mayor [[Sadiq Khan]] and Conservative candidate [[Shaun Bailey (London politician)|Shaun Bailey]].<ref>{{cite tweet|user=RoryStewartUK|number=1180054614713999361|date=4 October 2019|title=I am running as an Independent candidate for Mayor of London, and here's why. Please join me in my campaign: join.rorystewart.co.uk #Rory4London|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> On the day he announced his run, Stewart's odds to win were placed at 2/1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/1186873/when-next-london-mayor-elections-who-stand-rory-stewart-candidates-latest-odds|title=When are next London mayor elections? Who will stand against Rory Stewart? Latest odds|last=Whitfield|first=Kate|date=5 October 2019|website=Express.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Writing==\n===Books===\nHis first book, ''[[The Places in Between]]'', was an account of his 36-day solo walk across Afghanistan in early 2002.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.panmacmillan.com/authors/rory-stewart/the-places-in-between|title=The Places In Between|website=Pan Macmillan|language=en-GB|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sattin |first1=Anthony |title=Review: Travel: The Places In Between by Rory Stewart |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/review-travel-the-places-in-between-by-rory-stewart-kcl59q9v3r0 |website=The Times |accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref> It was a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' best-seller, with the newspaper also naming it one of its 10 notable books of 2006 and hailing it as  a \"flat-out masterpiece\".<ref name=\"NY101108\" /> It won the Royal Society of Literature Ondaatje Prize,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rsliterature.org/library-article/two-way-traffic-rory-stewart-on-writing-about-place/|title=Royal Society of Literature \u00bb Two-way traffic: Rory Stewart on writing about place|website=rsliterature.org|language=en-GB|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref> a [[Scottish Arts Council]] prize,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottisharts.org.uk/1/artsinscotland/literature/projects/archive/bookawards2005.aspx|title=Scottish Arts Council \u2013 Book Awards 2005|website=www.scottisharts.org.uk|language=en|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref> the Spirit of Scotland award,<ref name=\"About Rory - Rory Stewart\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/about-rory/|title=About Rory \u2013 Rory Stewart|work=Rory Stewart|access-date=8 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and the {{ill|Premio de Literatura de Viaje Caminos del Cid|es}}.<ref name=\"About Rory - Rory Stewart\"/> It was short-listed for a Scottish Arts Council prize,<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scottisharts.org.uk/1/artsinscotland/literature/projects/archive/bookawards2005.aspx|title=Scottish Arts Council \u2013 Book Awards 2005|website=www.scottisharts.org.uk|language=en|access-date=6 March 2018}}</ref> the [[Guardian First Book Award]]<ref name=\":5\" /> and the [[John Llewellyn Rhys Prize]].<ref name=\":5\" /> The book was adapted into a radio play by [[Benjamin Yeoh]] and was broadcast in 2007 on BBC Radio 4.<ref name=\":6\">{{Citation|last=Benjamin Yeoh|title=Places In Between, The|date=15 February 2007|url=https://archive.org/details/PlacesInBetweenThe|accessdate=6 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nStewart's second book, ''[[Occupational Hazards|The Prince of the Marshes: and other Occupational Hazards of a Year in Iraq]]'', also published as ''Occupational Hazards: My Time Governing in Iraq'', describes his experiences as a Deputy Governorate Co-ordinator in Iraq.<ref name=\"NY101108\" /> The ''New York Times'' critic William Grimes commented that Stewart \"seems to be living one of the more extraordinary lives on record\", but for him the \"real value of the new book is Mr. Stewart's sobering picture of the difficulties involved in creating a coherent Iraqi state based on the rule of law\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-KJ7JInCUR0C&pg=PP3&lpg=PP3&dq=%22rory+stewart%22+AND+%22seems+to+be+living+one+of+the+more+extraordinary+lives+on+record%22|title=The Prince of the Marshes: And Other Occupational Hazards of a Year in Iraq|last=Stewart|first=Rory|date=1 February 2007|publisher=HMH|isbn=9780156033008|language=en}}</ref> Stewart's books have been translated into multiple languages.\n\nIn 2017, Stewart's memoir ''Occupational Hazards'' was the subject of a play at the [[Hampstead Theatre]], written by Stephen Brown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hampsteadtheatre.com/whats-on/2017/occupational-hazards/|title=OCCUPATIONAL HAZARDS|website=Hampstead Theatre|access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nStewart's reflections on the circumstances under which outside military and political intervention in countries' internal affairs may or may not hope to achieve positive results were distilled in a 2011 book, ''Can Intervention Work?'', co-authored with [[Gerald Knaus]] and part of the Amnesty International Global Ethics Series. He has also written about theory and practice of travel writings in prefaces to [[Wilfred Thesiger]]'s ''[[Arabian Sands]]'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/arabiansandspeng00wilf|title=Arabian Sands|last=Thesiger|first=Wilfred|last2=Stewart|first2=Rory|date=25 October 2007|publisher=Penguin Classics|isbn=9780141442075|edition=Reissue|location=London|language=English|url-access=registration}}</ref> [[Charles Montagu Doughty|Charles Doughty]]'s ''[[Travels in Arabia Deserta|Arabia Deserta]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foliosociety.com/book/ADB/travels-in-arabia-deserta|title=Travels In Arabia Deserta {{!}} Folio Illustrated Book|website=www.foliosociety.com|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> and [[Robert Byron]]'s ''[[The Road to Oxiana]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/the-road-to-oxiana-9780195325607?cc=gb&lang=en&|title=The Road to Oxiana|last=Byron|first=Robert|last2=Stewart|first2=Rory|last3=Fussell|first3=Paul|date=18 May 2007|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195325607|location=Oxford, New York}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he published ''The Marches: Border Walks With My Father'' a travelogue about a 1,000-mile walk in the borderlands separating England and Scotland, known as the [[Scottish Marches]], and an extended essay on his father, Brian Stewart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/nov/18/the-marches-rory-stewart-review-brian-border-england-scotland|title=The Marches by Rory Stewart review \u2013 farewell to an imperial class|last=Jack|first=Ian|date=18 November 2016|website=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref> ''The Marches'' was long listed for the [[Orwell Prize]], won the Hunter Davies Lakeland Book of the Year,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jamescropper.com/news/rory-stewart-lakeland-book-of-the-year-winner-for-the-marches|title=Rory Stewart is the 33rd Lakeland Book of the Year Winner for 'The Marches'|website=www.jamescropper.com|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> was a Waterstones Book of the Month,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rorystewart.co.uk/books/the-marches/|title=THE MARCHES \u2013 Rory Stewart|work=Rory Stewart|access-date=8 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and became a [[Sunday Times]] top ten bestseller.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/What-did-your-MP-receive-last-year-Parliaments-gifts-and-donations-list-revealed-4ad1fbe4-c94c-4f70-891d-6a4df83e934e-ds|title=What did your MP receive last year? Parliament's gifts and donations list revealed|last=Barber|first=Caroline|access-date=8 March 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===Articles===\nStewart was a columnist for the ''[[Cumberland and Westmorland Herald]]'', contributing a monthly column,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwherald.com/|title=Latest Headlines|work=cwherald.com}}</ref> and has been a columnist for ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/23/opinion/23stewart.html|title=Opinion {{!}} The 'Good War' Isn't Worth Fighting|last=Stewart|first=Rory|date=22 November 2008|work=The New York Times|access-date=8 March 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> in addition to a contributor to the [[The New York Review of Books|''New York Review of Books'']],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nybooks.com/contributors/rory-stewart/|title=Rory Stewart|website=The New York Review of Books|language=en-US|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref> and the ''[[London Review of Books]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lrb.co.uk/contributors/rory-stewart|title=Rory Stewart \u00b7 LRB|website=www.lrb.co.uk|access-date=8 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Documentaries==\nStewart has written and presented three [[BBC]] documentaries: \n*''The Legacy of Lawrence of Arabia'' (2010).<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00pyrw1 The Legacy of Lawrence of Arabia] BBC Two</ref>\n*''[[Afghanistan: The Great Game \u2013 A Personal View by Rory Stewart]]'' (2012) a documentary in two parts that tells the story of foreign intervention by Britain, Russia and the United States in Afghanistan from the 19th century to the present day, which aired on [[BBC Two]] and which won a [[BAFTA Scotland|Scottish BAFTA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01jk6ch|title=BBC Two \u2013 Afghanistan: The Great Game \u2013 A Personal View by Rory Stewart|work=BBC}}</ref>\n*''Border Country: The Story of Britain's Lost Middleland'' (2014), which investigates the rift created by [[Hadrian's Wall]] and the issues of identity and culture in a region divided by the fabricated border.<ref name=\"Middleland\"/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n\n* In the [[2004 Birthday Honours|2004]] [[Queen's Birthday Honours]], Stewart was appointed an [[Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the Civil Division.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=57315 |date=12 June 2004 |page=23 |supp=y}}</ref>\n* He holds [[Honorary degree|honorary doctorates]] from the [[University of Stirling]] [[Doctor of the University]] (D.Univ) awarded on 23 November 2009. <ref>[http://www.externalrelations.stir.ac.uk/news/news_archive/2009/November2009.php#graduations Graduating Stirling students reap their rewards] University of Stirling, 23 November 2009</ref> and the [[American University of Paris]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aup.edu/news/commencement2011/honor.htm|title=AUP official website|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003153451/http://www.aup.edu/news/commencement2011/honor.htm|archive-date=3 October 2011|url-status=dead|access-date=26 July 2011}}</ref>\n* Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]] (2005).<ref name=\"rsliterature.org\">{{cite web|url=https://rsliterature.org/library-article/two-way-traffic-rory-stewart-on-writing-about-place/|title=Royal Society of Literature \u00bb Two-way traffic: Rory Stewart on writing about place|website=rsliterature.org|language=en-GB|access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n* Fellow of the [[Royal Scottish Geographical Society]] (FRSGS)  (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rsgs.org/inspiring-people/medals-awards/honorary-fellowship/|title=Honorary Fellowship (FRSGS) |work=rsgs.org|access-date=3 May 2019}}</ref>\n* The [[Livingstone Medal]] of the [[Royal Scottish Geographical Society]] (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rsgs.org/inspiring-people/medals-awards/livingstone-medal/|title=Livingstone Medal |website=rsgs.org|language=en-GB|access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n* The Prize del [[Camino del Cid]] (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caminodelcid.org/el-consorcio-informa/noticias/1629917-el-escoces-rory-stewart-gana-el-premio-de-literatura-de-viajes-camino-del-cid-con-su-libro-la-huella-de-babur/|title=Noticias Ruta Camino del CID {{!}}El escoc\u00e9s Rory Stewart gana el Premio de Literatura de Viajes Camino del Cid con su libro La huella de Babur|website=www.caminodelcid.org|language=es|access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n* [[BAFTA Scotland]] Award (2012).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/scotland/awards/ceremony/nominees-winners/british-academy-scotland-awards-winners-in-2012|title=British Academy Scotland Awards: Winners in 2012|website=www.bafta.org|language=en|access-date=5 March 2018}}</ref>\n*In 2019 Stewart was chosen as the ''[[GQ]]'' Politician of the Year.<ref>{{cite news| work=The Telegraph|URL=https://www-telegraph-co-uk.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/09/03/gq-men-year-2019-andrew-scott-rory-stewart-greta-thunberg/|title=GQ Men of the Year 2019: Andrew Scott, Rory Stewart and Greta Thunberg |date=3 September 2019|last=Singh| first=Anita}}</ref>\n* He was sworn in as a member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council]] in 2019 upon his appointment as [[Secretary of State for International Development|International Development Secretary]] in the [[Second May ministry]]. This gave him the [[Honorific|Honorific Title]] \"[[The Right Honourable]]\" for Life.\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 20 January 2008, Stewart appeared on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]].''<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/factual/desertislanddiscs_20082001.shtml Desert Island Discs \u2013 Rory Stewart], [[BBC Radio 4]], 20 January 2008.</ref> On 22 November 2019, he appeared on [[BBC One]]'s ''[[Have I Got News for You]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m000bj21|title=BBC One - Have I Got News for You, Series 58, Episode 6}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, he married American Shoshana Clark, a former employee.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\">{{cite web|title=Conservative MP Rory Stewart to marry American volunteer at his Afghan charity|url=http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/penrith-mp-rory-stewart-to-get-married-next-week-1.1007268?referrerPath=|date=24 October 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130422044457/http://www.newsandstar.co.uk/news/penrith-mp-rory-stewart-to-get-married-next-week-1.1007268?referrerPath=|url-status=dead|archive-date=22 April 2013|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cwherald.com/a/archive/penrith-and-the-border-mp-rory-stewart-and-his-american-bride.399926.html|title=Penrith and the Border MP Rory Stewart and his American bride, ...|website=www.cwherald.com|date=9 November 2012|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> They had their first child in November 2014, a son whom Stewart delivered at home in the absence of medical assistance,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/florence-of-arabia-tamed-by-a-toddler-bspbbvg08|title=Florence of Arabia tamed by a toddler|last=Thring|first=Oliver|date=9 October 2016|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=5 March 2018|language=en|issn=0956-1382}}</ref> and their second child was born in April 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/06/20/rory-stewarts-wife-shoshana-clark-leaves-tory-leadership-race-10017402/|title=Who is Rort Stewart's wife Shoshana Clark as he leaves the Tory leadership race?|newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|last=Milan|first=Aidan|date=20 June 2019|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/06/19/rory-stewart-eton-portrait/|title=Rory Stewart: the 'Florence of Belgravia' years, and the portrait that set him apart from his Eton peers|newspaper=The Telegraph|last=Tominey|first=Camilla|date=19 June 2019|url-access=subscription|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Shoshana and her former husband were volunteering at the Turquoise Mountain Foundation in Afghanistan when she met Stewart.<ref name=eden/>\n\nIn 2012, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' reported that in 2008, [[Brad Pitt]] bought the rights to make a film about Stewart, particularly his time in Afghanistan, with [[Orlando Bloom]] tipped to play the leading role.<ref name=eden>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9434945/How-lover-of-Conservative-MP-Rory-Stewart-left-her-husband-heartbroken-in-Afghanistan.html|title=How lover of Conservative MP Rory Stewart left her husband heartbroken in Afghanistan|first=Richard|last=Eden|date=29 July 2012|publisher=|accessdate=25 May 2019|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2019 Conservative Party (UK) leadership election|2019 Conservative leadership election]], Stewart admitted he had smoked [[opium]] during a [[Persian wedding|wedding in Iran]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mikhailova |first1=Anna |title=Rory Stewart admits smoking opium in Iran as he continues Tory leadership tour of Britain |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2019/05/29/rory-stewart-admits-smoking-opium-spell-iran-tells-telegraph/ |website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |accessdate=9 June 2019 |date=29 May 2019}}</ref> Several other candidates admitted to previous illegal drug use during the leadership contest.<ref>{{cite web |title=Michael Gove admits he was lucky to avoid jail over cocaine use |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48572982 |website=[[BBC]] |accessdate=9 June 2019 |date=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nStewart lives in [[South Kensington]], [[London]]<ref name=\"telegraphKensington\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2019/10/rory-stewart-s-diary-running-london-mayor-life-gang-and-getting-coached-dominic|title= Rory Stewart\u2019s Diary: Running for London mayor, life in a gang, and getting coached by Dominic Cummings|website=NewStatesman|date=30 October 2019|access-date=12 January 2020|last=Stewart|first=Rory|quote=I live in the same house in London that I lived in when I was one.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.onlondon.co.uk/rory-stewart-less-politics-more-action-from-city-hall-if-i-become-london-mayor/|title=Rory Stewart: \u2018Less politics, more action\u2019 from City Hall if I become London Mayor|website=OnLondon|date=27 November 2019|access-date=12 January 2020|last=Wright|first=Charles|quote=And finally, the former Conservative, who has had a family home in Kensington all his life, revealed that he has decided who he\u2019s voting for on December 12, but wasn\u2019t saying any more.}}</ref> as well as [[Dufton]], [[Cumbria]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/gallery/2010/jan/14/general-election-2010-conservatives|title=Would-be Tory MP Rory Stewart|date=14 January 2010|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 May 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He is a member of the [[Athenaeum Club, London|Athenaeum Club]] and the [[Special Forces Club]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Letts |first1= Quentin |author-link1= Quentin Letts |date= 5 Apr 2016 |title= Everything you need to know about Tory MP Rory Stewart |url= https://www.tatler.com/article/everything-you-need-to-know-about-rory-stewart-mp |journal= Tatler  |volume= |issue= |pages= |doi= |access-date= 29 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Books ==\n* ''[[The Places in Between]]'', Picador, 2004\u20132006 <!--See main article for multiple edition information-->\n* ''[[Occupational Hazards: My Time Governing in Iraq]]'', Picador, 2006, {{ISBN|0-330-44049-7}}\n** Published in the US as ''[[The Prince of the Marshes: And Other Occupational Hazards of a Year in Iraq]]'', [[Reed Elsevier|Harcourt]], 2006, {{ISBN|0-15-101235-0}}\n*''Can Intervention Work? Amnesty International Global Ethics Series'', co-authored with Gerald Knaus.  W.W. Norton and Co. (Published in the USA on 15 August 2011; due for UK publication on 7 October 2011). {{ISBN|0-393-08120-6}}.\n*''The Marches: A Borderland Journey between England and Scotland'', Houghton Mifflin Harcourt, 2016, {{ISBN|978-0544108882}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.rorystewart.co.uk Rory Stewart MP] ''Official constituency website''\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = rory-stewart/4137 | hansard = <!-- mr-rory-stewart --> | guardian = 12748/rory-stewart | publicwhip = Rory_Stewart | theywork = rory_stewart | record = Rory-Stewart/Penrith-and-The-Border/951 | bbc = 83410.stm | journalisted = rory-stewart }}\n{{Prone to spam|date=November 2014}}\n{{Z148}}<!--     {{No more links}}\n\n       Please be cautious adding more external links.\n\nWikipedia is not a collection of links and should not be used for advertising.\n\n     Excessive or inappropriate links will be removed.\n\n See [[Wikipedia:External links]] and [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.\n\nIf there are already suitable links, propose additions or replacements on\nthe article's talk page, or submit your link to the relevant category at\nDMOZ (dmoz.org) and link there using {{Dmoz}}.\n\n-->\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Maclean]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br>for [[Penrith and The Border (UK Parliament constituency)|Penrith and The Border]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Neil Hudson (politician)|Neil Hudson]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[James Arbuthnot]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Defence Select Committee|Chair of the Defence Select Committee]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Julian Lewis]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dan Rogerson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State <br/> for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]]|years=2015\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Th\u00e9r\u00e8se Coffey]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Desmond Swayne|Sir Desmond Swayne]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department of International Development|Minister of State for International Development]]|years=2016\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Harriett Baldwin]]|rows=2}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tobias Ellwood]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|Minister of State for Africa]]|years=2017\u20132018}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sam Gyimah]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Justice (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Prisons]]|years=2018\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert Buckland]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Penny Mordaunt]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for International Development]]|years=2019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Alok Sharma]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ach}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Lammy]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[GQ|''British GQ'' Politician of the Year]]|years=2019}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Second May Cabinet}}\n{{Secretary of State for International Development}}\n{{2019 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Rory}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:People educated at The Dragon School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Black Watch officers]]\n[[Category:British diplomats]]\n[[Category:Scottish non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government people]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Scottish Geographical Society]]\n[[Category:Independent members of the House of Commons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Abbyjjjj96", "label": "safe", "comment": "dash", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rory_Stewart"}
{"title_page": "Florida Atlantic University", "text_new": "{{short description|Public university in Boca Raton, Florida}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Florida Atlantic University\n| image_name = Florida Atlantic University seal.svg\n| image_upright = 0.8\n| motto = \"Where Tomorrow Begins\"\n| established = 1961\n| type = [[Public university|Public]]\n| endowment = [[USD|$]]275&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite web | title = The Florida Atlantic University Foundation Endowment | url = https://fauf.fau.edu/sites/default/files/fauf-financial-statement-2016.pdf | access-date = December 24, 2016 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161224164250/https://fauf.fau.edu/sites/default/files/fauf-financial-statement-2016.pdf | archive-date = December 24, 2016 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n| president = John W. Kelly\n| provost = Bret Danilowicz\n| faculty = 1,598<!--from Personnel section, includes both full and part-time faculty and adjuncts--><ref name=\"Facts\"/>\n| staff = 1,499<!--from Personnel section, includes both full and part-time AMP, and staff--><ref name=\"Facts\"/>\n| students = 30,808<ref name=\"Facts\"/>\n| undergrad = 24,687<ref name=\"Facts\"/>\n| postgrad = 4,670<ref name=\"Facts\"/>\n| doctoral = 790\n| city = [[Boca Raton]]\n| state = [[Florida]]\n| country = United States\n| coor = {{coord|26.3712|-80.1017|region:US-FL_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| campus = Urban area<br />850&nbsp;acres (3.5&nbsp;km\u00b2)<br />6 other satellite campuses<ref name=\"FAU Campuses\"/>\n| colors = Blue and red<ref name=\"Colors\"/><br />{{college color boxes|Florida Atlantic Owls}}\n| nickname = [[FAU Owls|Owls]]\n| mascot = Owlsley the [[Owl]]\n| athletics = [[NCAA Division I]] \u2013 [[Conference USA|C-USA]]<br />19 varsity teams\n| affiliations = [[AACSB]], [[NASULGC]]<br />[[National Space Grant College and Fellowship Program|NSGCFP]], [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools|SACS]], [[SUSF]]<br />[[ORAU]]\n| website = {{url|www.fau.edu}}\n| logo = Florida Atlantic University logo.svg\n| logo_size = 175\n}}\n\n'''Florida Atlantic University''' ('''FAU''' or '''Florida Atlantic''') is a [[public university]] with its main campus in [[Boca Raton, Florida]] and satellite campuses in [[Dania Beach, Florida|Dania Beach]], [[Davie, Florida|Davie]], [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], [[Jupiter, Florida|Jupiter]], and [[Fort Pierce, Florida|Fort Pierce]].<ref name=\"FAU Campuses\">{{cite web | url = http://www.fau.edu/explore/campuses.php | title = Explore FAU Campuses | publisher = Florida Atlantic University | accessdate = August 22, 2006}}</ref> FAU belongs to the 12-campus [[State University System of Florida]] and serves South Florida, which has more than five million people and spans more than 100&nbsp;miles (160&nbsp;km) of coastline.<ref name=\"Release\">{{cite press release | title =Early Detection of Developmental Disorders in Babies to be a Focus of New Infant Development Laboratory | publisher = Florida Atlantic University: University Communications and Marketing | date = September 22, 2005 | url =http://www.fau.edu/mediarelations/pressarchive/2005-09/16.php | accessdate = August 22, 2006}}</ref> Florida Atlantic University is [[Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education|classified]] among \"R1: Doctoral Universities \u2013 Very high research activity\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Carnegie Classifications {{!}} FAU Institution Profile|url=http://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=133669 |publisher=[[Indiana University]] |accessdate=April 20, 2018}}</ref> The university offers more than 170 undergraduate and graduate degree programs within its 10 colleges.<ref name=\"Points of Pride\">{{cite web|title=FAU Points of Pride|url=http://www.fau.edu/explore/pride.php|publisher=Florida Atlantic University|accessdate=October 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFlorida Atlantic opened in 1964 as the first public university in [[South Florida metropolitan area|southeast Florida]], offering only upper-division and graduate level courses. Initial enrollment was only 867&nbsp;students, increasing in 1984 when the university admitted its first lower-division undergraduate students.<ref name=\"History 1955-1969\">{{cite web | url = http://www.fau.edu/explore/timeline.php | title = Explore FAU History: Milestones in FAU History (1955\u20131969) | publisher = Florida Atlantic University |accessdate=August 22, 2006}}</ref> {{as of|2018}}, enrollment has grown to over 30,000&nbsp;students representing 140&nbsp;countries, 50&nbsp;states,<ref>FAU Fact Book http://www.fau.edu/explore/quickfacts.php</ref> and the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]]. Since its inception, Florida Atlantic has awarded more than 110,000&nbsp;degrees to nearly 153,160&nbsp;alumni.<ref name=\"Facts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fau.edu/newsdesk/articles/2016-fall-commencement.php|title=2013\u20132014 Quick Facts|website=|publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Office of Institutional Effectiveness & Analysis|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSince 2004, FAU has undertaken an effort to increase its academic and research standings while also evolving into a more traditional university. The university has raised admissions standards, increased research funding, built new facilities, and established notable partnerships with major research institutions.<ref name=\"Facts\"/><ref name=\"Admissions Standards\">{{cite news |last=Restrepo | first=Dan | title=New admissions standards: good for FAU, bad for Florida | publisher=[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]] |date=February 5, 2004 |url=http://www.upressonline.com/2004/02/new-admissions-standards-good-for-fau-bad-for-florida/ | accessdate=August 23, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Partnership\">{{cite news |last=Travis |first=Scott |title=FAU to boost scientific reputation with biomedical science college |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  |date=August 17, 2006 |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2006-08-17/news/0608170090_1_fau-torrey-pines-institute-jupiter-campus |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> Changes include an on-campus stadium, additional on-campus housing, and the establishment of a College of Medicine in 2010.<ref name=\"Double Applications\">{{Cite news | last = Travis | first = Scott | title = FAU's freshman applications double | newspaper = South Florida Sun-Sentinel  | date = March 5, 2011 | url = http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/education/highered/fl-fau-freshman-applications-20110305,0,75875.story | archive-url = https://archive.today/20130203211125/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/education/highered/fl-fau-freshman-applications-20110305,0,75875.story | url-status = dead | archive-date = February 3, 2013 | accessdate = March 5, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Establishment===\nOn July 15, 1961, to meet the burgeoning educational demands of South Florida, the state legislature passed an act authorizing the establishment of a new university in the City of Boca Raton. Florida Atlantic University was built on [[Boca Raton Army Airfield]], a 1940s-era army airbase. During World War II, the airfield served as the [[United States Army Air Corps|Army Air Corps]]' sole radar training facility. The base was built on the existing [[Boca Raton Airport]] and on 5,860&nbsp;acres (23.7&nbsp;km\u00b2) of adjacent land.<ref name=\"Morikami\">{{cite web | title = The Yamato Colony: Japanese Pioneers in Florida | publisher = The [[Morikami Museum and Japanese Gardens]] | url = http://www.morikami.org/index.php?src=gendocs&link=YamatoColony | accessdate =November 4, 2006}}</ref> A majority of the land was acquired from [[Japanese-American]] farmers from the failing [[Yamato Colony, Florida|Yamato Colony]]. The land was seized through [[eminent domain]], leaving many Japanese-Americans little recourse in the early days of World War II.<ref name=\"Morikami\"/>\n\n[[File:LBJ FAU Dedication.gif|left|thumb|President Johnson at the University's dedication]]\nThe airbase was used for radar training, anti-submarine patrols along the coast, and as a stop-over point for planes being ferried to Africa and Europe via South America. The airfield was composed of four runways, still visible on the Boca Campus today and mainly used for parking.\n\nBy early 1947, the military decided to transfer future radar training operations to [[Keesler Air Force Base]] in [[Mississippi]]. The departure of the air force in 1947 would leave Boca Raton Army Airfield essentially abandoned.\n\n===Expansion and growth===\nFlorida Atlantic University opened on September 14, 1964, with an initial student body of 867&nbsp;students in five colleges. The first degree awarded was an honorary doctorate given to President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] on October 25, 1964, at the dedication and opening of the university.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web | url = http://www.fau.edu/explore/history.php| title = Explore FAU History | publisher = Florida Atlantic University | accessdate = September 20, 2007}}</ref> At the time of its opening, there were 350&nbsp;employees, of which 120 were faculty . On-campus housing for students was first added in September 1965, when Algonquin Hall opened.<ref name=\"Admissions Standards\"/><ref name=\"Legacy History\">{{Cite news | last =Burdick | first =Bob | title =All Grown Up: FAU Looks Back and Steps Forward | newspaper =Legacy: A Magazine for Alumni and Friends of Florida Atlantic University | pages = 14\u201315 | volume= 5 | issue=1 | date=September 2007}}</ref>\n\nFlorida Atlantic's history is one of continuing expansion as the university's service population has grown. The university originally served only upper-division and graduate level students, because Florida intended the institution \"to complement the state's community college system, accepting students who had earned their associate degrees from those institutions.\"<ref name=\"Legacy History\"/>\n\nFlorida Atlantic began its expansion beyond a one-campus university in 1971, when it opened its Commercial Boulevard campus in [[Fort Lauderdale]]. Due to a rapidly expanding population in South Florida, in 1984 Florida Atlantic opened its doors to lower-division undergraduate students. The following year, the university added its third campus, in downtown Fort Lauderdale on Las Olas Boulevard.\n\n===Recent history===\n[[File:FAU Social Science Building.jpg|right|thumb|Florida Atlantic University's Social Science Building, [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]] campus]]\nIn 1989, the [[Florida Legislature]] recognized demands for higher education in South Florida by designating Florida Atlantic as the lead state university serving Broward County. To fill this role, the university would establish a campus in [[Dania Beach]] in 1997 and another campus in the City of [[Davie, Florida|Davie]] in western [[Broward County]] in 1990. Florida Atlantic later purchased 50 acres (20 ha) of land in [[Port St. Lucie, Florida|Port St. Lucie]] in 1994 to establish a campus on the [[Treasure Coast]]. This would be the institution's fifth campus. The university continued its expansion in 1999 when it opened its [[Jupiter, Florida|Jupiter]] Campus, named for the late [[John D. MacArthur]]. This campus houses the university's honors college.\n\nFlorida Atlantic University and the [[University of Miami]]'s [[Miller School of Medicine]] established a [[Doctor of Medicine|medical training]] program within the [[Charles E. Schmidt College of Biomedical Science]] in 2004. Plans originally called for the construction of a new [[teaching hospital]] in coordination with [[Boca Raton Community Hospital]] on the main campus. Following successive budgets deficits in 2007, the hospital delayed its participation indefinitely. However, Florida Atlantic later established its own College of Medicine in 2010.<ref name=\"Medical School\">{{cite web|title=UMSM@FAU |publisher=The University of Miami |url=http://www6.miami.edu/UMH/CDA/UMH_Main/0,1770,2600-1;31823-3,00.html |accessdate=May 26, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070422135806/http://www6.miami.edu/UMH/CDA/UMH_Main/0%2C1770%2C2600-1%3B31823-3%2C00.html |archivedate=April 22, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=\"Medical School Questions\">{{cite web | title = UMMSM at FAU Questions | publisher = Florida Atlantic University | url =http://med.fau.edu/biomedical/ummsm_rmc/prospective_students.html#FrequentlyAskedQuestions | accessdate =May 26, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217074138/http://med.fau.edu/biomedical/ummsm_rmc/prospective_students.html|archivedate=February 17, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Establishment of Hospital\">{{cite press release|title=Boca Raton Community Hospital Receives $75 Million |publisher=PNN Online |date=January 30, 2006 |url=http://pnnonline.org/article.php?sid=7242 |accessdate=October 12, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071014170105/http://pnnonline.org/article.php?sid=7242 |archivedate=October 14, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=\"Deficit\">{{cite news | last =Pensa | first = Patty | title =Boca Raton Community Hospital loses $28&nbsp;million, replaces CEO: Plan to build teaching facility set back |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  | date =January 5, 2008}}</ref> The [[Harbor Branch Oceanographic Institution]] (HBOI) also joined the university in 2007, creating Florida Atlantic's seventh campus.<ref name=\"Merged\">{{cite news | title =Editorial: Harbor Branch swimming downstream with FAU | publisher =Scripps Interactive Newspapers Group | date =December 2, 2007 | url =http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2007/dec/02/editorial-harbor-branch-swimming-downstream-fau/ |accessdate=February 22, 2008}}</ref> To bring HBOI into the university family the Florida Legislature allocated $44&nbsp;million to Florida Atlantic to acquire the institution.<ref name=\"Merger 1\">{{cite news |last =Travis | first =Scott | title =Universities fight to save funding for big projects |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  | date =September 23, 2007 <!--|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/local/palmbeach/sfl-flpbudgetcuts0923nbsep23,0,3269119.story (Dead) |accessdate=October 14, 2007 -->}}</ref>\n\nFlorida Atlantic has changed dramatically since its opening in 1964. {{as of|2013}}, there were more than 30,000 students attending classes on seven campuses spread across 120&nbsp;miles (193&nbsp;km). The university consists of ten colleges and employs more than 3,200 faculty and staff. The university's endowment decreased from $182&nbsp;million in June 2008 to $142&nbsp;million in January 2009 due to a worsening economy. However, with the national economic recovery the endowment has increased to $179&nbsp;million by the end of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Florida Atlantic University Foundation Endowment, 2012 NACUBO \u2013 Florida Foundation Comparisons And Discretionary Gifts |publisher=The Florida Atlantic University Foundation |url=http://fauf.fau.edu/cgi-bin/files/pdf/O'Flannery%20FAUF%20Endowments%20Comparison%20April%202013.pdf |accessdate=June 25, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508220542/http://fauf.fau.edu/cgi-bin/files/pdf/O%27Flannery%20FAUF%20Endowments%20Comparison%20April%202013.pdf |archivedate=May 8, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nSince its founding, the university has been led by seven presidents. The university's immediate past president is [[Mary Jane Saunders]]. She was named president on March 3, 2010, then resigned on May 15, 2013. Her appointment followed the resignation of [[Frank T. Brogan|Frank Brogan]]. Brogan, a former [[Lieutenant Governor of Florida]], left the university in late 2009 to become Chancellor of the [[State University System of Florida]]. Past university presidents also included [[Anthony J. Catanese]], Helen Popovich, Glenwood Creech, and Kenneth Rast Williams. On January 17, 2014, the Board of Trustees announced the selection of John W. Kelly, formerly a vice president of [[Clemson University]], to be the seventh president of the university with a starting date of March 1, 2014.\n\n==Academics==\n\n[[File:FAU Sign NW 20th St.jpg|left|thumb|The NW 20th Street entrance sign, [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]] campus]]\nAs of fall 2013, the university's student body consists of 24,686&nbsp;undergraduates, 4,666&nbsp;graduate and professional students, 256 medical students, and 1,451 unclassified students.<ref name=\"Facts\"/> {{as of|2013}}, the undergraduate student body contains 47% ethnic minorities and includes students from more than 180 countries,<ref>{{cite web|title=FAU \u2013 Diversity|url=http://www.fau.edu/diversity/|publisher=Florida Atlantic University|accessdate=January 19, 2014}}</ref> 49&nbsp;states, and the [[District of Columbia]].<ref name=\"Enroll by Country\">{{cite web|title=Headcount Enrollment by Nation of Origin |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Office of Institutional Effectiveness & Analysis |url=http://www.fau.edu/iea/factbook/nation12f.pdf |accessdate=January 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510040540/http://www.fau.edu/iea/factbook/nation12f.pdf |archivedate=May 10, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Enroll by State\">{{cite web|title=Headcount Enrollment by State Residency |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Office of Institutional Effectiveness & Analysis |url=http://www.fau.edu/iea/factbook/state12f.pdf |accessdate=January 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510042519/http://www.fau.edu/iea/factbook/state12f.pdf |archivedate=May 10, 2013 }}</ref> For the undergraduate class of 2012, the acceptance rate was 35% for first-time-in-college students. In 2016 advance registration begins.<ref>{{cite web | title = Florida Atlantic University Academic Calendar 2015 \u2013 2016|publisher=Florida Atlantic University|url=https://www.fau.edu/registrar/pdf/acadcal1516.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe university has ten colleges which altogether offer over 180 different [[bachelor's degree|bachelor's]], [[master's degree|master's]] and [[doctorate|doctoral]] degree programs:<ref name=\"Degrees\">{{cite web | title =University Characteristics, Fall 2008 | publisher =Florida Atlantic University: Office of Institutional Effectiveness & Analysis | url =http://iea.fau.edu/fb05/char8f.pdf | accessdate =December 30, 2011}}</ref> the [[Charles E. Schmidt College of Science]], [[Charles E. Schmidt College of Medicine]], [[Christine E. Lynn College of Nursing]], [[Florida Atlantic University College for Design and Social Inquiry|College for Design and Social Inquiry]], [[Florida Atlantic University College of Business|College of Business]], [[Florida Atlantic University College of Education|College of Education]], [[Florida Atlantic University College of Engineering and Computer Science|College of Engineering and Computer Science]], [[Dorothy F. Schmidt College of Arts and Letters]], [[Harriet L. Wilkes Honors College]], and the Graduate College.<ref name=\"Colleges\">{{cite web | title = Colleges and Degrees | publisher = Florida Atlantic University | url = http://www.fau.edu/explore/CollegesandDegrees.php | accessdate = August 5, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe university offers two honors options: the Harriet L. Wilkes Honors College and a University Scholars Program. The Wilkes Honors College is located on the John D. MacArthur campus in Jupiter, Florida. It offers a [[liberal arts college|liberal arts education]] in the platform of a public university, yet is comparable to a private liberal arts college.<ref name=\"HC FAQ\">{{cite web | title =General FAQ | publisher =Florida Atlantic University: Wilkes Honors College | url =http://www.fau.edu/honors/ | accessdate =October 10, 2007}}</ref> The Boca Raton campus houses the University Scholars Program, which offers special honors seminars, forums, courses, and advanced course substitution for freshmen.\n\nIn recent years, FAU has increased its admission requirements for prospective freshmen. The fall 2013 freshmen profile for the mid-50% includes 3.38\u20133.98 high school [[GPA]], a 22\u201326 [[ACT (examination)|ACT]] composite score, and a 1520\u20131740 SAT total score.<ref>{{cite web|title=FAU \u2013 Freshman Requirements|url=http://www.fau.edu/admissions/freshmanreq.php|publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Office of Undergraduate Admissions|accessdate=January 19, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606045121/http://www.fau.edu/admissions/freshmanreq.php|archivedate=June 6, 2013}}</ref> Following a surge in the university's popularity, in early 2009, the university created its first wait-list for undergraduate enrollment. After February 15, 2009, applicants for admission in the 2009\u20132010 academic year were required to have a 3.5 GPA or an SAT score of 1600 to be considered for admission.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/schools/sfl-flpfau0309sbmar09,0,1135008.story |title=Florida Atlantic University goes to waiting list for first time as enrollment jumps |last=Travis |first=Scott |date=March 9, 2009 |newspaper=\"South Florida Sun-Sentinel\"  |accessdate=April 8, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312033435/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/schools/sfl-flpfau0309sbmar09%2C0%2C1135008.story |archivedate=March 12, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe average class size at FAU for undergraduates is 33&nbsp;students, and for graduate classes, 12&nbsp;students. The student-to-faculty ratio is 20:1.<ref name=\"Facts\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Travis |first=Scott |title =Florida universities grow in number of students, but not in faculty, data shows | newspaper=floridatrend |url=http://www.floridatrend.com/article/9497/florida-universities-grow-in-number-of-students-but-not-in-faculty }}</ref> The top three undergraduate majors by enrollment are [[Education|elementary education]], accounting, and management, respectively. The top three graduate majors by enrollment are [[business administration]], educational leadership, and accounting, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fall 2010 Entering Graduate Student Characteristics|url=http://iea.fau.edu/factbk/trangrad10f.pdf|publisher=Florida Atlantic University|accessdate=January 19, 2014}}</ref> The average age for first-year students is 18; however, the average age for all undergraduates is 24 and the average age for graduate students is 33.<ref name=\"Facts\"/> The average 4-year graduation rate for first-time, non-transfer students is 14% while the 6-year graduation rate is 39%.<ref name=\"Grad Rates\">{{cite web |title=IPEDS Data Feedback Report 2009 |publisher=Integrated Postsecondary Education Data System |url=http://iea.fau.edu/inst/feedback09.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=December 7, 2009}}</ref>\n\nFlorida Atlantic University has long ranked as the most racially, ethnically and culturally diverse institution in [[State University System of Florida|Florida's State University System]]. ''U.S. News & World Report'' has ranked FAU the 27th most diverse university in the nation.<ref name=\"Diversity\">{{cite web|title=FAU Diversity|url=http://www.fau.edu/diversity/|publisher=Florida Atlantic University|accessdate=January 19, 2014}}</ref> Florida Atlantic University students come from all 50 states, every county in Florida, and more than 180 countries. Enrichment opportunities include internships, hands-on research, study abroad experiences, and 310 clubs and campus organizations.<ref>{{cite web|title=FAU \u2013 Points of Pride|url=http://www.fau.edu/explore/pride.php|publisher=Florida Atlantic University|accessdate=January 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Lifelong Learning Society operates programs that serve the educational interests of more than 19,000&nbsp;senior citizens by providing classes focusing on subjects of specific interest, and audit options for regular university classes.<ref name=\"Life Long\">{{cite news | last =Travis | first =Scott | title =Florida Atlantic University's Lifelong Learning enrollment surges |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  | date =February 10, 2008}}</ref> Under the university's Commercial Music Program, Hoot/Wisdom Recordings was created in 2002, enabling students to work in all creative and business aspects of the music industry. This program generated music that landed a Top 10&nbsp;spot on the [[Billboard charts|Billboard's Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles Sales Chart]] during its first week of release.<ref name=\"Hoot 1\">{{cite web|title=FAU hits a high note with music studies |publisher=Oxendine Publishing |url=http://www.floridaleader.com/best2003_15.htm |accessdate=May 26, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070404170734/http://floridaleader.com/best2003_15.htm |archivedate=April 4, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hoot Records\">{{cite press release | title =FAU Graduate's Masters Thesis Produces Billboard Hit |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: University Communications and Marketing | date =February 26, 2007 | url = http://fau.edu/mediarelations/Releases0207/020719.php |accessdate =May 25, 2007}}</ref> The university's two-story [[trading room]] simulator, located in the College of Business, provides hands-on financial education using 25&nbsp;dual-monitor computers and can accommodate 50&nbsp;people at one time. A second lab provides full audio/visual connectivity and 25&nbsp;additional workstations. Florida Atlantic allows local financial businesses to use the Trading Room for training.<ref name=\"Trading Room\">{{cite web |title=Students experience Wall Street in FAU's two-story trading room simulator| publisher=Florida Atlantic University |url=http://www.fau.edu/explore/homepage-stories/2007-04trading.php |accessdate=May 26, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Rankings===\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| Forbes = 557<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/colleges/florida-atlantic-university/ |work=Forbes |title=Florida Atlantic University |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20111224065239/http://www.forbes.com/colleges/florida-atlantic-university/ |archivedate=December 24, 2011 |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref>\n| USNWR_NU = 281\n| Wamo_NU = 241\n| THE_WSJ = 601\u2013800\n| USNWR_W = 924\n| THES_W = 801\u20131000\n}}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR graduate school rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR Grad School Rankings\">{{cite magazine|title=Florida Atlantic University \u2013 U.S. News Best Grad School Rankings|magazine=U.S. News & World Report|accessdate=June 4, 2017|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/florida-atlantic-university-133669/overall-rankings}}</ref>\n|-\n| Nursing: Doctorate\n| 44\n|-\n| Nursing: Master's\n| 45\n|}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR departmental rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR Grad School Rankings\"/>\n|-\n| Fine Arts\n| 198\n|-\n| Psychology\n| 112\n|-\n| Public Affairs\n| 96\n|-\n| Rehabilitation Counseling\n| 24\n|-\n| Social Work\n| 141\n|-\n| Speech\u2013Language Pathology\n| 183\n|}\n\nFor 2019, Florida Atlantic University was classified as a second-tier university by the ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'s'' rankings of \"Best Colleges.\"<ref name=\"US News\">{{cite magazine|title=America's Best Colleges 2013: Florida Atlantic University |magazine=U.S. News & World Report |url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/florida-atlantic-university-1481 |accessdate=September 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608040457/http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/florida-atlantic-university-1481 |archivedate=June 8, 2012 }}</ref> ''U.S. News'' ranks universities into one of two tiers, with one being the highest, based on how they compare with other colleges in a peer assessment, retention rates, student selectivity, faculty resources, financial resources, graduation rates, and the amount of alumni giving.<ref name=\"Best Colleges\">{{cite magazine|last=Morse |first=Robert J. |author2=R. Morse |author3=S. Flanigan |title=America's Best Colleges 2008: How We Do the Rankings |magazine=U.S. News & World Report |date=August 17, 2007 |url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/usnews/edu/college/rankings/about/rank_brief.php |accessdate=October 17, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011012149/http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/usnews/edu/college/rankings/about/rank_brief.php |archivedate=October 11, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The university was named one of the 146 \"Best Southeastern Colleges\" in the United States by the [[Princeton Review]].<ref name=\"Princeton Review\">{{cite web | title =Florida Atlantic University | publisher =The Princeton Review | url =http://www.princetonreview.com/college/research/profiles/schoolsays.asp?category=1&listing=1022927&LTID=1&intbucketid= | accessdate =July 15, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Princeton Review 2\">{{cite web | title =Florida Atlantic University: Rankings & Lists | publisher =The Princeton Review | url =http://www.princetonreview.com/college/research/profiles/rankings.asp?listing=1022927&LTID=1&intbucketid= | accessdate =October 17, 2007}}</ref> Princeton Review also recognized FAU's business program by naming the College of Business to their list of \"Best 296 Business Schools\" for 2009.<ref>{{cite news | title = FAU business school named one of best in U.S. | publisher = Scripps Interactive Newspapers Group | date = October 30, 2008 |url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2008/oct/30/fau-business-school-named-one-best-us/ |accessdate =December 17, 2008}}</ref> For 2011, Florida Atlantic was ranked 249th in the nation by ''[[Washington Monthly]]''.<ref name=\"WM Rankings\">{{cite magazine | title =The Washington Monthly College Rankings | magazine =The Washington Monthly | url =http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/college_guide/rankings_2011/national_university_rank_2nd_page.php | accessdate =October 7, 2011 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20130706132723/http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/college_guide/rankings_2011/national_university_rank_2nd_page.php | archivedate =July 6, 2013 | df =mdy-all }}</ref> The magazine based its rankings on the following three criteria: \"how well a university performs as an engine of social mobility (ideally helping the poor to get rich rather than the very rich to get very, very rich), how well a university does in fostering scientific and humanistic research, and how well a university promotes an ethic of service to country.\"<ref name=\"WM Criteria\">{{cite magazine|title=The Washington Monthly's Annual College Guide |magazine=The Washington Monthly |url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2006/0609.collegeguide.html |accessdate=July 15, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070718083449/http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2006/0609.collegeguide.html |archivedate=July 18, 2007  }}</ref> The university was also ranked 28th in the United States and fourth in Florida by ''[[The Hispanic Outlook in Higher Education]]'' magazine for awarding 738 bachelor's degrees to [[Hispanic]] students during the 2006\u20132007 academic year.<ref name=\"Hispanic Students\">{{cite news | last =Tyko | first =Kelly | title =Florida schools top the nation in awarding degrees to Hispanics | publisher =Scripps Interactive Newspapers Group | date =June 9, 2008 | url =http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2008/jun/09/florida-schools-top-nation-awarding-degrees-hispan/ | accessdate =June 12, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Hispanic Students detail\">{{cite news | title = Boca Raton: FAU awards 738 degrees to Hispanics in 2006\u2013'07 |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  |date=July 15, 2008 <!--|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/community/news/palmbeach/sfl-flpdig07151pnjul15,0,4835017.story (Dead) |accessdate=July 15, 2008 -->}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\n[[File:Schmidt Biomedical Center.jpeg|right|thumb|The [[Charles E. Schmidt College of Medicine]] on Florida Atlantic University's [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]] campus. The sculpture is \"Orgonelle,\" designed by Rob Fisher.<ref>{{cite web |title=Art in State Buildings |url=https://www.fau.edu/facilities/asb/fau_asb/br635_638.php |website=Florida Atlantic University |publisher=Florida Atlantic University |accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>]]\nFlorida Atlantic is classified by [[the Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching]] as a research university with high research activity.<ref name=\"Carnegie\">{{cite web |title=Florida Atlantic University | publisher = The Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching |url=http://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=133669 |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> The university has established notable partnerships with major research institutions such as [[the Scripps Research Institute]], the [[Torrey Pines Institute for Molecular Studies]], and the [[Max Planck Society]].<ref name=\"Partnership\"/><ref name=\"Research\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fau.edu/research/ovp/index.php |title=Message from the Vice President |publisher=Florida Atlantic University |accessdate=January 31, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070518233053/http://www.fau.edu/research/ovp/index.php|archivedate=May 18, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Max Planck\">{{cite news|last=Johnston |first=John |title=Planck to plant Palm Beach county roots |newspaper=Boca Raton News |date=July 25, 2008 |url=http://www.bocanews.com/local-news/8787planck-to-plant-palm-beach-county-roots.htm |url-status=dead |accessdate=August 1, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517142149/http://www.bocanews.com/local-news/8787planck-to-plant-palm-beach-county-roots.htm |archivedate=May 17, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe university is the home of two centers of excellence: the Center of Excellence in Biomedical and Marine Biotechnology and the Center for Ocean Energy Technology. These centers have been selected by Florida's Emerging Technology Commission to receive grants to continue and increase their operations. Florida Atlantic beat out some of Florida's top research universities, including the [[University of Florida]] and [[Florida State University]], for the initial money from the state.<ref name=\"Research Week\">{{cite news | last = Reed | first = Charlie | title =FAU Research Week starts today | publisher = Scripps Interactive Newspapers Group | date = April 2, 2007 <!--|url=http://www1.tcpalm.com/tcp/local_news/article/0,2545,TCP_16736_5458129,00.html (Dead) |accessdate=May 26, 2007 -->}}</ref>\n\nSince receiving its startup funding, Florida Atlantic has secured additional funds from other sources, including federal and private research grants. As a result, both centers have engaged in academic and industry partnerships, combining expertise in [[Marine electronics|ocean engineering]], [[biotechnology|marine biotechnology]], [[functional genomics]], [[proteomics]], and [[bioinformatics]]. Researchers, scientists, and students at the centers are designing technologies to explore the sea, harvest [[renewable energy]], discover new medicines, and develop new therapeutics to combat agents of [[bioterrorism]].<ref name=\"Center for Ocean\">{{cite press release | title = FAU to Receive $5 Million to Establish The Florida Center of Excellence in Ocean Energy Technology | publisher = Technology Daily News | date =November 18, 2006 <!--|url=http://www.technologynewsdaily.com/node/5240 (Dead) |accessdate=October 12, 2007 -->}}</ref><ref name=\"Research list\">{{cite web | title = About the Center | publisher = Center of Excellence in Biomedical and Marine Biotechnology | url = http://www.floridabiotech.org/ | accessdate = October 12, 2007}}</ref> As a result of this research, in 2007 the university and [[Lockheed Martin]] announced an exclusive licensing agreement to develop and produce a rapidly deployable and autonomous mooring buoy system for military and scientific uses.<ref name=\"Lockheed Martin\">{{cite press release | title = Florida Atlantic University and Lockheed Martin to Develop Autonomous Mooring Buoy System for Military and Scientific Use | publisher = Lockheed Martin | date = May 17, 2007 | url = http://www.fau.edu/mediarelations/Releases0407/040710.php | accessdate = October 11, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, the [[United States Department of Energy]] designated FAU as one of three national centers for ocean energy research and development. The Southeast National Marine Renewable Energy Center joins centers in the Pacific Northwest ([[University of Washington]] and [[Oregon State University]]) and in Hawaii ([[University of Hawaii]]). The Southeast National Marine Renewable Energy Center is undertaking research and development of technologies capable of generating renewable power from ocean currents and ocean thermal energy.<ref name=\"DOE Designates New National Marine Renewable Energy Center for Ocean Energy Research\">{{cite press release|title=DOE Designates New National Marine Renewable Energy Center for Ocean Energy Research |publisher=U.S. Department of Energy |date=August 3, 2010 |url=http://apps1.eere.energy.gov/news/progress_alerts.cfm/news_id=20025 |accessdate=February 11, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909023635/http://apps1.eere.energy.gov/news/progress_alerts.cfm/news_id%3D20025 |archivedate=September 9, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nThe university houses both an Imaging Technology Center and a [[NASA]] Imaging Technology Space Center. Located in the College of Engineering and Computer Science, the centers specialize in digital imaging research and development for use in both government and commercial applications in the areas of [[medical technology]], [[surveillance]], communications, education, [[inspection]], [[observation|scientific observation]], manufacturing, visual recognition and identification, and motion picture and [[digital video]]. The Florida Atlantic Imaging Technology Center is developing a curriculum for [[digital imaging]] and processing, thereby establishing Florida Atlantic as the only university in the nation to offer this technical concentration.<ref name=\"Tech Concentration\">{{cite web | title =Florida Atlantic University Legislative Budget Request For 2005\u201306 | publisher =Florida Atlantic University | date =July 2, 2003 | url =http://wise.fau.edu/financial/files/Narrative-2005-06-Request.doc | accessdate =October 11, 2007 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20071025182432/http://wise.fau.edu/financial/files/Narrative-2005-06-Request.doc | archive-date =October 25, 2007 | url-status =dead | df =mdy-all }}</ref> The NASA Imaging Technology Center is one of 12&nbsp;NASA Research Partnership Centers throughout the nation which develop dual-use research and development with the participation of NASA and other related industries in the US. The center occupies two sets of laboratories and administrative offices, one on Florida Atlantic's main campus in Boca Raton, the other at the Fort Lauderdale campus.<ref name=\"Research list\"/>\n\nFlorida Atlantic is affiliated to the [[Research Park at Florida Atlantic University]], with properties in Deerfield Beach and Boca Raton. The Research Park provides outside research facilities for companies which enable them to interact with the university community and its facilities, resources, and expertise. The Research Park operates the Technology Business Incubator;<ref>{{cite web |title=Research Park at Florida Atlantic University: Technology Business Incubator |publisher=Florida Atlantic Research & Development Park |url=http://www.research-park.org/Technology-Business-Incubator |accessdate=November 12, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112045752/http://www.research-park.org/Technology-Business-Incubator |archivedate=November 12, 2014  }}</ref> The incubator works to foster the start-up and growth of technology-based businesses, seeking to scale them and build relationships for them with the university. The Boca Raton campus is also home to the Center for Complex Systems and Brain Sciences, which includes the Machine Perception and Cognitive Robotics Laboratory\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:Living Room Theaters.jpg|thumb|right|FAU's Living Room Theaters Complex, located in the Culture and Society Building in [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]]]]\nFlorida Atlantic University is a distributed university located on seven campuses spread across [[Palm Beach County|Palm Beach]], [[Broward County|Broward]], and [[St. Lucie County|St. Lucie]] counties. The region is home to more than three million people.<ref name=\"Release\"/><ref name=\"Dist Univ\">{{cite web|title=Department of Exercise Science and Health Promotion (ESHP) |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: College of Education |url=http://www.coe.fau.edu/eshp/ |accessdate=July 13, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629080736/http://www.coe.fau.edu/eshp/ |archivedate=June 29, 2007 }}</ref> The university's main campus is located in the City of Boca Raton in Palm Beach County. The county is also home to the John D. MacArthur Campus located in the [[Jupiter, Florida|City of Jupiter]]. In addition to its campuses in [[Palm Beach County, Florida|Palm Beach County]], the university operates three campuses in the [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]] cities of [[Dania Beach, Florida|Dania Beach]], [[Davie, Florida|Davie]], and [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]]. Florida Atlantic University also operates two campuses in the [[St. Lucie County, Florida|St. Lucie County]] cities of [[Port St. Lucie, Florida|Port St. Lucie]] and [[Fort Pierce, Florida|Fort Pierce]]. In addition to students who attend classes on the universities campuses, there are 1,612&nbsp;distance learning students who conduct their studies over the internet or through other means. These students account for 6% of the university's student body.<ref name=\"Campus Enroll\">{{cite web | title = Headcount Enrollment by Campus | publisher = Florida Atlantic University: Office of Institutional Effectiveness & Analysis | url = http://iea.fau.edu/fb05/camenr8f.pdf | accessdate = December 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nFlorida Atlantic is a signatory of the American College & University presidents Climate Commitment Association for the Advancement of Sustainability in Higher Education. This commits the institution to ensuring all new construction projects meet the [[U.S. Green Building Council]]'s [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED)]] Silver standards.<ref>{{cite web | title = Implementation Profile for Florida Atlantic University | publisher = American College & University Presidents Climate Commitment Association | date = November 12, 2010 | url = http://acupcc.aashe.org/ip/168/ | archive-url = https://archive.today/20120701180546/http://acupcc.aashe.org/ip/168/ | url-status = dead | archive-date = July 1, 2012 | accessdate = March 5, 2011 }}</ref> In 2011, the College of Engineering and Computer Science Building was LEED Platinum certified.\n\n===Palm Beach County campuses===\n\n====Boca Raton====\n{{see also|FAU Stadium}}\n[[File:FAUStadium night.jpg|thumb|left|[[FAU Stadium]] in [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]]]]\nFlorida Atlantic University's main campus in [[Boca Raton]] was established on the remnants of a World War II American [[United States Army Air Corps|Army airbase]] in 1964. Spanning 850&nbsp;acres (3.5&nbsp;km\u00b2), the site is located between the cities of [[Palm Beach, Florida|Palm Beach]] and Fort Lauderdale. The campus was designated a [[burrowing owl]] sanctuary in 1971 by the [[Audubon Society]]. The owls find the campus appealing because there are few predators, due to the university's proximity to the Boca Raton Airport, and because the campus was originally cleared of vegetation when operating as an airbase during World War II. \"The feisty bird, traditionally associated with wisdom and determination, serves as the university's mascot.\"<ref name=\"FAU Trad\">{{cite web | title =FAU Traditions | publisher =Florida Atlantic University: Athletics Department | url =http://fausports.cstv.com/trads/fau-trads.html | accessdate =July 15, 2007 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20090530002813/http://fausports.cstv.com/trads/fau-trads.html | archive-date =May 30, 2009 | url-status =dead | df =mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Boca Raton campus is home to a wide variety of university programs and facilities. These facilities are labs and classrooms, housing for students, a 6,000-gallon shark tank for aquatic research, a movie theater, athletic and recreational facilities, and the student-run record label Hoot/Wisdom Recordings.<ref name=\"Boca Raton campus\"/> In addition to academic and cultural programs, the campus also houses Florida Atlantic's [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[Florida Atlantic Owls|athletics program]]. The main campus serves approximately 19,077&nbsp;students, or 70% of the university's student body, offering a number of academic programs, activities, and services.<ref name=\"Facts\"/><ref name=\"Campus Enroll\"/><ref name=\"Boca Raton campus\">{{cite web | title = FAU Boca Raton | publisher = Florida Atlantic University | url = http://www.fau.edu/explore/boca_raton.php | accessdate = April 2, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe Boca Raton campus also houses a number of other institutions, including the [[Alexander D. Henderson University School|A. D. Henderson University School]], [[Florida Atlantic University High School|FAU High School]], one of two Florida Atlantic University Research Parks, and the Lifelong Learning Society.\n\n====Jupiter\u2013John D. MacArthur Campus====\nIn addition to the Boca Raton campus in southern [[Palm Beach County]], Florida Atlantic University operates a campus in northern Palm Beach County, in [[Jupiter, Florida|Jupiter]]. The John D. MacArthur Campus, named after businessman and philanthropist [[John D. MacArthur]], was established in 1999 to serve residents of central and northern Palm Beach and southern [[Martin County, Florida|Martin]] counties. The MacArthur Campus occupies 45&nbsp;acres (0.18&nbsp;km\u00b2), upon which are eight classroom and office buildings, a library, a 500-seat auditorium, two residence halls, a dining hall, museum building, and utility plant.<ref name=\"About Jupiter\">{{cite web|title=About FAU at Jupiter |publisher=Florida Atlantic University |url=http://wise.fau.edu/jupiter/about-fau/ |accessdate=July 8, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629130441/http://wise.fau.edu/jupiter/about-fau/ |archivedate=June 29, 2007 }}</ref> The MacArthur Campus also houses the [[Harriet L. Wilkes Honors College]], [[The Scripps Research Institute|Scripps Florida]], FAU Brain Institute, and the [[Max Planck Florida Institute for Neuroscience]]. The campus serves approximately 1,262&nbsp;students, or 4% of the university's student body.<ref name=\"Campus Enroll\"/>\n\n===Broward County campuses===\n\n====Dania Beach\u2013SeaTech====\nThe [[Dania Beach, Florida|Dania Beach]] Campus, also known as SeaTech, was founded in 1997 as a state-funded Type&nbsp;II research center.<ref name=\"Dania Campus\">{{cite web | title = Dania Beach Campus | publisher =Florida Atlantic University | url =http://wise.fau.edu/broward/daniabeach/ | accessdate =June 24, 2007}}</ref> The institute is part of Florida Atlantic's Department of Ocean Engineering which was founded in 1965 as the first ocean engineering undergraduate program in the nation. The campus is located on 8&nbsp;acres (0.03&nbsp;km\u00b2) of land between the Atlantic Ocean and the [[Intracoastal Waterway]]. SeaTech is home to university faculty and students engaged in sponsored ocean engineering research and development in the areas of [[acoustics]], marine vehicles, [[hydrodynamics]] and [[physical oceanography]], marine materials and [[Nanotechnology|nanocomposites]].<ref name=\"Dania Campus\"/> The Dania Beach Campus serves approximately 70&nbsp;students, roughly 1% of the university's total student body.<ref name=\"Campus Enroll\"/>\n\n====Davie====\n[[File:FAU Davie Campus.jpg|thumb|right|Senator James A. Scott Education and Science Building on the FAU [[Davie, Florida|Davie]] campus]] The [[Davie, Florida|Davie]] Campus of Florida Atlantic University was established in 1990 on 38 acres (0.15&nbsp;km\u00b2) of land in western Broward County.<ref name=\"Davie Campus\">{{cite web | title = Davie Campus | publisher =Florida Atlantic University | url =http://wise.fau.edu/broward/davie/ | accessdate =June 24, 2007}}</ref> The campus serves approximately 3,488&nbsp;students, or 13% of the Florida Atlantic student body, making it the university's second largest campus by enrollment.<ref name=\"Campus Enroll\"/> The campus features a multi-story [[Student activity center|student union]] with offices for [[student government#United States|student government]] and student organizations, a multipurpose area and student lounge, a bookstore, and cafeteria.<ref name=\"Student Union\">{{cite press release | title =FAU Constructs Student Union at Davie Campus |publisher =Florida Atlantic University: University Communications and Marketing | date =May 7, 2007 | url =http://fau.edu/mediarelations/Releases0507/050706.php | accessdate =July 10, 2007}}</ref> The union also contains a student health center that provides medical services and health counseling.<ref name=\"Student Union\"/> Davie is also the home of \"environmental research initiatives focused on [[Everglades]] restoration.\"<ref name=\"FAU Broward\">{{cite web|title=About FAU in Broward |publisher=Florida Atlantic University |url=http://wise.fau.edu/broward/about.php |accessdate=June 24, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070522221218/http://wise.fau.edu/broward/about.php |archivedate=May 22, 2007 }}</ref> FAU colleges offering courses at the FAU Davie campus include Design and Social Inquiry; Arts and Letters; Business; Education; Nursing; and Science. The campus is located on [[Broward College]]'s Central Campus. Students may enter BC as freshmen and graduate from FAU with undergraduate degrees in over 14 disciplines. More than 315,000 square feet of carefully designed classrooms, laboratories and faculty, staff and student offices are located on this campus along with a shared-use, 112,000 square-foot FAU/BC library designed for the 21st century.\n\nOther support facilities include a shared Childcare Center, a student Wellness Center and a multi-service Student Union. The campus also offers a rich and varied program of student activities provided by the Division of Student Affairs. Students have all of the services they require for career counseling, wellness, testing and evaluation, tutoring, health services, student government and financial aid, among others. Like a small college within a large university, the Davie Campus is seen as a \"model\" branch campus for the state of Florida and the nation.<ref name=\"Davie Campus\" />\n\n====Fort Lauderdale====\nThe university has two buildings in downtown [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], both of which are considered part of one Fort Lauderdale campus. The Askew Tower (AT) and the Higher Education Complex (HEC) on Las Olas Boulevard. The campus offers courses in communication, [[graphic design]], architecture, and urban and regional planning.<ref name=\"Fort Lauderdale\">{{cite web | title = Fort Lauderdale Campus | publisher =Florida Atlantic University | url =http://wise.fau.edu/broward/fortlauderdale/ | accessdate =June 24, 2007}}</ref> The campus is home to approximately 900&nbsp;students or 3.2% of the university's student body.<ref name=\"Campus Enroll\"/>\n\n===St. Lucie County campuses===\n\n====Fort Pierce\u2013Harbor Branch Oceanographic Institution====\nIn addition to the Treasure Coast Campus, Florida Atlantic University operates a campus in [[Fort Pierce, Florida|Fort Pierce]] at the [[Harbor Branch Oceanographic Institution]]. Harbor Branch merged with the university in 2007 to become the HBOI at FAU.<ref name=\"Facts\"/><ref name=\"FAU Campuses\"/><ref name=\"Merged\"/> The Florida Legislature allocated $44&nbsp;million for the university to acquire the institution and its 600-acre (2.4&nbsp;km\u00b2) campus.<ref name=\"Merger 1\"/><ref name=\"Merger\">{{cite news | last =Reed | first =Charlie |title=Work begins on merger plan for Harbor Branch and FAU | publisher = Scripps Interactive Newspapers Group |date =May 17, 2007 <!--|url=http://www.tcpalm.com/tcp/local_news/article/0,2545,TCP_16736_5540530,00.html (Dead) |accessdate=May 27, 2007 -->}}</ref><ref name=\"HBOI into FAU\">{{cite news|last=Bierman |first=Noah |title=Harbor Branch institute becoming part of Florida Atlantic University |work=Herald-Tribune |date=June 18, 2007 |url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20070618/NEWS/706180563 |accessdate=July 9, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070917192418/http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20070618/NEWS/706180563 |archivedate=September 17, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n===Former Campuses===\n\n====Port St. Lucie\u2013Treasure Coast Campus====\nTreasure Coast Campus of Florida Atlantic University operated through a partnership with [[Indian River State College]] (IRSC). Florida Atlantic purchased 50&nbsp;acres (0.2&nbsp;km\u00b2) of land in Port St. Lucie in 1994. At the end of Spring 2012 class term, Florida Atlantic University ended offering classes at the Port St. Lucie campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fau.edu/explore/campuses.php|title=FAU \u2013 Campuses & Maps|work=fau.edu}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n{{main|Florida Atlantic Owls}}\nFlorida Atlantic's 18&nbsp;varsity sports teams, the [[Florida Atlantic Owls|Owls]], compete in NCAA's Division I. The Owls recently joined [[Conference USA]] for the 2013\u201314 season. The university's athletics program began in 1979, when Florida Atlantic first started sponsoring intercollegiate teams.<ref name=\"Athletics HF\">{{cite press release | title =FAU Inducts Seven into Inaugural Athletic Hall of Fame |publisher = Florida Atlantic University: FAU Athletics | date =October 27, 2006 | url =http://fausports.cstv.com/genrel/100906aaa.html | accessdate =July 12, 2007}}</ref> Since then, the university has worked to expand the quality of its intercollegiate program by attracting coaches such as [[Howard Schnellenberger]], [[Matt Doherty (basketball)|Matt Doherty]], [[Rex Walters]], [[Lane Kiffin]], and [[Mike Jarvis]]. In 2006, the athletic department was ranked 79th in the nation by the [[National Association of Collegiate Directors of Athletics]] (NACDA). Along with ''[[USA Today]]'' and the United States Sports Academy, NACDA recognized the university for its Division&nbsp;I athletic programs and accomplishments.\"<ref name=\"79th Ranking\">{{cite press release |title =University MRI Continues Commitment with FAU Football | publisher =Florida Atlantic University: University Communications and Marketing | date =August 2, 2006 | url =http://fau.edu/mediarelations/Releases0806/080602.php |accessdate =July 12, 2007}}</ref> This ranking placed Florida Atlantic in the top 24% of 326&nbsp;NCAA Division&nbsp;I universities.<ref name=\"79th Ranking\"/> The university's colors are FAU Blue, FAU Red, and FAU Silver.<ref name=\"Colors\">{{cite web | url = http://www.fau.edu/branding/FAU_VSM.pdf| format = PDF | title = Florida Atlantic University: Visual Standards Manual Version 2.1 (updated 9/2008) |publisher = Florida Atlantic University: University Communications and Marketing | accessdate = April 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[2008 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|In 2008]], the [[Florida Atlantic Owls football|Florida Atlantic football team]] finished six wins and six losses in regular season play and was invited to the [[2008 Motor City Bowl|Motor City Bowl]].<ref name=\"Motor City Bowl\">{{cite news | last = Hutton | first = Ted | title = FAU loves bowl as a gift |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  | date = December 15, 2008 <!-- |url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/college/fau/sfl-flspfau15sbdec15,0,744256.story (Dead) |accessdate=December 17, 2008 -->}}</ref> The Owls defeated [[Central Michigan University]] 24\u201321, increasing their bowl record to two wins and zero losses.<ref>{{cite news | last = Hutton | first = Ted | title = Owls beat Central Michigan 24\u201321 in Motor City Bowl |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  |date=December 27, 2008 <!--|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/college/fau/sfl-motorcity,0,6513765.story (Dead) |accessdate=January 7, 2009 -->}}</ref> During the previous season, the [[2007 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|football team]] beat [[Troy University]] in the final game of regular season play to become Sun Belt Co-Champions and receive an invitation to the [[New Orleans Bowl]]. In just the seventh year of the football program's history, and the third year playing in Division I, Florida Atlantic set NCAA records by both becoming the youngest program ever to receive an invitation to, and win, a [[2007 New Orleans Bowl|bowl game]].<ref name=\"Fastest Ever\">{{cite news | last =Hutton | first =Ted | title =Owls bowl-bound |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  | date =December 2, 2007 <!--|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/college/fau/sfl-flspfau02sbdec02,0,6253873.story (Dead) |accessdate=December 4, 2007 -->}}</ref><ref name=\"NCAA Record\">{{cite news | last =Shain |first=Jeff |title=Florida Atlantic secures its first bowl berth |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |date=December 1, 2007 <!-- |url=http://www.kansascity.com/467/story/386090.html (Dead) |accessdate=December 4, 2007 -->}}</ref><ref name=\"Another NCAA Record\">{{cite news | last =Hutton| first =Ted| title =FAU storms to victory in New Orleans Bowl |newspaper=Orlando Sentinel  |date=December 22, 2007 <!--|url =http://www.dailypress.com/topic/orl-fau2207dec22,0,6813064.story (Dead) |accessdate=July 10, 2008 -->}}</ref> As a result of the New Orleans Bowl the university has seen a surge in school spirit.<ref name=\"Spirit Surge\">{{cite news | last = Zinn | first = Dori | title = Bleeding Red and Blue: School spirit at FAU remains high despite a losing football season | publisher = [[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]] | date = October 16, 2008 | url = http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2008/10/16/CurrentIssue/Bleeding.Red.And.Blue-3486934.shtml | accessdate = December 17, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717171639/http://www.upressonline.com/2.9209/bleeding-red-and-blue-1.1238246 |archivedate=July 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn past seasons the Owls have garnered a number of accolades for their accomplishments. During the 2006\u20132007 season, the men's basketball team was noted as \"one of the [[Sun Belt Conference]]'s top offensive teams,\" with a \"scary offense\" that earned it the reputation of the \"best shooting team in the conference\".<ref name=\"HS FAU\">{{cite news | last =Shugart | first =Kim | title =Jaguars seek to rebound against high-scoring FAU | publisher =Alabama Live LLC | date =February 21, 2007 <!--|url=http://www.al.com/sports/mobileregister/index.ssf?/base/sports/1172053012189330.xml&coll=3 (Dead) |accessdate =July 12, 2007 -->}}</ref> In 2010, the men's basketball team defeated its first-ever [[Southeastern Conference]] opponent [[Mississippi State University]] 61\u201359<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mstateathletics.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=16800&ATCLID=205039259|title=State Cagers Drop Nailbiter To FAU, 61\u201359|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref> as well as [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]] opponent the [[University of South Florida]] 50\u201342<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gousfbulls.com/ViewArticle.dbml?&DB_OEM_ID=7700&ATCLID=205042808&SPID=2923&SPSID=36686|title=Bulls Drop Defensive Struggle to FAU, 50\u201342|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref> en route to a 21\u20139 overall record and claimed the [[Sun Belt Conference]] title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fau.edu/explore/homepage-stories/2011_02basketbllwin.php|title=FAU \u2013 Homepage Stories|website=fau.edu|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe baseball team was also recognized by the NCAA as ranking in the Top&nbsp;10 in five team categories. The team was also ranked third in the nation in home runs per game (1.66) and in [[slugging percentage]] (.563).<ref name=\"BB High\">{{cite news | title =Baseball Ranks High in NCAA Stats | publisher =CSTV Networks, Inc | date =April 11, 2007 | url =http://www.cstv.com/sports/m-basebl/stories/041107acy.html | accessdate =July 12, 2007}}</ref> In 2010, the Owls baseball team was 37\u201324 (21\u20139) and claimed their first Sun Belt Conference regular-season title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fauowlaccess.com/articles/194/fau-baseball-team-winning-sun-belt-title-is-our-no-2-story-of-the-year.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716033752/http://www.fauowlaccess.com/articles/194/fau-baseball-team-winning-sun-belt-title-is-our-no-2-story-of-the-year.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 16, 2010|title=FAU baseball team winning Sun Belt title is our No. 2 Story of the Year|website=fauowlaccess.com|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Traditions===\n[[File:New Rat's Mouth.jpg|thumb|left|The \"Rat's Mouth\" student tailgating area located at the grassy area directly in front of  FAU Stadium. In 2015, this area was moved to Lot 5 behind the stadium.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Gregory |title=NewsTop Stories Confirmed, Lot Five will remain 2015 tailgate location |url=https://www.upressonline.com/2015/06/confirmed-lot-five-will-remain-2015-tailgate-location/ |website=University Press |publisher=University Press |accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref>]]\nFlorida Atlantic University is home to a number of sports-related traditions and school spirit organizations.\n\nEvery fall before the first football game of the season, FAU's Student Government Association sponsors the annual football \"Bonfire\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fauowlaccess.com/blogs/owlthingsconsidered/2010/08/thursdays-daily-briefing-blazers-beware-faus-bonfire-is-tonight.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110405190343/http://www.fauowlaccess.com/blogs/owlthingsconsidered/2010/08/thursdays-daily-briefing-blazers-beware-faus-bonfire-is-tonight.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 5, 2011|title=Thursday's Daily Briefing: Blazers beware, FAU\u2019s bonfire is tonight|website=fauowlaccess.com|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://upressonline.com/2011/08/fourth-annual-bonfire-postponed/|title=Fourth annual bonfire postponed|first=Ryan|last=Cortes|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref> where the opposing team's mascot is burned in effigy. This event typically includes a concert and a speech by the university's head football coach.\n\nAlso in football, Florida Atlantic challenges its rival [[Florida International]] (FIU) is the annual [[Shula Bowl]]. This intercollegiate football game is named after legendary coach [[Don Shula]]; so named because at the time of its inception, both head coaches, Florida Atlantic's [[Howard Schnellenberger]] and Florida International coach [[Don Strock]], had worked under Shula at some point during their careers. Even though both universities have since moved on to new head coaches, the Shula Bowl is still played. As a home game, the competition takes place at university's own stadium; as an away game, the bowl is played at [[FIU Stadium]] in Miami.<ref name=\"FAU Trad\" />\n\nFor basketball, Florida Atlantic celebrates the \"Red Hot Madness and Stroll Off\" pep rally that introduces fans to the team and coaches, host a number of basketball-related contests such as 3-point shoot-outs and slam dunk competitions, and features step performances by the school's [[National Pan-Hellenic Council]] fraternities and sororities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2011-10-20/sports/fau-basketball-102011_1_greg-gantt-brett-royster-sun-belt|title=FAU Midnight Madness Thursday at FAU Arena|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref> During the regular season, the \"Bury the Burrow in Red\" event calls for Florida Atlantic students to wear as much red as possible and fill the [[FAU Arena|Burrow]], the university's multi-purpose arena, during the annual [[college basketball|basketball]] rivalry game between Florida Atlantic and Florida International University.<ref>{{cite press release | title = Support FAU Basketball at 'Bury the Burrow in Red' on Feb. 10 | publisher = Florida Atlantic University: University Communications and Marketing | url = http://www.fau.edu/communications/internal/update/archive/07Feb/univnews.html#4 | accessdate = April 7, 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090625085013/http://www.fau.edu/communications/internal/update/archive/07Feb/univnews.html#4 | archivedate = June 25, 2009 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe official spirit group supporting Florida Atlantic athletics is the \"prOWLers\". The group began in February 2002 to support the men's basketball program during the team's run for the [[Atlantic Sun Conference|Atlantic Sun Conference Championship]]. The group is funded by the Student Alumni Association, and can now be found at most sporting events cheering for Florida Atlantic.<ref>{{cite web | title =prOWLers \u2013 The rowdiest students at FAU | publisher =Florida Atlantic University: Athletics Department | url =http://fausports.cstv.com/trads/prowlers.html | accessdate =July 15, 2007 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20080228021328/http://fausports.cstv.com/trads/prowlers.html | archive-date =February 28, 2008 | url-status =dead | df =mdy-all }}</ref> The prOWLers are joined by the Owl Rangers,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.owlrangers.com/|title=Owl Rangers \u2013 Wow, It's Owls|website=owlrangers.com|accessdate=May 6, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519193842/http://owlrangers.com/|archive-date=May 19, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> a fan group that paints their bodies in the Florida Atlantic school colors. The hOWLetts are a student club that attend gameday events and assist in recruiting athletes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fau.collegiatelink.net/organization/howlett-club/about|title=Owl Central -|website=fau.collegiatelink.net|accessdate=May 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426002246/http://fau.collegiatelink.net/organization/howlett-club/about|archivedate=April 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSince 2002, Florida Atlantic students have been using Owl Fingers (the \"OK\" hand sign) to show school pride and wish the athletic teams luck during football point after attempts (PATs) and basketball free throws.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://upressonline.com/2011/10/we-have-spirit-yes-we-do-we-have-spirit%E2%80%A6wait-we-do/|title=We have spirit, yes we do, we have spirit\u2026wait, we do?|first=Jessica|last=Cohn-Kleinberg|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref> The Florida Atlantic University Athletics Department has chosen to use Owl Fingers as part of its \"Salute the Hoot\" 2012 marketing campaign that encourages students to \"proudly raise the hand salute that depicts the eyes of the owl, FAU's mascot.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fausports.com/genrel/020912aaa.html|title=FAU Launches 'Salute the Hoot' Campaign|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://upressonline.com/2012/02/with-added-development-and-expansion-time-for-fau-community-to-give-a-hoot/|title=With added development and expansion, time for FAU, community, to give a hoot|first=Rolando|last=Rosa|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Residential life===\n[[File:FAU Parliament Hall.JPG|thumb|Florida Atlantic University's Parliament Hall on the [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]] campus]]\nResidential housing at Florida Atlantic University is available on the Boca Raton and John D. MacArthur campuses. \"All full-time freshmen are required to reside in university housing,\" however, \"exemptions from this policy are made for students who: are 21 or older by the first day of class, reside with parent(s) or legal guardian(s) within a {{convert|50|mi|km|adj=on}} radius of the Boca Raton campus, or are married.\"<ref name=\"Housing Info\">{{cite web|title=General Information |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Department of Housing and Residential Life |url=http://www.fau.edu/housing/General_Information/index.php?mainlinks=3 |accessdate=April 2, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090412010644/http://www.fau.edu/housing/General_Information/index.php?mainlinks=3 |archivedate=April 12, 2009 }}</ref> {{as of|2011}}, 4,555&nbsp;students live on-campus in Boca Raton.<ref name=\"Facts\"/><ref name=\"On-Campus Housing\">{{cite web|title=On-Campus Housing |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Office of Institutional Effectiveness & Analysis |url=http://www.fau.edu/iea/factbook/house11.pdf |accessdate=February 11, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510042518/http://www.fau.edu/iea/factbook/house11.pdf |archivedate=May 10, 2013 }}</ref> The Wilkes Honors College on the MacArthur Campus requires all students live on-campus within its two residence halls, however, exceptions are made for students who are 26&nbsp;years of age, married, or have dependent children.<ref name=\"On-Campus Housing Jupiter 1\">{{cite web|publisher=Florida Atlantic University: The Harriet L. Wilkes Honors College |title=Residential Life |url=http://www.fau.edu/divdept/honcol/residential.htm |accessdate=October 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070608034745/http://www.fau.edu/divdept/honcol/residential.htm |archivedate=June 8, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"On-Campus Housing Jupiter 2\">{{cite web|publisher=Florida Atlantic University: The Harriet L. Wilkes Honors College |title=Your New Home |url=http://www.fau.edu/divdept/honcol/residential_brochure.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=October 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025182506/http://www.fau.edu/divdept/honcol/residential_brochure.pdf |archivedate=October 25, 2007 }}</ref> {{as of|2011}}, there are 231&nbsp;students residing on-campus at the honors college.<ref name=\"On-Campus Housing\"/>\n\n[[File:FAU Innovation Village.JPG|right|thumb|Florida Atlantic University's Innovation Village student apartments on the [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]] campus]]\nBoca Raton's on-campus housing facilities are: Indian River Towers (opened 2001), Heritage Park Towers (opened 2004), Glades Park Towers (opened 2007), Parliament Hall (opened 2013), University Village Apartments (UVA), and Innovation Village Apartments (IVA) (opened 2011). Heritage Park and Glades Park Towers each offer 602 beds with 96 single rooms.<ref name=\"Glades Park\">{{cite web | title =Joint Audit and Finance/Strategic Planning Committee | publisher =FAU Board of Trustees | date =June 13, 2007 | url =http://www.fau.edu/bot/files/061307_AFSPA-1.pdf | format = PDF | accessdate =June 24, 2007}}</ref> UVA and IVA exclusively serve upperclassmen while the other residence halls exclusively serve freshmen students. The university also offers upper-division undergraduate and graduate student housing in the Business and Professional Women's Scholarship House for women with a strong academic background.<ref name=\"BPW House\">{{cite web|title=Business & Professional Woman's Scholarship House |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Department of Housing and Residential Life |url=http://www.fau.edu/housing/Our_Residence_Halls_and_Apartments/BPW_House.php |accessdate=April 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090322090849/http://www.fau.edu/housing/Our_Residence_Halls_and_Apartments/BPW_House.php |archivedate=March 22, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Housing Options\">{{cite web|title=Our Residence Halls and Apartments |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Department of Housing and Residential Life |url=http://www.fau.edu/housing/Our_Residence_Halls_and_Apartments/index.php?mainlinks=4 |accessdate=April 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090412014557/http://www.fau.edu/housing/Our_Residence_Halls_and_Apartments/index.php?mainlinks=4 |archivedate=April 12, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOne of the newest residences on the Boca Raton campus is the Innovation Village Apartments (IVA), consisting of two buildings: IVA North and IVA South. It is a 1,200-bed apartment-style housing facility for upperclassmen, graduate, and medical students. It offers amenities that one would find in a high-rise apartment complex: lounges, retail dining, fitness centers, a pool/cabana, a volleyball court, common areas, and more. The facility opened in fall 2011.<ref name=\"New Grad Apts\">{{cite web|title=BT-651 Innovation Village Apartments Phase I |publisher=Florida Atlantic University Architect & Vice President for Facilities |date=November 20, 2007 |format=PDF |url=http://www.fau.edu/facilities/uavp/programs-folder/600_Bed_Innov_Village_Program_for_Signiture_11.20.07.pdf |accessdate=February 25, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080719161311/http://www.fau.edu/facilities/uavp/programs-folder/600_Bed_Innov_Village_Program_for_Signiture_11.20.07.pdf |archivedate=July 19, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301170817/http://www.upressonline.com/building-the-future-1.2137444|author=Persaud, Chris |url=http://www.upressonline.com/building-the-future-1.2137444|title= Building the future: Stadium and apartment buildings construction to begin in April|archivedate=March 1, 2010|publisher=University Press|date=January 18, 2010}}</ref> FAU's newest residence hall is Parliament Hall, a lakeside freshmen housing facility offering 614 beds, a fitness center, lounges, retail dining, and views of the nearby Atlantic Ocean from top floors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2013-08-28/news/fl-brf-parliament-0828-20130828_1_anthony-barbar-fau-student-affairs|title=FAU opens $46&nbsp;million Parliament Hall dorm|work=tribunedigital-sunsentinel}}</ref>\n\nWithin its existing residential life programs, Florida Atlantic offers a number of Learning Communities for freshmen and students with similar interests and concentrations. Participants meet people with similar interests, live on the same floor and take courses with others in their community, while receiving additional guidance related to those interests.<ref name=\"LLC\">{{cite web|title=Becoming a Part of the Community: Living Learning Communities |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Department of Housing and Residential Life |url=http://www.fau.edu/retention/2007-08LLCBrochure.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=July 9, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025182428/http://www.fau.edu/retention/2007-08LLCBrochure.pdf |archivedate=October 25, 2007 }}</ref> The university's Learning Community programs are divided into two categories, Freshman Learning Communities and Living Learning Communities. The freshman program offers 16 different concentrations, including business, nursing, and education. The Living program offers six concentrations for students residing in the Glades Park Towers [[dormitory]], including engineering, computer science, and a Women's Leadership program.<ref name=\"LLC\"/>\n\nThe university's Department of Housing and Residential Life and the university's fraternities and sororities sponsor a program for [[freshman|freshmen]] and other students returning to Florida Atlantic in the fall semester. This program, called the \"Weeks of Welcome\", spans 11&nbsp;days and all campuses, and works to acclimate students with university life and to build a good on-campus community.<ref name=\"Weeks of Welcome\">{{cite news|last=Reil |first=Quinn |title=Welcome Weeks at FAU offer fun for new students |publisher=[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]] |date=September 11, 2003 |url=http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2003/09/11/News/Welcome.Weeks.At.Fau.Offer.Fun.For.New.Students-461664.shtml |accessdate=July 22, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071129221456/http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2003/09/11/News/Welcome.Weeks.At.Fau.Offer.Fun.For.New.Students-461664.shtml |archivedate=November 29, 2007 }}</ref> On each day, a number of different events are scheduled, including Hall Wars, which are athletic competitions between dormitories, [[Luau]]s, and a number of other events.<ref name=\"List of WoW events 2007\">{{cite news|title=Weeks of welcome: What's happening on your campus |publisher=[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]] |date=August 12, 2004 |url=http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2004/08/12/WhatsUpevents/Weeks.Of.Welcome-701802.shtml |accessdate=July 22, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027122050/http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2004/08/12/WhatsUpevents/Weeks.Of.Welcome-701802.shtml |archivedate=October 27, 2007 }}</ref> The Weeks of Welcome is the second largest campus-wide event held by Florida Atlantic.<ref name=\"Weeks of Welcome\"/>\n\n===Student housing===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:500px; float:left; margin:10px\"\n! FAU residence halls<ref>{{cite web|title=FIU Housing |url=http://www.housing.fiu.edu/Buildings/index.html |publisher=FIU Office of Housing and Residential Life |accessdate=September 16, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080912081651/http://www.housing.fiu.edu/Buildings/index.html |archivedate=September 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n! Year opened\n! Students\n! Accommodations\n|-\n| Business Professional Women's Scholarship House {{small| (BPWSH)}}\n| 1996\n| 16\n| Female residence requiring dedicated application\n|-\n| Indian River Towers {{small| (IRT)}}\n| 2001\n| 611\n| Freshmen\n|-\n| Heritage Park Towers {{small| (HPT)}}\n| 2004\n| 603\n| Freshmen\n|-\n| Glades Park Towers {{small| (GPT)}}\n| 2007\n| 602\n| Freshmen\n|-\n| Parliament Hall {{small| (PAR)}}\n| 2013\n| 614\n|Freshmen\n|-\n| University Village Apartments {{small| (UVA)}}\n| 1995\n| 524\n| Upperclassmen\n|-\n| Innovation Village Apartments South {{small| (IVA-S)}}\n| 2011\n| 605\n| Upperclassmen\n|-\n| Innovation Village Apartments North {{small| (IVA-N)}}\n| 2011\n| 611\n| Upperclassmen\n|-\n| Total\n| \u2013\n| 4,317 students\n| \u2013\n|}\n\n===Campus organizations and activities===\nFor the 2010\u20132011 academic year, Florida Atlantic had approximately 300&nbsp;registered student organizations. Among the groups are academic organizations, honor societies, spiritual/religious organizations, diversity-appreciation organizations, service organizations, personal interest organizations, sports clubs, and student government agencies. These clubs and organizations run the gamut from [[sailing]] to [[Ultimate Frisbee]], from varsity and club sports and a [[jazz]] group to a [[pottery]] [[guild]], from political organizations to chess and video game clubs.<ref name=\"Registered Club List\">{{cite web|title=FAU Registered Club List |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Student Development & Activities |url=https://swise.fau.edu/universitycenter/clubreg/clubs_list.php |accessdate=April 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719192937/https://swise.fau.edu/universitycenter/clubreg/clubs_list.php |archivedate=July 19, 2011 }}</ref> These organizations are funded by student tuition, from which $10.00 per credit hour goes toward an activities and service fee fund. This generates approximately $9&nbsp;million that is then given to [[student government#United States|student government]] for allocation to student clubs and organizations. The student government also finances other student life programs, including career fairs, the ''[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]]'', OWL TV and Owl Radio, and Homecoming.<ref name=\"SGA $\">{{cite web | title =Activity and Service (A&S) Fee | publisher =Florida Atlantic University: Student Government Accounting and Budget Office | url =http://www.fau.edu/student/fees.php| accessdate =December 30, 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:I Heart FAU Sign Sunset.jpg|thumb|The \"I love FAU\" mural near student residence halls]]\n\nFlorida Atlantic's [[homecoming]], also known as the \"Owl Prowl,\" is celebrated annually in the fall semester. Events occur mainly on the Boca Raton Campus, but a number of other campuses host their own events as well. In the past, homecoming has had kickoff parties, costumed dances, [[bonfires]], comedy shows, alumni events and dinners, a golf cart parade, and [[tailgating]].<ref name=\"HC 2004\">{{cite news\n |title=Some traditions continued, new ones started\n |publisher=[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]]\n |date=November 25, 2004\n |url=http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2004/11/25/CoverStory/Owl-Prowl.2004-815187.shtml?sourcedomain=www.upressonline.com&MIIHost=media.collegepublisher.com\n |accessdate=July 15, 2007\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071129215208/http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2004/11/25/CoverStory/Owl-Prowl.2004-815187.shtml?sourcedomain=www.upressonline.com&MIIHost=media.collegepublisher.com\n |archivedate=November 29, 2007\n}}</ref><ref name=\"HC 2006 List\">{{cite news | last =Boyet | first =Michele |title=Homecoming Listings |publisher=[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]] |date=October 19, 2006 <!--|url=http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2006/10/19/CoverStory/Homecoming.Listings-2372548.shtml?sourcedomain=www.upressonline.com&MIIHost=media.collegepublisher.com (Dead) |accessdate=July 15, 2007 -->}}</ref><ref name=\"HC 2006\">{{cite news|title=Student Government Page |publisher=[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]] |date=November 9, 2006 |url=http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2006/11/09/StudentGovernment/Student.Government.Page-2444958.shtml?sourcedomain=www.upressonline.com&MIIHost=media.collegepublisher.com |accessdate=July 15, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071129221507/http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2006/11/09/StudentGovernment/Student.Government.Page-2444958.shtml?sourcedomain=www.upressonline.com&MIIHost=media.collegepublisher.com |archivedate=November 29, 2007 }}</ref> Florida Atlantic students have an organized football tailgating area known as the Rat's Mouth.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fau.edu/sil/Tailgating%20Expectations.pdf |title=Guide to A Successful Rat's Mouth Tailgate |access-date=November 26, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111119063000/http://fau.edu/sil/Tailgating%20Expectations.pdf |archive-date=November 19, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The name references the Spanish translation of [[Boca Raton]].\n\nFlorida Atlantic completed an $18.6&nbsp;million Recreation and Wellness Center in spring 2010. The facility houses an outdoor leisure and lap pool, a cardio equipment and free weight room, two multipurpose rooms, three indoor courts and health club-style locker rooms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/facility/rec_center.php |title=FAU \u2013 Recreation & Fitness Center |publisher=Fau.edu |accessdate=December 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111222151455/http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/facility/rec_center.php |archivedate=December 22, 2011 }}</ref> In 2011, the facility won the NIRSA Outstanding Sports Facilities Award. Other recreation facilities include a $4.2&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fausports.com/facilities/trackandfieldcomplex.html |title=FLORIDA ATLANTIC UNIVERSITY Facilities \u2013 FLORIDA ATLANTIC University Official Athletic Site |publisher=Fausports.com |date=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref> track and field complex,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/facility/track.php |title=FAU \u2013 Track & Field Complex |publisher=Fau.edu |accessdate=December 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123112931/http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/facility/track.php |archivedate=November 23, 2011 }}</ref> with synthetic turf (opened January 2007), a ropes challenge course<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/challenge_course/challenge_course.php |title=FAU \u2013 Challenge Course |publisher=Fau.edu |accessdate=December 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111218212408/http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/challenge_course/challenge_course.php |archivedate=December 18, 2011 }}</ref> and the 6.5 acre Henderson Fields, utilized most often by the FAU Intramural Sports and Club Sports programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/facility/henderson.php |title=FAU \u2013 Henderson Field |publisher=Fau.edu |accessdate=December 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123112906/http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/facility/henderson.php |archivedate=November 23, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Greek life===\nFlorida Atlantic is home to approximately 28&nbsp;chapters of national [[fraternities and sororities]], encompassing approximately 1,077 members or 5% of the undergraduate population.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fraternity & Sorority Life Community Report \u2013 Fall 2011|publisher=Florida Atlantic University|url=http://www.fau.edu/fslife/documents/Reports/FSLife_CommunityReport_F11_Revised.pdf |accessdate=April 14, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Greek Percentage\">{{cite web | title = Greek Life Community Report Executive Summary | publisher = Florida Atlantic University\" Office of Greek Life | url = http://www.fau.edu/greeklife/documents/Reports/GLCommunityReport_F09.pdf | format = PDF | accessdate =February 22, 2010}}</ref> The highpoint of Greek life at Florida Atlantic is \"Greek Week.\" This event is held annually during the spring semester and showcases a number of themed competitions between the university's Greek organizations. There are currently no on-campus Greek houses.<ref name=\"Where are rushers?\">{{cite news | last =Blanchett | first =Jordan | title =Greeks Ask: Where Have all the 'Rushers' Gone? | publisher =[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]] | date =January 8, 2007 | url =http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2007/01/18/ExclusivelyOnlineGreeks.Ask.Where.Have.All.The.rushers.Gone-2670580.shtml | accessdate =July 22, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717171833/http://www.upressonline.com/2.9208/greeks-ask-where-have-all-the-rushers-gone-1.1240033 |archivedate=July 17, 2011}}</ref> However, a Greek Life Housing [[task force]] has been formed to explore various housing models, including the cost of construction, \"and make recommendations on how to improve the overall quality of the Greek housing....\"<ref name=\"Task Force\">{{cite web|title=Division of Student Affairs Divisional Committees |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Division of Student Affairs |url=http://www.fau.edu/student/documents/committees.php |accessdate=February 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527100924/http://www.fau.edu/student/documents/committees.php |archivedate=May 27, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Alumni==\n{{main|List of Florida Atlantic University people}}\nFlorida Atlantic University has awarded more than 110,000&nbsp;degrees to nearly 105,000&nbsp;alumni worldwide since its opening. Some notable Florida Atlantic alumni are:\n\n* [[Daniel Bluman]] (born 1990), Colombian-born Israeli Olympic [[show jumping]] rider\n* [[R. David Paulison]], former head of the United States [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]]<ref>{{cite news | last = Hsu | first = Spencer S. |author2=Lee, Christopher | title = Paulison Is Skilled at Disasters | page = A12 |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=September 13, 2005 | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/09/12/AR2005091201829.html | accessdate =April 3, 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Charles Ghigna]] or \"Father Goose\", children's poet and former nationally syndicated columnist<ref>{{cite web | title = Charles Ghigna Papers | publisher = [[de Grummond Children's Literature Collection]]. University of Southern Mississippi | url = http://www.lib.usm.edu/legacy/degrum/public_html/html/research/findaids/DG1054f.html | accessdate =June 21, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Judith Ortiz Cofer]], acclaimed Puerto Rican author whose works span a range of literary genres including poetry, short stories, and essays<ref>{{cite web|title=Judith Ortiz Cofer Complete Vita |publisher=Judith Ortiz Cofer |url=http://www.english.uga.edu/~jcofer/vita.html |accessdate=December 20, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061220094653/http://www.english.uga.edu/~jcofer/vita.html |archivedate=December 20, 2006 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n*[[Greg Joseph]], placekicker for the [[Tennessee Titans]] of the [[National Football League]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Titans Player Roster |url=https://www.titansonline.com/team/players-roster/ |website=Tennessee Titans |publisher=The Tennessee Titans |accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Phil Zimmermann]], creator of [[Pretty Good Privacy]]<ref>{{cite web | last = Zimmermann | first = Phil | title = Philip Zimmermann's Home Page | publisher = Phil Zimmermann & Associates LLC | url = http://www.philzimmermann.com | accessdate = November 25, 2006}}</ref>\n* [[Mary Carey (actress)|Mary Carey]], pornographic actress and former candidate for Governor of California<ref>{{cite news | title =Reality TV show to feature porn stars | publisher =NBC News | date =May 4, 2006 | url =http://www.nbcnews.com/id/12631189 | accessdate =October 12, 2007 | at=1m:50s}}</ref>\n* [[Carrot Top]], [[Prop comedy|prop comedian]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Entertainer detail: Carrot Top |publisher=NationalActs.com |url=http://www.nationalacts.com/comedians/carrot_top.htm |accessdate=January 26, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503223951/http://www.nationalacts.com/comedians/carrot_top.htm |archivedate=May 3, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n* [[Devin Singletary]], running back for the NFL's [[Buffalo Bills]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Devin Signletary |url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinsingletary/2562734/profile |website=NFL.com |publisher=National Football League |accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Steven Swanson]], [[NASA]] [[astronaut]] who went to space aboard [[Space Shuttle Atlantis|Space Shuttle ''Atlantis'']] during [[STS-117]] in June 2007, and [[Space Shuttle Discovery|Space Shuttle ''Discovery'']] during [[STS-119]] in March 2009<ref>{{cite web | title = Astronaut Bio: Steven R. Swanson | publisher = [[NASA]] | url = http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/swanson.html | accessdate = October 9, 2007}}</ref>\n*[[Edith Stern]], award-winning inventor and child prodigy<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyvoice.com/new-york/yorktown/neighbors/yorktown-engineer-former-prodigy-wins-national-award/554897/|title=Yorktown Engineer, Former Prodigy Wins National Award|last=Marschhauser|first=Brian|date=December 12, 2012|website=Yorktown Daily Voice|access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Florida<!--State institution-->}}\n* {{commons category-inline}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.fausports.com/ Florida Atlantic Athletics website]\n* [http://www.upressonline.com/ ''University Press''] \u2013 student newspaper\n\n{{Florida Atlantic University}}\n{{Navboxes\n|titlestyle = {{CollegePrimaryStyle|Florida Atlantic Owls|color=white}}\n|list1 =\n{{Boca Raton, Florida}}\n{{State University System of Florida}}\n{{Southeastern Universities Research Association}}\n{{Conference USA navbox}}\n{{USAAF Training Bases World War II}}\n}}\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Florida Atlantic University| ]]\n[[Category:1961 establishments in Florida]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Boca Raton, Florida]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1961]]\n[[Category:Public universities and colleges in Florida]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Broward County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Florida]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Palm Beach County, Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Public university in Boca Raton, Florida}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Florida Atlantic University\n| image_name = Florida Atlantic University seal.svg\n| image_upright = 0.8\n| motto = \"Where Tomorrow Begins\"\n| established = 1961\n| type = [[Public university|Public]]\n| endowment = [[USD|$]]275&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite web | title = The Florida Atlantic University Foundation Endowment | url = https://fauf.fau.edu/sites/default/files/fauf-financial-statement-2016.pdf | access-date = December 24, 2016 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20161224164250/https://fauf.fau.edu/sites/default/files/fauf-financial-statement-2016.pdf | archive-date = December 24, 2016 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n| president = John W. Kelly\n| provost = Bret Danilowicz\n| faculty = 1,598<!--from Personnel section, includes both full and part-time faculty and adjuncts--><ref name=\"Facts\"/>\n| staff = 1,499<!--from Personnel section, includes both full and part-time AMP, and staff--><ref name=\"Facts\"/>\n| students = 30,808<ref name=\"Facts\"/>\n| undergrad = 24,687<ref name=\"Facts\"/>\n| postgrad = 4,670<ref name=\"Facts\"/>\n| doctoral = 790\n| city = [[Boca Raton]]\n| state = [[Florida]]\n| country = United States\n| coor = {{coord|26.3712|-80.1017|region:US-FL_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| campus = Urban area<br />850&nbsp;acres (3.5&nbsp;km\u00b2)<br />6 other satellite campuses<ref name=\"FAU Campuses\"/>\n| colors = Blue and red<ref name=\"Colors\"/><br />{{college color boxes|Florida Atlantic Owls}}\n| nickname = [[FAU Owls|Owls]]\n| mascot = Owlsley the [[Owl]]\n| athletics = [[NCAA Division I]] \u2013 [[Conference USA|C-USA]]<br />19 varsity teams\n| affiliations = [[AACSB]], [[NASULGC]]<br />[[National Space Grant College and Fellowship Program|NSGCFP]], [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools|SACS]], [[SUSF]]<br />[[ORAU]]\n| website = {{url|www.fau.edu}}\n| logo = Florida Atlantic University logo.svg\n| logo_size = 175\n}}\n\n'''Florida Atlantic University''' ('''FAU''' or '''Florida Atlantic''') is a [[public university]] with its main campus in [[Boca Raton, Florida]] and satellite campuses in [[Dania Beach, Florida|Dania Beach]], [[Davie, Florida|Davie]], [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], [[Jupiter, Florida|Jupiter]], and [[Fort Pierce, Florida|Fort Pierce]].<ref name=\"FAU Campuses\">{{cite web | url = http://www.fau.edu/explore/campuses.php | title = Explore FAU Campuses | publisher = Florida Atlantic University | accessdate = August 22, 2006}}</ref> FAU belongs to the 12-campus [[State University System of Florida]] and serves South Florida, which has more than five million people and spans more than 100&nbsp;miles (160&nbsp;km) of coastline.<ref name=\"Release\">{{cite press release | title =Early Detection of Developmental Disorders in Babies to be a Focus of New Infant Development Laboratory | publisher = Florida Atlantic University: University Communications and Marketing | date = September 22, 2005 | url =http://www.fau.edu/mediarelations/pressarchive/2005-09/16.php | accessdate = August 22, 2006}}</ref> Florida Atlantic University is [[Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education|classified]] among \"R1: Doctoral Universities \u2013 Very high research activity\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Carnegie Classifications {{!}} FAU Institution Profile|url=http://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=133669 |publisher=[[Indiana University]] |accessdate=April 20, 2018}}</ref> The university offers more than 170 undergraduate and graduate degree programs within its 10 colleges.<ref name=\"Points of Pride\">{{cite web|title=FAU Points of Pride|url=http://www.fau.edu/explore/pride.php|publisher=Florida Atlantic University|accessdate=October 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFlorida Atlantic opened in 1964 as the first public university in [[South Florida metropolitan area|southeast Florida]], offering only upper-division and graduate level courses. Initial enrollment was only 867&nbsp;students, increasing in 1984 when the university admitted its first lower-division undergraduate students.<ref name=\"History 1955-1969\">{{cite web | url = http://www.fau.edu/explore/timeline.php | title = Explore FAU History: Milestones in FAU History (1955\u20131969) | publisher = Florida Atlantic University |accessdate=August 22, 2006}}</ref> {{as of|2018}}, enrollment has grown to over 30,000&nbsp;students representing 140&nbsp;countries, 50&nbsp;states,<ref>FAU Fact Book http://www.fau.edu/explore/quickfacts.php</ref> and the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]]. Since its inception, Florida Atlantic has awarded more than 110,000&nbsp;degrees to nearly 153,160&nbsp;alumni.<ref name=\"Facts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fau.edu/newsdesk/articles/2016-fall-commencement.php|title=2013\u20132014 Quick Facts|website=|publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Office of Institutional Effectiveness & Analysis|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSince 2004, FAU has undertaken an effort to increase its academic and research standings while also evolving into a more traditional university. The university has raised admissions standards, increased research funding, built new facilities, and established notable partnerships with major research institutions.<ref name=\"Facts\"/><ref name=\"Admissions Standards\">{{cite news |last=Restrepo | first=Dan | title=New admissions standards: good for FAU, bad for Florida | publisher=[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]] |date=February 5, 2004 |url=http://www.upressonline.com/2004/02/new-admissions-standards-good-for-fau-bad-for-florida/ | accessdate=August 23, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Partnership\">{{cite news |last=Travis |first=Scott |title=FAU to boost scientific reputation with biomedical science college |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  |date=August 17, 2006 |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2006-08-17/news/0608170090_1_fau-torrey-pines-institute-jupiter-campus |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> Changes include an on-campus stadium, additional on-campus housing, and the establishment of a College of Medicine in 2010.<ref name=\"Double Applications\">{{Cite news | last = Travis | first = Scott | title = FAU's freshman applications double | newspaper = South Florida Sun-Sentinel  | date = March 5, 2011 | url = http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/education/highered/fl-fau-freshman-applications-20110305,0,75875.story | archive-url = https://archive.today/20130203211125/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/education/highered/fl-fau-freshman-applications-20110305,0,75875.story | url-status = dead | archive-date = February 3, 2013 | accessdate = March 5, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Establishment===\nOn July 15, 1961, to meet the burgeoning educational demands of South Florida, the state legislature passed an act authorizing the establishment of a new university in the City of Boca Raton. Florida Atlantic University was built on [[Boca Raton Army Airfield]], a 1940s-era army airbase. During World War II, the airfield served as the [[United States Army Air Corps|Army Air Corps]]' sole radar training facility. The base was built on the existing [[Boca Raton Airport]] and on 5,860&nbsp;acres (23.7&nbsp;km\u00b2) of adjacent land.<ref name=\"Morikami\">{{cite web | title = The Yamato Colony: Japanese Pioneers in Florida | publisher = The [[Morikami Museum and Japanese Gardens]] | url = http://www.morikami.org/index.php?src=gendocs&link=YamatoColony | accessdate =November 4, 2006}}</ref> A majority of the land was acquired from [[Japanese-American]] farmers from the failing [[Yamato Colony, Florida|Yamato Colony]]. The land was seized through [[eminent domain]], leaving many Japanese-Americans little recourse in the early days of World War II.<ref name=\"Morikami\"/>\n\n[[File:LBJ FAU Dedication.gif|left|thumb|President Johnson at the University's dedication]]\nThe airbase was used for radar training, anti-submarine patrols along the coast, and as a stop-over point for planes being ferried to Africa and Europe via South America. The airfield was composed of four runways, still visible on the Boca Campus today and mainly used for parking.\n\nBy early 1947, the military decided to transfer future radar training operations to [[Keesler Air Force Base]] in [[Mississippi]]. The departure of the air force in 1947 would leave Boca Raton Army Airfield essentially abandoned.\n\n===Expansion and growth===\nFlorida Atlantic University opened on September 14, 1964, with an initial student body of 867&nbsp;students in five colleges. The first degree awarded was an honorary doctorate given to President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] on October 25, 1964, at the dedication and opening of the university.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web | url = http://www.fau.edu/explore/history.php| title = Explore FAU History | publisher = Florida Atlantic University | accessdate = September 20, 2007}}</ref> At the time of its opening, there were 350&nbsp;employees, of which 120 were faculty . On-campus housing for students was first added in September 1965, when Algonquin Hall opened.<ref name=\"Admissions Standards\"/><ref name=\"Legacy History\">{{Cite news | last =Burdick | first =Bob | title =All Grown Up: FAU Looks Back and Steps Forward | newspaper =Legacy: A Magazine for Alumni and Friends of Florida Atlantic University | pages = 14\u201315 | volume= 5 | issue=1 | date=September 2007}}</ref>\n\nFlorida Atlantic's history is one of continuing expansion as the university's service population has grown. The university originally served only upper-division and graduate level students, because Florida intended the institution \"to complement the state's community college system, accepting students who had earned their associate degrees from those institutions.\"<ref name=\"Legacy History\"/>\n\nFlorida Atlantic began its expansion beyond a one-campus university in 1971, when it opened its Commercial Boulevard campus in [[Fort Lauderdale]]. Due to a rapidly expanding population in South Florida, in 1984 Florida Atlantic opened its doors to lower-division undergraduate students. The following year, the university added its third campus, in downtown Fort Lauderdale on Las Olas Boulevard.\n\n===Recent history===\n[[File:FAU Social Science Building.jpg|right|thumb|Florida Atlantic University's Social Science Building, [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]] campus]]\nIn 1989, the [[Florida Legislature]] recognized demands for higher education in South Florida by designating Florida Atlantic as the lead state university serving Broward County. To fill this role, the university would establish a campus in [[Dania Beach]] in 1997 and another campus in the City of [[Davie, Florida|Davie]] in western [[Broward County]] in 1990. Florida Atlantic later purchased 50 acres (20 ha) of land in [[Port St. Lucie, Florida|Port St. Lucie]] in 1994 to establish a campus on the [[Treasure Coast]]. This would be the institution's fifth campus. The university continued its expansion in 1999 when it opened its [[Jupiter, Florida|Jupiter]] Campus, named for the late [[John D. MacArthur]]. This campus houses the university's honors college.\n\nFlorida Atlantic University and the [[University of Miami]]'s [[Miller School of Medicine]] established a [[Doctor of Medicine|medical training]] program within the [[Charles E. Schmidt College of Biomedical Science]] in 2004. Plans originally called for the construction of a new [[teaching hospital]] in coordination with [[Boca Raton Community Hospital]] on the main campus. Following successive budgets deficits in 2007, the hospital delayed its participation indefinitely. However, Florida Atlantic later established its own College of Medicine in 2010.<ref name=\"Medical School\">{{cite web|title=UMSM@FAU |publisher=The University of Miami |url=http://www6.miami.edu/UMH/CDA/UMH_Main/0,1770,2600-1;31823-3,00.html |accessdate=May 26, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070422135806/http://www6.miami.edu/UMH/CDA/UMH_Main/0%2C1770%2C2600-1%3B31823-3%2C00.html |archivedate=April 22, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=\"Medical School Questions\">{{cite web | title = UMMSM at FAU Questions | publisher = Florida Atlantic University | url =http://med.fau.edu/biomedical/ummsm_rmc/prospective_students.html#FrequentlyAskedQuestions | accessdate =May 26, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217074138/http://med.fau.edu/biomedical/ummsm_rmc/prospective_students.html|archivedate=February 17, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Establishment of Hospital\">{{cite press release|title=Boca Raton Community Hospital Receives $75 Million |publisher=PNN Online |date=January 30, 2006 |url=http://pnnonline.org/article.php?sid=7242 |accessdate=October 12, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071014170105/http://pnnonline.org/article.php?sid=7242 |archivedate=October 14, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=\"Deficit\">{{cite news | last =Pensa | first = Patty | title =Boca Raton Community Hospital loses $28&nbsp;million, replaces CEO: Plan to build teaching facility set back |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  | date =January 5, 2008}}</ref> The [[Harbor Branch Oceanographic Institution]] (HBOI) also joined the university in 2007, creating Florida Atlantic's seventh campus.<ref name=\"Merged\">{{cite news | title =Editorial: Harbor Branch swimming downstream with FAU | publisher =Scripps Interactive Newspapers Group | date =December 2, 2007 | url =http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2007/dec/02/editorial-harbor-branch-swimming-downstream-fau/ |accessdate=February 22, 2008}}</ref> To bring HBOI into the university family the Florida Legislature allocated $44&nbsp;million to Florida Atlantic to acquire the institution.<ref name=\"Merger 1\">{{cite news |last =Travis | first =Scott | title =Universities fight to save funding for big projects |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  | date =September 23, 2007 <!--|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/local/palmbeach/sfl-flpbudgetcuts0923nbsep23,0,3269119.story (Dead) |accessdate=October 14, 2007 -->}}</ref>\n\nFlorida Atlantic has changed dramatically since its opening in 1964. {{as of|2013}}, there were more than 30,000 students attending classes on seven campuses spread across 120&nbsp;miles (193&nbsp;km). The university consists of ten colleges and employs more than 3,200 faculty and staff. The university's endowment decreased from $182&nbsp;million in June 2008 to $142&nbsp;million in January 2009 due to a worsening economy. However, with the national economic recovery the endowment has increased to $179&nbsp;million by the end of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Florida Atlantic University Foundation Endowment, 2012 NACUBO \u2013 Florida Foundation Comparisons And Discretionary Gifts |publisher=The Florida Atlantic University Foundation |url=http://fauf.fau.edu/cgi-bin/files/pdf/O'Flannery%20FAUF%20Endowments%20Comparison%20April%202013.pdf |accessdate=June 25, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508220542/http://fauf.fau.edu/cgi-bin/files/pdf/O%27Flannery%20FAUF%20Endowments%20Comparison%20April%202013.pdf |archivedate=May 8, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nSince its founding, the university has been led by seven presidents. The university's immediate past president is [[Mary Jane Saunders]]. She was named president on March 3, 2010, then resigned on May 15, 2013. Her appointment followed the resignation of [[Frank T. Brogan|Frank Brogan]]. Brogan, a former [[Lieutenant Governor of Florida]], left the university in late 2009 to become Chancellor of the [[State University System of Florida]]. Past university presidents also included [[Anthony J. Catanese]], Helen Popovich, Glenwood Creech, and Kenneth Rast Williams. On January 17, 2014, the Board of Trustees announced the selection of John W. Kelly, formerly a vice president of [[Clemson University]], to be the seventh president of the university with a starting date of March 1, 2014.\n\n==Academics==\n\n[[File:FAU Sign NW 20th St.jpg|left|thumb|The NW 20th Street entrance sign, [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]] campus]]\nAs of fall 2013, the university's student body consists of 24,686&nbsp;undergraduates, 4,666&nbsp;graduate and professional students, 256 medical students, and 1,451 unclassified students.<ref name=\"Facts\"/> {{as of|2013}}, the undergraduate student body contains 47% ethnic minorities and includes students from more than 180 countries,<ref>{{cite web|title=FAU \u2013 Diversity|url=http://www.fau.edu/diversity/|publisher=Florida Atlantic University|accessdate=January 19, 2014}}</ref> 49&nbsp;states, and the [[District of Columbia]].<ref name=\"Enroll by Country\">{{cite web|title=Headcount Enrollment by Nation of Origin |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Office of Institutional Effectiveness & Analysis |url=http://www.fau.edu/iea/factbook/nation12f.pdf |accessdate=January 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510040540/http://www.fau.edu/iea/factbook/nation12f.pdf |archivedate=May 10, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"Enroll by State\">{{cite web|title=Headcount Enrollment by State Residency |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Office of Institutional Effectiveness & Analysis |url=http://www.fau.edu/iea/factbook/state12f.pdf |accessdate=January 14, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510042519/http://www.fau.edu/iea/factbook/state12f.pdf |archivedate=May 10, 2013 }}</ref> For the undergraduate class of 2012, the acceptance rate was 35% for first-time-in-college students. In 2016 advance registration begins.<ref>{{cite web | title = Florida Atlantic University Academic Calendar 2015 \u2013 2016|publisher=Florida Atlantic University|url=https://www.fau.edu/registrar/pdf/acadcal1516.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe university has ten colleges which altogether offer over 180 different [[bachelor's degree|bachelor's]], [[master's degree|master's]] and [[doctorate|doctoral]] degree programs:<ref name=\"Degrees\">{{cite web | title =University Characteristics, Fall 2008 | publisher =Florida Atlantic University: Office of Institutional Effectiveness & Analysis | url =http://iea.fau.edu/fb05/char8f.pdf | accessdate =December 30, 2011}}</ref> the [[Charles E. Schmidt College of Science]], [[Charles E. Schmidt College of Medicine]], [[Christine E. Lynn College of Nursing]], [[Florida Atlantic University College for Design and Social Inquiry|College for Design and Social Inquiry]], [[Florida Atlantic University College of Business|College of Business]], [[Florida Atlantic University College of Education|College of Education]], [[Florida Atlantic University College of Engineering and Computer Science|College of Engineering and Computer Science]], [[Dorothy F. Schmidt College of Arts and Letters]], [[Harriet L. Wilkes Honors College]], and the Graduate College.<ref name=\"Colleges\">{{cite web | title = Colleges and Degrees | publisher = Florida Atlantic University | url = http://www.fau.edu/explore/CollegesandDegrees.php | accessdate = August 5, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe university offers two honors options: the Harriet L. Wilkes Honors College and a University Scholars Program. The Wilkes Honors College is located on the John D. MacArthur campus in Jupiter, Florida. It offers a [[liberal arts college|liberal arts education]] in the platform of a public university, yet is comparable to a private liberal arts college.<ref name=\"HC FAQ\">{{cite web | title =General FAQ | publisher =Florida Atlantic University: Wilkes Honors College | url =http://www.fau.edu/honors/ | accessdate =October 10, 2007}}</ref> The Boca Raton campus houses the University Scholars Program, which offers special honors seminars, forums, courses, and advanced course substitution for freshmen.\n\nIn recent years, FAU has increased its admission requirements for prospective freshmen. The fall 2013 freshmen profile for the mid-50% includes 3.38\u20133.98 high school [[GPA]], a 22\u201326 [[ACT (examination)|ACT]] composite score, and a 1520\u20131740 SAT total score.<ref>{{cite web|title=FAU \u2013 Freshman Requirements|url=http://www.fau.edu/admissions/freshmanreq.php|publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Office of Undergraduate Admissions|accessdate=January 19, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130606045121/http://www.fau.edu/admissions/freshmanreq.php|archivedate=June 6, 2013}}</ref> Following a surge in the university's popularity, in early 2009, the university created its first wait-list for undergraduate enrollment. After February 15, 2009, applicants for admission in the 2009\u20132010 academic year were required to have a 3.5 GPA or an SAT score of 1600 to be considered for admission.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/schools/sfl-flpfau0309sbmar09,0,1135008.story |title=Florida Atlantic University goes to waiting list for first time as enrollment jumps |last=Travis |first=Scott |date=March 9, 2009 |newspaper=\"South Florida Sun-Sentinel\"  |accessdate=April 8, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312033435/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/schools/sfl-flpfau0309sbmar09%2C0%2C1135008.story |archivedate=March 12, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe average class size at FAU for undergraduates is 33&nbsp;students, and for graduate classes, 12&nbsp;students. The student-to-faculty ratio is 20:1.<ref name=\"Facts\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Travis |first=Scott |title =Florida universities grow in number of students, but not in faculty, data shows | newspaper=floridatrend |url=http://www.floridatrend.com/article/9497/florida-universities-grow-in-number-of-students-but-not-in-faculty }}</ref> The top three undergraduate majors by enrollment are [[Education|elementary education]], accounting, and management, respectively. The top three graduate majors by enrollment are [[business administration]], educational leadership, and accounting, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fall 2010 Entering Graduate Student Characteristics|url=http://iea.fau.edu/factbk/trangrad10f.pdf|publisher=Florida Atlantic University|accessdate=January 19, 2014}}</ref> The average age for first-year students is 18; however, the average age for all undergraduates is 24 and the average age for graduate students is 33.<ref name=\"Facts\"/> The average 4-year graduation rate for first-time, non-transfer students is 14% while the 6-year graduation rate is 39%.<ref name=\"Grad Rates\">{{cite web |title=IPEDS Data Feedback Report 2009 |publisher=Integrated Postsecondary Education Data System |url=http://iea.fau.edu/inst/feedback09.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=December 7, 2009}}</ref>\n\nFlorida Atlantic University has long ranked as the most racially, ethnically and culturally diverse institution in [[State University System of Florida|Florida's State University System]]. ''U.S. News & World Report'' has ranked FAU the 27th most diverse university in the nation.<ref name=\"Diversity\">{{cite web|title=FAU Diversity|url=http://www.fau.edu/diversity/|publisher=Florida Atlantic University|accessdate=January 19, 2014}}</ref> Florida Atlantic University students come from all 50 states, every county in Florida, and more than 180 countries. Enrichment opportunities include internships, hands-on research, study abroad experiences, and 310 clubs and campus organizations.<ref>{{cite web|title=FAU \u2013 Points of Pride|url=http://www.fau.edu/explore/pride.php|publisher=Florida Atlantic University|accessdate=January 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Lifelong Learning Society operates programs that serve the educational interests of more than 19,000&nbsp;senior citizens by providing classes focusing on subjects of specific interest, and audit options for regular university classes.<ref name=\"Life Long\">{{cite news | last =Travis | first =Scott | title =Florida Atlantic University's Lifelong Learning enrollment surges |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  | date =February 10, 2008}}</ref> Under the university's Commercial Music Program, Hoot/Wisdom Recordings was created in 2002, enabling students to work in all creative and business aspects of the music industry. This program generated music that landed a Top 10&nbsp;spot on the [[Billboard charts|Billboard's Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles Sales Chart]] during its first week of release.<ref name=\"Hoot 1\">{{cite web|title=FAU hits a high note with music studies |publisher=Oxendine Publishing |url=http://www.floridaleader.com/best2003_15.htm |accessdate=May 26, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070404170734/http://floridaleader.com/best2003_15.htm |archivedate=April 4, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"Hoot Records\">{{cite press release | title =FAU Graduate's Masters Thesis Produces Billboard Hit |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: University Communications and Marketing | date =February 26, 2007 | url = http://fau.edu/mediarelations/Releases0207/020719.php |accessdate =May 25, 2007}}</ref> The university's two-story [[trading room]] simulator, located in the College of Business, provides hands-on financial education using 25&nbsp;dual-monitor computers and can accommodate 50&nbsp;people at one time. A second lab provides full audio/visual connectivity and 25&nbsp;additional workstations. Florida Atlantic allows local financial businesses to use the Trading Room for training.<ref name=\"Trading Room\">{{cite web |title=Students experience Wall Street in FAU's two-story trading room simulator| publisher=Florida Atlantic University |url=http://www.fau.edu/explore/homepage-stories/2007-04trading.php |accessdate=May 26, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Rankings===\n{{Infobox US university ranking\n| Forbes = 557<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/colleges/florida-atlantic-university/ |work=Forbes |title=Florida Atlantic University |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20111224065239/http://www.forbes.com/colleges/florida-atlantic-university/ |archivedate=December 24, 2011 |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref>\n| USNWR_NU = 281\n| Wamo_NU = 241\n| THE_WSJ = 601\u2013800\n| USNWR_W = 924\n| THES_W = 801\u20131000\n}}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR graduate school rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR Grad School Rankings\">{{cite magazine|title=Florida Atlantic University \u2013 U.S. News Best Grad School Rankings|magazine=U.S. News & World Report|accessdate=June 4, 2017|url=https://www.usnews.com/best-graduate-schools/florida-atlantic-university-133669/overall-rankings}}</ref>\n|-\n| Nursing: Doctorate\n| 44\n|-\n| Nursing: Master's\n| 45\n|}\n\n{|class=\"infobox\" style=\"width: 22em;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"font-size: 100%; text-align: center;\" |\n<big>USNWR departmental rankings</big><ref name=\"USNWR Grad School Rankings\"/>\n|-\n| Fine Arts\n| 198\n|-\n| Psychology\n| 112\n|-\n| Public Affairs\n| 96\n|-\n| Rehabilitation Counseling\n| 24\n|-\n| Social Work\n| 141\n|-\n| Speech\u2013Language Pathology\n| 183\n|}\n\nFor 2019, Florida Atlantic University was classified as a second-tier university by the ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'s'' rankings of \"Best Colleges.\"<ref name=\"US News\">{{cite magazine|title=America's Best Colleges 2013: Florida Atlantic University |magazine=U.S. News & World Report |url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/florida-atlantic-university-1481 |accessdate=September 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608040457/http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/florida-atlantic-university-1481 |archivedate=June 8, 2012 }}</ref> ''U.S. News'' ranks universities into one of two tiers, with one being the highest, based on how they compare with other colleges in a peer assessment, retention rates, student selectivity, faculty resources, financial resources, graduation rates, and the amount of alumni giving.<ref name=\"Best Colleges\">{{cite magazine|last=Morse |first=Robert J. |author2=R. Morse |author3=S. Flanigan |title=America's Best Colleges 2008: How We Do the Rankings |magazine=U.S. News & World Report |date=August 17, 2007 |url=http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/usnews/edu/college/rankings/about/rank_brief.php |accessdate=October 17, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011012149/http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/usnews/edu/college/rankings/about/rank_brief.php |archivedate=October 11, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The university was named one of the 146 \"Best Southeastern Colleges\" in the United States by the [[Princeton Review]].<ref name=\"Princeton Review\">{{cite web | title =Florida Atlantic University | publisher =The Princeton Review | url =http://www.princetonreview.com/college/research/profiles/schoolsays.asp?category=1&listing=1022927&LTID=1&intbucketid= | accessdate =July 15, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Princeton Review 2\">{{cite web | title =Florida Atlantic University: Rankings & Lists | publisher =The Princeton Review | url =http://www.princetonreview.com/college/research/profiles/rankings.asp?listing=1022927&LTID=1&intbucketid= | accessdate =October 17, 2007}}</ref> Princeton Review also recognized FAU's business program by naming the College of Business to their list of \"Best 296 Business Schools\" for 2009.<ref>{{cite news | title = FAU business school named one of best in U.S. | publisher = Scripps Interactive Newspapers Group | date = October 30, 2008 |url=http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2008/oct/30/fau-business-school-named-one-best-us/ |accessdate =December 17, 2008}}</ref> For 2011, Florida Atlantic was ranked 249th in the nation by ''[[Washington Monthly]]''.<ref name=\"WM Rankings\">{{cite magazine | title =The Washington Monthly College Rankings | magazine =The Washington Monthly | url =http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/college_guide/rankings_2011/national_university_rank_2nd_page.php | accessdate =October 7, 2011 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20130706132723/http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/college_guide/rankings_2011/national_university_rank_2nd_page.php | archivedate =July 6, 2013 | df =mdy-all }}</ref> The magazine based its rankings on the following three criteria: \"how well a university performs as an engine of social mobility (ideally helping the poor to get rich rather than the very rich to get very, very rich), how well a university does in fostering scientific and humanistic research, and how well a university promotes an ethic of service to country.\"<ref name=\"WM Criteria\">{{cite magazine|title=The Washington Monthly's Annual College Guide |magazine=The Washington Monthly |url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2006/0609.collegeguide.html |accessdate=July 15, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070718083449/http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/features/2006/0609.collegeguide.html |archivedate=July 18, 2007  }}</ref> The university was also ranked 28th in the United States and fourth in Florida by ''[[The Hispanic Outlook in Higher Education]]'' magazine for awarding 738 bachelor's degrees to [[Hispanic]] students during the 2006\u20132007 academic year.<ref name=\"Hispanic Students\">{{cite news | last =Tyko | first =Kelly | title =Florida schools top the nation in awarding degrees to Hispanics | publisher =Scripps Interactive Newspapers Group | date =June 9, 2008 | url =http://www.tcpalm.com/news/2008/jun/09/florida-schools-top-nation-awarding-degrees-hispan/ | accessdate =June 12, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Hispanic Students detail\">{{cite news | title = Boca Raton: FAU awards 738 degrees to Hispanics in 2006\u2013'07 |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  |date=July 15, 2008 <!--|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/community/news/palmbeach/sfl-flpdig07151pnjul15,0,4835017.story (Dead) |accessdate=July 15, 2008 -->}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\n[[File:Schmidt Biomedical Center.jpeg|right|thumb|The [[Charles E. Schmidt College of Medicine]] on Florida Atlantic University's [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]] campus. The sculpture is \"Orgonelle,\" designed by Rob Fisher.<ref>{{cite web |title=Art in State Buildings |url=https://www.fau.edu/facilities/asb/fau_asb/br635_638.php |website=Florida Atlantic University |publisher=Florida Atlantic University |accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>]]\nFlorida Atlantic is classified by [[the Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching]] as a research university with high research activity.<ref name=\"Carnegie\">{{cite web |title=Florida Atlantic University | publisher = The Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching |url=http://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=133669 |accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref> The university has established notable partnerships with major research institutions such as [[the Scripps Research Institute]], the [[Torrey Pines Institute for Molecular Studies]], and the [[Max Planck Society]].<ref name=\"Partnership\"/><ref name=\"Research\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fau.edu/research/ovp/index.php |title=Message from the Vice President |publisher=Florida Atlantic University |accessdate=January 31, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070518233053/http://www.fau.edu/research/ovp/index.php|archivedate=May 18, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Max Planck\">{{cite news|last=Johnston |first=John |title=Planck to plant Palm Beach county roots |newspaper=Boca Raton News |date=July 25, 2008 |url=http://www.bocanews.com/local-news/8787planck-to-plant-palm-beach-county-roots.htm |url-status=dead |accessdate=August 1, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130517142149/http://www.bocanews.com/local-news/8787planck-to-plant-palm-beach-county-roots.htm |archivedate=May 17, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe university is the home of two centers of excellence: the Center of Excellence in Biomedical and Marine Biotechnology and the Center for Ocean Energy Technology. These centers have been selected by Florida's Emerging Technology Commission to receive grants to continue and increase their operations. Florida Atlantic beat out some of Florida's top research universities, including the [[University of Florida]] and [[Florida State University]], for the initial money from the state.<ref name=\"Research Week\">{{cite news | last = Reed | first = Charlie | title =FAU Research Week starts today | publisher = Scripps Interactive Newspapers Group | date = April 2, 2007 <!--|url=http://www1.tcpalm.com/tcp/local_news/article/0,2545,TCP_16736_5458129,00.html (Dead) |accessdate=May 26, 2007 -->}}</ref>\n\nSince receiving its startup funding, Florida Atlantic has secured additional funds from other sources, including federal and private research grants. As a result, both centers have engaged in academic and industry partnerships, combining expertise in [[Marine electronics|ocean engineering]], [[biotechnology|marine biotechnology]], [[functional genomics]], [[proteomics]], and [[bioinformatics]]. Researchers, scientists, and students at the centers are designing technologies to explore the sea, harvest [[renewable energy]], discover new medicines, and develop new therapeutics to combat agents of [[bioterrorism]].<ref name=\"Center for Ocean\">{{cite press release | title = FAU to Receive $5 Million to Establish The Florida Center of Excellence in Ocean Energy Technology | publisher = Technology Daily News | date =November 18, 2006 <!--|url=http://www.technologynewsdaily.com/node/5240 (Dead) |accessdate=October 12, 2007 -->}}</ref><ref name=\"Research list\">{{cite web | title = About the Center | publisher = Center of Excellence in Biomedical and Marine Biotechnology | url = http://www.floridabiotech.org/ | accessdate = October 12, 2007}}</ref> As a result of this research, in 2007 the university and [[Lockheed Martin]] announced an exclusive licensing agreement to develop and produce a rapidly deployable and autonomous mooring buoy system for military and scientific uses.<ref name=\"Lockheed Martin\">{{cite press release | title = Florida Atlantic University and Lockheed Martin to Develop Autonomous Mooring Buoy System for Military and Scientific Use | publisher = Lockheed Martin | date = May 17, 2007 | url = http://www.fau.edu/mediarelations/Releases0407/040710.php | accessdate = October 11, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, the [[United States Department of Energy]] designated FAU as one of three national centers for ocean energy research and development. The Southeast National Marine Renewable Energy Center joins centers in the Pacific Northwest ([[University of Washington]] and [[Oregon State University]]) and in Hawaii ([[University of Hawaii]]). The Southeast National Marine Renewable Energy Center is undertaking research and development of technologies capable of generating renewable power from ocean currents and ocean thermal energy.<ref name=\"DOE Designates New National Marine Renewable Energy Center for Ocean Energy Research\">{{cite press release|title=DOE Designates New National Marine Renewable Energy Center for Ocean Energy Research |publisher=U.S. Department of Energy |date=August 3, 2010 |url=http://apps1.eere.energy.gov/news/progress_alerts.cfm/news_id=20025 |accessdate=February 11, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909023635/http://apps1.eere.energy.gov/news/progress_alerts.cfm/news_id%3D20025 |archivedate=September 9, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nThe university houses both an Imaging Technology Center and a [[NASA]] Imaging Technology Space Center. Located in the College of Engineering and Computer Science, the centers specialize in digital imaging research and development for use in both government and commercial applications in the areas of [[medical technology]], [[surveillance]], communications, education, [[inspection]], [[observation|scientific observation]], manufacturing, visual recognition and identification, and motion picture and [[digital video]]. The Florida Atlantic Imaging Technology Center is developing a curriculum for [[digital imaging]] and processing, thereby establishing Florida Atlantic as the only university in the nation to offer this technical concentration.<ref name=\"Tech Concentration\">{{cite web | title =Florida Atlantic University Legislative Budget Request For 2005\u201306 | publisher =Florida Atlantic University | date =July 2, 2003 | url =http://wise.fau.edu/financial/files/Narrative-2005-06-Request.doc | accessdate =October 11, 2007 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20071025182432/http://wise.fau.edu/financial/files/Narrative-2005-06-Request.doc | archive-date =October 25, 2007 | url-status =dead | df =mdy-all }}</ref> The NASA Imaging Technology Center is one of 12&nbsp;NASA Research Partnership Centers throughout the nation which develop dual-use research and development with the participation of NASA and other related industries in the US. The center occupies two sets of laboratories and administrative offices, one on Florida Atlantic's main campus in Boca Raton, the other at the Fort Lauderdale campus.<ref name=\"Research list\"/>\n\nFlorida Atlantic is affiliated to the [[Research Park at Florida Atlantic University]], with properties in Deerfield Beach and Boca Raton. The Research Park provides outside research facilities for companies which enable them to interact with the university community and its facilities, resources, and expertise. The Research Park operates the Technology Business Incubator;<ref>{{cite web |title=Research Park at Florida Atlantic University: Technology Business Incubator |publisher=Florida Atlantic Research & Development Park |url=http://www.research-park.org/Technology-Business-Incubator |accessdate=November 12, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112045752/http://www.research-park.org/Technology-Business-Incubator |archivedate=November 12, 2014  }}</ref> The incubator works to foster the start-up and growth of technology-based businesses, seeking to scale them and build relationships for them with the university. The Boca Raton campus is also home to the Center for Complex Systems and Brain Sciences, which includes the Machine Perception and Cognitive Robotics Laboratory\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:Living Room Theaters.jpg|thumb|right|FAU's Living Room Theaters Complex, located in the Culture and Society Building in [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]]]]\nFlorida Atlantic University is a distributed university located on seven campuses spread across [[Palm Beach County|Palm Beach]], [[Broward County|Broward]], and [[St. Lucie County|St. Lucie]] counties. The region is home to more than three million people.<ref name=\"Release\"/><ref name=\"Dist Univ\">{{cite web|title=Department of Exercise Science and Health Promotion (ESHP) |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: College of Education |url=http://www.coe.fau.edu/eshp/ |accessdate=July 13, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629080736/http://www.coe.fau.edu/eshp/ |archivedate=June 29, 2007 }}</ref> The university's main campus is located in the City of Boca Raton in Palm Beach County. The county is also home to the John D. MacArthur Campus located in the [[Jupiter, Florida|City of Jupiter]]. In addition to its campuses in [[Palm Beach County, Florida|Palm Beach County]], the university operates three campuses in the [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]] cities of [[Dania Beach, Florida|Dania Beach]], [[Davie, Florida|Davie]], and [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]]. Florida Atlantic University also operates two campuses in the [[St. Lucie County, Florida|St. Lucie County]] cities of [[Port St. Lucie, Florida|Port St. Lucie]] and [[Fort Pierce, Florida|Fort Pierce]]. In addition to students who attend classes on the universities campuses, there are 1,612&nbsp;distance learning students who conduct their studies over the internet or through other means. These students account for 6% of the university's student body.<ref name=\"Campus Enroll\">{{cite web | title = Headcount Enrollment by Campus | publisher = Florida Atlantic University: Office of Institutional Effectiveness & Analysis | url = http://iea.fau.edu/fb05/camenr8f.pdf | accessdate = December 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nFlorida Atlantic is a signatory of the American College & University presidents Climate Commitment Association for the Advancement of Sustainability in Higher Education. This commits the institution to ensuring all new construction projects meet the [[U.S. Green Building Council]]'s [[Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design|Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED)]] Silver standards.<ref>{{cite web | title = Implementation Profile for Florida Atlantic University | publisher = American College & University Presidents Climate Commitment Association | date = November 12, 2010 | url = http://acupcc.aashe.org/ip/168/ | archive-url = https://archive.today/20120701180546/http://acupcc.aashe.org/ip/168/ | url-status = dead | archive-date = July 1, 2012 | accessdate = March 5, 2011 }}</ref> In 2011, the College of Engineering and Computer Science Building was LEED Platinum certified.\n\n===Palm Beach County campuses===\n\n====Boca Raton====\n{{see also|FAU Stadium}}\n[[File:FAUStadium night.jpg|thumb|left|[[FAU Stadium]] in [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]]]]\nFlorida Atlantic University's main campus in [[Boca Raton]] was established on the remnants of a World War II American [[United States Army Air Corps|Army airbase]] in 1964. Spanning 850&nbsp;acres (3.5&nbsp;km\u00b2), the site is located between the cities of [[Palm Beach, Florida|Palm Beach]] and Fort Lauderdale. The campus was designated a [[burrowing owl]] sanctuary in 1971 by the [[Audubon Society]]. The owls find the campus appealing because there are few predators, due to the university's proximity to the Boca Raton Airport, and because the campus was originally cleared of vegetation when operating as an airbase during World War II. \"The feisty bird, traditionally associated with wisdom and determination, serves as the university's mascot.\"<ref name=\"FAU Trad\">{{cite web | title =FAU Traditions | publisher =Florida Atlantic University: Athletics Department | url =http://fausports.cstv.com/trads/fau-trads.html | accessdate =July 15, 2007 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20090530002813/http://fausports.cstv.com/trads/fau-trads.html | archive-date =May 30, 2009 | url-status =dead | df =mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe Boca Raton campus is home to a wide variety of university programs and facilities. These facilities are labs and classrooms, housing for students, a 6,000-gallon shark tank for aquatic research, a movie theater, athletic and recreational facilities, and the student-run record label Hoot/Wisdom Recordings.<ref name=\"Boca Raton campus\"/> In addition to academic and cultural programs, the campus also houses Florida Atlantic's [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[Florida Atlantic Owls|athletics program]]. The main campus serves approximately 19,077&nbsp;students, or 70% of the university's student body, offering a number of academic programs, activities, and services.<ref name=\"Facts\"/><ref name=\"Campus Enroll\"/><ref name=\"Boca Raton campus\">{{cite web | title = FAU Boca Raton | publisher = Florida Atlantic University | url = http://www.fau.edu/explore/boca_raton.php | accessdate = April 2, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe Boca Raton campus also houses a number of other institutions, including the [[Alexander D. Henderson University School|A. D. Henderson University School]], [[Florida Atlantic University High School|FAU High School]], one of two Florida Atlantic University Research Parks, and the Lifelong Learning Society.\n\n====Jupiter\u2013John D. MacArthur Campus====\nIn addition to the Boca Raton campus in southern [[Palm Beach County]], Florida Atlantic University operates a campus in northern Palm Beach County, in [[Jupiter, Florida|Jupiter]]. The John D. MacArthur Campus, named after businessman and philanthropist [[John D. MacArthur]], was established in 1999 to serve residents of central and northern Palm Beach and southern [[Martin County, Florida|Martin]] counties. The MacArthur Campus occupies 45&nbsp;acres (0.18&nbsp;km\u00b2), upon which are eight classroom and office buildings, a library, a 500-seat auditorium, two residence halls, a dining hall, museum building, and utility plant.<ref name=\"About Jupiter\">{{cite web|title=About FAU at Jupiter |publisher=Florida Atlantic University |url=http://wise.fau.edu/jupiter/about-fau/ |accessdate=July 8, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629130441/http://wise.fau.edu/jupiter/about-fau/ |archivedate=June 29, 2007 }}</ref> The MacArthur Campus also houses the [[Harriet L. Wilkes Honors College]], [[The Scripps Research Institute|Scripps Florida]], FAU Brain Institute, and the [[Max Planck Florida Institute for Neuroscience]]. The campus serves approximately 1,262&nbsp;students, or 4% of the university's student body.<ref name=\"Campus Enroll\"/>\n\n===Broward County campuses===\n\n====Dania Beach\u2013SeaTech====\nThe [[Dania Beach, Florida|Dania Beach]] Campus, also known as SeaTech, was founded in 1997 as a state-funded Type&nbsp;II research center.<ref name=\"Dania Campus\">{{cite web | title = Dania Beach Campus | publisher =Florida Atlantic University | url =http://wise.fau.edu/broward/daniabeach/ | accessdate =June 24, 2007}}</ref> The institute is part of Florida Atlantic's Department of Ocean Engineering which was founded in 1965 as the first ocean engineering undergraduate program in the nation. The campus is located on 8&nbsp;acres (0.03&nbsp;km\u00b2) of land between the Atlantic Ocean and the [[Intracoastal Waterway]]. SeaTech is home to university faculty and students engaged in sponsored ocean engineering research and development in the areas of [[acoustics]], marine vehicles, [[hydrodynamics]] and [[physical oceanography]], marine materials and [[Nanotechnology|nanocomposites]].<ref name=\"Dania Campus\"/> The Dania Beach Campus serves approximately 70&nbsp;students, roughly 1% of the university's total student body.<ref name=\"Campus Enroll\"/>\n\n====Davie====\n[[File:FAU Davie Campus.jpg|thumb|right|Senator James A. Scott Education and Science Building on the FAU [[Davie, Florida|Davie]] campus]] The [[Davie, Florida|Davie]] Campus of Florida Atlantic University was established in 1990 on 38 acres (0.15&nbsp;km\u00b2) of land in western Broward County.<ref name=\"Davie Campus\">{{cite web | title = Davie Campus | publisher =Florida Atlantic University | url =http://wise.fau.edu/broward/davie/ | accessdate =June 24, 2007}}</ref> The campus serves approximately 3,488&nbsp;students, or 13% of the Florida Atlantic student body, making it the university's second largest campus by enrollment.<ref name=\"Campus Enroll\"/> The campus features a multi-story [[Student activity center|student union]] with offices for [[student government#United States|student government]] and student organizations, a multipurpose area and student lounge, a bookstore, and cafeteria.<ref name=\"Student Union\">{{cite press release | title =FAU Constructs Student Union at Davie Campus |publisher =Florida Atlantic University: University Communications and Marketing | date =May 7, 2007 | url =http://fau.edu/mediarelations/Releases0507/050706.php | accessdate =July 10, 2007}}</ref> The union also contains a student health center that provides medical services and health counseling.<ref name=\"Student Union\"/> Davie is also the home of \"environmental research initiatives focused on [[Everglades]] restoration.\"<ref name=\"FAU Broward\">{{cite web|title=About FAU in Broward |publisher=Florida Atlantic University |url=http://wise.fau.edu/broward/about.php |accessdate=June 24, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070522221218/http://wise.fau.edu/broward/about.php |archivedate=May 22, 2007 }}</ref> FAU colleges offering courses at the FAU Davie campus include Design and Social Inquiry; Arts and Letters; Business; Education; Nursing; and Science. The campus is located on [[Broward College]]'s Central Campus. Students may enter BC as freshmen and graduate from FAU with undergraduate degrees in over 14 disciplines. More than 315,000 square feet of carefully designed classrooms, laboratories and faculty, staff and student offices are located on this campus along with a shared-use, 112,000 square-foot FAU/BC library designed for the 21st century.\n\nOther support facilities include a shared Childcare Center, a student Wellness Center and a multi-service Student Union. The campus also offers a rich and varied program of student activities provided by the Division of Student Affairs. Students have all of the services they require for career counseling, wellness, testing and evaluation, tutoring, health services, student government and financial aid, among others. Like a small college within a large university, the Davie Campus is seen as a \"model\" branch campus for the state of Florida and the nation.<ref name=\"Davie Campus\" />\n\n====Fort Lauderdale====\nThe university has two buildings in downtown [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], both of which are considered part of one Fort Lauderdale campus. The Askew Tower (AT) and the Higher Education Complex (HEC) on Las Olas Boulevard. The campus offers courses in communication, [[graphic design]], architecture, and urban and regional planning.<ref name=\"Fort Lauderdale\">{{cite web | title = Fort Lauderdale Campus | publisher =Florida Atlantic University | url =http://wise.fau.edu/broward/fortlauderdale/ | accessdate =June 24, 2007}}</ref> The campus is home to approximately 900&nbsp;students or 3.2% of the university's student body.<ref name=\"Campus Enroll\"/>\n\n===St. Lucie County campuses===\n\n====Fort Pierce\u2013Harbor Branch Oceanographic Institution====\nIn addition to the Treasure Coast Campus, Florida Atlantic University operates a campus in [[Fort Pierce, Florida|Fort Pierce]] at the [[Harbor Branch Oceanographic Institution]]. Harbor Branch merged with the university in 2007 to become the HBOI at FAU.<ref name=\"Facts\"/><ref name=\"FAU Campuses\"/><ref name=\"Merged\"/> The Florida Legislature allocated $44&nbsp;million for the university to acquire the institution and its 600-acre (2.4&nbsp;km\u00b2) campus.<ref name=\"Merger 1\"/><ref name=\"Merger\">{{cite news | last =Reed | first =Charlie |title=Work begins on merger plan for Harbor Branch and FAU | publisher = Scripps Interactive Newspapers Group |date =May 17, 2007 <!--|url=http://www.tcpalm.com/tcp/local_news/article/0,2545,TCP_16736_5540530,00.html (Dead) |accessdate=May 27, 2007 -->}}</ref><ref name=\"HBOI into FAU\">{{cite news|last=Bierman |first=Noah |title=Harbor Branch institute becoming part of Florida Atlantic University |work=Herald-Tribune |date=June 18, 2007 |url=http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20070618/NEWS/706180563 |accessdate=July 9, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070917192418/http://www.heraldtribune.com/article/20070618/NEWS/706180563 |archivedate=September 17, 2007 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n===Former Campuses===\n\n====Port St. Lucie\u2013Treasure Coast Campus====\nTreasure Coast Campus of Florida Atlantic University operated through a partnership with [[Indian River State College]] (IRSC). Florida Atlantic purchased 50&nbsp;acres (0.2&nbsp;km\u00b2) of land in Port St. Lucie in 1994. At the end of Spring 2012 class term, Florida Atlantic University ended offering classes at the Port St. Lucie campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fau.edu/explore/campuses.php|title=FAU \u2013 Campuses & Maps|work=fau.edu}}</ref>\n\n==Athletics==\n{{main|Florida Atlantic Owls}}\nFlorida Atlantic's 18&nbsp;varsity sports teams, the [[Florida Atlantic Owls|Owls]], compete in NCAA's Division I. The Owls recently joined [[Conference USA]] for the 2013\u201314 season. The university's athletics program began in 1979, when Florida Atlantic first started sponsoring intercollegiate teams.<ref name=\"Athletics HF\">{{cite press release | title =FAU Inducts Seven into Inaugural Athletic Hall of Fame |publisher = Florida Atlantic University: FAU Athletics | date =October 27, 2006 | url =http://fausports.cstv.com/genrel/100906aaa.html | accessdate =July 12, 2007}}</ref> Since then, the university has worked to expand the quality of its intercollegiate program by attracting coaches such as [[Howard Schnellenberger]], [[Matt Doherty (basketball)|Matt Doherty]], [[Rex Walters]], [[Lane Kiffin]], and [[Mike Jarvis]]. In 2006, the athletic department was ranked 79th in the nation by the [[National Association of Collegiate Directors of Athletics]] (NACDA). Along with ''[[USA Today]]'' and the United States Sports Academy, NACDA recognized the university for its Division&nbsp;I athletic programs and accomplishments.\"<ref name=\"79th Ranking\">{{cite press release |title =University MRI Continues Commitment with FAU Football | publisher =Florida Atlantic University: University Communications and Marketing | date =August 2, 2006 | url =http://fau.edu/mediarelations/Releases0806/080602.php |accessdate =July 12, 2007}}</ref> This ranking placed Florida Atlantic in the top 24% of 326&nbsp;NCAA Division&nbsp;I universities.<ref name=\"79th Ranking\"/> The university's colors are FAU Blue, FAU Red, and FAU Silver.<ref name=\"Colors\">{{cite web | url = http://www.fau.edu/branding/FAU_VSM.pdf| format = PDF | title = Florida Atlantic University: Visual Standards Manual Version 2.1 (updated 9/2008) |publisher = Florida Atlantic University: University Communications and Marketing | accessdate = April 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[2008 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|In 2008]], the [[Florida Atlantic Owls football|Florida Atlantic football team]] finished six wins and six losses in regular season play and was invited to the [[2008 Motor City Bowl|Motor City Bowl]].<ref name=\"Motor City Bowl\">{{cite news | last = Hutton | first = Ted | title = FAU loves bowl as a gift |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  | date = December 15, 2008 <!-- |url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/college/fau/sfl-flspfau15sbdec15,0,744256.story (Dead) |accessdate=December 17, 2008 -->}}</ref> The Owls defeated [[Central Michigan University]] 24\u201321, increasing their bowl record to two wins and zero losses.<ref>{{cite news | last = Hutton | first = Ted | title = Owls beat Central Michigan 24\u201321 in Motor City Bowl |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  |date=December 27, 2008 <!--|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/college/fau/sfl-motorcity,0,6513765.story (Dead) |accessdate=January 7, 2009 -->}}</ref> During the previous season, the [[2007 Florida Atlantic Owls football team|football team]] beat [[Troy University]] in the final game of regular season play to become Sun Belt Co-Champions and receive an invitation to the [[New Orleans Bowl]]. In just the seventh year of the football program's history, and the third year playing in Division I, Florida Atlantic set NCAA records by both becoming the youngest program ever to receive an invitation to, and win, a [[2007 New Orleans Bowl|bowl game]].<ref name=\"Fastest Ever\">{{cite news | last =Hutton | first =Ted | title =Owls bowl-bound |newspaper=South Florida Sun-Sentinel  | date =December 2, 2007 <!--|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/college/fau/sfl-flspfau02sbdec02,0,6253873.story (Dead) |accessdate=December 4, 2007 -->}}</ref><ref name=\"NCAA Record\">{{cite news | last =Shain |first=Jeff |title=Florida Atlantic secures its first bowl berth |newspaper=The Kansas City Star |date=December 1, 2007 <!-- |url=http://www.kansascity.com/467/story/386090.html (Dead) |accessdate=December 4, 2007 -->}}</ref><ref name=\"Another NCAA Record\">{{cite news | last =Hutton| first =Ted| title =FAU storms to victory in New Orleans Bowl |newspaper=Orlando Sentinel  |date=December 22, 2007 <!--|url =http://www.dailypress.com/topic/orl-fau2207dec22,0,6813064.story (Dead) |accessdate=July 10, 2008 -->}}</ref> As a result of the New Orleans Bowl the university has seen a surge in school spirit.<ref name=\"Spirit Surge\">{{cite news | last = Zinn | first = Dori | title = Bleeding Red and Blue: School spirit at FAU remains high despite a losing football season | publisher = [[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]] | date = October 16, 2008 | url = http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2008/10/16/CurrentIssue/Bleeding.Red.And.Blue-3486934.shtml | accessdate = December 17, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717171639/http://www.upressonline.com/2.9209/bleeding-red-and-blue-1.1238246 |archivedate=July 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn past seasons the Owls have garnered a number of accolades for their accomplishments. During the 2006\u20132007 season, the men's basketball team was noted as \"one of the [[Sun Belt Conference]]'s top offensive teams,\" with a \"scary offense\" that earned it the reputation of the \"best shooting team in the conference\".<ref name=\"HS FAU\">{{cite news | last =Shugart | first =Kim | title =Jaguars seek to rebound against high-scoring FAU | publisher =Alabama Live LLC | date =February 21, 2007 <!--|url=http://www.al.com/sports/mobileregister/index.ssf?/base/sports/1172053012189330.xml&coll=3 (Dead) |accessdate =July 12, 2007 -->}}</ref> In 2010, the men's basketball team defeated its first-ever [[Southeastern Conference]] opponent [[Mississippi State University]] 61\u201359<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mstateathletics.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=16800&ATCLID=205039259|title=State Cagers Drop Nailbiter To FAU, 61\u201359|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref> as well as [[Big East Conference (1979\u20132013)|Big East]] opponent the [[University of South Florida]] 50\u201342<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gousfbulls.com/ViewArticle.dbml?&DB_OEM_ID=7700&ATCLID=205042808&SPID=2923&SPSID=36686|title=Bulls Drop Defensive Struggle to FAU, 50\u201342|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref> en route to a 21\u20139 overall record and claimed the [[Sun Belt Conference]] title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fau.edu/explore/homepage-stories/2011_02basketbllwin.php|title=FAU \u2013 Homepage Stories|website=fau.edu|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe baseball team was also recognized by the NCAA as ranking in the Top&nbsp;10 in five team categories. The team was also ranked third in the nation in home runs per game (1.66) and in [[slugging percentage]] (.563).<ref name=\"BB High\">{{cite news | title =Baseball Ranks High in NCAA Stats | publisher =CSTV Networks, Inc | date =April 11, 2007 | url =http://www.cstv.com/sports/m-basebl/stories/041107acy.html | accessdate =July 12, 2007}}</ref> In 2010, the Owls baseball team was 37\u201324 (21\u20139) and claimed their first Sun Belt Conference regular-season title.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fauowlaccess.com/articles/194/fau-baseball-team-winning-sun-belt-title-is-our-no-2-story-of-the-year.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100716033752/http://www.fauowlaccess.com/articles/194/fau-baseball-team-winning-sun-belt-title-is-our-no-2-story-of-the-year.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 16, 2010|title=FAU baseball team winning Sun Belt title is our No. 2 Story of the Year|website=fauowlaccess.com|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Traditions===\n[[File:New Rat's Mouth.jpg|thumb|left|The \"Rat's Mouth\" student tailgating area located at the grassy area directly in front of  FAU Stadium. In 2015, this area was moved to Lot 5 behind the stadium.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cox |first1=Gregory |title=NewsTop Stories Confirmed, Lot Five will remain 2015 tailgate location |url=https://www.upressonline.com/2015/06/confirmed-lot-five-will-remain-2015-tailgate-location/ |website=University Press |publisher=University Press |accessdate=February 13, 2020}}</ref>]]\nFlorida Atlantic University is home to a number of sports-related traditions and school spirit organizations.\n\nEvery fall before the first football game of the season, FAU's Student Government Association sponsors the annual football \"Bonfire\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fauowlaccess.com/blogs/owlthingsconsidered/2010/08/thursdays-daily-briefing-blazers-beware-faus-bonfire-is-tonight.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110405190343/http://www.fauowlaccess.com/blogs/owlthingsconsidered/2010/08/thursdays-daily-briefing-blazers-beware-faus-bonfire-is-tonight.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 5, 2011|title=Thursday's Daily Briefing: Blazers beware, FAU\u2019s bonfire is tonight|website=fauowlaccess.com|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://upressonline.com/2011/08/fourth-annual-bonfire-postponed/|title=Fourth annual bonfire postponed|first=Ryan|last=Cortes|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref> where the opposing team's mascot is burned in effigy. This event typically includes a concert and a speech by the university's head football coach.\n\nAlso in football, Florida Atlantic challenges its rival [[Florida International]] (FIU) is the annual [[Shula Bowl]]. This intercollegiate football game is named after legendary coach [[Don Shula]]; so named because at the time of its inception, both head coaches, Florida Atlantic's [[Howard Schnellenberger]] and Florida International coach [[Don Strock]], had worked under Shula at some point during their careers. Even though both universities have since moved on to new head coaches, the Shula Bowl is still played. As a home game, the competition takes place at university's own stadium; as an away game, the bowl is played at [[FIU Stadium]] in Miami.<ref name=\"FAU Trad\" />\n\nFor basketball, Florida Atlantic celebrates the \"Red Hot Madness and Stroll Off\" pep rally that introduces fans to the team and coaches, host a number of basketball-related contests such as 3-point shoot-outs and slam dunk competitions, and features step performances by the school's [[National Pan-Hellenic Council]] fraternities and sororities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2011-10-20/sports/fau-basketball-102011_1_greg-gantt-brett-royster-sun-belt|title=FAU Midnight Madness Thursday at FAU Arena|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref> During the regular season, the \"Bury the Burrow in Red\" event calls for Florida Atlantic students to wear as much red as possible and fill the [[FAU Arena|Burrow]], the university's multi-purpose arena, during the annual [[college basketball|basketball]] rivalry game between Florida Atlantic and Florida International University.<ref>{{cite press release | title = Support FAU Basketball at 'Bury the Burrow in Red' on Feb. 10 | publisher = Florida Atlantic University: University Communications and Marketing | url = http://www.fau.edu/communications/internal/update/archive/07Feb/univnews.html#4 | accessdate = April 7, 2009 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090625085013/http://www.fau.edu/communications/internal/update/archive/07Feb/univnews.html#4 | archivedate = June 25, 2009 | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe official spirit group supporting Florida Atlantic athletics is the \"prOWLers\". The group began in February 2002 to support the men's basketball program during the team's run for the [[Atlantic Sun Conference|Atlantic Sun Conference Championship]]. The group is funded by the Student Alumni Association, and can now be found at most sporting events cheering for Florida Atlantic.<ref>{{cite web | title =prOWLers \u2013 The rowdiest students at FAU | publisher =Florida Atlantic University: Athletics Department | url =http://fausports.cstv.com/trads/prowlers.html | accessdate =July 15, 2007 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20080228021328/http://fausports.cstv.com/trads/prowlers.html | archive-date =February 28, 2008 | url-status =dead | df =mdy-all }}</ref> The prOWLers are joined by the Owl Rangers,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.owlrangers.com/|title=Owl Rangers \u2013 Wow, It's Owls|website=owlrangers.com|accessdate=May 6, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519193842/http://owlrangers.com/|archive-date=May 19, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> a fan group that paints their bodies in the Florida Atlantic school colors. The hOWLetts are a student club that attend gameday events and assist in recruiting athletes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fau.collegiatelink.net/organization/howlett-club/about|title=Owl Central -|website=fau.collegiatelink.net|accessdate=May 6, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426002246/http://fau.collegiatelink.net/organization/howlett-club/about|archivedate=April 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSince 2002, Florida Atlantic students have been using Owl Fingers (the \"OK\" hand sign) to show school pride and wish the athletic teams luck during football point after attempts (PATs) and basketball free throws.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://upressonline.com/2011/10/we-have-spirit-yes-we-do-we-have-spirit%E2%80%A6wait-we-do/|title=We have spirit, yes we do, we have spirit\u2026wait, we do?|first=Jessica|last=Cohn-Kleinberg|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref> The Florida Atlantic University Athletics Department has chosen to use Owl Fingers as part of its \"Salute the Hoot\" 2012 marketing campaign that encourages students to \"proudly raise the hand salute that depicts the eyes of the owl, FAU's mascot.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fausports.com/genrel/020912aaa.html|title=FAU Launches 'Salute the Hoot' Campaign|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://upressonline.com/2012/02/with-added-development-and-expansion-time-for-fau-community-to-give-a-hoot/|title=With added development and expansion, time for FAU, community, to give a hoot|first=Rolando|last=Rosa|accessdate=May 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Residential life===\n[[File:FAU Parliament Hall.JPG|thumb|Florida Atlantic University's Parliament Hall on the [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]] campus]]\nResidential housing at Florida Atlantic University is available on the Boca Raton and John D. MacArthur campuses. \"All full-time freshmen are required to reside in university housing,\" however, \"exemptions from this policy are made for students who: are 21 or older by the first day of class, reside with parent(s) or legal guardian(s) within a {{convert|50|mi|km|adj=on}} radius of the Boca Raton campus, or are married.\"<ref name=\"Housing Info\">{{cite web|title=General Information |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Department of Housing and Residential Life |url=http://www.fau.edu/housing/General_Information/index.php?mainlinks=3 |accessdate=April 2, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090412010644/http://www.fau.edu/housing/General_Information/index.php?mainlinks=3 |archivedate=April 12, 2009 }}</ref> {{as of|2011}}, 4,555&nbsp;students live on-campus in Boca Raton.<ref name=\"Facts\"/><ref name=\"On-Campus Housing\">{{cite web|title=On-Campus Housing |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Office of Institutional Effectiveness & Analysis |url=http://www.fau.edu/iea/factbook/house11.pdf |accessdate=February 11, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510042518/http://www.fau.edu/iea/factbook/house11.pdf |archivedate=May 10, 2013 }}</ref> The Wilkes Honors College on the MacArthur Campus requires all students live on-campus within its two residence halls, however, exceptions are made for students who are 26&nbsp;years of age, married, or have dependent children.<ref name=\"On-Campus Housing Jupiter 1\">{{cite web|publisher=Florida Atlantic University: The Harriet L. Wilkes Honors College |title=Residential Life |url=http://www.fau.edu/divdept/honcol/residential.htm |accessdate=October 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070608034745/http://www.fau.edu/divdept/honcol/residential.htm |archivedate=June 8, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"On-Campus Housing Jupiter 2\">{{cite web|publisher=Florida Atlantic University: The Harriet L. Wilkes Honors College |title=Your New Home |url=http://www.fau.edu/divdept/honcol/residential_brochure.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=October 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025182506/http://www.fau.edu/divdept/honcol/residential_brochure.pdf |archivedate=October 25, 2007 }}</ref> {{as of|2011}}, there are 231&nbsp;students residing on-campus at the honors college.<ref name=\"On-Campus Housing\"/>\n\n[[File:FAU Innovation Village.JPG|right|thumb|Florida Atlantic University's Innovation Village student apartments on the [[Boca Raton, Florida|Boca Raton]] campus]]\nBoca Raton's on-campus housing facilities are: Indian River Towers (opened 2001), Heritage Park Towers (opened 2004), Glades Park Towers (opened 2007), Parliament Hall (opened 2013), University Village Apartments (UVA), and Innovation Village Apartments (IVA) (opened 2011). Heritage Park and Glades Park Towers each offer 602 beds with 96 single rooms.<ref name=\"Glades Park\">{{cite web | title =Joint Audit and Finance/Strategic Planning Committee | publisher =FAU Board of Trustees | date =June 13, 2007 | url =http://www.fau.edu/bot/files/061307_AFSPA-1.pdf | format = PDF | accessdate =June 24, 2007}}</ref> UVA and IVA exclusively serve upperclassmen while the other residence halls exclusively serve freshmen students. The university also offers upper-division undergraduate and graduate student housing in the Business and Professional Women's Scholarship House for women with a strong academic background.<ref name=\"BPW House\">{{cite web|title=Business & Professional Woman's Scholarship House |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Department of Housing and Residential Life |url=http://www.fau.edu/housing/Our_Residence_Halls_and_Apartments/BPW_House.php |accessdate=April 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090322090849/http://www.fau.edu/housing/Our_Residence_Halls_and_Apartments/BPW_House.php |archivedate=March 22, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"Housing Options\">{{cite web|title=Our Residence Halls and Apartments |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Department of Housing and Residential Life |url=http://www.fau.edu/housing/Our_Residence_Halls_and_Apartments/index.php?mainlinks=4 |accessdate=April 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090412014557/http://www.fau.edu/housing/Our_Residence_Halls_and_Apartments/index.php?mainlinks=4 |archivedate=April 12, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOne of the newest residences on the Boca Raton campus is the Innovation Village Apartments (IVA), consisting of two buildings: IVA North and IVA South. It is a 1,200-bed apartment-style housing facility for upperclassmen, graduate, and medical students. It offers amenities that one would find in a high-rise apartment complex: lounges, retail dining, fitness centers, a pool/cabana, a volleyball court, common areas, and more. The facility opened in fall 2011.<ref name=\"New Grad Apts\">{{cite web|title=BT-651 Innovation Village Apartments Phase I |publisher=Florida Atlantic University Architect & Vice President for Facilities |date=November 20, 2007 |format=PDF |url=http://www.fau.edu/facilities/uavp/programs-folder/600_Bed_Innov_Village_Program_for_Signiture_11.20.07.pdf |accessdate=February 25, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080719161311/http://www.fau.edu/facilities/uavp/programs-folder/600_Bed_Innov_Village_Program_for_Signiture_11.20.07.pdf |archivedate=July 19, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301170817/http://www.upressonline.com/building-the-future-1.2137444|author=Persaud, Chris |url=http://www.upressonline.com/building-the-future-1.2137444|title= Building the future: Stadium and apartment buildings construction to begin in April|archivedate=March 1, 2010|publisher=University Press|date=January 18, 2010}}</ref> FAU's newest residence hall is Parliament Hall, a lakeside freshmen housing facility offering 614 beds, a fitness center, lounges, retail dining, and views of the nearby Atlantic Ocean from top floors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2013-08-28/news/fl-brf-parliament-0828-20130828_1_anthony-barbar-fau-student-affairs|title=FAU opens $46&nbsp;million Parliament Hall dorm|work=tribunedigital-sunsentinel}}</ref>\n\nWithin its existing residential life programs, Florida Atlantic offers a number of Learning Communities for freshmen and students with similar interests and concentrations. Participants meet people with similar interests, live on the same floor and take courses with others in their community, while receiving additional guidance related to those interests.<ref name=\"LLC\">{{cite web|title=Becoming a Part of the Community: Living Learning Communities |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Department of Housing and Residential Life |url=http://www.fau.edu/retention/2007-08LLCBrochure.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=July 9, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025182428/http://www.fau.edu/retention/2007-08LLCBrochure.pdf |archivedate=October 25, 2007 }}</ref> The university's Learning Community programs are divided into two categories, Freshman Learning Communities and Living Learning Communities. The freshman program offers 16 different concentrations, including business, nursing, and education. The Living program offers six concentrations for students residing in the Glades Park Towers [[dormitory]], including engineering, computer science, and a Women's Leadership program.<ref name=\"LLC\"/>\n\nThe university's Department of Housing and Residential Life and the university's fraternities and sororities sponsor a program for [[freshman|freshmen]] and other students returning to Florida Atlantic in the fall semester. This program, called the \"Weeks of Welcome\", spans 11&nbsp;days and all campuses, and works to acclimate students with university life and to build a good on-campus community.<ref name=\"Weeks of Welcome\">{{cite news|last=Reil |first=Quinn |title=Welcome Weeks at FAU offer fun for new students |publisher=[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]] |date=September 11, 2003 |url=http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2003/09/11/News/Welcome.Weeks.At.Fau.Offer.Fun.For.New.Students-461664.shtml |accessdate=July 22, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071129221456/http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2003/09/11/News/Welcome.Weeks.At.Fau.Offer.Fun.For.New.Students-461664.shtml |archivedate=November 29, 2007 }}</ref> On each day, a number of different events are scheduled, including Hall Wars, which are athletic competitions between dormitories, [[Luau]]s, and a number of other events.<ref name=\"List of WoW events 2007\">{{cite news|title=Weeks of welcome: What's happening on your campus |publisher=[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]] |date=August 12, 2004 |url=http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2004/08/12/WhatsUpevents/Weeks.Of.Welcome-701802.shtml |accessdate=July 22, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027122050/http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2004/08/12/WhatsUpevents/Weeks.Of.Welcome-701802.shtml |archivedate=October 27, 2007 }}</ref> The Weeks of Welcome is the second largest campus-wide event held by Florida Atlantic.<ref name=\"Weeks of Welcome\"/>\n\n===Student housing===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:500px; float:left; margin:10px\"\n! FAU residence halls<ref>{{cite web|title=FIU Housing |url=http://www.housing.fiu.edu/Buildings/index.html |publisher=FIU Office of Housing and Residential Life |accessdate=September 16, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080912081651/http://www.housing.fiu.edu/Buildings/index.html |archivedate=September 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n! Year opened\n! Students\n! Accommodations\n|-\n| Business Professional Women's Scholarship House {{small| (BPWSH)}}\n| 1996\n| 16\n| Female residence requiring dedicated application\n|-\n| Indian River Towers {{small| (IRT)}}\n| 2001\n| 611\n| Freshmen\n|-\n| Heritage Park Towers {{small| (HPT)}}\n| 2004\n| 603\n| Freshmen\n|-\n| Glades Park Towers {{small| (GPT)}}\n| 2007\n| 602\n| Freshmen\n|-\n| Parliament Hall {{small| (PAR)}}\n| 2013\n| 614\n|Freshmen\n|-\n| University Village Apartments {{small| (UVA)}}\n| 1995\n| 524\n| Upperclassmen\n|-\n| Innovation Village Apartments South {{small| (IVA-S)}}\n| 2011\n| 605\n| Upperclassmen\n|-\n| Innovation Village Apartments North {{small| (IVA-N)}}\n| 2011\n| 611\n| Upperclassmen\n|-\n| Total\n| \u2013\n| 4,317 students\n| \u2013\n|}\n\n===Campus organizations and activities===\nFor the 2010\u20132011 academic year, Florida Atlantic had approximately 300&nbsp;registered student organizations. Among the groups are academic organizations, honor societies, spiritual/religious organizations, diversity-appreciation organizations, service organizations, personal interest organizations, sports clubs, and student government agencies. These clubs and organizations run the gamut from [[sailing]] to [[Ultimate Frisbee]], from varsity and club sports and a [[jazz]] group to a [[pottery]] [[guild]], from political organizations to chess and video game clubs.<ref name=\"Registered Club List\">{{cite web|title=FAU Registered Club List |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Student Development & Activities |url=https://swise.fau.edu/universitycenter/clubreg/clubs_list.php |accessdate=April 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719192937/https://swise.fau.edu/universitycenter/clubreg/clubs_list.php |archivedate=July 19, 2011 }}</ref> These organizations are funded by student tuition, from which $10.00 per credit hour goes toward an activities and service fee fund. This generates approximately $9&nbsp;million that is then given to [[student government#United States|student government]] for allocation to student clubs and organizations. The student government also finances other student life programs, including career fairs, the ''[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]]'', OWL TV and Owl Radio, and Homecoming.<ref name=\"SGA $\">{{cite web | title =Activity and Service (A&S) Fee | publisher =Florida Atlantic University: Student Government Accounting and Budget Office | url =http://www.fau.edu/student/fees.php| accessdate =December 30, 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:I Heart FAU Sign Sunset.jpg|thumb|The \"I love FAU\" mural near student residence halls]]\n\nFlorida Atlantic's [[homecoming]], also known as the \"Owl Prowl,\" is celebrated annually in the fall semester. Events occur mainly on the Boca Raton Campus, but a number of other campuses host their own events as well. In the past, homecoming has had kickoff parties, costumed dances, [[bonfires]], comedy shows, alumni events and dinners, a golf cart parade, and [[tailgating]].<ref name=\"HC 2004\">{{cite news\n |title=Some traditions continued, new ones started\n |publisher=[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]]\n |date=November 25, 2004\n |url=http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2004/11/25/CoverStory/Owl-Prowl.2004-815187.shtml?sourcedomain=www.upressonline.com&MIIHost=media.collegepublisher.com\n |accessdate=July 15, 2007\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071129215208/http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2004/11/25/CoverStory/Owl-Prowl.2004-815187.shtml?sourcedomain=www.upressonline.com&MIIHost=media.collegepublisher.com\n |archivedate=November 29, 2007\n}}</ref><ref name=\"HC 2006 List\">{{cite news | last =Boyet | first =Michele |title=Homecoming Listings |publisher=[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]] |date=October 19, 2006 <!--|url=http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2006/10/19/CoverStory/Homecoming.Listings-2372548.shtml?sourcedomain=www.upressonline.com&MIIHost=media.collegepublisher.com (Dead) |accessdate=July 15, 2007 -->}}</ref><ref name=\"HC 2006\">{{cite news|title=Student Government Page |publisher=[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]] |date=November 9, 2006 |url=http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2006/11/09/StudentGovernment/Student.Government.Page-2444958.shtml?sourcedomain=www.upressonline.com&MIIHost=media.collegepublisher.com |accessdate=July 15, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071129221507/http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2006/11/09/StudentGovernment/Student.Government.Page-2444958.shtml?sourcedomain=www.upressonline.com&MIIHost=media.collegepublisher.com |archivedate=November 29, 2007 }}</ref> Florida Atlantic students have an organized football tailgating area known as the Rat's Mouth.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.fau.edu/sil/Tailgating%20Expectations.pdf |title=Guide to A Successful Rat's Mouth Tailgate |access-date=November 26, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111119063000/http://fau.edu/sil/Tailgating%20Expectations.pdf |archive-date=November 19, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The name references the Spanish translation of [[Boca Raton]].\n\nFlorida Atlantic completed an $18.6&nbsp;million Recreation and Wellness Center in spring 2010. The facility houses an outdoor leisure and lap pool, a cardio equipment and free weight room, two multipurpose rooms, three indoor courts and health club-style locker rooms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/facility/rec_center.php |title=FAU \u2013 Recreation & Fitness Center |publisher=Fau.edu |accessdate=December 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111222151455/http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/facility/rec_center.php |archivedate=December 22, 2011 }}</ref> In 2011, the facility won the NIRSA Outstanding Sports Facilities Award. Other recreation facilities include a $4.2&nbsp;million<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fausports.com/facilities/trackandfieldcomplex.html |title=FLORIDA ATLANTIC UNIVERSITY Facilities \u2013 FLORIDA ATLANTIC University Official Athletic Site |publisher=Fausports.com |date=January 11, 2007 |accessdate=December 30, 2011}}</ref> track and field complex,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/facility/track.php |title=FAU \u2013 Track & Field Complex |publisher=Fau.edu |accessdate=December 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123112931/http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/facility/track.php |archivedate=November 23, 2011 }}</ref> with synthetic turf (opened January 2007), a ropes challenge course<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/challenge_course/challenge_course.php |title=FAU \u2013 Challenge Course |publisher=Fau.edu |accessdate=December 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111218212408/http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/challenge_course/challenge_course.php |archivedate=December 18, 2011 }}</ref> and the 6.5 acre Henderson Fields, utilized most often by the FAU Intramural Sports and Club Sports programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/facility/henderson.php |title=FAU \u2013 Henderson Field |publisher=Fau.edu |accessdate=December 30, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123112906/http://www.fau.edu/campusrec/facility/henderson.php |archivedate=November 23, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Greek life===\nFlorida Atlantic is home to approximately 28&nbsp;chapters of national [[fraternities and sororities]], encompassing approximately 1,077 members or 5% of the undergraduate population.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fraternity & Sorority Life Community Report \u2013 Fall 2011|publisher=Florida Atlantic University|url=http://www.fau.edu/fslife/documents/Reports/FSLife_CommunityReport_F11_Revised.pdf |accessdate=April 14, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Greek Percentage\">{{cite web | title = Greek Life Community Report Executive Summary | publisher = Florida Atlantic University\" Office of Greek Life | url = http://www.fau.edu/greeklife/documents/Reports/GLCommunityReport_F09.pdf | format = PDF | accessdate =February 22, 2010}}</ref> The highpoint of Greek life at Florida Atlantic is \"Greek Week.\" This event is held annually during the spring semester and showcases a number of themed competitions between the university's Greek organizations. There are currently no on-campus Greek houses.<ref name=\"Where are rushers?\">{{cite news | last =Blanchett | first =Jordan | title =Greeks Ask: Where Have all the 'Rushers' Gone? | publisher =[[University Press (Florida Atlantic University)|University Press]] | date =January 8, 2007 | url =http://media.www.upressonline.com/media/storage/paper518/news/2007/01/18/ExclusivelyOnlineGreeks.Ask.Where.Have.All.The.rushers.Gone-2670580.shtml | accessdate =July 22, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717171833/http://www.upressonline.com/2.9208/greeks-ask-where-have-all-the-rushers-gone-1.1240033 |archivedate=July 17, 2011}}</ref> However, a Greek Life Housing [[task force]] has been formed to explore various housing models, including the cost of construction, \"and make recommendations on how to improve the overall quality of the Greek housing....\"<ref name=\"Task Force\">{{cite web|title=Division of Student Affairs Divisional Committees |publisher=Florida Atlantic University: Division of Student Affairs |url=http://www.fau.edu/student/documents/committees.php |accessdate=February 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527100924/http://www.fau.edu/student/documents/committees.php |archivedate=May 27, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Alumni==\n{{main|List of Florida Atlantic University people}}\nFlorida Atlantic University has awarded more than 110,000&nbsp;degrees to nearly 105,000&nbsp;alumni worldwide since its opening. Some notable Florida Atlantic alumni are:\n\n* [[Daniel Bluman]] (born 1990), Colombian-born Israeli Olympic [[show jumping]] rider\n* [[R. David Paulison]], former head of the United States [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]]<ref>{{cite news | last = Hsu | first = Spencer S. |author2=Lee, Christopher | title = Paulison Is Skilled at Disasters | page = A12 |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=September 13, 2005 | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/09/12/AR2005091201829.html | accessdate =April 3, 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Charles Ghigna]] or \"Father Goose\", children's poet and former nationally syndicated columnist<ref>{{cite web | title = Charles Ghigna Papers | publisher = [[de Grummond Children's Literature Collection]]. University of Southern Mississippi | url = http://www.lib.usm.edu/legacy/degrum/public_html/html/research/findaids/DG1054f.html | accessdate =June 21, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Judith Ortiz Cofer]], acclaimed Puerto Rican author whose works span a range of literary genres including poetry, short stories, and essays<ref>{{cite web|title=Judith Ortiz Cofer Complete Vita |publisher=Judith Ortiz Cofer |url=http://www.english.uga.edu/~jcofer/vita.html |accessdate=December 20, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061220094653/http://www.english.uga.edu/~jcofer/vita.html |archivedate=December 20, 2006 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n*[[Greg Joseph]], placekicker for the [[Tennessee Titans]] of the [[National Football League]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Titans Player Roster |url=https://www.titansonline.com/team/players-roster/ |website=Tenneesee Titans |publisher=The Tennessee Titans |accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Phil Zimmermann]], creator of [[Pretty Good Privacy]]<ref>{{cite web | last = Zimmermann | first = Phil | title = Philip Zimmermann's Home Page | publisher = Phil Zimmermann & Associates LLC | url = http://www.philzimmermann.com | accessdate = November 25, 2006}}</ref>\n* [[Mary Carey (actress)|Mary Carey]], pornographic actress and former candidate for Governor of California<ref>{{cite news | title =Reality TV show to feature porn stars | publisher =NBC News | date =May 4, 2006 | url =http://www.nbcnews.com/id/12631189 | accessdate =October 12, 2007 | at=1m:50s}}</ref>\n* [[Carrot Top]], [[Prop comedy|prop comedian]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Entertainer detail: Carrot Top |publisher=NationalActs.com |url=http://www.nationalacts.com/comedians/carrot_top.htm |accessdate=January 26, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503223951/http://www.nationalacts.com/comedians/carrot_top.htm |archivedate=May 3, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n* [[Devin Singletary]], running back for the NFL's [[Buffalo Bills]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Devin Signletary |url=http://www.nfl.com/player/devinsingletary/2562734/profile |website=NFL.com |publisher=National Football League |accessdate=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Steven Swanson]], [[NASA]] [[astronaut]] who went to space aboard [[Space Shuttle Atlantis|Space Shuttle ''Atlantis'']] during [[STS-117]] in June 2007, and [[Space Shuttle Discovery|Space Shuttle ''Discovery'']] during [[STS-119]] in March 2009<ref>{{cite web | title = Astronaut Bio: Steven R. Swanson | publisher = [[NASA]] | url = http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/swanson.html | accessdate = October 9, 2007}}</ref>\n*[[Edith Stern]], award-winning inventor and child prodigy<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyvoice.com/new-york/yorktown/neighbors/yorktown-engineer-former-prodigy-wins-national-award/554897/|title=Yorktown Engineer, Former Prodigy Wins National Award|last=Marschhauser|first=Brian|date=December 12, 2012|website=Yorktown Daily Voice|access-date=July 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Florida<!--State institution-->}}\n* {{commons category-inline}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.fausports.com/ Florida Atlantic Athletics website]\n* [http://www.upressonline.com/ ''University Press''] \u2013 student newspaper\n\n{{Florida Atlantic University}}\n{{Navboxes\n|titlestyle = {{CollegePrimaryStyle|Florida Atlantic Owls|color=white}}\n|list1 =\n{{Boca Raton, Florida}}\n{{State University System of Florida}}\n{{Southeastern Universities Research Association}}\n{{Conference USA navbox}}\n{{USAAF Training Bases World War II}}\n}}\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Florida Atlantic University| ]]\n[[Category:1961 establishments in Florida]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Boca Raton, Florida]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1961]]\n[[Category:Public universities and colleges in Florida]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Broward County, Florida]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Florida]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Palm Beach County, Florida]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAlumni:Typo fixing, replaced: Tenneesee \u2192 Tennessee", "url_pag