tanella]]\n| 14\n| bgcolor=gold| '''[[2016\u201317 Maltese FA Trophy|W]]'''\n| 7th\n| R2\n|-\n| 2017\u20132018\n| '''[[2017\u201318 Maltese Premier League|5th]]'''\n| 26\n| 12\n| 10\n| 4\n| 48\n| 18\n| '''46'''\n| {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Mario Fontanella]]\n| 17\n| [[2017\u201318 Maltese FA Trophy|R3]]\n| bgcolor=FFCCCB| 9th\n| QF\n|-\n| 2018\u20132019\n| '''[[2018\u201319 Maltese Premier League|8th]]'''\n| 26\n| 9\n| 5\n| 12\n| 28\n| 25\n| '''32'''\n| {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Arthur Henrique Ricciardi Oyama|Arthur Oyama]]\n| 5\n| [[2018\u201319 Maltese FA Trophy|R3]]\n| C\n| 4th\n| R3\n|-\n|}\n</div>\n\n==References==\n\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.florianafc.com/ Official Website]\n\n{{Maltese football clubs}}\n{{Maltese football}}\n\n[[Category:Football clubs in Malta]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1894]]\n[[Category:Floriana]]\n[[Category:1894 establishments in Malta]]\n[[Category:Floriana F.C.]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Typo fixing, replaced: teams colours \u2192 team's colours (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floriana_F.C."}
{"title_page": "Josef Mitterer", "text_new": "'''Josef Mitterer''' (born 1948) is an Austrian philosopher, and a [[professor emeritus]] at the [[University of Klagenfurt]] Institute for Philosophy.<ref name=\"aau.at\" />\n\nMitterer studied psychology and sociology in Innsbruck and Linz and philosophy in Graz. His studies also took him to the London School of Economics ([[Imre Lakatos]]), to Heidelberg University ([[Richard Rorty]]), IUC Dubrovnik ([[Michael Dummett]], [[Willard Van Orman Quine]]) and in 1976 to Berkeley where he studied with [[Paul Feyerabend]]. Mitterer received his doctorate at the [[University of Graz]] in 1978. He then worked as a Tour Director in Europe and Asia and as a Management Consultant for the Travel Industry in the USA. Since 1990 Mitterer has been teaching philosophy at the [[University of Klagenfurt]]<ref name=\"aau.at\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aau.at/team/mitterer-josef/|title=Visitenkarte Mitterer Josef}}</ref>; he held guest lectureships at the universities of Innsbruck, Linz, Ljubljana and Siegen. \n\nIn his book ''Das Jenseits der Philosophie'' (''The Beyond of Philosophy''), based on his dissertation, he developed a Non-dualizing Philosophy of Change, which foregoes the categorical distinction between language and language-distinct reality. In ''Die Flucht aus der Beliebigkeit'' (''The Flight from Contingency'') (2001) he critically examines the epistemological goal of truth. His critically acclaimed books have been translated into Polish and the [[A&HCI]]-Journal ''[[Constructivist Foundations]]'' has published two special issues on Mitterer's philosophy, ''The Non-dualizing Philosophy of Josef Mitterer'' (2008) and ''Non-dualism: A Conceptual Revision?'' (2013).\n\nJosef Mitterer is a member of the Board of the [[Austrian Ludwig Wittgenstein Society]], a member of the Advisory Board of the [[Karl Popper]] Foundation and one of the literary executors of [[Ernst von Glasersfeld]]. He was co-organizer of the 38th [[International Wittgenstein Symposium]] \"Realism - Relativism - Constructivism\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alws.at/symposium/38th-international-wittgenstein-symposium/|title=38th International Wittgenstein Symposium 2015 \u2013 Austrian Ludwig Wittgenstein Society}}</ref>\nIn 2018 Mitterer delivered the [[Heinz von Foerster]] Lecture at the University of Vienna.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.univie.ac.at/zeitgeschichte/12-11-heinz-von-foerster-lecture-18-josef-mitterer-die-richtung-des-denkens/|title=Institut f\u00fcr Zeitgeschichte \u00bb 12.11. \u2013 Heinz von Foerster Lecture \u201918 \u2013 Josef Mitterer: Die Richtung des Denkens}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Primary===\n* ''Das Jenseits der Philosophie''. Wider das dualistische Erkenntnisprinzip.Passagen-Verlag, Wien 1992. {{ISBN|3-85165-016-6}}.\n* ''Die Flucht aus der Beliebigkeit''.  Fischer Taschenbuch Verlag Nr. 14929, Frankfurt/M. 2001. {{ISBN|3-596-14929-0}}.\n\n===Secondary===\n* Riegler, Alexander & [[Stefan Weber (media researcher)|Weber, Stefan]] (Hg.) (2008): ''The Non-dualizing Philosophy of Josef Mitterer''. Special Issue of [[Constructivist Foundations]] 3 (3).<ref>{{cite web |title=Constructivist Foundations - Volume 3, Number 3 - The Non-Dualizing Philosophy of Josef Mitterer |url=https://constructivist.info/3/3 |website=constructivist.info |language=en |date=15 July 2008}}</ref>\n* Riegler, Alexander & Weber, Stefan (Hg.) (2010): ''Die Dritte Philosophie. Kritische Beitr\u00e4ge zu Josef Mitterers Non-Dualismus''. Weilerswist: Velbr\u00fcck Wissenschaft.\n* Riegler, Alexander & Weber, Stefan (Hg.) (2013): ''Non-dualism: A Conceptual Revision?'' Special Issue of [[Constructivist Foundations]] 8 (2).<ref>{{cite web |title=Constructivist Foundations - Volume 8, Number 2 - Non-dualism: A Conceptual Revision? |url=https://constructivist.info/8/2 |website=constructivist.info |language=en |date=15 March 2013}}</ref>\n* Kletzl S. (2015) Edifying non-dualism: Richard Rorty meets Josef Mitterer. In: Kanzian C. & Mitterer J. & Neges K. (eds.) Realism \u2013 relativism \u2013 constructivism: Contributions of the 38th International Wittgenstein Symposium. Austrian Ludwig Wittgenstein Society, Kirchberg am Wechsel: 160\u2013162\n\n==Talks and presentations==\n* [http://er2017.pros.webs.upv.es/keynote-2/ ''Conceptual Modeling: Philosophical Reflections'' (abstract for a guest honor talk at the 36th International Conference on Conceptual Modeling, Nov. 6th-9th, 2017, Valencia Spain)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=18DzbWnvvCg ''Wahrheit unterwegs'' on youtube]\n* [https://www.literaturhaus-hamburg.de/programm/veranstaltungen/2012-05-15/philosophisches-cafe-josef-mitterer Caf\u00e9 philosophique with Josef Mitterer at the Literaturhaus Hamburg]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nondualism.info/ The Non-dualizing Philosophy of Josef Mitterer]\n*[https://www.wienerzeitung.at/nachrichten/reflexionen/zeitgenossen/482102-Der-Philosoph-als-Reiseleiter.html Der Philosoph als Reiseleiter (The philosopher as a Tour Director)]\n*[https://316am.site123.me/articles/the-rhetoric-and-lethargy-of-the-anthropocene Interview with Ewa Bi\u0144czyk about the philosophy of Josef Mitterer and other topics]\n*[https://science.orf.at/v2/stories/2921821/ \u00dcber das Erfinden einer Philosophie (article on the occasion of Josef Mitterer's 70th birthday on the website of the Austrian Broadcasting Corporation ORF)]\n*[https://www.diepresse.com/658146/wir-beissen-nicht-in-das-wort \"Wir bei\u00dfen nicht in das Wort\" - about Mitterer's philosophy in the Austrian newspaper ''Die Presse'']\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitterer, Josef}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Austrian philosophers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Austrian philosophers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Josef Mitterer''' (born 1948) is an Austrian philosopher, and a [[professor emeritus]] at the [[University of Klagenfurt]] Institute for Philosophy.<ref name=\"aau.at\" />\n\nMitterer studied psychology and sociology in Innsbruck and Linz and philosophy in Graz. His studies also took him to the London School of Economics ([[Imre Lakatos]]), to Heidelberg University ([[Richard Rorty]]), IUC Dubrovnik ([[Michael Dummett]], [[Willard Van Orman Quine]]) and in 1976 to Berkeley where he studied with [[Paul Feyerabend]]. Mitterer received his doctorate at the [[University of Graz]] in 1978. He then worked as a Tour Director in Europe and Asia and as a Management Consultant for the Travel Industry in the USA. Since 1990 Mitterer has been teaching philosophy at the [[University of Klagenfurt]]<ref name=\"aau.at\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aau.at/team/mitterer-josef/|title=Visitenkarte Mitterer Josef}}</ref>; he held guest lectureships at the universities of Innsbruck, Linz, Ljubljana and Siegen. \n\nIn his book ''Das Jenseits der Philosophie'' (''The Beyond of Philosophy''), based on his dissertation, he developed a Non-dualizing Philosophy of Change, which foregoes the categorical distinction between language and language-distinct reality. In ''Die Flucht aus der Beliebigkeit'' (The Flight from Contingency) (2001) he critically examines the epistemological goal of truth. His critically acclaimed books have been translated into Polish and the [[A&HCI]]-Journal ''[[Constructivist Foundations]]'' has published two special issues on Mitterers philosophy, ''The Non-dualizing Philosophy of Josef Mitterer'' (2008) and ''Non-dualism: A Conceptual Revision?'' (2013).\n\nJosef Mitterer is a member of the Board of the [[Austrian Ludwig Wittgenstein Society]], a member of the Advisory Board of the [[Karl Popper]] Foundation and one of the literary executors of [[Ernst von Glasersfeld]]. He was co-organizer of the 38th [[International Wittgenstein Symposium]] \"Realism - Relativism - Constructivism\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alws.at/symposium/38th-international-wittgenstein-symposium/|title=38th International Wittgenstein Symposium 2015 \u2013 Austrian Ludwig Wittgenstein Society}}</ref>\nIn 2018 Mitterer delivered the [[Heinz von Foerster]] Lecture at the University of Vienna.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.univie.ac.at/zeitgeschichte/12-11-heinz-von-foerster-lecture-18-josef-mitterer-die-richtung-des-denkens/|title=Institut f\u00fcr Zeitgeschichte \u00bb 12.11. \u2013 Heinz von Foerster Lecture \u201918 \u2013 Josef Mitterer: Die Richtung des Denkens}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Primary===\n* ''Das Jenseits der Philosophie''. Wider das dualistische Erkenntnisprinzip.Passagen-Verlag, Wien 1992. {{ISBN|3-85165-016-6}}.\n* ''Die Flucht aus der Beliebigkeit''.  Fischer Taschenbuch Verlag Nr. 14929, Frankfurt/M. 2001. {{ISBN|3-596-14929-0}}.\n\n===Secondary===\n* Riegler, Alexander & [[Stefan Weber (media researcher)|Weber, Stefan]] (Hg.) (2008): ''The Non-dualizing Philosophy of Josef Mitterer''. Special Issue of [[Constructivist Foundations]] 3 (3).<ref>{{cite web |title=Constructivist Foundations - Volume 3, Number 3 - The Non-Dualizing Philosophy of Josef Mitterer |url=https://constructivist.info/3/3 |website=constructivist.info |language=en |date=15 July 2008}}</ref>\n* Riegler, Alexander & Weber, Stefan (Hg.) (2010): ''Die Dritte Philosophie. Kritische Beitr\u00e4ge zu Josef Mitterers Non-Dualismus''. Weilerswist: Velbr\u00fcck Wissenschaft.\n* Riegler, Alexander & Weber, Stefan (Hg.) (2013): ''Non-dualism: A Conceptual Revision?'' Special Issue of [[Constructivist Foundations]] 8 (2).<ref>{{cite web |title=Constructivist Foundations - Volume 8, Number 2 - Non-dualism: A Conceptual Revision? |url=https://constructivist.info/8/2 |website=constructivist.info |language=en |date=15 March 2013}}</ref>\n* Kletzl S. (2015) Edifying non-dualism: Richard Rorty meets Josef Mitterer. In: Kanzian C. & Mitterer J. & Neges K. (eds.) Realism \u2013 relativism \u2013 constructivism: Contributions of the 38th International Wittgenstein Symposium. Austrian Ludwig Wittgenstein Society, Kirchberg am Wechsel: 160\u2013162\n\n==Talks and presentations==\n* [http://er2017.pros.webs.upv.es/keynote-2/ ''Conceptual Modeling: Philosophical Reflections'' (abstract for a guest honor talk at the 36th International Conference on Conceptual Modeling, Nov. 6th-9th, 2017, Valencia Spain)]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=18DzbWnvvCg ''Wahrheit unterwegs'' on youtube]\n* [https://www.literaturhaus-hamburg.de/programm/veranstaltungen/2012-05-15/philosophisches-cafe-josef-mitterer Caf\u00e9 philosophique with Josef Mitterer at the Literaturhaus Hamburg]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nondualism.info/ The Non-dualizing Philosophy of Josef Mitterer]\n*[https://www.wienerzeitung.at/nachrichten/reflexionen/zeitgenossen/482102-Der-Philosoph-als-Reiseleiter.html Der Philosoph als Reiseleiter (The philosopher as a Tour Director)]\n*[https://316am.site123.me/articles/the-rhetoric-and-lethargy-of-the-anthropocene Interview with Ewa Bi\u0144czyk about the philosophy of Josef Mitterer and other topics]\n*[https://science.orf.at/v2/stories/2921821/ \u00dcber das Erfinden einer Philosophie (article on the occasion of Josef Mitterer's 70th birthday on the website of the Austrian Broadcasting Corporation ORF)]\n*[https://www.diepresse.com/658146/wir-beissen-nicht-in-das-wort \"Wir bei\u00dfen nicht in das Wort\" - about Mitterer's philosophy in the Austrian newspaper ''Die Presse'']\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitterer, Josef}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Austrian philosophers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Austrian philosophers]]\n", "name_user": "Bronsky 2020", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josef_Mitterer"}
{"title_page": "Don Bluth", "text_new": "{{short description|American animator born 1937}}\n{{Infobox person\n|birthname=Donald Virgil Bluth\n|image=DonBluth.jpg\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1937|9|13}}\n|birth_place=[[El Paso, Texas]], U.S. \n|residence=[[Scottsdale, Arizona]], U.S.\n|years_active = 1955\u2013present\n|nationality=American\n|alma_mater=[[Brigham Young University]]\n|occupation=Animator, film director, producer, writer, production designer, animation instructor\n| employer      = [[Walt Disney Animation Studios]] (1955\u20131957, 1971\u20131979)<br />[[Filmation]] (1967\u20131970)\n|known_for=\n*Various animation work with [[Walt Disney Animation Studios]] and other companies\n*Co-founder of [[Sullivan Bluth Studios]] and [[Fox Animation Studios]]\n|family=[[Toby Bluth]] <small>(brother)</small>\n|website={{url|http://www.donbluth.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Donald Virgil Bluth''' ({{IPAc-en|b|l|u\u02d0|\u03b8}}; born September 13, 1937)<ref>{{cite book |last=Bendazzi |first=Giannalberto |date=October 2015 |title=Animation: A World History: Volume II: The Birth of a Style - The Three Markets |url=https://books.google.com/?id=razMCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PT267&pg=PP1#v=onepage |publisher=CRC Press |section=A Cat in the Heavy Traffic |isbn=9781317519904 |quote=Among the directors of feature films, Don Bluth is noteworthy. Born in El Paso, Texas, on 13 September 1937, Bluth went to Disney in 1956 (...).}}</ref> is an American [[animator]] and [[film director]]. He directed animated films, including ''[[The Secret of NIMH]]'' (1982), ''[[The Land Before Time]]'' (1988), ''[[All Dogs Go to Heaven]]'' (1989), ''[[Rock-a-Doodle]]'' (1991), and ''[[Titan A.E.]]'' (2000), and animated the [[LaserDisc]] game ''[[Dragon's Lair (1983 video game)|Dragon's Lair]]'' (1983). He also competed with former employer [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Walt Disney Productions]] during the years leading up to the films that became the [[Disney Renaissance]]. He is the older brother of illustrator [[Toby Bluth]].\n\n==Early life and Disney years==\nBluth was born in [[El Paso, Texas]], the son of Emaline (n\u00e9e Pratt) and Virgil Ronceal Bluth.<ref>{{cite web|title=Don Bluth|url=http://mormonsinbusiness.org/mormon_businessmen/don-bluth|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110115064455/http://www.mormonsinbusiness.org/mormon_businessmen/don-bluth|url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-01-15|publisher=Mormons in Business|accessdate=2012-07-25}}</ref> His great-grandfather was [[Helaman Pratt]], an early leader in [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]]. He is of [[Swedish people|Swedish]], [[English people|English]], [[Irish people|Irish]], [[Scottish people|Scottish]], and [[Germans|German]] descent.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.wargs.com/political/romney.html| title=The Ancestors of Mitt Romney| author=William Addams Reitwiesner| accessdate=2012-07-24}}</ref>\n\nAs a child in El Paso, he rode his horse to the town movie theater to watch Disney films; Bluth said later, \"then I'd go home and copy every [[Disney comic book]] I could find\".<ref name=\"cardwell19840218\">{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9aUfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XdYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1426%2C2440647 | title=Laser disc arcade games could become wave of the future | work=The Gadsden Times | date=1984-02-18 | accessdate=10 November 2013 | author=Cardwell, Lynda | pages=A8}}</ref> At the age of six, his family moved to [[Payson, Utah]], where he lived on a family farm. Bluth has stated that he and his siblings do not have much communication with each other as adults.<ref>{{cite web|work=Channel Awesome|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cGpupHNRgag|title=Shut Up and Talk: Don Bluth and Gary Goldman|accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref> In 1954, his family moved to [[Santa Monica, California]], where he attended part of his final year of high school before returning to Utah and graduating from [[Springville High School (Utah)|Springville High School]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2017}} Bluth attended [[Brigham Young University]] in Utah for one year and afterwards got a job at [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Walt Disney Productions]]. He started in 1955 as an assistant to [[John Lounsbery]] for ''[[Sleeping Beauty (1959 film)|Sleeping Beauty]]''. In 1957, Bluth left Disney only two years after being hired. Afterward, Bluth spent two and a half years in Argentina on a [[missionary (LDS Church)|mission]] for the [[LDS Church]]. He returned to the United States where he opened the Bluth Brothers Theater with his younger brother [[Toby Bluth|Fred]], though he occasionally worked for Disney.\n\nBluth returned to college and got a degree in English Literature from Brigham Young University. Bluth returned to the animation business and joined [[Filmation]] in 1967, working on layouts for ''[[The Archies]]'' and other projects. He returned full-time to Disney in 1971, where he worked on ''[[Robin Hood (1973 film)|Robin Hood]]'', ''[[Winnie the Pooh and Tigger Too]]'', and ''[[The Rescuers]]'', and directed animation on ''[[Pete's Dragon (1977 film)|Pete's Dragon]]''. His last involvement with Disney was the 1978 short ''[[The Small One]]''. Then he made and produced his first own short film, ''[[Banjo the Woodpile Cat]]'', which takes place in his hometown Payson, Utah, during the 1940s as Banjo travels to [[Salt Lake City]] to find the urban world.\n\n==Independent years==\n\n===Early critical success===\nOn his 42nd birthday in 1979, Bluth, along with [[Gary Goldman]], [[John Pomeroy]], and nine fellow Disney animators, set out to start his own [[List of animation studios|animation studio]], [[Don Bluth Productions]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About Don|url=http://donbluthanimation.com/_Don_Bluth_Animation_About_Don.html|publisher=Don Bluth Animation|accessdate=2012-07-25|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120826222344/http://donbluthanimation.com/_Don_Bluth_Animation_About_Don.html|archivedate=2012-08-26}}</ref><ref name=\"comicsjournal\">{{cite news|last=Heintjes|first=Tom|title=Newswatch: Bluth animation firm goes bankrupt|url=http://www.tcj.com/archive-viewer-issue-98/?pid=7634|accessdate=2012-07-30|newspaper=The Comics Journal No. 98|page=19|date=May 1985}}</ref> He drew a few (uncredited) scenes for ''[[The Fox and the Hound (film)|The Fox and the Hound]]'' but left early in production. Bluth was disheartened with the way the Disney company was run. He wanted to revive the [[Golden Age of American animation|classical animation style]] of the studio's early classics.<ref name=\"cataroo\">{{cite web|last=Cawley|first=John|title=Don Bluth Biography|url=http://www.cataroo.com/DBbio.html|work=The Animated Films of Don Bluth|publisher=Cataroo.com|accessdate=2012-07-25}}</ref> To this end, his studio, Don Bluth Productions, demonstrated its ability in its first production, a short film titled ''[[Banjo the Woodpile Cat]]'', and this led to work on an animated segment of the live-action film ''[[Xanadu (film)|Xanadu]]'' (1980).\n\nThe studio's first feature-length film was ''[[The Secret of NIMH]]'' (1982), an adaptation of ''[[Mrs. Frisby and the Rats of NIMH]]'', the 1972 [[Newbery Medal]] winner. Bluth employed 160 animators during the production and agreed to the first [[profit sharing]] contract in the animation industry.<ref name=\"comicsjournal\" /> Though only a moderate success in the box office, the movie received critical acclaim. Later, with the home video release and cable showings, it became a cult classic.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cawley|first=John|title=The Secret of N.I.M.H.|url=http://www.cataroo.com/DBnimh.html|work=The Animated Films of Don Bluth|publisher=Cataroo.com|accessdate=2012-07-30|quote=The film developed a cult following which only increased with easy access via video and cable showings.}}</ref> Nevertheless, due to its modest box office take, and an industry-wide animation strike, Don Bluth Productions filed for [[bankruptcy]].<ref name=\"cataroo\" />\n\nHis next film would have been an animated version of the Norwegian folk tale ''[[East of the Sun and West of the Moon#Film adaptations|East of the Sun and West of the Moon]]'', but was never made when the financial resources were drawn back.<ref>{{cite news|last=Beck|first=Jerry|title=Don Bluth Goes Independent|url=http://www.awn.com/mag/issue1.3/articles/beck1.3.html|accessdate=10 August 2012|newspaper=Animation World Magazine|date=June 1996|quote=That failure [of Secret of NIMH] caused Aurora to back out of producing Bluth's next film, East of the Sun, West of the Moon.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, he, [[Rick Dyer (video game designer)|Rick Dyer]], Goldman, and Pomeroy started the Bluth Group and created the groundbreaking [[arcade game]] ''[[Dragon's Lair (1983 video game)|Dragon's Lair]]'', which let the player control an animated-[[cartoon]] character on screen (whose adventures were played off a [[LaserDisc]]). This was followed in 1984 by ''[[Space Ace]]'', a [[science fiction|science-fiction]] game based on the same technology, but which gave the player a choice of different routes to take through the story. Bluth not only created the animation for ''Space Ace'', but he also supplied the voice of the villain, Borf.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cawley|first=John|title=Space Ace|url=http://www.cataroo.com/DBspace.html|work=The Animated Films of Don Bluth|publisher=Cataroo.com|accessdate=2012-07-25}}</ref> Work on a ''Dragon's Lair'' sequel was underway when the video arcade business [[North American video game crash of 1983|crashed]]. Bluth's studio was left without a source of income and the Bluth Group filed for bankruptcy on March 1, 1985.<ref name=\"comicsjournal\" /> A sequel called ''[[Dragon's Lair II: Time Warp]]'' was made in 1991, but it was rarely seen in [[video arcade|arcades]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Dragon's Lair II|url=http://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=7648|publisher=The International Arcade Museum|accessdate=10 August 2012|quote=This game ranks a 24 on a scale out of 100 (100 = most often seen, 1=least common) in popularity based on census ownership records.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Bluth, Pomeroy, and Goldman established, with businessman [[Morris Sullivan]], the [[Sullivan Bluth Studios]]. It initially operated from an animation facility in [[Van Nuys, California]], but later moved to [[Dublin]], Ireland, to take advantage of government investment and incentives. Sullivan Bluth Studios also helped boost animation as an industry within Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.estudiosirlandeses.org/reviews/drawing-conclusions-irish-animation-and-national-cinema/|title=Estudios Irlandeses   \u2013  Drawing Conclusions: Irish Animation and National Cinema|website=www.estudiosirlandeses.org|language=es-ES|access-date=2017-02-12}}</ref> Bluth and his colleagues taught an animation course at [[Ballyfermot Senior College]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2010-11-19|url=http://carpetbagger.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/03/03/an-animated-irish-invasion/|title=An Animated Irish Invasion|author=Melena Ryzik|work=The New York Times|date=2010-03-03}}</ref>\n\n===Affiliation with Steven Spielberg===\nTeaming up with producer [[Steven Spielberg]], Bluth's next project was ''[[An American Tail]]'' (1986), which at the time of its release became the highest grossing non-Disney animated film of all time, grossing $45 million in the United States and over $84 million worldwide.<ref name=\"americantail\">{{cite web|last=Cawley|first=John|title=An American Tail|url=http://www.cataroo.com/DBtail.html|work=The Animated Films of Don Bluth|publisher=Cataroo.com|accessdate=2012-07-30}}</ref> The second Spielberg-Bluth collaboration ''[[The Land Before Time]]'' (1988) did even better in theaters and both found a successful life on home video.<ref name=\"americantail\" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Cawley|first=John|title=The Land Before Time|url=http://www.cataroo.com/DBland.html|work=The Animated Films of Don Bluth|publisher=Cataroo.com|accessdate=2012-07-31}}</ref> The main character in ''An American Tail'' (Fievel Mouskewitz) became the mascot for [[Amblimation]] while ''The Land Before Time'' was followed by thirteen direct-to-video sequels.\n\nBluth broke with Spielberg before his next film, ''[[All Dogs Go to Heaven]]'' (1989).{{Citation needed|date=March 2017}} (Bluth was not involved with the Spielberg-produced ''[[An American Tail: Fievel Goes West]]'', released in 1991, nor with any of the numerous subsequent sequels to his other films.) Although ''All Dogs Go To Heaven'' only had moderate theatrical success, it was highly successful in its release to home video.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cawley|first=John|title=All Dogs Go To Heaven|url=http://www.cataroo.com/DBdogs.html|work=The Animated Films of Don Bluth|publisher=Cataroo.com|accessdate=2012-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103084802/http://www.cataroo.com/DBdogs.html|archive-date=2014-01-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> Like ''The Land Before Time'', ''The Secret of NIMH,'' and ''An American Tail'', ''All Dogs Go to Heaven'' was followed by related projects, none of which involved Bluth and his studio. He also directed films, such as ''[[Rock-a-Doodle]]'' (1992), ''[[Thumbelina (1994 film)|Thumbelina]]'' (1994), ''[[A Troll in Central Park]]'' (1994), and ''[[The Pebble and the Penguin]]'' (1995), which were critical and box office failures.\n\n===Work at Fox Animation Studios===\nBluth scored a hit with ''[[Anastasia (1997 film)|Anastasia]]'' (1997), produced at [[Fox Animation Studios]] in [[Phoenix, Arizona]], which grossed nearly US $140 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anastasia (1997)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=anastasia.htm|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=2012-07-31}}</ref> In a positive review of the movie, critic [[Roger Ebert]] observed that its creators \"consciously include[d] the three key ingredients in the big Disney hits: action, romance, and music.\" ''Anastasia'' established [[20th Century Fox]] as a Disney competitor.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ebert|first=Roger|title=Anastasia|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19971121/REVIEWS/711210301/1023|accessdate=2012-07-31|newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times|date=November 21, 1997}}</ref>\n\nDespite the success of ''Anastasia,'' Bluth resumed his string of box office failures with ''[[Titan A.E.]]'' (2000), which made less than $37 million worldwide despite an estimated $75 million budget.<ref>{{cite web|title=Titan A.E. (2000)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=titanae.htm|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=2012-07-31}}</ref> In 2000, 20th Century Fox Studios shut down the Fox Animation Studio facility in Phoenix, making ''Titan A.E.'' the last traditionally animated film released by 20th Century Fox in theaters until the release of 2007's ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=20th Century Fox Feature Films (Fox Animation Studios) Animated Theatrical Cartoons (1977-)|url=http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/20th_Century_Fox/Feature_Films/|publisher=The Big Cartoon Database|accessdate=2012-07-30}}</ref>\n\n===Return to animation===\nOn October 26, 2015, Bluth and Goldman started a [[Kickstarter]] campaign in hopes of resurrecting hand-drawn animation by creating an animated feature-length film of ''[[Dragon's Lair]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/donbluth/dragons-lair-the-movie?ref=video|title=Dragon's Lair: The Movie (Canceled)|website=Kickstarter}}</ref>Bluth plans for the film to provide more backstory for Dirk and Daphne and show that she is not a \"blonde airhead\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dragons-lair-movie-wont-depict-sexualized-version-/1100-6433325/|title=Dragon's Lair Movie Won't Depict \"Sexualized\" Version of Princess Daphne|work=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=September 13, 2016}}</ref> The Kickstarter funding was canceled when not enough funds had been made close to the deadline, but an [[Indiegogo]] page for the project was created in its place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/dragon-s-lair-returns/x/12369452|title=Dragon's Lair Returns|website=Indiegogo}}</ref> \n\nOn December 14, 2015, the Indiegogo campaign reached its goal of $250,000, 14 days after the campaign launched<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/dragon-s-lair-returns#/updates|title=Dragon's Lair Returns|website=Indiegogo}}</ref> {{As of|2018|February|lc=y}} the total exceeded $728,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/dragon-s-lair-returns#/|title=Dragon's Lair Returns|website=Indiegogo}}</ref> On March 26, 2020, it was announced that [[Netflix]] will be releasing it on its streaming service in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/dragons-lair-movie-ryan-reynolds/?fbclid=IwAR12wS1rNN-AfiRbTVCuZM3rcmy6y6TwstDrrTWHZZe6n2Y_jEFwnS2-Zd8|title=Netflix requires rights to the Dragon's Lair film|work=[[/Film]]}}</ref>\n\n==Unproduced projects==\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2019}}\n{{overly detailed|section|date=September 2019}}\nAn animated short film based on the ''[[Pied Piper of Hamelin]]'' story was in development, entering pre-production in the early 1970s. Art designs and works were created for the film, but it ended up being abandoned for unknown reasons. Some of the artwork can be found online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0WHDRFl0rSs|title=Sections of Piper Short|website=[[YouTube]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DonBluth/status/940981302722887680|title=ENROLL TODAY! Get a full year of ONLINE classes from Master Animator & Director Don Bluth! Classes start Feb 6th, 2018. Only 14 seats left! |first=Don|last=Bluth|date=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1980s, Bluth Productions started production work on an animated feature film entitled ''[[East of the Sun and West of the Moon#Film adaptations|East of the Sun and West of the Moon]]''.<ref>John Grant, p 35, ''Masters of Animation'',  Special Effects Are Revolutionizing Film\"</ref><ref>John Culhane, \"[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F00E3DB123BF937A35754C0A964948260&sec=technology&spon=&pagewanted=3 Special Effects Are Revolutionizing Film]\"</ref> Ultimately, the film was never made due to a loss of financial backing,<ref>\"Newswatch: Bluth animation film goes bankrupt\", ''[[The Comics Journal]]'' #98 (May 1985), p. 19.</ref> even though the film was heavily into post-production at the time of its cancellation. They decided to make ''[[An American Tail]]'' as its second animated film, starting production in December 1984 and released in November 1986.<ref>Jerry Beck, \"[http://www.awn.com/mag/issue1.3/articles/beck1.3.html Don Bluth Goes Independent]\"</ref>\n\nAn animated film that Don Bluth started pre-production work with Steven Spielberg. The film would have been an outer space adventure movie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dragonslairthemovie.com/canine-mysteries/|title=Canine Mysteries \u2013 Dragon's Lair Club}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cartoonbrew.com/interviews/exclusive-don-bluth-talks-about-his-return-to-dragons-lair-61996.html|title=EXCLUSIVE: Don Bluth {{sic|Inte|view|hide=y}} About His Return To \"Dragon's Lair\"|date=May 4, 2012|website=Cartoon Brew}}</ref>\n\nAfter acquiring the rights to [[The Beatles]]{{'}} songs in the mid-1980s, [[Michael Jackson]] approached Bluth with a movie idea called ''Strawberry Fields Forever''. The film would have had animated ''[[Fantasia (1940 film)|Fantasia]]''-style vignettes featuring Beatles songs, similar to ''[[Yellow Submarine (album)|Yellow Submarine]]''. Not only did Don Bluth agree to it, he also planned on making it entirely in [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]]. Had the movie been made, it would have predated the ground-breaking 1995 Pixar film ''[[Toy Story]]'' by about eight years. From deep within production of the project, the premise became revamped so that characters from Beatles songs (like [[Mean Mr. Mustard|Mr. Mustard]] and [[I Am the Walrus|the Walrus]]) would act as New York City gangsters. Among other reasons, the main reason why the project fell through was because the surviving Beatles members denied permission to use their images in the animated film. The only surviving part of the film was test footage of the \"Beatles gangsters\".<ref name=\"Institute2011\">{{cite book|author=Bathroom Readers' Institute|title=Uncle John's Endlessly Engrossing Bathroom Reader|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vihZDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT420|date=1 October 2011|publisher=Portable Press|isbn=978-1-60710-459-9|pages=420\u2013}}</ref>\n\nBluth was in production for an animated feature film that involved whales but more of a discovery experience through a whale's eye with a beautiful score and narration.{{cn|date=March 2019}} While scenes were made in 1991, the film's production was canceled due to problems with studios, resulting in Bluth working on other productions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cartoonresearch.com/index.php/animation-anecdotes-195/|title=Animation Anecdotes #195 &#124;|website=cartoonresearch.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Blitz Games]] planned a video game adaptation of Bluth's ''Titan A.E.'' to be released for the [[PlayStation]] and [[Microsoft Windows|PC]] in Fall 2000 in North America, following the film's summer release.<ref name=\"game\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2000/06/23/titan-ae-3|title=Titan A.E.|website=[[IGN]]|date=June 22, 2000|first=Perry|last=Douglas C.|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> Development on both platforms had begun in March 1999 under the film's original title ''Planet Ice'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/i_blitz|title=Philip Oliver of Blitz Games|website=[[Eurogamer]]|date=November 8, 2000|author=Gestalt|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> and an early playable version was showcased at the 2000 [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]] in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"game\"/> In July 2000, a spokesman from the game's publisher [[Fox Interactive]], announced that development on the title had been halted largely due to the film's poor box office performance which was \"only one of many different factors\" that led to its cancellation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2000/07/27/titan-ae-canned|title=Titan A.E. Canned|website=[[IGN]]|date=July 26, 2000|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA sequel to the 2003 game ''[[I-Ninja]]'' was planned, which had input from Bluth.{{cn|date=March 2019}} Work on the sequel started soon after the first game's release, but its studio [[Argonaut Games]] had some economic problems and eventually closed down in October 2004. The few aspects remaining from ''I-Ninja 2''{{'s}} development are some concept drawings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unseen64.net/2009/12/03/i-ninja-2-ps2-xbox-gamecube-cancelled/|title=I-Ninja 2 Cancelled|website=Unseen64|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA project called Pac Man Adventures was originally planned in partnership with [[Namco]] around 2003, but was scrapped due to financial problems on Namco's part leading to their merger with [[Bandai]] in 2007 and whatever development assets were left over was made into ''[[Pac Man World 3]]'' with no involvement from Bluth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ecollections.scad.edu/iii/cpro/DigitalItemViewPage.external?lang=eng&sp=1000278&sp=T&sp=Pall%2CRu1000001%40%2CQdon+bluth&suite=def|title=Content Pro}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/donbluth/status/677270407037059072|title=Check out these storyboard concept cut scenes for an interactive Pac-man game back in 2004.|first=Don|last=Bluth|date=December 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOne of the animated films that Bluth started pre-production with [[Steven Spielberg]] on, where it is an animation adaptation of the story ''[[The Velveteen Rabbit]]'', which is about a toy rabbit trying to become a real rabbit after his beloved human child owner is forced to abandon him.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nPlans for other arcade games similar to ''[[Dragon's Lair]]'' were in production such as \"The Sea Beast\", \"Jason and the Golden Fleece\", \"Devil's Island\", \"Haywire\", \"Drac\", \"Cro Magnon\", and \"Sorceress\".{{cn|date=March 2020}} Due to the budgeting issues and the [[Video game crash of 1983|1983 video game crash]], leading to the bankruptcy of both Bluth and [[Cinematronics]] (dispute the first game being massively successful), these projects were abandoned, with the only laserdisc games released by Bluth were ''[[Space Ace]]'' in 1984 and ''[[Dragon's Lair II: Time Warp]]'' in 1991.<ref>https://twitter.com/donbluth/status/664179126303985664</ref>\n\nAn animated film that Don Bluth was in pre-production with Steven Spielberg and [[George Lucas]]. The project is based on a story by [[Steven Bauer]] where a young boy in a fantasy world goes on a quest to get the moon back and save the sun from evil forces. Some of the film's concepts latter went into the 2014 French animated film ''[[Mune: Guardian of the Moon]]''.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nBluth was in production of an animated film about a little girl and her animal friends try to protect a little whale from evil whalers.<ref>http://ecollections.scad.edu/iii/cpro/DigitalItemViewPage.external?lang=eng&sp=1000249&sp=T&sp=1&suite=def</ref> The project was abandoned by its co-production studio [[Carolco Pictures]] after the commercial and critically failure of its first animated film ''[[Pound Puppies and the Legend of Big Paw]]''.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nBluth was deep in production on an animated feature film adaptation of the classic fairy tale directed. While a few scenes were made in 1984, the film's production was canceled when Don Bluth and the film's distributor [[Columbia Pictures|Columbia]] heard the news of [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Disney]] making an animated film with the [[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|same name]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nProduction commenced on a TV mini-series of a boy finds a magical tooth, while a video showed a clip of what the show is.<ref>[http://dragonslairthemovie.com/jawbreaker-story/ \u201cJawbreaker\u201d Story]</ref> The mini-series' production was shut down when Don Bluth started [[Fox Animation Studios]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nAn animated short film was in production that centered around a magical talking pencil starring [[Dom DeLuise]],<ref>http://ecollections.scad.edu/iii/cpro/DigitalItemViewPage.external?lang=eng&sp=1000076&sp=T&sp=1&suite=def</ref> until Don Bluth started Fox Animation Studios, abandoning work on it.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nAfter Don Bluth and Fox Animation Studios would release ''[[Anastasia (1997 film)|Anastasia]]'' one of their next films was going to be an animated film based on the book ''[[Deep Wizardry]]'' by [[Diane Duane]]. However development stalled and the project was canceled.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nOne of Don Bluth and Fox Animation Studios' next films after ''Anastasia'' was going to be a animated film based on the ''[[Quintaglio Ascension]]'' trilogy by [[Robert J. Sawyer]]. But production was put on ice, eventually shutting down.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe film was developed to be a comedy-less drama similar to ''[[The Land Before Time]]'', but due to the closure of Fox Animation Studios and the box office disaster of ''[[Titan A.E.]]'' the film was lent over to [[Blue Sky Studios]] who turned it into a dramedy.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nAnother animated film that was in production by Don Bluth and Fox Animation Studios was a animated film based on ''[[The Belgariad]]'' series by [[David Eddings]]. Production for the film was canceled, for unknown reasons.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nWhen [[20th Century Fox]] got the rights to ''[[The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy]]'' series by [[Douglas Adams]], they hired Don Bluth and Fox Animation Studios to make an animated film of it. But production was canceled when problems happened at Fox Animation Studios and [[Touchstone Pictures]] got the rights to make movie from Fox which became [[The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy (film)|the live-action film of the same name]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Recent work==\nIn 2002, Bluth and video game company [[Ubisoft]] developed the [[video game]] ''[[Dragon's Lair 3D: Return to the Lair]]'', an attempt to recreate the feel of the original Dragon's Lair LaserDisc game in a more interactive, three-dimensional environment. Reviews were mixed, with critics both praising and panning the controls and storyline. However, the visuals were noteworthy, using groundbreaking [[Cel-shaded animation|cel-shading]] techniques that lent the game a hand-animated feel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dragon's Lair 3D: Return to the Lair|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/dragons-lair-3d|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=2012-07-25}}</ref> {{as of|2012||}},<ref>{{cite news|last=Arrant|first=Chris|title=EXCLUSIVE: Don Bluth Talks About His Return To \"Dragon's Lair\"|url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/interviews/exclusive-don-bluth-talks-about-his-return-to-dragons-lair.html|accessdate=2012-07-25|newspaper=Cartoon Brew|date=2012-04-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509041052/http://www.cartoonbrew.com/interviews/exclusive-don-bluth-talks-about-his-return-to-dragons-lair.html|archivedate=2012-05-09}}</ref> Don Bluth and Gary Goldman were seeking funding for a film version of ''Dragon's Lair''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kelly|first=Kevin|title=Don Bluth trying to make Dragon's Lair movie|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2007/05/01/don-bluth-trying-to-make-dragons-lair-movie|accessdate=2012-07-25|newspaper=Joystiq|date=2007-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Weinberg|first=Scott|title=Don Bluth Still Wants to Make a 'Dragon's Lair' Movie|url=http://blog.moviefone.com/2007/04/29/don-bluth-still-wants-to-make-a-dragons-lair-movie/|accessdate=2012-07-25|newspaper=Moviefone|date=2007-04-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008061112/http://blog.moviefone.com/2007/04/29/don-bluth-still-wants-to-make-a-dragons-lair-movie/|archive-date=2012-10-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> After apparently sitting in development for over a decade, the project raised over $570,000 via a successful crowdfunding campaign in January 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dragons Lair Returns &#124; Indiegogo|url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/dragon-s-lair-returns#/|accessdate=2016-04-03}}</ref>\n\nBluth and Goldman continued to work in video games and were hired to create the in-game cinematics for [[Namco]]'s ''[[I-Ninja]]'', released in 2003.\n\nIn 2004, Bluth did the animation for the [[music video]] \"[[Mary (Scissor Sisters song)|Mary]]\", by the [[Scissor Sisters]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Paolo|title=Don Bluth animates Scissor Sisters video|url=http://animatedviews.com/2004/don-bluth-animates-scissor-sisters-video/|accessdate=2012-07-25|newspaper=Animated Views|date=2004-10-22}}</ref> The band contacted Bluth after having recalled fond memories of the sequence from ''[[Xanadu (film)|Xanadu]]''.\n\nIn 2009, Bluth was asked to produce storyboards for, and to direct, the 30-minute Saudi Arabian festival film ''Gift of the Hoopoe''. He ultimately had little say in the animation and content of the film and asked that he not be credited as the director or producer. Nonetheless, he was credited as the director, possibly to improve the film's sales by attaching his name.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gift of the Hoopoe -Recent film of Don Bluth?|url=http://donbluthanimation.com/forum/showthread.php?t=559|accessdate=2012-07-25|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310143446/http://donbluthanimation.com/forum/showthread.php?t=559|archivedate=2012-03-10}}</ref>\n\nOn February 3, 2011, it was announced that Bluth and his game development company [[Square One Studios]] were working with [[Warner Bros.]] Digital Distribution to develop a modern reinterpretation of the 1983 arcade classic ''[[Tapper (arcade game)|Tapper]]'', titled ''[[Tapper World Tour]]''.\n\n===As an author===\nBluth has authored a series of books for students of animation: 2004's ''The Art of Storyboard'', and 2005's ''The Art of Animation Drawing''.\n\n==As a theater director==\nIn the 1990s, Bluth began hosting youth theater productions in the living room of his Scottsdale, Arizona, home. As the popularity of these productions grew and adults expressed their wishes to become involved, Bluth formed an adult and youth theatre troupe called Don Bluth Front Row Theatre. The troupe's productions were presented in Bluth's home until 2012, when their administrative team leased a space off Shea Boulevard in Scottsdale and converted it into a small theater.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/arts/don-bluth-front-row-theatre-in-scottsdale-needs-50-000-to-stay-open-8418740|title=Don Bluth Front Row Theatre in Scottsdale Needs $50,000 to Stay Open|first=Lynn|last=Trimble|date=7 July 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography ==\n\n=== Feature films ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n! colspan=\"4\" |Functioned as\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Notes\n|-\n![[Film director|Director]]\n![[Film producer|Producer]]\n![[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n![[Animation department|Animation<br>department]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Sleeping Beauty (1959 film)|Sleeping Beauty]]''\n|1959\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|assistant animator\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[The Sword in the Stone (1963 film)|The Sword in the Stone]]''\n|1963\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|assistant animator\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Journey Back to Oz]]''\n|1972\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|layout artist\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Robin Hood (1973 film)|Robin Hood]]''\n|1973\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|character animator\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Escape to Witch Mountain (1975 film)|Escape to Witch Mountain]]''\n|1975\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|animator: titles\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[The Many Adventures of Winnie the Pooh]]''\n|1977\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|animator\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[The Rescuers]]''\n|1977\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|directing animator\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Pete's Dragon (1977 film)|Pete's Dragon]]''\n|1977\n|{{no}}\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|animation director\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Xanadu (film)|Xanadu]]''\n|1980\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|animator: animation sequence unit\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[The Fox and the Hound]]''\n|1981\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|animator\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[The Secret of NIMH]]''\n|1982\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|story adaptation / layout artist / visual development\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[An American Tail]]''\n|1986\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|production designer / storyboard artist / title designer\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[The Land Before Time]]''\n|1988\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|production designer / storyboard artist\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[All Dogs Go to Heaven]]''\n|1989\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|story / production designer / storyboard artist\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Rock-a-Doodle]]''\n|1991\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|story / storyboard artist\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Thumbelina (1994 film)|Thumbelina]]''\n|1994\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}} \n|screenplay\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[A Troll in Central Park]]''\n|1994\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}} \n|story\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[The Pebble and the Penguin]]''\n|1995\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Anastasia (1997 film)|Anastasia]]''\n|1997\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Bartok the Magnificent]]'' ([[direct-to-video]])\n|1999\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Titan A.E.]]''\n|2000\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|\n|-\n\n|}\n\n=== Short films ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n! colspan=\"4\" |Functioned as\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Notes\n|-\n!Director\n!Producer\n!Writer\n!Animation<br>department\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''Lost and Foundation''\n|1970\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|layout artist\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''Train Terrain''\n|1971\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|layout artist\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Winnie the Pooh and Tigger Too]]''\n|1974\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|story / animator\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[The Small One]]''\n|1978\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|animator\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Banjo the Woodpile Cat]]'' (for television)\n|1979\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|screenplay / animator\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''You Are Mine'' \n|2002\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|storyboard artist\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |[[Scissor Sisters]] - \"[[Mary (Scissor Sisters song)|''Mary'']]\" (music video)\n|2004\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|animation director\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''Gift of the Hoopoe''\n|2009\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|nominally director / storyboard artist\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''Circus Sam''\n|2019\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|animator\n|}\n\n=== Television series ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+\n!Title\n!Year(s)\n!Functioned as\n!Episode(s)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Fantastic Voyage (TV series)|Fantastic Voyage]]''\n|1968-1969\n|layout artist\n|17 episodes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[The Archie Show]]''\n|1969\n|production designer\n|special episode ''Archie and His New Pals''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Sabrina the Teenage Witch (1970 TV series)|Sabrina, the Teenage Witch]]''\n|1969-1972\n|layout artist\n|58 episodes\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Will the Real Jerry Lewis Please Sit Down]]''\n|1970\n|layout artist\n|episode \"Computer Suitor\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Groovie Goolies]]''\n|1970\n|layout artist\n|16 episodes\n|}\n\n== Video games  ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n! colspan=\"3\" |Functioned as\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Voice role\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Notes\n|-\n!Director\n!Producer\n!Animation<br>department\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Dragon's Lair (1983 video game)|Dragon's Lair]]''\n|1983\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}} \n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Space Ace]]''\n|1983\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|Borf\n|game designer\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Dragon's Lair II: Time Warp]]''\n|1991\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}} \n|\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Dragon's Lair 3D: Return to the Lair]]''\n|2002\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|{{yes}}\n|\n|intro and ending: animation director / background artist\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[I-Ninja]]''\n|2003\n|{{yes}}\n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|\n|cinematics: director / storyboard artist\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Tapper World Tour]]''\n|2011\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|\n|animator\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Animation|Disney}}\n*[[Sullivan Bluth Studios]]\n*[[Fox Animation Studios]]\n*[[Rich Animation Studios]]\n*[[Amblimation]]\n*[[John Pomeroy]]\n*[[Gary Goldman]]\n*[[Toby Bluth]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*John Cawley, ''The Animated Films of Don Bluth'', 1991, Image Publishing, {{ISBN|0-685-50334-8}}\n*John Grant, ''Masters of Animation'', 2001, Watson-Guptill Publications, {{ISBN|0-8230-3041-5}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.donbluthanimation.com}}\n*{{YouTube|user=DonBluthProductions}}\n*{{IMDb name|89940}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070723032930/http://www.thedoteaters.com/p2_stage6.php The Dot Eaters entry] on Bluth and the development of ''Dragon's Lair''\n*[http://adammcdaniel.com/DonBluth/Don_Bluth_Interview.htm Remembering NIMH] An interview with Don Bluth Studios about the making of ''The Secret of NIMH''\n* [http://www.crescentblues.com/5_1issue/int_don_bluth.shtml Don Bluth & Gary Goldman: Long-running Fun] An interview with Don Bluth and Gary Goldman\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120301202755/http://manvsart.com/man-vs-art-episode-28-animation-legend-don-bluth-interview-part-1/ Don Bluth Interview Part 1] and [https://web.archive.org/web/20110714031648/http://manvsart.com/man-vs-art-episode-29-don-bluth-interview-pt-2-plus-webcomic-diva-onezumi-hartstein/ Part 2] about his influences and the making of ''Dragon's Lair''\n*[http://www.cataroo.com/DBbio.html Don Bluth Biography] at Cataroo.com\n\n{{Don Bluth}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bluth, Don}}\n[[Category:Don Bluth| ]]\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Animators from Texas]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Ireland]]\n[[Category:American animated film directors]]\n[[Category:American animated film producers]]\n[[Category:American film producers]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Swedish descent]]\n[[Category:American storyboard artists]]\n[[Category:American video game designers]]\n[[Category:American video game producers]]\n[[Category:American video game directors]]\n[[Category:Animation screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Brigham Young University alumni]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Animation Studios people]]\n[[Category:People from El Paso, Texas]]\n[[Category:Writers from Phoenix, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Sullivan Bluth Studios people]]\n<!--He must publicly self-identify with the religious label[[Category:Latter Day Saints from Arizona]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saints from Texas]]-->\n[[Category:American production designers]]\n[[Category:Artists from Phoenix, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Texas]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Texas]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American animator born 1937}}\n{{Infobox person\n|birthname=Donald Virgil Bluth\n|image=DonBluth.jpg\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1937|9|13}}\n|birth_place=[[El Paso, Texas]], U.S. \n|residence=[[Scottsdale, Arizona]], U.S.\n|years_active = 1955\u2013present\n|nationality=American\n|alma_mater=[[Brigham Young University]]\n|occupation=Animator, film director, producer, writer, production designer, animation instructor\n| employer      = [[Walt Disney Animation Studios]] (1955\u20131957, 1971\u20131979)<br />[[Filmation]] (1967\u20131970)\n|known_for=\n*Various animation work with [[Walt Disney Animation Studios]] and other companies\n*Co-founder of [[Sullivan Bluth Studios]] and [[Fox Animation Studios]]\n|family=[[Toby Bluth]] <small>(brother)</small>\n|website={{url|http://www.donbluth.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Donald Virgil Bluth''' ({{IPAc-en|b|l|u\u02d0|\u03b8}}; born September 13, 1937)<ref>{{cite book |last=Bendazzi |first=Giannalberto |date=October 2015 |title=Animation: A World History: Volume II: The Birth of a Style - The Three Markets |url=https://books.google.com/?id=razMCgAAQBAJ&lpg=PT267&pg=PP1#v=onepage |publisher=CRC Press |section=A Cat in the Heavy Traffic |isbn=9781317519904 |quote=Among the directors of feature films, Don Bluth is noteworthy. Born in El Paso, Texas, on 13 September 1937, Bluth went to Disney in 1956 (...).}}</ref> is an American [[animator]] and [[film director]]. He directed animated films, including ''[[The Secret of NIMH]]'' (1982), ''[[An American Tail]]'' (1986), ''[[The Land Before Time]]'' (1988), ''[[All Dogs Go to Heaven]]'' (1989), and ''[[Anastasia (1997 film)|Anastasia]]'' (1997), and animated the [[LaserDisc]] game ''[[Dragon's Lair (1983 video game)|Dragon's Lair]]'' (1983). He also competed with former employer [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Walt Disney Productions]] during the years leading up to the films that became the [[Disney Renaissance]]. He is the older brother of illustrator [[Toby Bluth]].\n\n==Early life and Disney years==\nBluth was born in [[El Paso, Texas]], the son of Emaline (n\u00e9e Pratt) and Virgil Ronceal Bluth.<ref>{{cite web|title=Don Bluth|url=http://mormonsinbusiness.org/mormon_businessmen/don-bluth|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110115064455/http://www.mormonsinbusiness.org/mormon_businessmen/don-bluth|url-status=dead|archive-date=2011-01-15|publisher=Mormons in Business|accessdate=2012-07-25}}</ref> His great-grandfather was [[Helaman Pratt]], an early leader in [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]]. He is of [[Swedish people|Swedish]], [[English people|English]], [[Irish people|Irish]], [[Scottish people|Scottish]], and [[Germans|German]] descent.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.wargs.com/political/romney.html| title=The Ancestors of Mitt Romney| author=William Addams Reitwiesner| accessdate=2012-07-24}}</ref>\n\nAs a child in El Paso, he rode his horse to the town movie theater to watch Disney films; Bluth said later, \"then I'd go home and copy every [[Disney comic book]] I could find\".<ref name=\"cardwell19840218\">{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9aUfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XdYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1426%2C2440647 | title=Laser disc arcade games could become wave of the future | work=The Gadsden Times | date=1984-02-18 | accessdate=10 November 2013 | author=Cardwell, Lynda | pages=A8}}</ref> At the age of six, his family moved to [[Payson, Utah]], where he lived on a family farm. Bluth has stated that he and his siblings do not have much communication with each other as adults.<ref>{{cite web|work=Channel Awesome|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cGpupHNRgag|title=Shut Up and Talk: Don Bluth and Gary Goldman|accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref> In 1954, his family moved to [[Santa Monica, California]], where he attended part of his final year of high school before returning to Utah and graduating from [[Springville High School (Utah)|Springville High School]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2017}} Bluth attended [[Brigham Young University]] in Utah for one year and afterwards got a job at [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Walt Disney Productions]]. He started in 1955 as an assistant to [[John Lounsbery]] for ''[[Sleeping Beauty (1959 film)|Sleeping Beauty]]''. In 1957, Bluth left Disney only two years after being hired. Afterward, Bluth spent two and a half years in Argentina on a [[missionary (LDS Church)|mission]] for the [[LDS Church]]. He returned to the United States where he opened the Bluth Brothers Theater with his younger brother [[Toby Bluth|Fred]], though he occasionally worked for Disney.\n\nBluth returned to college and got a degree in English Literature from Brigham Young University. Bluth returned to the animation business and joined [[Filmation]] in 1967, working on layouts for ''[[The Archies]]'' and other projects. He returned full-time to Disney in 1971, where he worked on ''[[Robin Hood (1973 film)|Robin Hood]]'', ''[[Winnie the Pooh and Tigger Too]]'', and ''[[The Rescuers]]'', and directed animation on ''[[Pete's Dragon (1977 film)|Pete's Dragon]]''. His last involvement with Disney was the 1978 short ''[[The Small One]]''. Then he made and produced his first own short film, ''[[Banjo the Woodpile Cat]]'', which takes place in his hometown Payson, Utah, during the 1940s as Banjo travels to [[Salt Lake City]] to find the urban world.\n\n==Independent years==\n\n===Early critical success===\nOn his 42nd birthday in 1979, Bluth, along with [[Gary Goldman]], [[John Pomeroy]], and nine fellow Disney animators, set out to start his own [[List of animation studios|animation studio]], [[Don Bluth Productions]].<ref>{{cite web|title=About Don|url=http://donbluthanimation.com/_Don_Bluth_Animation_About_Don.html|publisher=Don Bluth Animation|accessdate=2012-07-25|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120826222344/http://donbluthanimation.com/_Don_Bluth_Animation_About_Don.html|archivedate=2012-08-26}}</ref><ref name=\"comicsjournal\">{{cite news|last=Heintjes|first=Tom|title=Newswatch: Bluth animation firm goes bankrupt|url=http://www.tcj.com/archive-viewer-issue-98/?pid=7634|accessdate=2012-07-30|newspaper=The Comics Journal No. 98|page=19|date=May 1985}}</ref> He drew a few (uncredited) scenes for ''[[The Fox and the Hound (film)|The Fox and the Hound]]'' but left early in production. Bluth was disheartened with the way the Disney company was run. He wanted to revive the [[Golden Age of American animation|classical animation style]] of the studio's early classics.<ref name=\"cataroo\">{{cite web|last=Cawley|first=John|title=Don Bluth Biography|url=http://www.cataroo.com/DBbio.html|work=The Animated Films of Don Bluth|publisher=Cataroo.com|accessdate=2012-07-25}}</ref> To this end, his studio, Don Bluth Productions, demonstrated its ability in its first production, a short film titled ''[[Banjo the Woodpile Cat]]'', and this led to work on an animated segment of the live-action film ''[[Xanadu (film)|Xanadu]]'' (1980).\n\nThe studio's first feature-length film was ''[[The Secret of NIMH]]'' (1982), an adaptation of ''[[Mrs. Frisby and the Rats of NIMH]]'', the 1972 [[Newbery Medal]] winner. Bluth employed 160 animators during the production and agreed to the first [[profit sharing]] contract in the animation industry.<ref name=\"comicsjournal\" /> Though only a moderate success in the box office, the movie received critical acclaim. Later, with the home video release and cable showings, it became a cult classic.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cawley|first=John|title=The Secret of N.I.M.H.|url=http://www.cataroo.com/DBnimh.html|work=The Animated Films of Don Bluth|publisher=Cataroo.com|accessdate=2012-07-30|quote=The film developed a cult following which only increased with easy access via video and cable showings.}}</ref> Nevertheless, due to its modest box office take, and an industry-wide animation strike, Don Bluth Productions filed for [[bankruptcy]].<ref name=\"cataroo\" />\n\nHis next film would have been an animated version of the Norwegian folk tale ''[[East of the Sun and West of the Moon#Film adaptations|East of the Sun and West of the Moon]]'', but was never made when the financial resources were drawn back.<ref>{{cite news|last=Beck|first=Jerry|title=Don Bluth Goes Independent|url=http://www.awn.com/mag/issue1.3/articles/beck1.3.html|accessdate=10 August 2012|newspaper=Animation World Magazine|date=June 1996|quote=That failure [of Secret of NIMH] caused Aurora to back out of producing Bluth's next film, East of the Sun, West of the Moon.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, he, [[Rick Dyer (video game designer)|Rick Dyer]], Goldman, and Pomeroy started the Bluth Group and created the groundbreaking [[arcade game]] ''[[Dragon's Lair (1983 video game)|Dragon's Lair]]'', which let the player control an animated-[[cartoon]] character on screen (whose adventures were played off a [[LaserDisc]]). This was followed in 1984 by ''[[Space Ace]]'', a [[science fiction|science-fiction]] game based on the same technology, but which gave the player a choice of different routes to take through the story. Bluth not only created the animation for ''Space Ace'', but he also supplied the voice of the villain, Borf.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cawley|first=John|title=Space Ace|url=http://www.cataroo.com/DBspace.html|work=The Animated Films of Don Bluth|publisher=Cataroo.com|accessdate=2012-07-25}}</ref> Work on a ''Dragon's Lair'' sequel was underway when the video arcade business [[North American video game crash of 1983|crashed]]. Bluth's studio was left without a source of income and the Bluth Group filed for bankruptcy on March 1, 1985.<ref name=\"comicsjournal\" /> A sequel called ''[[Dragon's Lair II: Time Warp]]'' was made in 1991, but it was rarely seen in [[video arcade|arcades]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Dragon's Lair II|url=http://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=7648|publisher=The International Arcade Museum|accessdate=10 August 2012|quote=This game ranks a 24 on a scale out of 100 (100 = most often seen, 1=least common) in popularity based on census ownership records.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1985, Bluth, Pomeroy, and Goldman established, with businessman [[Morris Sullivan]], the [[Sullivan Bluth Studios]]. It initially operated from an animation facility in [[Van Nuys, California]], but later moved to [[Dublin]], Ireland, to take advantage of government investment and incentives. Sullivan Bluth Studios also helped boost animation as an industry within Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.estudiosirlandeses.org/reviews/drawing-conclusions-irish-animation-and-national-cinema/|title=Estudios Irlandeses   \u2013  Drawing Conclusions: Irish Animation and National Cinema|website=www.estudiosirlandeses.org|language=es-ES|access-date=2017-02-12}}</ref> Bluth and his colleagues taught an animation course at [[Ballyfermot Senior College]].<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2010-11-19|url=http://carpetbagger.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/03/03/an-animated-irish-invasion/|title=An Animated Irish Invasion|author=Melena Ryzik|work=The New York Times|date=2010-03-03}}</ref>\n\n===Affiliation with Steven Spielberg===\nTeaming up with producer [[Steven Spielberg]], Bluth's next project was ''[[An American Tail]]'' (1986), which at the time of its release became the highest grossing non-Disney animated film of all time, grossing $45 million in the United States and over $84 million worldwide.<ref name=\"americantail\">{{cite web|last=Cawley|first=John|title=An American Tail|url=http://www.cataroo.com/DBtail.html|work=The Animated Films of Don Bluth|publisher=Cataroo.com|accessdate=2012-07-30}}</ref> The second Spielberg-Bluth collaboration ''[[The Land Before Time]]'' (1988) did even better in theaters and both found a successful life on home video.<ref name=\"americantail\" /><ref>{{cite web|last=Cawley|first=John|title=The Land Before Time|url=http://www.cataroo.com/DBland.html|work=The Animated Films of Don Bluth|publisher=Cataroo.com|accessdate=2012-07-31}}</ref> The main character in ''An American Tail'' (Fievel Mouskewitz) became the mascot for [[Amblimation]] while ''The Land Before Time'' was followed by thirteen direct-to-video sequels.\n\nBluth broke with Spielberg before his next film, ''[[All Dogs Go to Heaven]]'' (1989).{{Citation needed|date=March 2017}} (Bluth was not involved with the Spielberg-produced ''[[An American Tail: Fievel Goes West]]'', released in 1991, nor with any of the numerous subsequent sequels to his other films.) Although ''All Dogs Go To Heaven'' only had moderate theatrical success, it was highly successful in its release to home video.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cawley|first=John|title=All Dogs Go To Heaven|url=http://www.cataroo.com/DBdogs.html|work=The Animated Films of Don Bluth|publisher=Cataroo.com|accessdate=2012-07-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103084802/http://www.cataroo.com/DBdogs.html|archive-date=2014-01-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> Like ''The Land Before Time'', ''The Secret of NIMH,'' and ''An American Tail'', ''All Dogs Go to Heaven'' was followed by related projects, none of which involved Bluth and his studio. He also directed films, such as ''[[Rock-a-Doodle]]'' (1992), ''[[Thumbelina (1994 film)|Thumbelina]]'' (1994), ''[[A Troll in Central Park]]'' (1994), and ''[[The Pebble and the Penguin]]'' (1995), which were critical and box office failures.\n\n===Work at Fox Animation Studios===\nBluth scored a hit with ''[[Anastasia (1997 film)|Anastasia]]'' (1997), produced at [[Fox Animation Studios]] in [[Phoenix, Arizona]], which grossed nearly US $140 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anastasia (1997)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=anastasia.htm|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=2012-07-31}}</ref> In a positive review of the movie, critic [[Roger Ebert]] observed that its creators \"consciously include[d] the three key ingredients in the big Disney hits: action, romance, and music.\" ''Anastasia'' established [[20th Century Fox]] as a Disney competitor.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ebert|first=Roger|title=Anastasia|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19971121/REVIEWS/711210301/1023|accessdate=2012-07-31|newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times|date=November 21, 1997}}</ref>\n\nDespite the success of ''Anastasia,'' Bluth resumed his string of box office failures with ''[[Titan A.E.]]'' (2000), which made less than $37 million worldwide despite an estimated $75 million budget.<ref>{{cite web|title=Titan A.E. (2000)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=titanae.htm|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=2012-07-31}}</ref> In 2000, 20th Century Fox Studios shut down the Fox Animation Studio facility in Phoenix, making ''Titan A.E.'' the last traditionally animated film released by 20th Century Fox in theaters until the release of 2007's ''[[The Simpsons Movie]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=20th Century Fox Feature Films (Fox Animation Studios) Animated Theatrical Cartoons (1977-)|url=http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/20th_Century_Fox/Feature_Films/|publisher=The Big Cartoon Database|accessdate=2012-07-30}}</ref>\n\n===Return to animation===\nOn October 26, 2015, Bluth and Goldman started a [[Kickstarter]] campaign in hopes of resurrecting hand-drawn animation by creating an animated feature-length film of ''[[Dragon's Lair]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/donbluth/dragons-lair-the-movie?ref=video|title=Dragon's Lair: The Movie (Canceled)|website=Kickstarter}}</ref>Bluth plans for the film to provide more backstory for Dirk and Daphne and show that she is not a \"blonde airhead\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/dragons-lair-movie-wont-depict-sexualized-version-/1100-6433325/|title=Dragon's Lair Movie Won't Depict \"Sexualized\" Version of Princess Daphne|work=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=September 13, 2016}}</ref> The Kickstarter funding was canceled when not enough funds had been made close to the deadline, but an [[Indiegogo]] page for the project was created in its place.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/dragon-s-lair-returns/x/12369452|title=Dragon's Lair Returns|website=Indiegogo}}</ref> \n\nOn December 14, 2015, the Indiegogo campaign reached its goal of $250,000, 14 days after the campaign launched<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/dragon-s-lair-returns#/updates|title=Dragon's Lair Returns|website=Indiegogo}}</ref> {{As of|2018|February|lc=y}} the total exceeded $728,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/dragon-s-lair-returns#/|title=Dragon's Lair Returns|website=Indiegogo}}</ref> On March 26, 2020, it was announced that [[Netflix]] will be releasing it on its streaming service in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/dragons-lair-movie-ryan-reynolds/?fbclid=IwAR12wS1rNN-AfiRbTVCuZM3rcmy6y6TwstDrrTWHZZe6n2Y_jEFwnS2-Zd8|title=Netflix requires rights to the Dragon's Lair film|work=[[/Film]]}}</ref>\n\n==Unproduced projects==\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2019}}\n{{overly detailed|section|date=September 2019}}\nAn animated short film based on the ''[[Pied Piper of Hamelin]]'' story was in development, entering pre-production in the early 1970s. Art designs and works were created for the film, but it ended up being abandoned for unknown reasons. Some of the artwork can be found online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0WHDRFl0rSs|title=Sections of Piper Short|website=[[YouTube]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DonBluth/status/940981302722887680|title=ENROLL TODAY! Get a full year of ONLINE classes from Master Animator & Director Don Bluth! Classes start Feb 6th, 2018. Only 14 seats left! |first=Don|last=Bluth|date=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1980s, Bluth Productions started production work on an animated feature film entitled ''[[East of the Sun and West of the Moon#Film adaptations|East of the Sun and West of the Moon]]''.<ref>John Grant, p 35, ''Masters of Animation'',  Special Effects Are Revolutionizing Film\"</ref><ref>John Culhane, \"[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F00E3DB123BF937A35754C0A964948260&sec=technology&spon=&pagewanted=3 Special Effects Are Revolutionizing Film]\"</ref> Ultimately, the film was never made due to a loss of financial backing,<ref>\"Newswatch: Bluth animation film goes bankrupt\", ''[[The Comics Journal]]'' #98 (May 1985), p. 19.</ref> even though the film was heavily into post-production at the time of its cancellation. They decided to make ''[[An American Tail]]'' as its second animated film, starting production in December 1984 and released in November 1986.<ref>Jerry Beck, \"[http://www.awn.com/mag/issue1.3/articles/beck1.3.html Don Bluth Goes Independent]\"</ref>\n\nAn animated film that Don Bluth started pre-production work with Steven Spielberg. The film would have been an outer space adventure movie.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dragonslairthemovie.com/canine-mysteries/|title=Canine Mysteries \u2013 Dragon's Lair Club}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cartoonbrew.com/interviews/exclusive-don-bluth-talks-about-his-return-to-dragons-lair-61996.html|title=EXCLUSIVE: Don Bluth {{sic|Inte|view|hide=y}} About His Return To \"Dragon's Lair\"|date=May 4, 2012|website=Cartoon Brew}}</ref>\n\nAfter acquiring the rights to [[The Beatles]]{{'}} songs in the mid-1980s, [[Michael Jackson]] approached Bluth with a movie idea called ''Strawberry Fields Forever''. The film would have had animated ''[[Fantasia (1940 film)|Fantasia]]''-style vignettes featuring Beatles songs, similar to ''[[Yellow Submarine (album)|Yellow Submarine]]''. Not only did Don Bluth agree to it, he also planned on making it entirely in [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]]. Had the movie been made, it would have predated the ground-breaking 1995 Pixar film ''[[Toy Story]]'' by about eight years. From deep within production of the project, the premise became revamped so that characters from Beatles songs (like [[Mean Mr. Mustard|Mr. Mustard]] and [[I Am the Walrus|the Walrus]]) would act as New York City gangsters. Among other reasons, the main reason why the project fell through was because the surviving Beatles members denied permission to use their images in the animated film. The only surviving part of the film was test footage of the \"Beatles gangsters\".<ref name=\"Institute2011\">{{cite book|author=Bathroom Readers' Institute|title=Uncle John's Endlessly Engrossing Bathroom Reader|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vihZDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT420|date=1 October 2011|publisher=Portable Press|isbn=978-1-60710-459-9|pages=420\u2013}}</ref>\n\nBluth was in production for an animated feature film that involved whales but more of a discovery experience through a whale's eye with a beautiful score and narration.{{cn|date=March 2019}} While scenes were made in 1991, the film's production was canceled due to problems with studios, resulting in Bluth working on other productions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cartoonresearch.com/index.php/animation-anecdotes-195/|title=Animation Anecdotes #195 &#124;|website=cartoonresearch.com}}</ref>\n\n[[Blitz Games]] planned a video game adaptation of Bluth's ''Titan A.E.'' to be released for the [[PlayStation]] and [[Microsoft Windows|PC]] in Fall 2000 in North America, following the film's summer release.<ref name=\"game\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2000/06/23/titan-ae-3|title=Titan A.E.|website=[[IGN]]|date=June 22, 2000|first=Perry|last=Douglas C.|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> Development on both platforms had begun in March 1999 under the film's original title ''Planet Ice'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/i_blitz|title=Philip Oliver of Blitz Games|website=[[Eurogamer]]|date=November 8, 2000|author=Gestalt|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> and an early playable version was showcased at the 2000 [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]] in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"game\"/> In July 2000, a spokesman from the game's publisher [[Fox Interactive]], announced that development on the title had been halted largely due to the film's poor box office performance which was \"only one of many different factors\" that led to its cancellation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2000/07/27/titan-ae-canned|title=Titan A.E. Canned|website=[[IGN]]|date=July 26, 2000|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nA sequel to the 2003 game ''[[I-Ninja]]'' was planned, which had input from Bluth.{{cn|date=March 2019}} Work on the sequel started soon after the first game's release, but its studio [[Argonaut Games]] had some economic problems and eventually closed down in October 2004. The few aspects remaining from ''I-Ninja 2''{{'s}} development are some concept drawings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unseen64.net/2009/12/03/i-ninja-2-ps2-xbox-gamecube-cancelled/|title=I-Ninja 2 Cancelled|website=Unseen64|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA project called Pac Man Adventures was originally planned in partnership with [[Namco]] around 2003, but was scrapped due to financial problems on Namco's part leading to their merger with [[Bandai]] in 2007 and whatever development assets were left over was made into ''[[Pac Man World 3]]'' with no involvement from Bluth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ecollections.scad.edu/iii/cpro/DigitalItemViewPage.external?lang=eng&sp=1000278&sp=T&sp=Pall%2CRu1000001%40%2CQdon+bluth&suite=def|title=Content Pro}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/donbluth/status/677270407037059072|title=Check out these storyboard concept cut scenes for an interactive Pac-man game back in 2004.|first=Don|last=Bluth|date=December 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOne of the animated films that Bluth started pre-production with [[Steven Spielberg]] on, where it is an animation adaptation of the story ''[[The Velveteen Rabbit]]'', which is about a toy rabbit trying to become a real rabbit after his beloved human child owner is forced to abandon him.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nPlans for other arcade games similar to ''[[Dragon's Lair]]'' were in production such as \"The Sea Beast\", \"Jason and the Golden Fleece\", \"Devil's Island\", \"Haywire\", \"Drac\", \"Cro Magnon\", and \"Sorceress\".{{cn|date=March 2020}} Due to the budgeting issues and the [[Video game crash of 1983|1983 video game crash]], leading to the bankruptcy of both Bluth and [[Cinematronics]] (dispute the first game being massively successful), these projects were abandoned, with the only laserdisc games released by Bluth were ''[[Space Ace]]'' in 1984 and ''[[Dragon's Lair II: Time Warp]]'' in 1991.<ref>https://twitter.com/donbluth/status/664179126303985664</ref>\n\nAn animated film that Don Bluth was in pre-production with Steven Spielberg and [[George Lucas]]. The project is based on a story by [[Steven Bauer]] where a young boy in a fantasy world goes on a quest to get the moon back and save the sun from evil forces. Some of the film's concepts latter went into the 2014 French animated film ''[[Mune: Guardian of the Moon]]''.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nBluth was in production of an animated film about a little girl and her animal friends try to protect a little whale from evil whalers.<ref>http://ecollections.scad.edu/iii/cpro/DigitalItemViewPage.external?lang=eng&sp=1000249&sp=T&sp=1&suite=def</ref> The project was abandoned by its co-production studio [[Carolco Pictures]] after the commercial and critically failure of its first animated film ''[[Pound Puppies and the Legend of Big Paw]]''.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nBluth was deep in production on an animated feature film adaptation of the classic fairy tale directed. While a few scenes were made in 1984, the film's production was canceled when Don Bluth and the film's distributor [[Columbia Pictures|Columbia]] heard the news of [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Disney]] making an animated film with the [[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|same name]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nProduction commenced on a TV mini-series of a boy finds a magical tooth, while a video showed a clip of what the show is.<ref>[http://dragonslairthemovie.com/jawbreaker-story/ \u201cJawbreaker\u201d Story]</ref> The mini-series' production was shut down when Don Bluth started [[Fox Animation Studios]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nAn animated short film was in production that centered around a magical talking pencil starring [[Dom DeLuise]],<ref>http://ecollections.scad.edu/iii/cpro/DigitalItemViewPage.external?lang=eng&sp=1000076&sp=T&sp=1&suite=def</ref> until Don Bluth started Fox Animation Studios, abandoning work on it.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nAfter Don Bluth and Fox Animation Studios would release ''[[Anastasia (1997 film)|Anastasia]]'' one of their next films was going to be an animated film based on the book ''[[Deep Wizardry]]'' by [[Diane Duane]]. However development stalled and the project was canceled.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nOne of Don Bluth and Fox Animation Studios' next films after ''Anastasia'' was going to be a animated film based on the ''[[Quintaglio Ascension]]'' trilogy by [[Robert J. Sawyer]]. But production was put on ice, eventually shutting down.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nThe film was developed to be a comedy-less drama similar to ''[[The Land Before Time]]'', but due to the closure of Fox Animation Studios and the box office disaster of ''[[Titan A.E.]]'' the film was lent over to [[Blue Sky Studios]] who turned it into a dramedy.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nAnother animated film that was in production by Don Bluth and Fox Animation Studios was a animated film based on ''[[The Belgariad]]'' series by [[David Eddings]]. Production for the film was canceled, for unknown reasons.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nWhen [[20th Century Fox]] got the rights to ''[[The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy]]'' series by [[Douglas Adams]], they hired Don Bluth and Fox Animation Studios to make an animated film of it. But production was canceled when problems happened at Fox Animation Studios and [[Touchstone Pictures]] got the rights to make movie from Fox which became [[The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy (film)|the live-action film of the same name]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Recent work==\nIn 2002, Bluth and video game company [[Ubisoft]] developed the [[video game]] ''[[Dragon's Lair 3D: Return to the Lair]]'', an attempt to recreate the feel of the original Dragon's Lair LaserDisc game in a more interactive, three-dimensional environment. Reviews were mixed, with critics both praising and panning the controls and storyline. However, the visuals were noteworthy, using groundbreaking [[Cel-shaded animation|cel-shading]] techniques that lent the game a hand-animated feel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dragon's Lair 3D: Return to the Lair|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/dragons-lair-3d|publisher=Metacritic|accessdate=2012-07-25}}</ref> {{as of|2012||}},<ref>{{cite news|last=Arrant|first=Chris|title=EXCLUSIVE: Don Bluth Talks About His Return To \"Dragon's Lair\"|url=http://www.cartoonbrew.com/interviews/exclusive-don-bluth-talks-about-his-return-to-dragons-lair.html|accessdate=2012-07-25|newspaper=Cartoon Brew|date=2012-04-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509041052/http://www.cartoonbrew.com/interviews/exclusive-don-bluth-talks-about-his-return-to-dragons-lair.html|archivedate=2012-05-09}}</ref> Don Bluth and Gary Goldman were seeking funding for a film version of ''Dragon's Lair''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kelly|first=Kevin|title=Don Bluth trying to make Dragon's Lair movie|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2007/05/01/don-bluth-trying-to-make-dragons-lair-movie|accessdate=2012-07-25|newspaper=Joystiq|date=2007-05-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Weinberg|first=Scott|title=Don Bluth Still Wants to Make a 'Dragon's Lair' Movie|url=http://blog.moviefone.com/2007/04/29/don-bluth-still-wants-to-make-a-dragons-lair-movie/|accessdate=2012-07-25|newspaper=Moviefone|date=2007-04-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008061112/http://blog.moviefone.com/2007/04/29/don-bluth-still-wants-to-make-a-dragons-lair-movie/|archive-date=2012-10-08|url-status=dead}}</ref> After apparently sitting in development for over a decade, the project raised over $570,000 via a successful crowdfunding campaign in January 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dragons Lair Returns &#124; Indiegogo|url=https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/dragon-s-lair-returns#/|accessdate=2016-04-03}}</ref>\n\nBluth and Goldman continued to work in video games and were hired to create the in-game cinematics for [[Namco]]'s ''[[I-Ninja]]'', released in 2003.\n\nIn 2004, Bluth did the animation for the [[music video]] \"[[Mary (Scissor Sisters song)|Mary]]\", by the [[Scissor Sisters]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Paolo|title=Don Bluth animates Scissor Sisters video|url=http://animatedviews.com/2004/don-bluth-animates-scissor-sisters-video/|accessdate=2012-07-25|newspaper=Animated Views|date=2004-10-22}}</ref> The band contacted Bluth after having recalled fond memories of the sequence from ''[[Xanadu (film)|Xanadu]]''.\n\nIn 2009, Bluth was asked to produce storyboards for, and to direct, the 30-minute Saudi Arabian festival film ''Gift of the Hoopoe''. He ultimately had little say in the animation and content of the film and asked that he not be credited as the director or producer. Nonetheless, he was credited as the director, possibly to improve the film's sales by attaching his name.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gift of the Hoopoe -Recent film of Don Bluth?|url=http://donbluthanimation.com/forum/showthread.php?t=559|accessdate=2012-07-25|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310143446/http://donbluthanimation.com/forum/showthread.php?t=559|archivedate=2012-03-10}}</ref>\n\nOn February 3, 2011, it was announced that Bluth and his game development company [[Square One Studios]] were working with [[Warner Bros.]] Digital Distribution to develop a modern reinterpretation of the 1983 arcade classic ''[[Tapper (arcade game)|Tapper]]'', titled ''[[Tapper World Tour]]''.\n\n===As an author===\nBluth has authored a series of books for students of animation: 2004's ''The Art of Storyboard'', and 2005's ''The Art of Animation Drawing''.\n\n==As a theater director==\nIn the 1990s, Bluth began hosting youth theater productions in the living room of his Scottsdale, Arizona, home. As the popularity of these productions grew and adults expressed their wishes to become involved, Bluth formed an adult and youth theatre troupe called Don Bluth Front Row Theatre. The troupe's productions were presented in Bluth's home until 2012, when their administrative team leased a space off Shea Boulevard in Scottsdale and converted it into a small theater.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/arts/don-bluth-front-row-theatre-in-scottsdale-needs-50-000-to-stay-open-8418740|title=Don Bluth Front Row Theatre in Scottsdale Needs $50,000 to Stay Open|first=Lynn|last=Trimble|date=7 July 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography ==\n\n=== Feature films ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n! colspan=\"4\" |Functioned as\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Notes\n|-\n![[Film director|Director]]\n![[Film producer|Producer]]\n![[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n![[Animation department|Animation<br>department]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Sleeping Beauty (1959 film)|Sleeping Beauty]]''\n|1959\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|assistant animator\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[The Sword in the Stone (1963 film)|The Sword in the Stone]]''\n|1963\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|assistant animator\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Journey Back to Oz]]''\n|1972\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|layout artist\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Robin Hood (1973 film)|Robin Hood]]''\n|1973\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|character animator\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[Escape to Witch Mountain (1975 film)|Escape to Witch Mountain]]''\n|1975\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|animator: titles\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[The Many Adventures of Winnie the Pooh]]''\n|1977\n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{no}} \n|{{yes}}\n|animator\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''[[The 